<HEADLINE>
PUT RUSH LIMBAUGH IN `MONDAY NIGHT FOOTBALL' BOOTH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the network season proper is over and summer's (almost)
here, a TV critic's mind turns to ... football.
</P>
<P>
   Until Wednesday, anyway, when CBS launches ``Survivor.'' In the
meantime, I was thinking about how - and it kills me to say this -
Rush Limbaugh might not be such a terrible choice for the ``Monday
Night Football'' booth.
</P>
<P>
   (SLAP!)
</P>
<P>
   Ouch. Had to smack myself for even thinking it. Anyway, the
talk-radio king says he auditioned for the job last week (ABC
doesn't confirm this, but doesn't deny it, either). Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's a blowhard; yes, he's infuriating; yes, his views are
often so offensive that you want to pull the car over and yank out
the radio and hurl it into the river. (This would be more
satisfying if Arizona rivers had water in them.)
</P>
<P>
   All of which is why Limbaugh would be, if not exactly a good
pick, at least an intriguing one. People would tune in just to get
ticked off, and when's the last time that happened?
</P>
<P>
   Easy: Howard Cosell's last broadcast. ABC's sports bigwigs have
said this is the kind of juice they want to return to the booth,
juice that's been missing ever since the days of the Mouth That
Roared.
</P>
<P>
   How strong were the feelings Cosell stirred? Forget the
well-worn anecdote that a 1978 ``TV Guide'' poll named him both the
nation's most-liked and most-disliked sportscaster.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, look to last year's excellent HBO documentary, ``Howard
Cosell: Telling It Like It Is,'' for footage of shotgun-toting
yahoos blasting away at a TV set during a game.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Limbaugh's politics could be a problem, but not an
insurmountable one. ABC could forbid him to air his political
views. Or, what the heck, since the booth needs three people, hire
James Carville, too. &QL; 
_ Stuff you probably knew already: ABC finished first among major
networks for the 1999-2000 TV season, which officially ended
Wednesday night. Who wants to guess a million reasons why? A big
hint: One is Regis Philbin. &QL; 
_ Stuff you probably knew already, part two: The National
Organization for Women's recently issued Feminist Primetime Report
came down hardest on Fox's ``Who Wants To Marry a Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   To which the only appropriate reaction can be:
</P>
<P>
   Well, duh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
