<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-SEA-SON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEASON OF THE MILLIONAIRE': GAME SHOW REVIVES NETWORK HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scene: Last summer, a conference room in a California hotel
full of cynical, punch-drunk TV critics sitting through endless
network presentations of new shows.
</P>
<P>
   ABC trots out a couple of guys to talk about some game show it's
planning to air during the summer, when the TV pickings are slim
and competition non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   Yawn. That's the general reaction. Some stupid quiz show hosted
by that guy whose day job is chatting with Kathie Lee whatshername?
</P>
<P>
   Right. In a month it'll be history.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, of course, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' made
history, changing not only the course of the television season but
the way TV does business for the near future, if not beyond, for
better, worse and both.
</P>
<P>
   In a curious year for television, Regis Philbin became a
household name, unleashed a ubiquitous-if-idiotic catch phrase upon
the nation (I vote the next guy who says, ``Is that your final
answer?'' gets a punch in the throat) and arguably saved network
television from the advancing clutches of cable.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that last part might be a bit of a stretch, but not much of
one. A year ago, riding high on an increasing viewership,
superlative reviews of ``The Sopranos'' and more choices than any
self-respecting channel surfer could ever hope to indulge in, cable
looked like the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Still is, actually. People like choices - talk to a Home &AMP;
Garden Network fanatic sometime if you don't believe me. and
``Millionaire,'' you've got to believe, can't stay this popular
forever. (``Frasier's'' season finale, for instance, beat it in the
ratings.)
</P>
<P>
   But, largely on the strength of Regis' show, overall the big
networks not only didn't lose any viewers to cable this season,
stemming the tide of a recent trend, they actually picked up ... a
whopping 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's something.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to look a gift horse in the mouth, ABC - now the most
popular network - will flog its ``Millionaire'' breadwinner four
times a week next fall. So what kind of chance-taking,
rule-breaking programming did other networks use to fight back?
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. More game shows. At least until ``Twenty-One'' and
``Winning Lines'' bit the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Reality TV fared better, sort of. A month after swearing off
garbage, Fox gave us ``Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?'' As
famous-for-15-minutes (and soon to be naked, to boot) Darva Conger
proved, no one. Yet millions wanted to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, look for voyeuristic gems like ``Survivor'' and ``Big
Brother'' on a tube near you soon.
</P>
<P>
   This is not progress.
</P>
<P>
   What creative risks the networks did take backfired. Remember
``Action''?Probably not. How about ``Freaks and Geeks''? (The
beautiful end of the first episode, in which a geeky kid asks a
girl to dance to the Styx song ``Come Sail Away'' because it's slow
- only to listen in helpless horror as it speeds up - was the
single best moment in TV this season. When you don't know whether
to laugh or cry because you want to do both equally badly, it's a
sign of quality.)
</P>
<P>
   Wonderland, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think so. Tough sledding for a while there. Every time a
show took a chance, it seemed, viewers rejected it. The problem, it
seemed, wasn't so much the networks as it was us.
</P>
<P>
   Comedies in particular fell upon hard times. Never mind that
``Everybody Loves Raymond'' continued to improve and ``Frasier''
got funny again (if not as funny as it once was); stories of the
death of the sitcom began to surface.
</P>
<P>
   And then, just as comedy fans were searching for a tall building
and a short rope, Fox brought out ``Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilarious, smart, snarky - and, oddly enough, something critics
and audiences both loved.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the rope. Things are looking up.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're a teenager. Sure, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''
thrived as the gang started college, and remains one of the
smartest-written shows on TV (``Hush,'' the `silent` episode, was
an instant classic).
</P>
<P>
   But short-shorn ``Felicity,'' which underwent a big ratings
trim, as well, was more representative of the Clearasil set.
Coveting the younger viewers the WB exists to serve, networks piled
on the Beautiful Young People (``Odd Man Out,'' ``Get Real,''
``Wasteland,'' etc.).
</P>
<P>
   And viewers ignored them, opting for more adult fare, such as
``Judging Amy,'' ``Family Law'' and, best of all, ``The West
Wing,'' a show that managed the impossible: It made politics and
politicians likable.
</P>
<P>
   Not as likable as Regis, mind you, but in his million-dollar
television year, who was? &QL; 
Reach Goodykoontz at Bill.Goodykoontz(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
