<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ OUTDUELS CLEMENS AS RED SOX DOWN YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens turned, raised his chin and watched
Trot Nixon's long fly ball rise and fall, the ball disappearing
among fans in the right-field stands. For eight innings and two
outs, there had been no runs, and Clemens had been every bit as
good as Boston's Pedro Martinez _ better, perhaps. Clemens struck
out 13, Martinez nine.
</P>
<P>
   But there was that one pitch, that one high fastball that Nixon
slugged, the difference in a memorable duel. The Red Sox won, 2-0,
Sunday night at Yankee Stadium, although Martinez survived a scare
in the bottom of the ninth inning. ``It was a classic,'' said Joe
Torre, the Yankees' manager. ``I hope to hell it puts to rest all
the questions about Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won two of three games in this series and departed
with a one-game lead in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (4-5) got the first two outs easily in the top of the
ninth, and then Jeff Frye smashed a one-hopper back at Clemens. The
ball bounced off Clemens' glove and toward third, an infield
single. Nixon was next, having struck out in his first two at-bats
and tripled _ the second of Boston's four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens hurled a high fastball and the sound of Nixon hitting
the ball was all anyone needed to hear: a home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, stifled all night by Clemens, clapped and
high-fived one another in their dugout, the small noises of Red Sox
fans loud in an otherwise quiet Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez (8-2) hit Chuck Knoblauch with a fastball leading
off the bottom of the ninth, and Derek Jeter rolled a single to
right. Yankee Stadium was brimming with hope. Then Paul O'Neill
struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams lifted a high fly toward right, the way Nixon
had done. But Nixon, the Boston right fielder, caught the ball just
in front of the wall; Knoblauch tagged up and moved to third. With
Jorge Posada batting, Jeter swiped second, and then Martinez hit
Posada with a breaking ball. Bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez grounded to second, in what seemed an easy play,
but Frye double-clutched, trying to get a grip on the ball, before
finally tossing to first and barely nipping Martinez to end the
incredible duel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best pitched games I've seen, by both sides,''
Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens lasted only two innings in his playoff duel against
Pedro Martinez last year, surrendering five runs and straining his
lower back before Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre
decided it would be better if Clemens came out and did not
exacerbate his injury any further.
</P>
<P>
   Torre and Clemens never discussed that game again, but the
manager knew Clemens was badly disappointed; you could see it in
his eyes, Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by reporters the other day, Clemens quickly severed
conversation about that afternoon. ``I just pitched poorly and
we'll leave it at that,'' Clemens said. ``There's no reason to
rehash that and go back to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' nature is to look ahead, but several weeks ago he
actually went back in time to make a significant adjustment to his
pitching mechanics, reverting to the delivery he used while with
the Red Sox. Rather than holding his glove and right hand at chest
level at the outset of his motion, Clemens began pumping his hands
over his head. He has felt more comfortable since making that
change, his rhythm better.
</P>
<P>
   There also was a very practical reason for the alteration _
Clemens might have been tipping off his pitches for the hitters.
Holding his hands at his chest, Clemens sometimes raised his glove
a little higher before throwing the forkball; hitters could watch
his glove and make an educated guess about whether he was throwing
a fastball or a forkball. Now his pitches are disguised better; he
has more time to set his grip. Going into Sunday night's game,
Clemens had struck out 29 in his last 292/3 innings and won three
of his last five decisions.
</P>
<P>
   So he took his Red Sox style to the mound against the Red Sox,
and has never had better stuff since he joined the Yankees, his
fastball sailing, his forkball plunging, his slider veering. He
whiffed at least two batters in five of the first seven innings,
finishing some with 95 mph fastballs, while others flailed at his
forkball as it splattered against the dirt. Fifteen months ago
Yankee executives gathered on short notice at a restaurant in
Tampa, Fla., to discuss a trade of Clemens for David Wells and two
others, and when they unanimously agreed, this is what they
envisioned: Clemens dominating.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett rolled a single through the middle with one out
into the second inning. Before Clemens threw a pitch to Mike
Stanley, he attempted three times to pick off Everett _ and got him
on the third. Clemens threw exactly one pitch from the stretch in
the first eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens actually was better than Martinez, who allowed two hits
to Jeter and had prolonged battles with Knoblauch, who hit the ball
hard twice.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees could not score, either, going hitless in four
at-bats with runners in scoring position. In their last 86 at-bats
against Martinez, the Yankees have nine hits and 42 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The hitters were in trouble, and if they did not fully
comprehend this going into the game, they certainly knew in the
first inning. With the count three balls and two strikes to Nixon,
Clemens whipped a fastball off the outside edge of the strike zone
_ a called third strike, according to the home plate umpire, Ed
Rapuano.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon paused and stared before walking off. The star pitchers
were going to be the stars of this nationally televised game, which
turned into a feast of strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But in the bottom of the fifth inning, a foul ball slammed into
the right knee of Rapuano, who fell to the ground in agony. He
struggled to finish the inning, then was replaced by Paul Runge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
