<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE'S CUP STILL HALF-FULL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The ending was like so many others, in fact like all
the others, but this time different.
</P>
<P>
   The last game wasn't right for Ray Bourque. There was no pot of
gold at the end of the rainbow, no epiphany, no inflatable dingy
appearing miraculously at the shore to ferry him from the isle of
the marooned.
</P>
<P>
   But that was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had a blast playing with these guys,'' said Bourque,
following Colorado's 3-2 loss to Dallas Saturday night, ending the
Avalanche's season and snuffing out, for now, Bourque's lifelong
dream of winning the Stanley Cup. ``I really needed to play
somewhere else. It was nice to have a change. I needed a change.''
</P>
<P>
   That, above all, was why he left Boston. There was the Cup, of
course, the chance to find out what it would feel like to rhumba
around the ice with that trophy held high, feel the chilled
champagne stream through his hair like carbonated shampoo and light
fire in his aging eyes. For 20-plus years he lived that fantasy in
Boston, and twice, in '88 and '90, came as close as he ever would
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   For years, in fact, Bourque has carried around a mental image, a
precise idea of what the photograph of the winning moment would
look like. He would be hugging the Cup, smiling the smile of his
life, and the picture would detail every ounce that had been
extracted from his being.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would know that you'd been in a battle,'' he said. ``My
cheeks would be sunken. I'd have nicks and cuts. You'd know from
the picture that you'd paid a price. That's how I want it to
look.''
</P>
<P>
   To ask out, for a chance to be in that picture, was all about
that _ but not only about that. For Bourque, leaving Boston was
first to find out if his game was still intact, still able, and
truly to test himself under the fire, the challenge of a playoff
race. He got all of that in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, he had eased back into that comfortable chair of
resident icon, duly glorified for his past accomplishments, the
winner of five Norris Trophies. But the product surrounding him had
sagged to such a state, and the losing had become so constant and
numbing, that it was almost impossible for him to understand
anymore what his game was, what he meant to the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Had he remained in Boston any longer, he finally was convinced,
then he would retire in April. He was done. He didn't like how he
was playing, how the frustrating losses piled high, how the
footnote to 21 years was beginning to read like an obit rather than
an honor roll. Asking to be dealt wasn't a plea to send him out in
pursuit of a jackpot, but simply an act of self-preservation and a
chance to find out what he could do with what was left of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for an opportunity,'' Bourque reiterated
following the loss in Game 7 of the Western Conference finals,
leaving him one victory shy of his third trip to the finals. ``I
wanted to be with a team that made the playoffs, and I wanted to
have a good run.''
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off the names of his new teammates. They rolled from
his tongue in tones of respect, honor, admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick Roy. Peter Forsberg. Joe Sakic . . .'' said Bourque.
``You're talking about some talent. All these guys made it fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There were days he could tick off similar names in Boston. Adam
Oates. Cam Neely. John Bucyk. Brad Park. Jean Ratelle. Terry
O'Reilly. He could say his own name in context and feel excited.
Those teams ultimately didn't win the Cup, either, but they had
presence. As the years went by, though, he was the only one left
standing. There was promise in what was around him, but time was
running out, his time.
</P>
<P>
   Plugged into the Avalanche equation, the years peeled back.
Bourque played 30 minutes a night for the Avs, exactly as he had
for the Bruins, but the results were profoundly different. The
product moved ahead, not backward, important when the grains of
sand are sifting through the hourglass.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs were close to missing the playoffs when Bourque arrived
in Colorado, Dave Andreychuk in tow, and they went on to finish the
regular season 12-2-1 after his arrival. They knocked off the
Coyotes and Red Wings with ease in the first two rounds of the
postseason, even with Bourque sidelined for the last two games of
the Wings series with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee's fine,'' Bourque said before Game 7 with the Stars,
dismissing as absurd speculation that he will require offseason
surgery. ``Not a problem at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What was a problem for the Avs, in the end, was the overall
ineffectiveness of their forwards. The likes of Sakic and Forsberg
(``I wasn't good enough'') were rendered useless by the Stars. Even
with the help of Bourque's refined skill of moving the puck out of
their end, the Avs would see rush after rush break down in the
neutral zone or get turned back once cracking the offensive blue
line. It became painful to see Sakic botch a number of prime
scoring chances that did develop.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 7, when the Avs needed their forwards to establish a
presence early, they instead were striking only in their absence.
The Stars pressed the play, rolled up an 18-6 shot lead and scored
twice, both times on the power play. The second period began the
same, and by the time the Avs finally got their game going, the
Stars were in command of a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised,'' said Bourque, searching for reasons
for the poor start. ``When we came out, we were tentative. A game
like that, you should come out stormin'. But we were tentative.''
</P>
<P>
   When Roman Lyashenko scored for the three-goal lead, Dallas was
ahead, 24-10, in shots. Then the Avs decided to play, but far too
late. Over the remainder of the night, they outshot the Stars,
23-5, including a third period that rarely saw the Stars, content
to chip the puck out of their end, work the puck beyond mid-ice.
</P>
<P>
   With 5:25 gone in the third, Forsberg swept in a relay from
Chris Drury. With 11:34 to go, Milan Hejduk (seven shots on the
night) chopped the lead to 3-2, Bourque sending in the shot that
Hejduk deflected.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it was a footrace, and it didn't end until Bourque's
long-range wrister pinged off Adam Deadmarsh in the slot and then
ponged off the left post, a foot off the ice, with 12 seconds to
go. Season over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bourque is our general on the blue line,'' said Avs coach Bob
Hartley. He said it over and over again as the playoffs progressed.
Like his days in Boston, Bourque had a way of jumping on the ice
each time action would break into pieces and somehow reassemble it
all, instantly fitting together the disjointed pieces of the
puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk was the picture of dejection when it ended. It was
his roughing minor on Darryl Sydor with 16 seconds to go in the
first period that set the stage for Mike Modano's power-play strike
at 19:54. Andreychuk went at Sydor with elbow raised, ill-advised,
too blatant to ignore. The puck soon in the net, TV cameras caught
the stern-faced Hartley staring at Andreychuk as the ex-Bruins
forward slowly skated out of the penalty box amid the Stars'
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real bad for him,'' said Andreychuk, referring to
Bourque. ``But the good thing is, he's going to play again.
Hopefully, he'll be back here (in the playoffs). We all know he's a
guy who deserves a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   For Andreychuk, 37 in September, the night may have been
farewell to the game. He may find takers in the free agent market,
just as he did last summer, but he didn't leave with much
bargaining leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Reid, another of the ex-Bruins with the Avs, has a deal in
place to return to Denver. He likely won't know for a few weeks if
Bourque will be with him. As a group, the Avs were pulling for
Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd kind talk about that among ourselves _ how great it would
be for Ray to win it,'' said Reid, who won the Cup last season with
the Stars before becoming a free agent. ``Now, it's just another
part of the disappointment . . . you look at a guy like Ray, and
it's just so disappointing. Unbelievable. We had our chances . . .
we definitely had our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bourque sounded fine with that. In the postgame news
conference, he was subdued but not somber, bowed but not broken. He
has some experience with end-of-season farewells.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was good for me,'' he said, summing up the 11 weeks away
from Boston, away from routine, away from, in a sense, himself.
``The change was good. It did a lot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, everything the same, but different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
