<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Randy Wolf and Mike Lieberthal proved a home-town
advantage can exist at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers are the National League's only team with
a winning record that does better on the road than at home. Los
Angeles natives Wolf and Lieberthal continued that trend by leading
the Philadelphia Phillies to a 4-2 victory over the Dodgers on
Sunday in front of 28,603 at Dodger Stadium, dropping L.A. to 10-10
at home this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf used the added energy from playing in front of a large
group of supporters - he left 36 tickets for friends and family -
to pitch the first complete game of his career. He held the Dodgers
to six hits and improved to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   A day after his first home run in nearly three weeks provided
the deciding run Saturday, Lieberthal went 3 for 4, including an
RBI double in the seventh to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' said Wolf, who was coming off the shortest
outing of his career. ``It's pretty special to do it here at Dodger
Stadium. I've got all my friends and family here. It's something
I'll cherish for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Wolf, 23, pitched at Dodger Stadium was as a
student of El Camino Real High of Woodland Hills when he led the
Conquistadores to City titles in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   He attended more Dodgers games as a child than he can count,
usually dreaming of being a Dodger. Playing professionally at their
field, even if for a different team, ranks among the greatest
thrills of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty high up there,'' Wolf said. ``I've been coming
here since I was 5 years old watching the games. You dream to pitch
here. To win or to do well is even more of a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored a run off Wolf early when Shawn Green hit a
two-out double in the first and Gary Sheffield followed with a
single to drive him in. A solo home run by Chad Kreuter made it 2-0
Dodgers in the fourth, but Phillies manager Terry Francona said he
was intent on staying with the left-hander as long as possible to
rest an overworked bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a good job for us,'' Francona said. ``Today was a
very important day to get deep in the game and once you get deep in
the game, you can talk about winning the game. I understand that
was a lot to ask of him today.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf realized he wasn't fooling the Dodgers with his changeup so
he started relying primarily on his fastball. He did not give up
another hit after Mark Grudzielanek's one-out single in the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of Dodgers hitting should not be surprising since
Grudzielanek (.368) and Green (.394) are the only Dodgers batting
better than .300 at home. Of the remaining 11 position players on
the active roster, Sheffield was the only one to enter Sunday's
game with an average above .250 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dodgers bats quieted, the Phillies' became more
productive, leaving Dodgers starter Carlos Perez with a
no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Osuna (0-1) relieved Perez in the seventh. The first
batter he faced was Lieberthal, a Westlake High graduate.
Lieberthal's double tied the game. He scored two batters later to
give Philadelphia the lead and the Dodgers their second loss in a
row against the NL East's last-place team.
</P>
</TEXT>
