<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTLAND'S TITLE HOPES PISTOL-WHIPPED BY SHAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ As with Seattle, this is a town used to
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Trail Blazers flame out in a place where there is
nothing else, darkness goes pro.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Blazers fans find themselves this morning in a blacker
shade of grim, imagine the bleakness besetting Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost billions in the stock market lately, the Blazers
owner from Mercer Island can only sit idly as Shaquille O'Neal
tears up his team in the same fashion that the feds are tearing up
his old company.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. At least he'll have the privilege in Seattle next
month of opening up the world's ugliest building.
</P>
<P>
   Glory is often found in peculiar places.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Allen and the Blazers, there was nothing
peculiar Sunday about the Rose Garden scene. In fact, all it was,
was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Blazers were being swept out of the Western
Conference finals by the San Antonio Spurs. Sunday, they were being
swept out of the Western finals again, this time by the Los Angeles
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   True, it's not technically a sweep, since the Blazers have won
once in this best-of-seven series. But after a 103-91 vanquishing
in Game 4, the 3-1 deficit is large enough for its own telephone
prefix.
</P>
<P>
   After losing two straight at home to the Lakers, Portland's
freakish Game 2 blowout in Los Angeles last week is a dot shrinking
in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-point margin doesn't begin to describe how relentlessly
effective the Lakers were, and how disjointed and befuddled was the
team with the NBA's second-best record.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a strong argument could be made that the NBA
championship was decided Sunday. Now that the Blazers are broken
emotionally, and neither New York nor Indiana, the Eastern
Conference finalists, are close to the caliber of the Lakers, this
NBA postseason is ready for a eulogy, some flowers and a parade
down Wilshire Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   The only real hope for the rest of the league is that the Lakers
lose interest, starting Tuesday with Game 5 in L.A. It's possible,
of course, especially in a town that invented the 30-second
attention span. But the way the Lakers have taken control of what
was purported to be a spirited match among equals, chances are less
than remote.
</P>
<P>
   Even Scottie Pippen, the Blazers' leader who knows something
about championships, could not dodge the impression of purple
formidability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we had played well, if it would have helped,''
he said, ``as well as they played.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers looked so good because the Blazers were nothing close
to the two-man show of O'Neal and Kobe Bryant. With 21 points from
Glen Rice and 18 from Ron Harper, as well as the spidery team
defense that throttled the Blazers in the second halves of both
games in Portland, the Lakers displayed the weaponry and
versatility that made them a season-long nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in an afternoon of free-throw perfection from O'Neal _
9-for-9; I swear it's true on a stack of Bibles, as will 20,209
other witnesses, although their swearing is a little different _
and the Lakers were awash in giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal credited some of his success at the line to a phone
conversation with his 3-year-old daughter, Taahirah.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't know the game, and I said, `Daddy loves you,''' he
said. ``She answered, `Good luck, and bend your knees.'''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, it seems, is an expert.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who is developing a knack for reinventing himself faster
than the media can do it for him, harkened back to his Louisiana
State University days for an analogy to describe his suddenly deft
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel,'' he said, grinning, ``like Pete Maravich.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. A 330-pound Pistol. Who plays defense.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace, the lone effective Blazer with 34 points and 13
rebounds, did not take well a question asking for a description of
O'Neal's impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big cat, man,'' Wallace said. ``That's a pretty stupid
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a 7-foot-2, 350-pound factor, that's how big a factor he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, the Blazers have as difficult a time describing
Shaq as containing him.
</P>
<P>
   The task was illustrated late in the third period when O'Neal
was posted up on Brian Grant. O'Neal faked a move into the middle,
spun quickly to the baseline, slipping past the smaller Grant, then
lofted a gentle, one-handed double pump of a leaner that drew a
score and a foul.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the move of a man who weighs 30 pounds more than
the Seahawks' Cortez Kennedy. That was a Maravich move.
</P>
<P>
   And it turned into a Pistol-whipping.
</P>
<P>
   If the guy comes out Tuesday night with a crossover dribble and
a blind pass behind the back, the Blazers would be well-advised to
invite in Indiana or New York for the second half.
</P>
<P>
   For an ugly task, it is always best to get an early start.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8009
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
