<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA DOMINATES HIS FIRST INDIANAPOLIS 500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ He came, he raced, he conquered. Then Juan
Montoya smugly gulped milk in Victory Lane at Indianapolis Motor
Speedway Sunday, the first rookie to win the Indy 500 in 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year old Colombian made it look effortless, leading 167
of the 200 laps and saying later he never truly felt challenged.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, from the time Montoya first turned laps at auto
racing's most historic speedway two months ago, he had insisted the
track held no particular mystique to him and that the Indianapolis
500 was ``just another race.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But this was not just another victory _ not to
Montoya's CART counterparts, who felt vindicated by his flawless
victory over the Indy Racing League competition, or the 400,000
fans in the grandstands who watched one of the most dominant
winning performances in the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, who won the CART championship last year as a rookie,
beat IRL regulars Buddy Lazier, the 1996 Indy winner, and Eliseo
Salazar by a comfortable 7.183 seconds to become the first rookie
winner at Indy since Graham Hill in 1966. The last Indy winner to
so thoroughly cover the 33-car field was Al Unser, who led 190 laps
in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of fun today,'' said Montoya, who claimed $1.23
million of the record $9.4 million purse. ``We wanted to win here
like any other race, only now I'm a little happier than I was an
hour ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Much was made of Montoya and his Ganassi teammate Jimmy Vasser's
Indy entries because they were the first CART regulars to race in
the 500 since 1996, when open-wheel racing split into two rival
organizations. But team owner Chip Ganassi said he has been
welcomed back to the Speedway with open arms this month and has
enjoyed the chance to renew friendships.
</P>
<P>
   Race runner-up Lazier argued the welcome was a little too
friendly and actually blamed his IRL comrades for his difficulty in
mounting a better challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got stuck, I got hammered, I got boxed in and it was IRL
drivers doing it,'' said Lazier, who also finished second at Indy
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating because they could have at least let me go
through traffic like they let Juan. I guess you have to say the IRL
has really good sportsmanship, maybe too good. I was surprised. I
thought the IRL guys would stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the IRL's best hopes for victory didn't last halfway
through the event, which started three hours late because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter and reigning IRL champion Greg Ray led 26 laps but
hit the second-turn wall hard on lap 66, causing extensive damage
to his Oldsmobile. He returned to the track after repairs to his
car and crashed again in the same location on lap 142, ending his
day and bringing out the fifth of the race's seven yellow flags.
Ray finished the day 33rd.
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr., making his first Indy 500 start since 1995, was
caught up in Ray's initial mishap. Debris from Ray's wreck badly
damaged Unser's car, so the two-time Indy 500 champ decided to call
it quits, finishing in 29th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car just wasn't working after that and this isn't NASCAR,
it's 220-mph Indy cars _ I didn't want to be a danger,'' said
Unser, who left CART to compete full-time in the IRL this season.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest and oldest competitors in the field _ 19-year-old
Sarah Fisher and 53-year-old Lyn St. James _ also had a short day.
They collided negotiating traffic on lap 74 and were scored 31st
and 32nd, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven cars finished on the lead lap. Salazar's A.J. Foyt
Racing teammate, Jeff Ward, was fourth, followed by 1998 Indy
winner Eddie Cheever, who recorded Infiniti's best-ever Indy
finish. NASCAR Winston Cup driver Robby Gordon was sixth and Vasser
finished seventh, forced to pit for a splash of fuel with four laps
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   So in the IRL's first true test of ``us vs. them,'' the visitors
won. However, it was slightly easier to digest considering
Ganassi's team has beaten up the CART ranks, too, winning the past
four championships. Montoya won a series-best seven races last year
and either he or Vasser has finished on the podium in 11 of the
past 23 CART events.
</P>
<P>
   The pair even turned double duty this weekend, with finishes of
fourth and seventh, respectively, in the CART race at Nazareth,
Pa., on Saturday before jetting back to Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just one (CART driver) beat us today, but he's a super
talent,'' Salazar said.
</P>
<P>
   So good even IRL team owner and four-time Indy 500 winner A.J.
Foyt had to concede, ``That kid's just one hell of a race driver.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
<P>
   or hollycain &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
