<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDIANAPOLIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA WINS RESPECT WITH VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 500-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ He was openly criticized for being too brash, too
young, too cheeky to have any regard or sense of history for what
it meant to drive the Indianapolis 500, let alone win the Greatest
Spectacle in Racing.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Juan Montoya arrived at the Brickyard with teammate
Jimmy Vasser and Target/Chip Ganassi Racing from Championship Auto
Racing Teams, the 24-year-old virtuoso, who won last year's CART
title as a rookie, was treated with some disdain.
</P>
<P>
   Former CART driver and two-time Indy 500 winner Al Unser Jr.
didn't believe Montoya showed the Speedway its proper respect. He
felt Montoya didn't hold it in enough awe.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, though, all of Indy seemed to be in awe of Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   There was joy from Montoya's home in Bogota, Colombia, all the
way to CART's headquarters in Troy, Mich., after the reigning CART
FedEx Championship Series champion took on all comers from the Indy
Racing League _ from IRL champion Greg Ray, the pole-sitter who
twice crashed and finished last, to runner-up Buddy Lazier,
third-place finisher Eliseo Salazar, and fourth-place finisher Jeff
Ward _ and dominated the IRL's crown jewel by winning the 84th Indy
500 as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a CART deal,'' Ward said. ``It's a Montoya deal.''
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident from the rain-delayed start to the
euphoric finish after Montoya, winless in five CART races this
season, became the first rookie since Graham Hill in 1966 to be
received in Victory Lane. While Hill didn't drink the milk, Montoya
had milk and cookies when he snacked on Oreos with Ganassi at the
winner's press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya led 167 laps, including 143 consecutive to set a record
for a rookie driver, and captured a $1,235,690 share of Indy's
record purse of $9,476,505.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will take time to realize what I just won,'' said
Montoya. ``I was happy to cross the finish line. It's so exciting.
I can't believe it. The car was comfortable. Every lap today, I
just had to keep pushing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to Indy's hallowed traditions, Montoya rolled his
Target-sponsored G Force-Aurora into Victory Lane and partook in
all its spoils. He had the laurel wreath draped around his
shoulders, took a sloppy swig from an ice cold bottle of milk, and,
as an added bonus, enjoyed an even sloppier kiss from his
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   And while he admitted ``pushing it hard all day,'' Montoya
seemed to make everything look so facile. He qualified second in
the 33-car grid in a four-lap average of 223.372 miles per hour in
cold conditions that induced eight previous drivers to wave off in
succession. He sliced and diced with Ray, Lazier, et al., got great
fuel mileage from his car, and enjoyed flawless pit stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was perfect,'' Montoya said. ``We didn't have to risk
anything. And it's not only a win for me, or for Chip or for Jimmy,
but for every person on the team. They worked so hard. They wanted
this win so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Montoya had led so many consecutive laps he
thought he was going to lap his own teammate, Vasser, and radioed
Ganassi to have him pull over. Montoya, though, was unaware Vasser
inherited the lead when Montoya pitted for the last time on Lap
175.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls me and I was like, `Uh, Juan, he's the leader. That's
for position.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although Vasser wound up relinquishing the lead to Montoya on
Lap 179, Ganassi said Vasser played a critical role in the victory
in helping determine the proper wing adjustments to Montoya's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the decision was based on what Jimmy did earlier (on a
pit on Lap 159),'' said Ganassi, who explained that Vasser's wing
adjustments made for a loose setup on the car that prompted the
team to stay with a tight setup on Montoya's car. ``We did the
opposite, so Jimmy can take ownership in this win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could diminish this triumph for Montoya. Not the rainy
weather. Not the three-hour delay. Nor the condescending comments
from Unser, who said of Montoya, ``They carry people out of here on
stretchers, so if you don't respect this place, it will bite you.''
</P>
<P>
   Unser, though, appeared rusty in his first race back at Indy. He
finished a distant 29th when he parked it after 103 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to admire Al, because on the ovals he was a great
driver,'' said Montoya. ``I'm surprised that he said that. It's the
second time he does it. I don't know, but I just go out there and
push it. If someone else doesn't what to push it, then it's up to
them. I go out and just try to do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, taking a cheeky parting shot, he added with a laugh, ``It
really (bit) me, so I'm surprised I won.''
</P>
<P>
   If he was, then he was all alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
