<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE REALITY LIVES UP TO THE HYPE FOR A NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (REWRITES with result of game) 
By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   NEW YORK _ The celebrated pitching
matchup between Pedro Martinez and Roger Clemens took place at
Yankee Stadium Sunday night. If anyone had any question as to why
it should have been so celebrated, developments emphatically
provided the answer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Martinez half of the matchup in the Boston Red Sox game with
the New York Yankees had never been in question. If there had been
any doubt, it was about Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they want to acknowledge it or not, the Yankees have
found Clemens to be an enigma in his season and a third with them.
His 14-10 record and 4.60 earned run average were nothing to
celebrate last season, and the 4-4 record and 4.26 ERA he took into
Sunday night's game had not earned any raves.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday night Clemens was every bit as dominating as
Martinez, more so actually for the first eight innings. But in the
ninth, Clemens weakened ever so slightly and it cost him.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Clemens could not hold Jeff Frye's hard
one-bouncer, and it went for a single. Trot Nixon then drove a 2-1
Clemens fastball into the beerless bleachers in right-center field
for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez staggered slightly himself in the Yankees' half of the
ninth, allowing the first two batters to reach base. But he
recovered and completed his four-hit shutout and a 2-0 victory, at
the same time lowering his world-leading ERA to 1.05.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first six innings, Clemens faced the minimum number
of batters, 18. The Red Sox managed to get two singles in that
span, but Clemens picked Carl Everett off first base in the second
inning and Jorge Posada threw out John Valentin at second on what
appeared to be a botched hit-and-run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox threatened to break Clemens' stranglehold on them in
the seventh when Nixon lashed a one-out triple to left-center
field. But Clemens tightened his hold around their throats just a
little more, striking out Brian Daubach and Nomar Garciaparra, the
latter batter for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' 13-strikeout performance explained why no one was
jumping to any negative conclusions about the 37-year-old
right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Asked, for example, before the game if Clemens had lost
something, Mike Stanley, the Red Sox first baseman Sunday night,
said: ``I wouldn't tell him that. Every time somebody tells him he
can't do something, he goes out and proves them wrong. He was no
longer wanted in this organization and went out and won two Cy
Youngs. He almost relishes the fact that people think he can't do
it anymore. I'm going to give him every ounce of respect that I've
ever had for him when he was at the top of his game because he's
still a presence on the mound and still knows how to get people
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he had no intention of underestimating Clemens in
this confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take your `A' game out against Roger,'' he said before
getting no hits in three tries against Clemens. ``You go out
thinking he's going to be the five-time Cy Young award winner that
he is. You have to put just as much concentration and effort into
your at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, the Red Sox third baseman, said he had lost no respect
for the man who was his teammate in Boston for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he's getting a little bit older now, but he is still
throwing 95, 96 mph, still throwing hard,'' Valentin said before
getting a single in three at-bats. ``I still think he is Roger
Clemens. He's still one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentin offered an insight into why Clemens might not
attain the same results now as he did in his Cy Young years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more than anything he's having trouble with his
command,'' Valentin said. ``That's the only thing I think is
different. When he throws his off-speed pitches, sometimes he
misses and they're up in the zone and that's when he can get hit.
He falls behind hitters and he walks hitters. He's walking more
hitters these days, I think, than he ever has in his career. I
think that's a very big factor. Why is that happening? I don't have
that answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who had averaged four walks per nine innings, walked no
one last night.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Red Sox faced Clemens, they beat up on him in
the league championship series last October. They knocked him out
one batter into the third inning. Stanley, with a single, was that
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to beat him like we did last year in the
playoffs,'' Stanley said, ``is if he's off. If he's on his game,
then you're scratching to get a couple. He obviously wasn't on top
of his game. I'd hate to sit here and think it was all to our
credit, that he was on top of his game and we were better than he
was. That's not the way it works with a quality pitcher like
Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is Clemens was off his game, giving up five early runs
in the park where he had won so many games and before the fans who
had cheered so hard for him for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also pitched in that celebrated matchup. When he left
the game, after seven innings, he did so on his own terms. He had
allowed the Yankees only two hits and he had struck out 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give hitters a lot of credit,'' Valentin said.
``Roger's been in the league for a long, long time. When hitters
face you year after year, they get to know you a little better in
how you throw your slider, how you throw your split-finger and so
on. Pitchers have to make adjustments. Give hitters credit. They
make adjustments. He's not going to be as dominant as he was.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
