<HEADLINE>
TIGER'S DESTINY DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ The combination is nearly unbeatable: Tiger Woods
and Jack Nicklaus. We say nearly because, once again, Mother Nature
has proven to be more powerful than anything Woods can unleash off
the tee and more dogged than Nicklaus's legendary determination.
</P>
<P>
   After blessing the Memorial Tournament with three days of
playable weather, the forces of nature took over Sunday, unleashing
sheets of rain and pushing back Woods's victory march until Monday.
It will mark the third Monday finish in 25 years of this
prestigious but weather-plagued event that stands as Nicklaus's
testament to tournament golf.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, thanks to rounds of 71-63-65 at Muirfield Village Golf
Club, is on the threshold of his fourth win of the year and 19th in
his brief but spectacular career. He will tee off at approximately
10:30 a.m. at 17-under par, six shots ahead of playing partner
Steve Lowery, seven in front of Justin Leonard, and eight clear of
Mike Weir. In all, 36 players had not started the final round and
only one pairing _ Corey Pavin (71) and Don Pooley (71) _ finished.
</P>
<P>
   The rain, said Woods, was no big deal. ``It's easy if you
haven't teed off. When you've already played a few holes it's more
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended at 11:15 a.m. because of lightning, but Ben
Nelson, tournament director for the PGA Tour, said a second storm
passed through that actually caused the most damage. ``The bunkers
have been washed out, the creeks are over the banks, and the lakes
are over the hazard lines,'' said Nelson, who indicated the course
would be playable Monday. Cutting the event to 54 holes was not
seriously considered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can play Monday and the forecast is good (it is
reasonable, though not great), we'll play Monday. We intend to play
72 holes every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Twice already this year _ the Pebble Beach National Pro-Am and
the Tournament Players Championship _ the Tour has had to push a
finish back to Monday, and it should come as no surprise the
Memorial will be added to that list. It is, after all, the 16th
time in 25 starts that rain has played a role in this tourney and
for the 10th time in its history, the Memorial's final round was
interrupted by the forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Woods appeared unruffled. And for good reason. He
has, after all, built the largest 54-hole lead on Tour this year,
and there is the overwhelming reality that he has gone on to win 15
of the 17 events in which he held a third-round lead. Throw in his
68.13 average in final rounds this year _ best on Tour _ and you
have a sense of how secure the situation seems to be for him.
</P>
<P>
   CBS will have taped coverage from 2-4 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8459 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-29 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH FIRE MAY BE LEFT IN THIS MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a reason why sweeps at this juncture of the
NBA playoffs are news.
</P>
<P>
   They're not easy to get.
</P>
<P>
   Many a team puts its rival in jeopardy by winning its first two
games of a seven-game series at home. But landing the knockout blow
when the scene shifts to the other guy's gym is quite another
matter. There now have been 126 NBA seven-game series in either a
2-2-1-1-1 or 2-3-2 format in which the team with the home-court
advantage has won Games 1 and 2 in their friendly confines. The W-L
of that team in Game 3? It's 43-83.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened at Madison Square Garden Saturday should not
have surprised anyone. The team that is 0-2 and coming back home
can be counted on to play with uncommon ferocity, and if you've
been paying a little attention you may have noticed that the Knicks
play with more ferocity than most other folks. You can foist all
the Boston hatred you want on them, but never fail to respect the
competitive nature of this particular New York squad.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without Patrick Ewing and getting a negligible
five-minute contribution from Marcus Camby before he was taken to
the hospital for X-rays on his right knee, the Knicks shrugged off
a 21-point first-half bombardment by Indiana's Rik Smits. They
answered with a 30-point third period that led to a 98-95 victory
that was not, as we scribes are wont to say, as close as the final
score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, the journalistic fun has begun in the Big Apple.
The Great Debate (Resolved: The Knicks Are Better Off Without
Patrick Ewing) rages anew. For coach Jeff Van Gundy, eternal
guardian of the captain's honor, there is no more aggravating and
painful hoop topic. But there is nothing the brooding mentor can
do. The New York media and the Knicks faithful watch the games, and
they draw conclusions. They saw an energized New York team torment
the slower Pacers with a pivot-less, up-tempo offense that featured
the obvious offensive skills of Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston,
who combined for 60 points in the Game 3 victory. The immediate
thought: Who needs the Big Guy? Is he not a ponderous relic who
cloggeth the lane and sloweth down the offense and just plain
gummeth up the works?
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy would rather coach a full game in his birthday suit
than admit anything of the sort. The team needs Patrick's
rebounding. The team needs Patrick's low-post offense. The team
needs Patrick's (occasional) blocked shots. They need Patrick's
Yoda-like presence. At least, that's the way Van Gundy sees it. He
also points to the record, which does reveal that the team did
better with him last year, both in the regular season and in the
playoffs, than without him.
</P>
<P>
   Both factions are half right. It's all about matchups. What Van
Gundy should be thinking is that not all opponents are created
equal. His aging center has more value in some situations than
others. This is pretty clearly one of the others.
</P>
<P>
   The Knick players believe they can defeat Indiana with or
without Ewing, but it's rather obvious certain players perform more
freely against Indiana without him. The Pacers are a finesse team
with just one even remotely physical player _ Dale Davis. In Smits
they have a 7-foot-4-inch center who is 6-10 on offense and 6-4 on
defense. His value begins and ends with his ability to put the ball
in the basket. The Knicks respect that ability, but worry about his
presence in no other area.
</P>
<P>
   They got by Indiana without Ewing last year. But when they ran
up against San Antonio in the Finals it was an entirely different
matter. The Spurs suited up a pair of 7-footers, David Robinson and
Tim Duncan, who rebound, play defense, intimidate, and score. New
York had zero chance. As is the NBA norm, it's all about matchups.
</P>
<P>
   One major difference between this year and last year concerns
the status of Marcus Camby, who was a Pacer killer a year ago. If
he cannot play, the Knicks eventually will pay the price. They
probably will be too small and too limited in their approach.
</P>
<P>
   None of this mattered Saturday, because that was a classic Game
3 for the team in the 0-2 situation. In no fewer than 41 previous
cases, a team that would eventually lose a seven-game series by a
4-1 margin salvaged some dignity by winning Game 3. Call it the
Cornered Rat Syndrome, if you will, but acknowledge the essential
logic. If a team has any class at all, it will play maniacally in
that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe our team has exceptional pride,'' said Van Gundy.
``You could have, subconsciously, had a little give-in after
halftime (New York trailed by 1), and I just thought we hung in
there very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana did not hang in there at all, which came as no great
surprise to its mentor. ``I've been living with this for 2 1/2
years,'' said Larry Bird, who, like his predecessor Larry Brown,
cannot comprehend how the Pacers can be so continually fragile from
the eyebrows up. Before the game even started Bird was bemoaning
his team's approach, explaining that he had heard too many guys
talking in terms of ``getting a split'' in New York. Sure enough,
check out the postgame thoughts of Jalen Rose, author of one of the
great Golden Trashcan performances in playoff history, a 22-point
fourth quarter that meant zilch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here with the intention of trying to win one,''
Rose said. ``Obviously, we didn't win today, but we still have a
game on Monday . . . We are the team that, if we win on Monday, we
will be 3-1 and going back home, so we have no reason to hang our
heads.''
</P>
<P>
   History still favors the Pacers in a big way. In the previous
125 series in question, the series record of the team going up,
2-0, is 121-4. Losing Game 3 is very often part of the deal. All
the same, there is no doubt which of these two is the spunkier
team. Ever hear of Rasputin? He lives in the spirit of the New York
Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
