<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COMING HOME HAPPY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ After eight months of absorbing their coach's
Eastern philosophy, meditation sessions and unique views of the
universe, the whole Zen package came together for the Los Angeles
Lakers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With tension booming through the Rose Garden, with the Portland
Trail Blazers grasping for their throats, the Lakers were the
portrait of relaxation. It's as if all the chaos they've endured
for years had finally spun to its conclusion, leaving them
remarkably calm as they stood on the precipice of a new stage in
their team evolution.
</P>
<P>
   One more win, and they are Western Conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a giant step toward assuming that mantle Sunday,
methodically putting down the Blazers 103-91 to take a commanding
3-1 lead in the conference finals. The best-of-seven series moves
back to L.A. for Game 5 on Tuesday, and the Lakers appear poised to
finish this off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's huge,'' said Robert Horry, ``because now you need just
one win to take care of business. And we just have to keep going
out and playing extremely hard. The thing about this is, we can't
feel relaxed. We've got to go in like we're down 3-1 and go at them
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd part is, they already are as relaxed as can be.
Everything Zen.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson smiled as much as he hollered Sunday.
Shaquille O'Neal calmly sunk all nine free throws, grinning and
wagging his tongue. Kobe Bryant slipped a little, but Glen Rice,
celebrating his 33rd birthday, proved that even astrology was on
the Lakers' side, as he scored a postseason-high 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   All biorhythms, it seemed, were in sync. All the little pieces
fell into place with perfection, as if by design.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal scored 25 points to lead the way. Bryant overcame a slow
start for 18 points. Ron Harper kept slashing to the basket to
pitch in another 18, and reserves Derek Fisher and Robert Horry did
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the fourth quarter arrived, the Lakers were well in
command, A.C. Green's little stuffed bear was in place on his
shoulder, and Fisher was paying homage to his suspended teammate -
wearing Brian Shaw's No. 20 jersey to midcourt as he waited to
check in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for my boy Shaw back at the hotel,'' Harper said.
``We're about to go get him and go home on the flight and enjoy
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we had nothing to lose today,'' O'Neal said. ``So
we just came in kind of loose. I was loose the whole game. I played
a pretty good first quarter, a pretty good first half and I was
loose. I was real loose.''
</P>
<P>
   He can afford to be. O'Neal and Bryant are scoring less, but
have overcome the Blazers' quick double-teams. Scottie Pippen,
playing against Bryant's hyper defense, is no longer hurting them
(he had 11 points Sunday), and even with Rasheed Wallace scoring a
career-playoff-high 34 points, the Lakers seem to have mastered the
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the worth of owner Paul Allen's team is plummeting
faster than his Microsoft stock. And no amount of his monopoly
money can patch the holes fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are showing signs of cashing in. The frustration was
evident in Pippen's forced woeful smiles in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, you know,'' Fisher said. ``Both teams are the best
teams in basketball and it's kind of similar to what happened to us
in Game 2. Once a team builds momentum and takes control, they're
too good to try and fight back in the game. So I think they
recognized that this was our game today and they were just gonna
focus more on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   That Portland is in this position is due in large part to the
late arrival of Rice. Missing in action for much of the postseason,
Rice provided a 12-point burst in 10 minutes of the third quarter
and turned a five-point halftime deficit into a 76-66 Lakers lead
to enter the fourth quarter. The Blazers never got closer than
eight points after that.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's surge somewhat was by design. With Bryant going 2 for 9
in the first half, Jackson designed a play for Rice to start the
third quarter, and the Lakers kept feeding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good birthday present,'' Rice said, ``but I hope it
doesn't stop here. They really made a conscious effort to get me
involved today. ... Once I got going, it made it difficult on them,
because they had to put Scottie on me. That created matchup
problems for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland's bigger problem is imminent elimination, having lost
both of their home games. But they also have shown they can win at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipate they're going to be a very, very difficult team
to put away,'' Jackson said. ``They have confidence on our home
floor. ... We surely don't want to come back up here and face this
arena and this crowd, this team again here in this building Friday.
So we're going to give it the best we have on Tuesday to win this
thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
