</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEAL, LAKERS GET LINE ON SERIES VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Given that little has gone according to Hoyle
so far _ witness Shaquille O'Neal's 9-for-9 shooting at the line
Sunday _ it might be premature or even presumptuous to suggest the
Western Conference final is over.
</P>
<P>
   But it is.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers ensured that Sunday with a second straight gem in the
Rose Garden, taking a 103-91 victory for a 3-1 lead in the
best-of-seven affair. They can close out the moonwalking Trail
Blazers Tuesday night at the Staples Center, virtually a fait
accompli given the way the hosts collapsed in their own building.
LA then will await the winner of the junior varsity scrum between
New York and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   This one went a lot like Game 3. The Blazers started off strong,
but wilted like the rabbit in a marathon. The Lakers absorbed the
early rush and then put on an offensive clinic in the third quarter
to take control for good. They then cemented things from the line
in the fourth, with O'Neal making all six of his freebies and the
team connecting on 17 of 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called my daughter (before the game) and she's 3 years old.
She doesn't really understand that game,'' O'Neal said, recounting
a pregame chat with Taahirah. ``I said, `Daddy loves you.' She
said, `Good luck and bend your knees.' So this game was for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, O'Neal added, ``I felt like Pete Maravich, that guy from
LSU.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who also attended LSU, was so hot the Blazers even tried
to ice him by calling a timeout between free throws. It didn't
work. Shaq also had 25 points, 11 rebounds, and 2 blocked shots in
45 minutes, although Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy noted, somewhat
amazingly, that ``those are numbers you can live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. The Blazers will never know. They might as well call up
the folks at Pumpkin Ridge for tee times Wednesday. Their 29-point
thrashing in Game 2 now looks like the basketball equivalent of an
internet IPO, almost as if ordered by Jerry Buss to get another
home gate. Portland was completely outplayed in the second half,
the ultra-loose Lakers capitalizing as the Blazers tightened up
like a dry bivalve.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pressure was on them,'' said Kobe Bryant, who had a
very mortal shooting day (5 for 15) but still ended up with 18
points, 7 assists, and 3 blocks. ``We just wanted to play loose. We
felt if we hung in there, the pressure would get to them.''
</P>
<P>
   And did it? ``I think so, yeah,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   It fell apart for Portland in the third. The Blazers again
controlled the first period, despite missing four layups and a
dunk. They led by 9 after one, lost the lead, then regained it and
led, 47-42, at the half. The Lakers were doing nothing offensively,
shooting 37 percent and managing a scant 14 field goals on six
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not have played much worse,'' coach Phil Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The third opened with a 12-point barrage over the first six
minutes from the heretofore forgotten birthday boy (33 years) Glen
Rice, who finished with 21, his highest point total since April 14.
The points came during an 18-7 run in which the Lakers overtook
Portland for good. The Lakers outscored Portland, 34-19, in the
third, shooting 70 percent from the field. They matched their
first-half total in field goals (14), had 10 assists, outrebounded
Portland, 11-5, and held the Blazers to 29-percent shooting (5 for
17.)
</P>
<P>
   That, basically, was the game. Los Angeles took a 76-66 lead
into the fourth and LA knows how to close games, unlike the
first-quarter friendly Blazers. LA had the first two hoops of the
fourth (a Shaq jump hook followed by a pretty Robert Horry reverse
layup) and the Blazers never got closer than 8 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Portland got a heroic game from a gimpy Rasheed Wallace, who
played the full 48 on a sore left ankle and had 34 points and 13
rebounds, both career playoff highs. But Scottie Pippen's promised
aggression never materialized because of foul trouble and he
managed only 11 points, along with five turnovers. The non-Wallace
Blazers shot a lame 7 for 26 in the second half and no Blazer other
than Wallace managed a basket for the first 10 minutes of the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers talked about having already won once in Los Angeles
and trying to get the series back here for a Game 6 on Friday. But
their words were as hollow as their play. They went down hard in
Game 3 and meekly in Game 4. The epic we all expected has turned
into yet another mismatch, not to mention an impressive show of
strength by the best team in the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
