<SLUG> BC-KOREAVET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORGOTTEN WAR' REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ The soldier's mother was at home when the news
came. Rose tore open the envelope, her heart beating fast. The
Western Union telegram began:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Secretary of the Army has asked me to express deep regret
that your son Cpl. Rowley Arden A has been missing in action in
Korea since 1 Dec. 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   Arden. Missing.
</P>
<P>
   Please, God . . .
</P>
<P>
   Early this morning, a group will meet on the front lawn of a
Mesa home, the one with the white picket fence. Arden A. Rowley,
69, will be there. So will his wife and children and most of his 18
grandkids and his three young great-grandsons, along with veterans
and neighbors and church friends.
</P>
<P>
   They will gather at Arden's house, around a 20-foot pole where
an American flag flies almost every day. At the Memorial Day
service, a new flag will be raised, then respectfully lowered to
half-staff.
</P>
<P>
   At the base of the pole, shaded by rosebushes, is a granite
marker. Engraved are the words ``All Gave Some. Some Gave All.''
</P>
<P>
   The small monument honors those who served their country and the
cause of freedom during the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Bloody, bitterly fought, it is called The Forgotten War. But one
man hasn't forgotten. One man can't forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't WANT to forget,'' Rowley said. ``There's not a day
goes by that I don't think about those people and those
circumstances.'' Fellow soldiers. Buddies. Friends he buried. He
still can see their young faces. ``All those men who died.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months after arriving in that faraway land, 20-year-old
Arden Rowley was captured. For 24 nights he and other American
servicemen marched in bitter cold. On Christmas Day they arrived at
their new home, a prisoner of war camp.
</P>
<P>
   His Communist captors did not adhere to the Geneva Convention
guidelines that provided for the protection, health and welfare of
POWs. Prisoners were poorly housed. Underfed. Each day Rowley
received a bowl of cracked corn, or millet _ he called it birdseed.
He lost 60 pounds. Growing weaker each day, he watched their
numbers shrink. One fellow soldier after another died, many from
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest survived, fortified by thoughts of loved ones and
the caloric feasts of their imaginations. Alone together, the
prisoners took turns describing their favorite meals. Yankee pot
roast. Southern fried chicken. The kid from Mesa High School told
his pals they haven't lived until they taste his Aunt Mavel's
cinnamon rolls, and then Arden launched into a mouth-watering
narrative about the plump raisins and the warm gooey icing, sweet
as a letter from home.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes closed, the bony soldiers could see them, smell them, fresh
from the oven, half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   One day a prison guard gave Rowley a sheet of rice paper and a
pencil. In a letter that arrived five months later, Arden wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dearest Mom and Dad,
</P>
<P>
   I don't know exactly what to say or how to tell you that I am a
prisoner of war. I know you must have worried a lot about me . . .
I want you to know that I pray often for you folks at home and also
for all of us fellows here in the P.W. camp . . . I know that with
God's kind care and protection I will come home to you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forgotten War? Rowley, who spent 33 months in prison camps,
has that letter. He still can hear the joy in the voice he
recognized when he stepped off the ship in San Francisco. ``There
he is!'' his brother Duane cried.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley spotted his smiling brother, and his mother and
stepfather. Today he can't describe the reunion without the words
lodging in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   The Forgotten War?
</P>
<P>
   Not long before his release, a U.S. officer in the POW camp came
to him one night. Putting a finger to his lips, he motioned for
Arden to follow him. They slinked surreptitiously through the camp
and entered a small kitchen. It was pitch black.
</P>
<P>
   The officer reached up and pulled a string, illuminating a
single light bulb.
</P>
<P>
   Rowley found himself with about a dozen other U.S. servicemen.
On a table was a freshly baked cake. An officer had decorated it
like the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``That flag was as real to me as the one out there flying in the
breeze,'' Rowley said, pointing toward the Stars and Stripes
presiding over his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   Until he draws his last breath, the kid who came back home to
Arizona, married and raised a family and taught at Mesa High School
will cherish that remarkable moment in the shared company of those
proud, brave men.
</P>
<P>
   Before devouring the evidence each one placed a hand over his
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge allegiance to the flag . . .'' they began in a single
voice that moved every one of them to tears. &QL; 
Reach Casstevens at David.Casstevens(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-8635 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0022 </DOCNO>
