<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALVAREZ A CAPTAIN OF REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Leonel Alvarez' commanding presence on the soccer field
earned him the nickname ``El Baron'' in Colombia. Alvarez often
appears to be performing effortlessly, unhurriedly, his touches
more elegant than exigent.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also an inner intensity about Alvarez that is
manifested in an ultra-dedicated approach to the game. This side of
Alvarez has become apparent recently, as he quickly rehabilitated
from a severely sprained left ankle and has claimed an important
leadership role with the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was named captain of the team for a 2-1 win over Los
Angeles Wednesday and likely will remain in the role for Sunday's
game against the Colorado Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   At age 34, Alvarez is the Revolution's oldest player, but he
appeared rejuvenated against the Galaxy, defending playmaker
Mauricio Cienfuegos, making continuous sprints up field, and
remonstrating with officials and teammates. The absence of John
Harkes (calf), who was named captain at the start of the season by
coach Fernando Clavijo, has caused Alvarez to become even more
assertive in the midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he would have difficulty communicating with referees
because of the language but that has not been the case,'' Clavijo
said of his choice of Harkes over Alvarez. ``I don't want to know
what he is saying to them, but whatever it is, it is working.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez' recuperative methods are also functioning well. He was
injured in the second half of a 2-1 win over San Jose May 6. Less
than five days later, Alvarez returned for a full practice session
in an attempt to regain his place in the lineup. But Clavijo urged
caution, and Alvarez remained out until May 17, when the Revolution
lost, 4-3, to Colorado, surrendering three goals after Alvarez
departed in the 71st minute. A week later, though, Alvarez was at
full speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, teams put a young guy on Mauricio Cienfuegos,''
Clavijo said. ``But Leonel was able to keep up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be a lesson to everyone. He wants to play and he
never wants to leave the field. He knows that as you get older you
need to do more, not less.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was not nearly as involved in the opening games of the
season. But as his physical conditioning has improved, so have his
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to Alvarez' recovery was a combination of enterprise
and sacrifice. After the Revolution's morning practices, Alvarez
would meet with Colombian trainer Camilo Fernandez for an extra
training session that would include running with a parachute tied
to his back. The regimen appears to have paid off, and now that
Alvarez is in peak condition, Fernandez will depart to treat
another Colombian, former Revolution midfielder Oscar Pareja, in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez apparently still has the desire that brought him to
prominence in Colombia and took him to Spain before he joined Major
League Soccer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is going well and getting results, and it is
important that we are getting them against very good teams,''
Alvarez said. ``We have to keep working, keep doing good things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to maintain our seriousness, sense of responsibility,
humility, desire to train and to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winning mentality is what this team needed and now we are
getting it. Before the season, we didn't have it, but now we do.
The team is now more together, happier. There is camaraderie, and
this is very important. With this, we can demonstrate alegria
(`joyfulness') when we play. The team is united, and when this
happens you can overcome difficulties. Last year, it was difficult.
The team was not happy and things were not going well. Now, things
are going better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep going individually and getting better. A
winning mentality leads to a good disposition toward working.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paulo Dos Santos, a Revolution midfielder in 1996 and '99,
agreed to contract terms with Olesund, a club that is vying for
promotion to the first division in Norway. Dos Santos made a strong
impression in Norway while playing for the Boston Bulldogs during a
preseason tournament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
