<HEADLINE>
RENOWN FOR BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 WOMEN'S CREW-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. _ There should be no more doubts. No more
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the best varsity eight crew in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That became clear Sunday on the Cooper River, where Brown
swamped Washington by open water to defend its NCAA Women's Rowing
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers had expected a stroke-for-stroke war between the
East and West Coast titans, but it never materialized. Virginia and
Michigan came out of the chute fast, but 100 meters into the race
it was Brown in command.
</P>
<P>
   Washington was actually a nonfactor. The Huskies languished in
fourth most of the race and only a great spurt in the final 500
meters caught first Virginia, then California.
</P>
<P>
   Brown answered every challenge thrown its way. California cut
into the lead with a burst at 950 meters, but Brown increased its
stroke to 38 and pulled away. Then Virginia made its move, and
Brown just shrugged that off, too. By 1,000 meters, it was obvious
Brown was supreme and the race was for second.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was clocked in 6 minutes 37.2 seconds and Washington in
6:41.1. Virginia (6:42.79) was third, followed by California
(6:46.5), Michigan (6:49.29), and Princeton (6:50.2).
</P>
<P>
   When it crossed the finish line first, Brown also assured itself
the team championship with 59 points. Washington was runner-up with
55 and Virginia third with 48.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all season long, Brown had been content to sit back and
make its move at 500 meters. Sunday, it did things a little
differently, although not by plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owed it to ourselves to row nothing less than a perfect
race,'' said Brown stroke Caroline Grogan. ``We put so much into
this season and this was our ultimate goal. But to be leading at
500 meters was something we didn't figure on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown coach John Murphy, who hedged a bit Saturday when asked
how this crew compared with last year's, was a little more giving
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still a tough question to answer,'' he said, ``because
they've never raced against each other. But this is as fast a crew
as we've ever had. We've never had one faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that Washington was very fast and we also knew that
there were other crews with potential to win. For the most part, we
just did what we did all year. Certainly being ahead at 500 meters
was a bit different, a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington coach Jan Harville was at a loss to explain the
Huskies' poor start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lost a bit at the start and then had to stabilize where
we were and try to battle back,'' she said. ``I think we could have
made things a lot closer if we had gotten into the race in the
first 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown was a great crew today. You have to go out and hit your
rhythm and be aggressive and attack. Sometimes that doesn't all
come together the way you want. Then you have to have a backup plan
to battle back. We did, and that's why I'm satisfied, even if we
didn't have a perfect performance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston University won the varsity eight petite final for its
best finish since rowing became an NCAA sport in 1997. The Terriers
coasted home in 6:49.1 _ 2 lengths ahead of Michigan State.
Northeastern was fourth and Radcliffe sixth. ``It was an excellent
way to end the season,'' said BU coach Holly Hatton. ``We raced
better every day we were here.'' In the boat were coxswain Monya
Hudsick, stroke Fiola Foley, bow Hillary Hegener, and Carson
Converse, Lisa Masi, Lisa Waterhouse, Jelena Tomic, Amy Lawless,
and Colleen Madden . . . Radcliffe's varsity four with coxswain
(Cait Koss) won its petite final. Rowers were Tasha Pasternack,
April Larson, Katie Pollock, and Sarah Psutka . . . Brown very well
could be a power in the making. Its second varsity eight won by a
whopping 10 seconds over Washington. The day wasn't a total bust
for Washington. Its varsity four with coxswain beat Brown by four
seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
