u s BC-CAR-INDY-HNS &LR;      05-29 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ No doubt the men of Championship Auto Racing
Teams will do a little gloating today, and they have Juan Montoya
to thank for it.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on which Indy-car league is better will continue, but
it was clear that Montoya was the best driver Sunday with a
convincing victory in the 84th Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy,'' Montoya said. ``All the guys on our team did a
great job. I tried so hard today. This is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Colombian became the first rookie winner of the
event since Graham Hill in 1966. But the significance of Montoya's
win goes deeper than a rookie victory.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, the defending CART FedEx champion, was part of the
first CART team to return to the Brickyard since the split with the
Indy Racing League in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   With backing from Target and Budweiser, Chip Ganassi brought his
CART drivers, Montoya and Jimmy Vasser, back to Indy to set up the
first showdown between the top drivers of the two leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' said an ecstatic Ganassi, whose team
has won all four CART championships since the split. ``Juan is the
best driver in the world, and this is the biggest moment of my
life. I think this is the happiest I've ever been in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Lazier, who won the first Indy 500 after the split in
1996, finished second in the Delta Dallara/Oldsmobile, 7.184
seconds behind Montoya in the Target G-Force/Olds.
</P>
<P>
   Eliseo Salazar and Jeff Ward, two of the three drivers for A.J.
Foyt's team, were strong all day and finished third and fourth,
respectively. Billy Boat, who started 31st in a Foyt backup car,
managed to move up through the field and finish 15th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have three cars finish a 500-mile race, you've
done well,'' Foyt said. ``We ran fast, but things didn't fall our
way today. I thought it was a great race, and that kid (Montoya) is
a hell of a race-car driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser also ran well for the Target team and was in the lead
pack all race but had to come in for a splash of fuel with three
laps to go and finished seventh.
</P>
<P>
   A capacity crowd of more than 350,000 watched Montoya lead 167
laps of the 200-lap race on the historic 2.5-mile oval. His team
had flawless pit stops under 10 seconds each time he left the
track. Montoya rarely was challenged, usually leading the
second-place car by more than five seconds on the way to winning
$1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazier doesn't think it proves the best drivers in CART are
better than the best in the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team has dominated the other league,'' Lazier said.
``They are a very strong team. You have to be fair in the
assessment of what happened today. I was right on Juan for a while,
but I got boxed in by some IRL drivers. They could have done that
to Juan, but they showed great sportsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya started in the middle of the front row, next to
pole-winner and defending IRL champion Greg Ray. But the battle
between league champs ended when Ray crashed on lap 66. Ray hit the
wall in turn 2 when he was running fifth in the Conseco
Dallara/Olds. ``We had an oversteer problem today,'' Ray said. ``On
our second pit stop, we tried to put more downforce in the car. But
it took away from the balance. I got a big gust of wind, and it
sent me sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   The team did repairs to the car, and Ray returned to the track
but crashed again in almost the same spot. The Plano resident
finished last in the 33-car field.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's first accident also caused problems for Al Unser Jr., a
two-time Indy 500 winner who was competing at the speedway for the
first time in six years. Unser's Tickets.Com G-Force/Olds was
damaged when he hit some debris from Ray's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit the radiator, and we lost all the water,'' Unser said.
``We came in and fixed it because we need to keep going and get the
points, but I felt it was real unsafe when we went back out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a danger to the other drivers and a danger to myself. We
didn't have anybody to race, so we decided to park it. This isn't
stock cars. We're going 220 mph, and you can't just make laps.''
</P>
<P>
   At times it appeared Montoya was just making laps in front of
the field. His performance came one day after finishing fourth in
the CART event at Nazareth, Pa. But Ganassi said it wasn't as easy
as it looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it was like watching any other race,'' Ganassi said.
``Juan wasn't radioing in saying how easy it was. Lazier was tough,
and both the Foyt drivers were coming hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Montoya will return to defend his title is uncertain,
because he may be heading to Formula One next year. His victory
makes him a hero to all the CART supporters, but he doesn't look at
it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't here waving the CART flag,'' Montoya said. ``We
approached this like we were just another IRL team, and I didn't
put myself above any driver.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
