<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-HN     05-29 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PORTLAND, Ore. _ Shaquille O'Neal kept grinning as if he knew
something, some secret that would be revealed to defeat all the
grand efforts with which the Portland Trail Blazers would delude
themselves again.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cheshire Shaq smiled conspicuously when the Trail Blazers
made another early stand. He almost giggled to himself when he flew
past Brian Grant on a spin move so swift it would defy the laws of
physics. He smirked as they sent him to the free-throw line,
intentionally and in desperation, expecting him to let them back
into the game and the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal had begun his Sunday with a laugh, and for all the
Trail Blazers would try to save their season now at the brink, he
never could find reason to worry again.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson might be the Los Angeles Lakers' $6 million
coaching savior. But O'Neal's 3-year-old daughter Taahirah had said
just the right thing, offering just the right touch of coaching
genius to send the Lakers to a 103-91 win and a 3-1 lead in the
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 3 years old and really doesn't know the game,'' said
O'Neal, by then beaming. ``I said, `Daddy loves you.' She said,
`Good luck, and bend your knees.'''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his daughter's sage advice, O'Neal still showed the
shooting form of a telephone pole. But if the Trail Blazers' fate
had not been clear already, he sealed it.
</P>
<P>
   Superman juggled Kryptonite. O'Neal made nine of nine free
throws. Portland didn't stand a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the answer right there,'' Portland coach Mike Dunleavy
said in reference to defeating the hack-a-Shaq strategy the Blazers
had employed. ``It's not the league making new rules. It's not
anything else. That's the answer _ you make free throws, and it
makes it tough for the other teams to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with 25 points to lead the Lakers. But holding
him to 25 and Kobe Bryant to 5-of-15 shooting and 18 points could
have been considered a triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, O'Neal's perfection at the line only summed up
the Lakers' growing invulnerability and the Trail Blazers'
continued ability to find ways to lose at home, where they have
dropped four consecutive Western Conference finals games.
</P>
<P>
   After wasting a 15-2 start Friday, the Trail Blazers led by as
many as 11 on Sunday. The Lakers were shooting horribly _ 14-of-38
(36.8 percent) in the first half. Bryant never would find his
touch.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers finally had seemed to figure out that the
Lakers had no answer for Rasheed Wallace, who had been making
nearly 60 percent of his shots and would lead both teams with 34
points and 13 rebounds Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers seemed unimpressive and unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We relaxed at halftime,'' Bryant said. ``We talked about what
happened and then came out and executed and put it on them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all it took. The Lakers got their offense going by
rediscovering Glen Rice. They needed only a quick 9-1 run to take
their first lead. Within a few minutes, the Trail Blazers would
crack.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, averaging 12.9 points per game in the postseason and 9.7
points in the series' first three games, began the second half with
a three-point play. He would make four of six shots for 12 of his
21 points in the third quarter. When he nailed a trey midway
through the period, the Lakers led by six and were pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put Steve Smith on him, and we thought we could run him
off some picks and give us some different options,'' Jackson said.
``He's suffered a little bit the last few games, not getting enough
shots for a shooter like he is; we knew we had to get him shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glen got us going, and we rode a little bit of a hot hand and
it got everybody going.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers quickly shriveled. While the Lakers made 70
percent of their shots in the third quarter, the Blazers made just
29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers ended the quarter with O'Neal's spin around
Grant and an easy flight down the lane by Derek Fisher, they led
76-66.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers still held their hack-a-Shaq trump card, and
with the Lakers still leading by 10 midway through the fourth
quarter, Dunleavy played it.
</P>
<P>
   In 42 minutes, O'Neal had taken only three free throws. But in
the next 101 seconds, he would make six straight. Rice would add
another jumper, and the Lakers would join O'Neal's giddy
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was loose the whole game,'' O'Neal said. ``I played a pretty
good first quarter and a pretty good first half. I was loose. I was
real loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one fell. The second one fell. I just got into a
rhythm. I felt like Pete Maravich.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can develop some consistency, I can become a great player
in this league someday.''
</P>
<P>
   If he and the Lakers do earn the right to claim greatness in the
next few weeks, Sunday's game could prove the most important step,
an occasion they knew could be worth remembering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take him out (with three minutes left) so he could
keep that stat sheet,'' Jackson said. ``I told him, `Put that one
on the wall, frame that one.' The defensive strategy to foul Shaq
really backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Lakers had built a lead as insurmountable as 3-1 in
a series heading back to Los Angeles now seems.
</P>
<P>
   But the win might have been decided even earlier _ at roughly
the moment O'Neal hung up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
