<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     05-29 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros turned back the clock to a familiar brand of baseball
during Sunday's 4-3 victory over the Atlanta Braves.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the retractable roof closed for a second straight day,
Enron Field felt like the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, it sure looked a lot like Dome Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers Chris Holt and Kevin Millwood kept the score
low and close. Closer Billy Wagner pitched the ninth for the save.
And for one of the few times this season, the Astros staged a
late-inning come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   Things went so right Sunday, the newest Astro came away with the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a long time coming,'' manager Larry Dierker said
after the Astros completed a 4-2 homestand. ``A lot of things came
together the last couple of innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the ninth, when Wagner recorded the final three
outs for his first save since May 4 at Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were running out and hugging me like it was your first
victory,'' said Wagner, who had blown five consecutive save
opportunities and six of 10 for the season before Sunday. ``They
were happy for me and happy that we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Millwood held the Astros to one run and three hits through seven
innings and 103 pitches before taking himself out of the game
because of fatigue. The Astros rallied for three runs off Braves
reliever Rudy Seanez (2-3) in the eighth inning on home runs by
Lance Berkman and Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman hit a solo shot into the Crawford Boxes in left with one
out, and after Jeff Bagwell walked, Caminiti hit his 13th home run
of the season _ a towering two-run shot _ into the right-field
upper deck for a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti was 2-for-4 with three RBIs to raise his batting
average to .325. Berkman had two hits, including a double that
eventually led to the Astros' other run in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Before their eighth-inning rally, the Astros were 0-21 when
trailing after seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves threatened in the top of the ninth when pinch hitter
Rafael Furcal walked to lead off the inning. After Wagner struck
out pinch hitter Trenidad Hubbard, Quilvio Veras flied out to the
right-field warning track. Andruw Jones then hit a grounder to
third base that was bobbled by Caminiti _ it was ruled a hit _
putting two runners on base before Wagner coaxed Chipper Jones into
a popout in foul territory for his fifth save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just worked out right,'' Caminiti said of the tense ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Valdes (1-0), who had arrived in town 18 hours earlier
after being acquired Saturday from Tampa Bay, made his first
major-league appearance since 1998 and pitched a scoreless eighth
for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's immediately part of the family,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who had his fourth solid start in a row, allowed a pair of
home runs but was otherwise effective. Veras singled to lead off
the game, and Andruw Jones followed with his 14th home run, a blast
to left field. Javy Lopez added a solo homer off Holt in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed three runs and six hits in six innings while tying
a career high with eight strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got some big strikeouts and ground balls to get out of
trouble,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a ton of chances to get a ton of runs and just couldn't
get the big hit,'' said Braves manager Bobby Cox, whose team
stranded nine runners.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood, who was burned for six runs in three innings in his
last start at Milwaukee, was in typical form against the Astros. He
allowed only one hit after the first inning and matched his season
high with seven strikeouts before exiting with a 3-1 lead in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't dead tired, but I was close,'' said Millwood, who
pitched a one-hitter against the Astros last season in Game 2 of
the National League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   After winning back-to-back home series for the first time this
season, the Astros don't get long to celebrate. They begin a
three-game road trip at Colorado today against Pedro Astacio, who
beat them with a three-hitter earlier this season at Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get to lay back and enjoy this one very long,''
Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
