<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8471 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-29 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESA MAKES A MESS OF THINGS IN 14-4 LOSS TO DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ For reliever Jose Mesa, the day before
Memorial Day was anything but memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa's series of May showers continued to rain on the Mariners'
parade when he gave up a leadoff homer to Tampa Bay's Mike DiFelice
in the bottom of the eighth inning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   DiFelice's first homer of the year snapped a 3-all tie and
started a horrific 11-run Devil Rays rally that allowed the Rays to
win, 14-4, salvaging one game of the three-game series while ending
the Mariners' chances of gaining a split on the six-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa was charged with nine of the 11 runs. Things came unraveled
so quickly and so convincingly for Mesa that M's manager Lou
Piniella stuck with him rather than use up an overworked bullpen,
although that decision ultimately was taken out of Piniella's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa declined to talk about his outing, which, considering his
month, likely was prudent. But pitching coach Bryan Price, who
takes Mesa's slide almost as personally as does the pitcher, said
the problem ``is not Jose Mesa's stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that hitters are seeing too much of the ball,''
Price said, suggesting that Mesa needs to mask his delivery better
and that pitcher and pitching coach would work on that starting
Monday, when the team returns to Seattle to start a nine-game,
10-day homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jose makes better pitches, then there's no way he's going
to get hit like that,'' Price said. ``I've got to make make sure he
presents the ball better than he has been. He needs some variance
in how he gets the ball to the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa needs something. Price's variance theory might hold some
weight. Maybe just turning the page on the calendar would do it.
Mesa's May has been ignominious, and on the Mariners'
just-completed 2-4 road trip, Mesa twice was the losing pitcher in
the opponents' last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   A 33-save closer for Seattle in 1999, his 2000 season has seen
him lose his closer's job and put his situation in the bullpen in
peril. His May has been brutal _ 15 earned runs in 111/3 innings, a
1-3 record and an 11.91 ERA. Even without the mish-mash Sunday, May
had been anything but merry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose's struggles today were obvious,'' Piniella said. ``They
hit him good. Some of the hits were of the seeing-eye variety, but
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's voice trailed off at that point, the point being
that, starting with DiFelice's homer, many of the hits were
rockets. Certainly that was the case last Tuesday, when Cal Ripken
Jr.'s ninth-inning homer beat Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa didn't come out of the game until he walked DiFelice as the
inning's 10th batter. Ball four was an inside pitch that umpire
Dana DeMuth didn't like and he ejected Mesa. Piniella didn't see
much that he liked, either, but he argued against the ejection
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It set up backup outfielder/infielder John Mabry to become just
the second position player ever to pitch for the Mariners. Mabry
allowed two runs but got the two outs needed to finish the inning,
the highest-scoring inning in Tampa Bay history.
</P>
<P>
   ``John made a good decision,'' Price said. ``He didn't try to
pitch. He just threw the ball up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa has been pressing so hard that he appears to be doing the
same. But don't look for a change in Mesa's role anytime soon. The
Mariners are racking up big numbers of innings for the bullpen
lately, and closer Kazuhiro Sasaki hasn't been terrific, either.
Mesa remains one of the few members of the staff with experience as
a closer. Piniella and Price can't afford to lose him if he's got
anything resembling his 1999 stuff left.
</P>
<P>
   But the story wasn't all about Mesa. The Mariners only got five
hits, and that's no formula for victory. Mike Cameron homered in
the first and Edgar Martinez homered in the ninth. In between,
Seattle's offense was a wasteland worthy of T.S. Elliott _ just
three singles.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that Seattle was in a 3-3 tie entering the eighth
inning said more about the weakness of the Tampa Bay defense than
anything else. And, oh yes ... the Mariners showed they can run a
little.
</P>
<P>
   Down 3-1 in the fifth, the Mariners turned their legs loose.
With two outs and no one on, Rickey Henderson hit a grounder deep
in the hole between shortstop and third base. Second-year infielder
Felix Martinez made a terrific sliding stop, then made a powerful
throw without having untangled his legs. But he couldn't get the
flying Henderson, who then stole second and scored when Cameron
rifled a single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron never stopped running when Gerald Williams tried to get
Henderson at the plate. The throw skipped past the plate, and when
starting pitcher Albie Lopez didn't back up, Cameron raced to
third. Moments later, he tied the score at 3-all on Lopez's wild
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle would not get another hit until Martinez's homer in the
ninth, by which time it would have taken a couple of six-packs of
solo homers to impact the final score.
</P>
<P>
   So now the Mariners come home for Memorial Day. Recreationally,
Memorial Day weekend means racing at the Brickyard, time for the
start of the picnic season and time to get the boat ready for the
water.
</P>
<P>
   It's also time to get serious about baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Memorial Day signals the start of summer baseball,''
Piniella said. ``The weather starts to heat up in earnest. In a lot
of ways, this is the real start to the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long days of summer are directly ahead of you. You've got
two months of baseball behind you. Now the play intensifies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are clinging to the lead in the West. That should
provide an extra speck of intensity in Seattle, which was in third
place at this time a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   First place, at least, is memorable.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
