<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8472 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-HNS &LR;      05-29 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ For the New York Knicks, Sunday was a bad-news,
good-news day.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news was that Latrell Sprewell arrived at Sunday's
practice with a broken bone in his left foot, causing Knicks coach
Jeff Van Gundy to wonder whether his star guard would be able to
play today against the Indiana Pacers in Game 4 of the Eastern
Conference finals at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The good news was that center Patrick Ewing, who missed
Saturday's Game 3 win over the Pacers with acute tendinitis in his
right foot, and forward Marcus Camby, who played just five minutes
Saturday before spraining his right knee, might be ready to play
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Or is getting Ewing back bad news?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to figure.
</P>
<P>
   The question is legitimate, especially considering the way the
Knicks handled the Pacers on Saturday, taking a 98-95 win to pull
to within 2-1 in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because Saturday's victory came in their first game without
Ewing, but it was the Knicks' highest-scoring playoff game of the
season and also their best-shooting game (39-of-74, 52.7 percent).
And over the last two seasons, the Knicks are 1-3 with Ewing vs.
the Pacers in the conference finals, but 4-1 without him.
</P>
<P>
   So, are they better without Ewing?
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Bill Walton, now an analyst for NBC Sports, thinks
Ewing's absence creates more space for guys such as Sprewell (32
points in Game 3) and Allan Houston (28 points) to create shots for
themselves and their teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a perfectly put-together team, because you have
explosive guys in Sprewell and Houston who are so mobile and so
fresh with their games, but then you have the older guys like Ewing
and Larry Johnson, who are more methodical, so it's not a perfect
team by any stretch of the imagination,'' Walton said. ``What
happens when Ewing goes out is that Sprewell and Houston are
allowed to play their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite player as a kid was Bill Russell, and he's still
my favorite player of all time. What I loved about Russell is that
he did what the other guys couldn't do, and he played his game to
make the other players better. That should be Patrick's role.
What's to keep Patrick Ewing from being a defensive force, a
shot-blocker, a screener, a guy who helps set other guys up and who
allows the guys who can score to score?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   The New York players and Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy are
understandably hesitant to admit as much, but without Ewing
clogging the middle, demanding the ball on almost every possession,
the offense runs much smoother.
</P>
<P>
   And with that wide-open lane, penetrators such as Sprewell and
Charlie Ward, as well as a post-up type like Johnson, are suddenly
free to do their thing. And Houston is allowed to do more than
simply spot up and launch outside jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   That much was evident Saturday, when Sprewell's 32 points
equaled his output in the first two games combined, and Houston's
28 was not too far removed from his two-game total (33 points).
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing with Patrick out, Allan and myself and L.J. are
going to get more touches,'' Sprewell said. ``That's the bottom
line. When Patrick's in, he has to make sure he gets his touches.
But with him out, Jeff's going to put the ball in our hands a
little more. We have more opportunities to do things.''
</P>
<P>
   And they might have those same opportunities today.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell can play, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell said he injured his foot while chasing down a loose
ball in the closing seconds Saturday, but he expects to go even
though a post-practice MRI revealed what is being called an
incomplete fracture of the fifth metatarsal (the bone behind the
little toe) in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who injured the foot diving for a loose ball with 30
seconds left, was held out of practice Sunday along with Ewing,
Camby and Johnson (sore back).
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm going to play, no matter what,'' Sprewell said. ``I
don't feel like I'm in that (injury) equation. My mind says that
I'm fine and I'm going to be there. Patrick, we just don't know
about. Marcus, at this point I'm not sure if he can go. But I'll be
there. I'm going to play, regardless of what the MRI says.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who missed 17 games during the regular season with a
microscopic tear of his right anterior cruciate ligament, is taking
a cautious approach after injuring his knee with 8:49 to play in
the first half Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, it's really up in the air right now,'' Camby
said of his availability for today's game. ``But we're going to
keep treating it all day and see how it is (today) before the game.
It'll be a game-time decision.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be the same for Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   But is that what's best for the Knicks?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
