<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-HNS &LR;      05-29 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Early in the cycling segment of the U.S. men's Olympic
triathlon trials, Ryan Bolton started to wonder about his chances
of making the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   He had started the race with a poor swim, finishing 18th among
the 21 competitors, and had wound up in the third group of
cyclists. While he knew he was among the best runners in the field
and could make up ground in the last element of the race, the
10-kilometer run, he wondered if he had dug himself in too deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not nervous, but a little distressed,'' is how he described
his thinking at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton found out what he was made of Sunday, picking his way
into the second group of cyclists and ultimately passing Doug
Friman on the third and final lap of the run to secure the final
spot on the three-man team that will represent the United States at
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd have to work,'' said Bolton, a former track and
cross country athlete at the University of Wyoming. ``I knew I'd
have to put together something special. But I ran smart, stayed
within myself, and it worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's winner was Hunter Kemper, who had already secured an
Olympic berth. He finished 20 seconds ahead of Australian Chris
Hill, one of eight foreign competitors in the field. Gilberto
Gonzalez of Venezuela was third.
</P>
<P>
   Americans Nick Radkewich and Bolton finished fourth and fifth,
respectively, to earn the two available spots on the U.S. Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   Sending the trio of Kemper, Radkewich and Bolton to the Olympics
means the United States will have its top three among the multitude
diving into Sydney Harbor when the men's triathlon goes off on the
second day of the Games. Kemper is ranked 33rd in the world;
Radkewich is 55th and Bolton 63rd.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best team you could have picked,'' said
Radkewich, a product of the ``IronKids'' triathlon series who
competed in track and cross country at Notre Dame. ``No matter how
things go in Sydney, I think we'll have somebody in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Australians will be favored to win the first
triathlon medals awarded in Olympic competition, it is Bolton's
view that at least some of the focus in Sydney will be on how the
Americans perform in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see Americans as tough, as being Olympic performers,''
he said. ``So we do shoulder a bit of responsibility. People will
be looking at us more than some of the athletes from other
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Sunday's competition proved that Kemper and
crew can handle the killer fatigue that comes with swimming 1.5
kilometers, cycling 40 kilometers and running 10 kilometers on a
hot, muggy North Texas morning in late spring. Unlike their female
counterparts, the men never had the benefit of cloud cover as they
competed on the course put together in the Las Colinas business and
residential development.
</P>
<P>
   As the race unfolded, it appeared to be yielding an amazing
story in the effort of Friman.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked 124th in the world, he had barely made the field, which
was limited to those rated 125th or better. But he was the leader
after the swim and gained a spot in a group of five cyclists that
took the lead in that portion of the race. In addition to Friman,
the group included Kemper, Radkewich and two Australians, Hill and
Levi Maxwell _ meaning Friman and Radkewich would get spots on the
U.S. team if they hung in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much had the team made up right there,'' Kemper
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lead pack entered the transition to the 10K run with a gap
of 2 minutes, 15 seconds between it and a second group that
included Bolton and a dozen others. The run quickly shook things
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You set out on the run,'' Kemper said, ``and it's every man
for himself _ those hills and that heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolton was only a minute behind Friman after the first of the
three laps in the 10K and went by him at the start of lap No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Friman wound up finishing eighth and collapsed into the arms of
two race officials as he crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
