<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AT the moment of their birth four springs ago, the Comets had no
special cachet, no rep to live up to. Their marquee player, the
only one who possessed any kind of name recognition in Houston,
Sheryl Swoopes, wasn't even on the floor because she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper? You had to be a seriously hard-core women's
hoops geek to have the slightest memory of her exploits at USC more
than a decade earlier. Van Chancellor? Same story. He might have
been an institution at Ole Miss, where he spent 19 seasons, but he
had landed the Comets head coach's job only because others had
turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   Van's world had been the distaff SEC. The same as the rest of
us, Chancellor had no idea what to expect from his team or the
league. When the Comets made their debut in Cleveland before a
large and loud crowd, his jaw dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you as amazed as I am that we're drawing 12,000 here
tonight?'' he asked a reporter. ``And that we're expecting 12,000
back in Houston on Tuesday? Never in my wildest dreams did I see
this happening.''
</P>
<P>
   His amazement, of course, has only grown, what with the Comets
embarking on their fourth season today gunning for a fourth WNBA
title. Forget the '90s Chicago Bulls. The long-reigning champions _
and Chancellors _ of U.S. women's basketball are trying to venture
into th rarefied air the '60s Boston Celtics breathed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls won six NBA titles in eight seasons but failed to
string four of them together because of Michael Jordan's baseball
sabbatical. The Comets are well-positioned to go 4-for-4, though,
because their three-pronged nucleus of stars is intact and the
supporting cast might be deeper than ever.
</P>
<P>
   They rolled, and I do mean rolled, through the preseason despite
missing the services of Janeth Arcain, incumbent center Polina
Tzekova and top draft choice Elena Chakirova. With Arcain having
returned from Brazil, where she's a crucial cog for the national
team, and the talented Russian Chakirova also in camp as of
Saturday, many are conceding another title to the Comets, Polina or
no Polina.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely good for us, possibly bad for the WNBA. But,
honestly, probably not. We Houstonians need the Comets to keep this
dynasty thing going. Their parent company, the Rockets, missed the
playoffs for the first time in eight seasons, the Astros appear
headed for a free-fall return to the also-ran realm, and our
re-entry into the NFL is two seasons away. The Comets are no longer
mere time-killers and space-fillers. Why, they practically hold our
civic self-worth in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   They are a significant piece of the new downtown arena equation
as well. If the Rockets leave, remember, they go, too. And their
many rabid fans, exceedingly pleased with the cost of their tickets
relative to their team's winning percentage, wouldn't be pleased.
Community support for the Comets is broad-based enough to have a
modicum of influence on the negotiations between the Rockets and
the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   But league-wide, a groundswell of anti-Comets sentiment
increases with each Houston title. The attitude seems to be:
``Enough is enough. Let's spread the wealth around.'' Of course,
were the New York Liberty or the Los Angeles Sparks thrice charmed
instead, everybody in the NBA's marketing department _ and that's
all the WNBA was intended to be, a tactical marketing arm of the
NBA _ would be delighted.
</P>
<P>
   But as you can imagine, a surfeit of happiness in Houston makes
the suits in Manhattan nervous. Never mind how the Comets'
credibility as a bona fide superpower enhances the WNBA's
legitimacy, exactly as the Celtics, the Lakers and the Bulls did
for the NBA's.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets have established a standard of achievement where none
existed. That's their ongoing legacy.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crucial season for the WNBA because of its far broader
geographical reach _ from Seattle to Miami _ and because of the
NBA's current struggles with its image and appeal. The women's
league was born simultaneously with the men's game reaching a
pinnacle of popularity and prosperity, when Jordan's Bulls were in
championship form. Now, those giddy days are over, dragged down by
sluggish, thuggish behavior in tandem with high prices.
</P>
<P>
   Should the ladies manage to remain ascendant, and the WNBA has
considerable room for growing its fan base while polishing the
quality of the basketball, the WNBA will have weaned itself from
the NBA. No longer will the men be expected to nurse the women.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened in Houston, where the Comets are what the
Rockets aspire to be.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
