<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WE finally saw the blueprint to Astros success Sunday afternoon,
and it had nothing to do with a short porch in left, a flagpole in
play, a train steaming overhead, nooks and crannies all along the
outfield wall, or a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   Build it, and sure, they will come. They'll even pay $5.25 for a
beer.
</P>
<P>
   But follow the same old blueprint that has won three division
championships, and they go home happy.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that has looked to find its way since opening day, it
was a priceless day.
</P>
<P>
   There was strong starting pitching going deep into the game.
There were the Astros finding a way to stay close. There were
anonymous relievers doing their jobs _ a perfect inning from Joe
Slusarski in the seventh, another scoreless frame from Marc Valdes
in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Astros finding a way to scratch out a chance in
their last at-bat _ a Lance Berkman homer in the bottom of the
eighth, a Jeff Bagwell walk, a two-run shot from Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the stopper, Billy Wagner, stopping the best
team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't brain surgery Sunday afternoon at Enron Field. It was
the Astros playing the kind of ball that carried them to so many
similar wins over the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It was just baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astro baseball,'' as Wagner called it. ``Just play.''
</P>
<P>
   And as much as this entire successful homestand could be circled
as pivotal in the Astros' hopes for a turnaround, this one game
should be underlined, highlighted and printed in boldface.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude around here has been, `Oh, what's going to happen
to us today?''' Caminiti said. ``You could just feel it in the
clubhouse. But lately, we've been thinking, `What are we going to
do today to win?' It's been awhile. We had been doing a lot of
little things to lose. Today, we did the little things to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the opponent, no game might mean more than this one
if indeed a turnaround comes. And no player might have gotten more
out of Sunday's classic Astros effort than Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday night's opener against the Braves, Wagner's fastball
was clocked at 95-96 mph. On Sunday against the last two batters he
faced, it was clocked at 98-99 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think a mere 2 miles per hour on the gun was the
difference, you're wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gun doesn't mean anything,'' Wagner said. ``It's the
hitters that always let you know when you've got it.''
</P>
<P>
   The befuddled Braves batters clearly let the sellout crowd, the
Astros and most significantly Wagner know that on this day he was
at his best.
</P>
<P>
   After walking the first batter he faced, Wagner struck out pinch
hitter Trenidad Hubbard for the first out in the ninth, getting
Hubbard to swing wildly at a 98-mph fastball out of the strike
zone. Quilvio Veras then swung at a 99-mph fastball and flied out
to Berkman in right field. And after Andrew Jones dribbled an
infield hit to third, Chipper Jones popped out on a 3-0 fastball
that also was out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Billy can do,'' Bagwell said. ``He can make you
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike recent outings when he blew five save opportunities, on
Sunday Wagner's fastball wasn't coming in at 97 and going out at,
what, 120? Instead of trying every mechanical trick in the book to
no avail, this time he simply threw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to break his slump, Wagner had watched videotape, fiddled
with his release point, tried a two-seam fastball instead of his
usual four-seamer, and adjusted the landing point of his lead foot.
He spent hours dissecting mechanics with manager Larry Dierker and
pitching coach Vern Ruhle.
</P>
<P>
   But this time he got back to baseball. Just baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dierk told me, `See if you can throw your arm out of place,'''
Wagner said. ``He told me, `This team needs you. Just go up there
and throw it,' so I did that no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Wagner's first save since May 4 and possibly his best
effort of the year. It looked like the same old Wagner, and _ shock
of shocks _ it looked like the same old Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things came together,'' Dierker said. ``It was more
typical of the kind of game we'd play with the Braves when we were
in good form.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wagner clinched the save on the easy Jones pop-up, he
showed the kind of emotion rarely let out from this cool closer. He
shook his fist in the air, pointed at the boisterous crowd, gave
catcher Mitch Meluskey a hug, bumped chests with Caminiti and
darted into the clubhouse for more congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting it done today it almost feels like your first win,''
Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that has searched futilely for two months for this
kind of classic Astros effort, in many ways it was just that.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
