<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-29 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PORTLAND, Ore. _ He has that collection of gaudy championship rings
from his time with the Chicago Bulls. Less flashy but even more
valuable is all of the experience it took to earn them.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how to fight the battles, survive the skirmishes and
win the long wars. He understands it is as much about wits and
guile as ego and talent, which is what makes him such a precious
commodity at this late time of the season.
</P>
<P>
   This is why they so desperately wanted him to be a part of their
team, for games like this, for situations like this. To help them,
to guide them, to lift them, to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   While the Trail Blazers spent the weekend again looking like
fragile hothouse flowers in the Rose Garden and Scottie Pippen was
resuming his role as a shrinking violet, it was another former
member of Michael Jordan's supporting cast who was inching closer
to one more NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper stabbed the game-winning jumper in Game 3 on Friday
night and then came back Sunday to twist the knife in the Lakers'
103-91 victory.
</P>
<P>
   On the scale of improbable occurrences in the Western Conference
finals, you likely would say Shaquille O'Neal going a perfect
9-for-9 on free throws would be the equivalent of seeing pigs fly.
</P>
<P>
   But in a period of less than 48 hours when the Lakers
rediscovered their confidence and strut, the odds that it would not
be Shaq or the young phenom Kobe Bryant who saved their bacon was
off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   So Harper follows his late-game heroics with a season-high 18
points to go with seven rebounds and two assists, and now the
Blazers are teetering on a 3-1 brink in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel good about the fact that we have to live with Ron
Harper beating us with his shots,'' Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Or die with him.
</P>
<P>
   That's the difference between the pair of former Bulls. Pippen
makes pronouncements, and Harper makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the phony-baloney hype that surrounds LA coach Phil
Jackson and his image as the resident mystic of the NBA, there is
no doubt he knows what makes his former Chicago players tick.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Jackson said before the series that it was going to
be up to Pippen to carry the Blazers forward, to lead them in the
series. Jackson has been there before to see what shouldering the
lion's share of the burden has done to Pippen. He was there for the
migraine in Game 7 of the playoffs against Detroit. He was there
for the final 1.8 seconds against the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   When the situation heats up, Pippen melts like butter in a
microwave, which was the burnt smell that filled the arena Sunday
after Scottie scored just two points in the third quarter and none
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie is a good friend of mine, and he tries real hard,''
Harper said. ``So I'm not going to try to get inside his head, just
play my own game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a kind of defensive chess match, watching, studying and
waiting for his opponent to move and then taking advantage of the
opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really any kind of big secret,'' Harper said. ``You
go where there's nobody around.''
</P>
<P>
   When defenders are concentrating on big weapons such as Shaq and
Kobe, that's plenty of places, which leaves a lot of open shots.
</P>
<P>
   But Harper is about more than shots. He's about sliding inside
for big rebounds. He's about making the smart pass, finding the
right lane to step in and make a critical steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just one smart basketball player,'' said Lakers assistant
coach Frank Hamblen.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why one of Jackson's first moves after signing on as
the Lakers' $6 million savior was to pick up the phone and call the
36-year-old Harper, who had been thinking about calling it a
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``P.J. said, `Get yourself off the couch, and start getting into
basketball shape,''' Harper said. ``I told him I wasn't really sure
that I wanted to play anymore. I wasn't sure that I was done, but I
really needed the right situation. All P.J. said then was, `Harp, I
need you.' And yeah, this is the right situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He gets to play about 25 minutes a game and make the big baskets
when they come his direction. But he also gets to nurture and teach
Shaq and Kobe and all the rest of the Lakers who have the potential
to go so far but need a road map at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them when to pick their heads up, if they're down,''
Harper said. ``I tell them not to get too carried away when it's
going good. I'm like Phil out on the floor, and, hey, they
listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they see. Where he's been. What he can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have faith in me,'' Ron Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what being a leader is all about.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
