<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEILE HOME TO RAISE MONEY FOR WORTHY CAUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About this time last year, Julianne McNamara
noticed her 1-year-old daughter Hannah drinking cup after cup of
water as she scooted through the house. But never did it seem to
quench her excessive thirst.
</P>
<P>
   It's just because she runs around a lot and it's just another
hot summer in the Valley, friends tried to tell Julianne. But she
wasn't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, when her husband Todd Zeile had a few days off
for baseball's All-Star break, they took Hannah to see a doctor.
Turned out, she had a high blood-sugar count.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The next two days, as Hannah was admitted to the Children's
Diabetes Center at UCLA, the couple learned all they could about
the disease, which affects more than a million Americans and is one
of the most costly and chronic diseases of childhood. Treatment is
lifelong.
</P>
<P>
   When Todd went back to play for the Texas Rangers, the family,
along with 5-year-old son Garrett, followed him this time so both
parents could monitor Hannah's progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of maintenance,'' Zeile, the former Dodger and
current New York Mets first baseman admitted the other day after a
game in St. Louis, where he again was on the road, in a hotel room,
wondering about his daughter's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gets two insulin shots a day, plus as many as six tests.
We're lucky she's a really good eater because they need a
regimented diet. But there can be so many factors that affect her
sugar count aside from food - even things like altitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a constant worry. And she's at an age where she
can't tell us how she feels. There were plenty of times we'd do
tests and she'd be fine during the day, then we'd test her at 2
a.m. and find it to be abnormal, so all of the sudden we can't
sleep that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Zeile says Hannah today is an otherwise typical
terrible 2-year-old, ``very willful, a real tiger, with a brother
who's a real instigator.''
</P>
<P>
   He also calls her ``a tough little trooper.''
</P>
<P>
   Hannah's inspiration, and the work of the Children's Diabetes
Center at UCLA, was more than enough to get Zeile to pull a few
strings with the Dodgers today to help raise some money for the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't been with the team for a couple of seasons now, but
the former Hart High and UCLA star didn't feel awkward asking the
Dodgers if the foundation could buy a block of reserve-level
tickets for tonight's game - against his Mets - and resell them
through the UCLA central ticket office for $25, with $10 of it tax
deductible.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,000 tickets were bought; most have already been sold,
but some are still available for order - at (310) 825-2101 or
www.cto.ucla.edu - and can be picked up before the game at will
call.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also sold out 400 VIP packages ranging from
$1,000 to $2,500 that include luxury suite seats, special pregame
privileges and admission to a postgame reception and silent
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it helped that Dodgers second baseman Mark Grudzielanek
went to bat for Zeile on the fund-raising effort. But Grudzielanek
has something at stake, too. His brother Tim was diagnosed with
diabetes at age 7 and continues to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Dodgers) were great from the word 'go,' '' said Zeile of
setting up the charity event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great relationship with him since his playing days
here,'' said Derrick Hall, the Dodgers' director of communications.
``In our opinion, he'll always be part of the Dodger family.
Anything we could do to help, we feel honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact he and Mark are teaming up shows the sincerity and
passion they have for their cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile says there's a good chance this event could raise more
than $300,000 for the center, headed by Dr. Kevin Kaiserman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely thankful to Todd and Mark,'' said Dr.
Kaiserman. ``Their selfless dedication in helping to fight this
devastating disease serves as an inspiration and example to us
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
