<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHACON-LOPEZ SHOWDOWN SHOOK L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One reason the boxing community is so excited
about the June 17 bout between Oscar De La Hoya and Shane Mosley at
Staples Center is that the city has been starving for a truly big
fight.
</P>
<P>
   How long has the hunger lasted? Try 26 years this month.
</P>
<P>
   It was in May 1974 that rising prospects Bobby Chacon of Pacoima
and Danny ``Little Red'' Lopez of Alhambra thrilled a packed Sports
Arena crowd in perhaps the biggest fight in Los Angeles until now.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya-Mosley will dwarf Chacon-Lopez in terms of the money
it will generate and the ungodly sums the fighters will earn.
</P>
<P>
   However, the earlier fight, which took place during a time when
boxing still rivaled the major sports in the mainstream, created a
stir that not even the popular De La Hoya could hope to eclipse.
</P>
<P>
   Chacon, 22 at the time, had been beaten only by the great Ruben
Olivares in 24 fights, while the big-punching Lopez, 21, was
unbeaten and had knocked out all but one of his 23 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They, like De La Hoya and Mosley, were produced in the L.A.
area. Chacon was reared in the Valley while Lopez moved to town
from Utah as a young amateur and was based here throughout his
career.
</P>
<P>
   And they both were weaned in regular shows here, not in Las
Vegas or at various casinos as most of the big-name fighters are
today.
</P>
<P>
   They graduated from four-rounders to championship bouts before
the appreciative eyes of local boxing fans and their legends grew
with each convincing victory. They were stars even before they
became champions.[p The fans couldn't wait to see them rumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I remember most is the demand that the fight be
made,'' the matchmaker of the bout, Don Chargin, said after the
Golden State Boxer's Association honored Chacon and Lopez at a
luncheon last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember (promoter) Aileen Eaton calling me into her office
and saying, `I know you don't want to make this fight now (because
it's too early in their careers). We !ital!have!off! to make it.
The public is demanding it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both really celebrities in town.''
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the bout wasn't lost on the fighters or their
camps.
</P>
<P>
   The day Lopez's manager, Howie Steindler, signed for the fight
in Chargin's office and then realized what he'd one, he fainted.
</P>
<P>
   He had reason to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   Chacon was the favorite of the 16,080 that crammed into the
Sports Arena and the thousands of spill-over fans who watched on
closed circuit at the Olympic Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't disappoint them. Chacon, who later became a
slugger, gave Lopez a boxing lesson before finally taking him out
in the ninth round with a series of big rights.
</P>
<P>
   Referee John Thomas stopped it with Lopez leaning helplessly
against the ropes and Chacon firing away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sparred with Danny all the time (in the years) before the
fight,'' said Chacon, who survives on a small disability pension
because of punch- induced dementia but is able to work with kids in
a downtown gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``And day in and day out he'd whup me. Then one day his manager,
Howie Steindler, said, `no more sparring with Chacon because he
knew we would fight one day.'
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time I fought him, I was a lot better. It wasn't like
the gym.'' Lopez, now in construction and living in Chino Hills,
would agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I just couldn't hit the guy,'' he said. ``He always
gave me motion. He was a good boxer.''
</P>
<P>
   Chacon would go on to win the featherweight title that year, as
would Lopez a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   However, such fights as the one in 1974 became increasingly rare
in L.A. as the hub of boxing moved to Las Vegas, Atlantic City,
N.J., and other gambling-oriented towns willing to pay large fees
to stage fights.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when boxing fans here could see their
favorite, big- name boxers fighting in weekly shows around town, at
the Sports Arena, Forum, Olympic and the old Music Center in
Woodland Hills, as well as other venues.
</P>
<P>
   Again, local talent was developed locally.
</P>
<P>
   And the media - including a half-dozen major newspapers -
devoted much more time and space to boxing than they do today.
Chargin said not a day went be in the month before the Chacon-Lopez
fight without an article or radio report on it.
</P>
<P>
   It all contributed to an unforgettable fight - and era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is (De La Hoya-Mosley) different (from Chacon-Lopez)? Yes, it
is,'' said Don Fraser, Eaton's rival promoter. ``Chacon had all but
one fight locally. Lopez, I think, had every fight here. Between
them, they had 40-some local fights. De La Hoya and Mosley I don't
think have 10 local fights (actually 22 in the area).
</P>
<P>
   ``De La Hoya is big, but if Mosley walked in here, no one would
know who he is. It'll be the biggest local fight for monetary
reasons, but it's not the same as those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid watch: We might have seen the last of David Reid at 154
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Goossen, Reid's promoter, said an unusually low percentage
of body fat - 2.9 percent, according to recent tests - means the
former junior middleweight champ will have to move up to 160
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That test was done while he wasn't training,'' Goossen said.
``Imagine what it would be like if he were training.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he trains, he burns off muscle tissue, not fat, and we
want to burn off fat. He'll be 10 times stronger if he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Goossen suggested the body-fat revelation might explain why he
faded in his loss to Felix Trinidad in his last fight, which sounds
more like damage control than reality.
</P>
<P>
   It was a big punch by Trinidad that hurt Reid and changed the
course of the bout.
</P>
<P>
   However, it will be interesting to see how he performs at 160
and the impact his arrival will have on the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``He immediately makes the middleweight division something to
look at,'' Goossen said.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen said he hopes to have Reid back in the ring at 160
pounds by August.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: David Tua, deemed the biggest threat to
heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis, faces Obed Sullivan on Saturday
in Las Vegas on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a veteran heavyweight, would appear to be in over his
head but seems to understand the gravity of his situation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the prospect of turning his career around with a
surprise victory is his primary incentive, Sullivan said: ``Just
watching Tua fight, just knowing what he's capable of doing is
incentive enough. You can't play around in a fight like this, you
have to concentrate. If not, guess what? You might be looking up at
someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for that to happen Saturday. ...
</P>
<P>
   Robert Garcia of Oxnard, coming off his loss to Diego Corrales,
returns to the ring against Ben Tackie in a 10-round lightweight
bout on the Tua-Sullivan undercard.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen, Garcia's promoter, said his fighter might move down to
130 to challenge junior lightweight champ Joel Casamayor if he wins
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Garcia lost to Corrales is that he had a terrible
time making weight. He reportedly was eating only one meal a day
leading up to the fight.
</P>
<P>
   He's better off trying his luck at 135.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
