<HEADLINE>
USC WINS REGIONAL BASEBALL FINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULLERTON, Calif. _ The inaugural NCAA baseball Super Regionals
weren't too terrific for USC in 1999. In fact, they were a
downright bummer.
</P>
<P>
   The then-defending national champions were sent to Stanford and
eliminated in two games the Trojans thought they should have won.
</P>
<P>
   USC gets a second chance after defeating host Cal State
Fullerton 8-3 on Sunday in a regional final before 2,177 at Goodwin
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Trojans (41-18) travel to Georgia Tech in a
best-of-three Super Regional beginning Friday in Atlanta. The
series winner advances to the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bitterly frustrating weekend,'' Trojans coach Mike
Gillespie said of 1-0 and 5-3 losses to Stanford last year that
included a near no-hitter by Barry Zito in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were not only unhappy about playing a Pacific-10
Conference rival but also a fellow top 10-caliber team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt, not like we were cheated, but we had a really good
team and nobody on that team thought it was fair at all that we had
to lose two tough games,'' said junior shortstop Seth Davidson,
named the Fullerton regional's most outstanding player. ``That was
Omaha for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Trojans are playing now, getting to Omaha might be a
foregone conclusion even with a formidable Super Regional opponent
in Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   USC is on a 13-game winning streak, including three regional
victories over Virginia Tech, Loyola Marymount and Cal State
Fullerton by a combined score of 29-11.
</P>
<P>
   A balanced offensive attack was the most impressive part of
USC's dominance against what was considered one of the strongest of
16, four-team regionals.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-8-9 hitters in the lineup Alberto Concepcion, Abel
Martinez and Brian Barre - went 17 for 31 with 14 runs scored in
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awesome. Just think if we all hit,'' said Davidson, who
batted .714 (10 for 14) with a homer and six RBI. ``That's kind of
how it's been the past 13 games. Somebody different gets the job
done for us.''
</P>
<P>
   USC batted .427 (47 for 110) as a team despite the struggles of
top hitters Anthony Lunetta (.167), Josh Persell (.182) and Beau
Craig (.214).
</P>
<P>
   The top third of the order had the big hits against the Titans
(38-21). Davidson went 3 for 4 with two runs scored, Rob Garibaldi
2 for 4 and Justin Gemoll 3 for 4 with four RBI.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, Gillespie has options when filling out his
lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 7-8-9 slots in our lineup will be hitting 1-2-3 next
week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The effectiveness of the Trojans' offense took its toll on
Titans' starter Jon Smith (9-3), who allowed six earned runs on
eight hits in 3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive day, the Trojans fell behind 2-0, but
Montanez hit a solo homer, the first of his collegiate career, in
the third to spark a three-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   Persell, a Montclair Prep graduate who resides in Sherman Oaks,
hit a solo homer in the fourth to start another three-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fastball wasn't quite what it normally is. I just couldn't
get it by them. That's a good offensive team. I have to give them
credit,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Reyes (6-6), a freshman from Whittier, pitched five-plus
solid innings, allowing two runs on seven hits with five strikeouts
to earn the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
