<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ BESTS CLEMENS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took 179 minutes, nine innings, 255 pitches, 22
strikeouts, seven Cy Young trophies, and dozens of thrills and
chills to establish what we already knew.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is king of the hill. A-No. 1. Cream of the crop.
Top of the heap. Start spreading the news. In what can only be
described as one of the greatest regular-season games in 100 years
of American League play, Pedro Sunday &UR;  &LR; night bested five-time Cy
Brother Roger Clemens, 2-0, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In this lifetime, we are not likely to see a better early-season
matchup. Baseball is a six-month marathon of 162 games, but this
night offered a full year's worth of hardball history, tradition,
and talent. When will we ever again get Rocket and Pedro _ the once
and present aces of the Red Sox staff _ dueling in a sold-out
Yankee Stadium on Memorial Day weekend with first place hanging in
the balance? It was Ali-Frazier on God's green grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best regular-season game I've ever seen,'' said
Boston pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``It's one for the ages. Great
for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good for baseball,'' said Martinez. ``The fans came out
and clapped for both of us. I tried to give them what they want. We
were feeding off each other the whole game. (Clemens) was not going
to give you much to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time there was anything like this probably was in 1912
when Smoky Joe Wood beat Walter Johnson, 1-0, in a packed,
state-of-the-art Fenway Park (Sox ownership claimed it needed the
new park to stay competitive in the AL and Honey Fitz was a bigger
fan than Mayor Menino). It was Wood's 15th consecutive win,
bringing him within one of the Big Train's record. Carl Hubbell and
Dizzy Dean matched up regularly and there was a Juan Marichal vs.
Warren Spahn battle in the early 1960s that is still recalled.
</P>
<P>
   How good was it? It was still 0-0 after eight and Clemens was
winning on strikeouts and style points. But Trot Nixon hit a
two-out, two-run homer in the top of the ninth. Pedro loaded the
bases in the bottom of the ninth, but would not come out. He got
Tino Martinez to ground to second to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes. Pedro had the flu. That must be why he walked one guy
while striking out nine and lowering his ERA to 1.05. He also
retired 15 out of 16 before the ninth and threw 97 miles per hour
in the final frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of those games where if you wanted a sandwich,
you wanted to have somebody get it for you,'' said Sox manager Jimy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy's counterpart, Joe Torre, said, ``I think it's a game that
everyone should look back on and be glad you were here.''
</P>
<P>
   It was certainly nothing like the October '99 blowout when the
Rocket was shaving before the third inning ended. Clemens went the
distance Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, fanning 13 before Nixon rocked him in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Even the pregame warmups were intriguing. At 10 minutes to 8,
both Clemens and Pedro were in left center, long tossing. They were
almost side-by-side at one point, and Pedro looked tiny in Roger's
monstrous moonshadow.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was into it from the start. Brave Bostonians, wearing
Sox caps, cheered with gusto when Pedro was announced. Red-clad
K-Kids and Pedro's Dominican countrymen danced in the left-field
bleachers. It was nothing like the reception Clemens got in Boston
in October.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro has a New York state of mind. He loves the Dominican
flavor in the stands and the knowledge of Yankee fans. The feeling
is mutual. Like the Yankees themselves, New York fans haven't
forgotten his mastery of Sept. 10, 1999 (17 strikeouts). Seeing
Pedro back on the Yankee Stadium mound was a little like the
Beatles' second appearance on the ``Ed Sullivan Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees are a great team,'' said Pedro. ``I've only been
here three years. I wasn't here when the rivalry started. My
rivalry is against everybody. But I love watching these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And he loves pitching against them.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro gave up a scratch single to Derek Jeter in the first, but
Jeter was erased on a double play. Both pitchers faced the minimum
in the first two innings.
</P>
<P>
   By the third inning, the right-field bleacher chant was ``We
Want Beer.'' (New rules make brew a banned substance in the
bleachers.) Meanwhile, an upper deck banner reminded Bostonians,
``Roger gets his ring tomorrow _ only in New York.'' The Yankees
are holding their 1999 ring ceremony today before they play the
Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens got the Sox in order again in the third, then came a
stunner: Pedro walked Shane Spencer to open the bottom of the
inning. It was like seeing Larry Bird miss a foul shot in the final
minute of a playoff game. Pedro settled down and got the next three
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   The first man to reach scoring position was Jeter (who had three
of New York's four hits), who doubled to open the fourth. He was
stranded on second as New York's 3-4-5 hitters failed to get the
ball out of the infield. Pedro fanned Paul O'Neill, got Bernie
Williams on a popup, then struck out Jorge Posada on a hellacious
breaking pitch. The Yankee catcher almost fell down swinging and
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro's ninth was a wild ride. He hit leadoff man Chuck
Knoblauch with an 0-2 pitch, then surrendered a single to right to
the estimable Jeter. After a mound visit from Jimy (``I told him,
`Let me go after this guy' '' _ Pedro), Martinez fanned O'Neill
(swinging) then got Bernie Williams on a fly to right. He hit
Posada with a 1-2 pitch to load the bases, then got Tino Martinez
to ground out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sweated a little bit in that inning,'' Pedro said. ``I
didn't want to do what Roger did. Nixon was getting good hacks and
he made a mistake and it cost him the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan's right. It was a duel for the ages. Do not expect to
see its likes again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BO     05-29 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIXON HOMER SINKS CLEMENS, YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 77 years since its doors opened, there have
been 30 championship bouts at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous was when Joe Louis knocked out Max Schmeling in
1938, a two-fisted message to Adolf Hitler that his theory of Aryan
supremacy wasn't all it was cracked up to be.
</P>
<P>
   There was no title belt at stake Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, but this may
well be remembered as the second-best: Pedro Martinez, the
Dominican flyweight, and Roger Clemens, the Texas heavywight,
exchanging electrifying haymakers for eight scoreless innings until
Trot Nixon delivered the knockout punch, a ninth-inning, two-out,
two-run home run off Clemens that gave the Sox a 2-0 win over the
Yankees in a game that achieved instant classic status while the
sellout crowd of 55,339 was still on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   There was a message in this decision, too. It came from Nixon,
who took exception to Clemens screaming at him for daring to look
askance at a pitch in the first inning, when he was called out on
strikes, the first of Clemens' 13 K's on the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He mentioned something about that,'' said Jeff Frye, who
reached safely when Clemens couldn't handle his two-out comebacker
to the mound, giving Nixon his chance to launch his sixth home run
of the season deep into the right-field bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trot's a very intense individual. He took it personally. I
like to see that in a young guy. This was a big night for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was called out on a full count in the first, and heard
Clemens bark at him as he returned to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said something during my first at-bat,'' Nixon said. ``I
don't know what I did. I guess he yelled, `That's a strike.' I show
him a lot of respect. I give him respect. If he doesn't respect me,
that's fine. It's a war out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon struck out again in the fourth, when he returned to the
dugout and wiped out a row of paper cups with the only actual punch
thrown all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went up there for my third at-bat,'' said Nixon, who
tripled in the seventh but was left stranded when Clemens struck
out Brian Daubach and Nomar Garciaparra, ``I said to myself,
`Enough of this. I've got to attack the ball. Don't look at who's
on the mound.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who used a devastating splitter to register his most
K's since putting on pinstripes a year ago, was one out away from
finishing a 1-2-3 ninth when Frye's one-hop grounder bounced off
his glove and rolled toward third base.
</P>
<P>
   Frye, who one pitch earlier had failed to convince plate umpire
Brian Runge that he'd been hit by a pitch on his left hand, was
credited with an infield hit, only the fourth Sox hit of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as it hit his glove, it was obvious he didn't know
where the ball was,'' Nixon said. ``I knew (Scott) Brosius was
playing deep, so he had no shot at Frye.''
</P>
<P>
   Given one final shot at Clemens, Nixon connected. It was the
second home run of his career against the Rocket. And yes, he
acknowledged, for now it ranks as the biggest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he respects me or not, that's fine,'' Nixon said. ``I
have to earn my respect. It was a mistake pitch. He knows it, I
know it. It was probably a pitch he didn't want to throw there, and
I was able to put the bat on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole exchange was reminiscent of last season, when Clemens
hit rookie Wilton Veras in the back with a pitch after yelling at
Veras for taking too hard a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand that, a pitcher throwing at a hitter
because he took a big swing,'' Nixon said. ``He's an intense
player, and so am I. I guess he can yell as much as he wants.
That's fine and dandy. But that kind of fired me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens claimed to have no idea what Nixon was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I said anything to Trot,'' he said. ``I talk
to myself a lot out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens gave up five hits, did not walk a batter, and threw 127
pitches, 76 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has not allowed the Yankees a run in the last 25
innings he's pitched against them, struck out nine and allowed four
hits. He walked one and hit two in running his record to 8-2 with
his third complete game of the season. Martinez threw 128 pitches,
88 for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees pinned Martinez to the ropes in the bottom of the
ninth, when he hit Chuck Knoblauch with an 0-and-2 pitch and Derek
Jeter singled to right with no outs. Jimy Williams, playing the
Burgess Meredith role as Martinez's cornerman, strode to the mound
for a visit, but left his ace in to face the heart of the Yankee
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me what I wanted to do,'' said Martinez, who admitted
to exhaustion. ``I said, `Let me go after them.' In the ninth
inning, you want to go with the best that you have. You want to
have something left.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out Paul O'Neill on three pitches, then held his
breath as Bernie Williams launched a deep drive that died on the
warning track in right.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter stole second with Jorge Posada at the plate, but Martinez
was one strike away from victory when he hit Posada in the left
elbow with a 1-and-2 changeup, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   There was one last heart-stopping moment for the Sox when Tino
Martinez grounded to second base. Frye fielded the ball cleanly,
then double-pumped before throwing to first baseman Mike Stanley,
barely getting the out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan-o's foot slipped when he got to the bag,'' Frye said. ``I
was going to throw the ball, but I waited.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye smiled when asked how this compared with Pedro-Rocket I, a
13-1 Red Sox rout in the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This meant more to me tonight,'' he said. ``Last year, I
wasn't eligible to play. I asked a couple of teammates if that's
what it was like to be in the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
