<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     05-29 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT PHIL REALLY THINKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to a computer glitch that may be descended from the I
Love You (but only for your money)'' virus, e-mails sent Sunday
were mistakenly delivered to wrong addresses. One that fell into my
queue apparently was a message from Lakers coach Phil Jackson to a
friend in Montana. It was unsigned, of course, but it sure sounded
like Jackson, and the 'net handle was Zenmasterhoops.netz. In the
spirit of public disclosure, I chose to share it, purely for
entertainment value. Enjoy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Running Jay: I hope this e-mail finds you well. How are
Sacheen and the children? Did Little Hops get the CD I burned for
him? I found some trippy little jazz vinyl shop on Melrose. The
hiss is wonderful. I hope he enjoys it.
</P>
<P>
   We beat Portland today to go up 3-1 in the Western Conference
finals. It was probably our best overall performance of the season.
There is nothing like going into an opponent's house and turning a
rally into a funeral. Michael and I would often talk about how
deadly a road win can be.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, there are times when I believe I am stealing
money from Jerry Buss, the nice owner of the team. He has been very
accommodating to me, and oh-so thankful for how far we've come this
season after all of the anguish of the previous three.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, I'm the fortunate one. When Michael decided to
retire, the two best players in the league under 30 were Shaquille
O'Neal and Kobe Bryant. If I was going to return to coaching after
my one-year sabbatical, it was either going to be in New York where
I played or with a team that had a leg up on a winning a title.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the kind of thing I would have ever said for public
consumption, of course, because being under 30, neither Shaq nor
Kobe had the maturity yet to deal with that kind of identity.
Michael's mind had to catch up with his talent before he became the
player he was. People always talk about his superb talent, but the
truth is that Michael was a warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq and Kobe are incredibly gifted. I'm not sure there has ever
been a big man in the NBA that can do all that Shaquille can do.
Did you see that spin move he put on Brian Grant Sunday? A man that
big shouldn't be allowed to be that nimble. He's a genetic freak of
nature, and I am so lucky to have him.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about Shaq is that he's the son of a marine.
He can be goofy at times, endearingly so, but he has this amazing
work ethic and courage underneath it all. All he's ever wanted and
needed, I believe, is confidence in what he's asked to do and trust
in the person asking it.
</P>
<P>
   I always thought he was the perfect center for the triangle
offense. When you throw the ball into Shaq, what's the defense
supposed to do? Two years ago, I wondered if he was smart enough to
know what he can and can't do to become a winner. But he's been
perfect. He submitted to the triangle.
</P>
<P>
   I was more worried about the other lad because he's been
compared to Michael so often, and that's so terribly unfair. My
challenge was getting him to understand that the measure of the man
was winning, not highlight reels.
</P>
<P>
   They have become warriors. In Game 3 Friday, both men had to
extend themselves beyond the scoresheet to win. We won that game
because Shaq didn't dwell on his first half, because both men were
willing to give the ball up to the open man when we needed a
basket, and because each made great defensive plays at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe blocking a shot by that mastodon Sabonis Friday was all
warrior charisma, a moment similar to Michael stealing the ball
from Karl Malone in the final game in the 1998 playoffs. And Shaq's
free throws Sundays may not be the way he prefers to dominate, but
a hammer is a hammer.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team has been the same kind of puzzle I had in
Chicago. You have all these spare parts, and the challenge is to
make them work together. I always thought Glen Rice was a perfect
player for the triangle, and he is, but just not as reliable as I'd
like.
</P>
<P>
   The other fellows play hard. They don't like the way I use them
all the time, but the other Bulls didn't like a lot of the
decisions I made, either. L.A. is supposed to be laid-back, but
players are players wherever they play. They don't like to sit and
they chafe at my decisions. Many still don't understand the Zen
philosophy, that you have to be here for what you can do at this
moment.
</P>
<P>
   I do not think we would be in this position if not for Ron
Harper. He never got the credit he deserved in Chicago for being
such a steady player in an offense that asked him to sublimate. We
wouldn't be here, either, if not for Jerry West. How many de facto
general managers are secure enough to let someone coach the team
the way he sees fit?
</P>
<P>
   The only downside has been a tendency for the media out here to
wail every time we lose a game. They've been brain-washed to expect
the worst, I imagine. Truthfully, I've used this to my advantage a
few times. I think the players now know these are the things you
deal with when you lose.
</P>
<P>
   We have beaten Portland to the point where they wonder if
they're good enough, and resolved all of our own conflicts. All
that's left is the winning.
</P>
<P>
   I'll see you and the family this summer. I'll bring Dennis with
me for some fresh air and rehab, if I can find him.
</P>
<P>
   Yours, Phil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
