<HEADLINE>
ADVICE MAKES FREE THROWS SLAM DUNK FOR SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Shaquille O'Neal has grown weary of advice on
foul shooting, but Sunday morning he got a good tip from an
unlikely, but welcome, source - his daughter, Taahirah.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter's 3 years old, and of course she really doesn't
know the game,'' O'Neal said. ``But today I called and I said,
`Daddy loves you.' And she said, `Good luck, bend your knees.' ''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal then simulated his response: A ``What?'' and a stunned
look. But obviously daughter knew best - Daddy made all nine of his
free throws to lead the Los Angeles Lakers to their 103-91 victory
over the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Neal's best free-throw performance ever in a big
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that game was for her,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, for Portland coach Mike Dunleavy. O'Neal was 3 for 3 when
Dunleavy went to the ``Hack-a-Shaq'' routine, ordering intentional
fouls midway through the fourth quarter. O'Neal calmly sank both
and smiled, then finished out the string perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Pete Maravich, that guy from LSU,'' he said with a
laugh. ``I had a rhythm going. ... I think if I develop some
consistency, then I can become a great player in this league one
day.''
</P>
<P>
   He also might put an end to the intentional fouling that has at
times frustrated him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, that's the answer right there,'' said Dunleavy, who used
the tactic 12 times in Game 1. ``It's not the league making new
rules, it's not anything else. That's the answer. You make free
throws, and it makes it tough on other teams to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson proudly noted that the strategy ``really
backfired today on them, and it really sewed the game up for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take (O'Neal) out early so he could keep that stat
sheet for him,'' Jackson said. ``We told him to put that on the
wall, frame that one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparring: It was another day of exchanged glares, occasional
smiles and a little smack talk between Jackson and his former
Chicago Bulls pupil, Portland's Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two good friends, that's all that was,'' said Bulls alumnus
and current Laker Ron Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who had dubbed the Blazers ``jackals'' for celebrating
their Game 2 win in L.A., joked Sunday that Pippen was the ``lead
jackal,'' but downplayed their mini-rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing there, just looking at each other, kind
of,'' he said. ``We weren't conversing, just kind of checking each
other out. There was nothing to be said. Scottie's playing really
hard, and I was just checking out how he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up: Harper made his biggest contribution of the
postseason, scoring 18 points on 6-of-12 shooting to go with seven
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't say enough about Ronnie's game,'' Jackson said.
``He had foul trouble early in the game and the middle of the game.
And we just played him anyway with four fouls at one point in the
third quarter, simply because Brian Shaw (serving a suspension)
wasn't here, they were taking advantage of Derek Fisher down in the
post with Bonzi Wells the first half. And Ron just kept playing
better as the game went on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
