<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CLEMENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS HASN'T LOST IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Almost 15 minutes had passed since members of the
media were allowed into the New York clubhouse before Roger Clemens
strode in and went to his locker along the back wall. His
appearance following Sunday &UR;  &LR; night's 2-0 defeat to Pedro Martinez
and the Red Sox brought life to a locker room cloaked in somber
silence and filled with awkward glances.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a black T-shirt with the sleeves cut off, his oversized
biceps were clearly visible. His pitching arm was a solid block of
bright red, showing the effects of a postgame icing. Before facing
a throng of questioners, he brushed back his spiky brown hair and
donned a well-worn Yankees cap. A lone security man kept reporters
at bay until Clemens was ready to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good game,'' said Clemens. ``That's the way it's
supposed to be. Those 12-10 ballgames, you don't want to be in
those. You want to be in those ballgames right there. That was a
fun game to pitch in. The intensity was every bit of what it was
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated rematch between Clemens and Martinez _ who
met in last year's AL Championship Series _ lived up to all the
billing. While Clemens had made an early exit in the previous
meeting, a Boston rout, Sunday &UR;  &LR; night he matched Martinez all night
long. Almost. Clemens pitched all nine innings and logged 127
pitches, racking up 13 strikeouts and allowing just five hits and
two earned runs. Two runs too many.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the ninth inning of a 0-0 game, Trot Nixon sent
a 2-1 fastball into the right-field stands to spoil Clemens's
sparkling performance. However, it was the single by the previous
batter, Jeff Frye, that Clemens referred to as ``the only thing
disappointing about the night.'' On that play, Clemens fumbled a
comebacker to allow Frye to reach.
</P>
<P>
   But those two plays _ and the loss that resulted _ took little
away from Clemens's outing. It was arguably his best performance in
pinstripes. The 13 strikeouts were a season high, and Sunday &UR;  &LR; night
was his second 10-strikeout game as a Yankee and the 95th of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a classic. No question,'' said Yankees manager Joe
Torre. ``I hope to hell that it puts to rest all the questions
about Roger. It was an inspired performance on both sides, and
somebody had to lose, unfortunately. It was a great game. I sure as
hell wanted to win the thing. Nobody has to be ashamed of the
result. It definitely was a playoff atmosphere. The players felt
it. Everybody was pumped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we came out of this series knowing that these two
teams are going to be fighting for it to the end. It's a game that
I think everybody will look back on, and you should all be happy
that you were here to witness it. It certainly lived up to
everything it was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the last time Martinez and Clemens faced off, the
sing-song chants of ``Roger, Roger'' seemed to spur the Yankees ace
on, though the loss dropped Clemens to 4-5.
</P>
<P>
   His legs became a little tired, but his arm felt good until the
end. ``Our fans here are great, and that always gets you fired
up,'' said Clemens. ``That's why I enjoy pitching here the most. I
need to try to keep that level when I'm pitching on the road. It
was everything it was supposed to be . . . You want to go out there
and throw zeros, for sure. You think it's going to be that way.
It's supposed to be that way. That's why all those people were in
those stands tonight. You want to give them something fun to take
home.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that the 55,339 fans at Yankee Stadium
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night will be keeping the ticket stubs they brought home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
