<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-APACHEHUNT-AZR &LR;      05-29 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APACHEHUNT-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-APACHEHUNT-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    INVITING TOURISTS TO BORDER ``HUNTS'' FOR HUMANS IS NOTHING
NEW(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DANIEL GONZALEZ(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tourists as soldiers of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   That was the gist of an anonymous appeal that surfaced last
month: Fun in the Arizona sun. The great outdoors. The chance to
help ranchers hunt illegal immigrants along the U.S.-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't the first time the idea of hunting humans for
sport has cropped up in Douglas, a border town known for mining,
ranching - and now, illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy years ago, a similar proposal to tourists was pitched in
this same corner of Arizona. But rather than Mexicans, it was
Apache Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Fimbres Apache Expedition is not only a
reminder of the long-standing racial hostilities along the
Arizona-Mexico border, but it's also a tragic lesson about
vigilantism.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1930 and Douglas, the hub of the nation's copper-smelting
industry, was in an economic slump. The Great Depression was
underway and all the economic indicators pointed downward.
</P>
<P>
   The town's merchants, however, were pioneering people. If
ranching was slow and copper mining on the wane, they would find
some other way to generate money.
</P>
<P>
   And they did. Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   But not just any kind. A.C. Karger, then mayor of Douglas, and
the shrewd chiefs of the local Chamber of Commerce were going to
sell a special brand of tourism, one that capitalized on every
attribute Douglas had to offer: a magnificent railroad station,
excellent rail connections, a world-class hotel, a warm, dry
climate with blue skies and breathtaking scenery.
</P>
<P>
   And the chance to kill Apaches, although that was never overtly
stated in the fliers and newspaper ads promoting the expedition
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The stated purpose of the expedition was the attempted rescue of
a 7-year-old boy who had been kidnapped by a band of Apaches three
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the underlying message was not lost on the outpouring of
men who wrote letters hoping to join the expedition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never fought Indians, but I have chased Spics all
around Haiti and Nicaragua,'' wrote one adventure-seeker. ``I guess
I'll have the guts to chase these birds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have traveled all over the globe. I have seen a bit of life
and have fought men of all colors, so I would like to become a
member of your expedition, for I love action,'' wrote another.
</P>
<P>
   The Fimbres Apache Expedition stemmed from years of hostilities
between a Mexican rancher named Francisco Fimbres and a band of
Apaches based in the rugged Sierra Madres.
</P>
<P>
   Although warfare between the Indians and the United States
officially ended with Geronimo's surrender on Sept. 6, 1886,
hostilities with his band of Apaches - the Bronco group of the
Chiricahua - continued on both sides of the Mexican border for
another 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The hostilities exploded into open warfare on Oct. 26, 1926 when
the Apaches ambushed Fimbres and his family. The Apaches killed
Fimbres' wife and kidnapped his son, Geraldo. The Apaches were
seeking revenge for an earlier kidnapping of Geronimo's
great-granddaughter by Fimbres.
</P>
<P>
   The Fimbres Apache Expedition captured nationwide attention, but
in the end the expedition never got off the ground. Officials on
both sides of the border realized the idea of armed gringos roaming
around in Mexico could spell disaster and they quashed the
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop Fimbres. When he learned help from the gringos
was not coming, he reverted to his old tactics. With the help of
vaqueros (Mexican cowboys) and expatriate American mercenaries,
Fimbres hunted down the Apaches himself. A March 13, 1931, photo
captured Fimbres with the scalps of three Apaches.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Fimbres finally found his son in an Apache
camp, hanging from a tree. In revenge for the three Apaches killed
earlier by Fimbres and his men, the Apaches had swung the boy by
his heels and smashed his skull against an oak tree.
</P>
<P>
   Fimbres and his men retaliated yet again, until the last of the
Apaches were hunted down and killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Fimbres Apache Expedition was chronicled in a 1993 book,
``They Never Surrendered: Bronco Apaches of the Sierra Madres,
1890-1935,'' by Texas author Douglas Meed.
</P>
<P>
   Meed sees a parallel between the Fimbres expedition and a
``Neighborhood Ranch Watch'' flier distributed in April that hoped
to convert tourists into soldiers of fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a parallel there, because what you are doing is
asking people to come down and hunt people as sport,'' Meed said.
``The difference is that the ranchers are trying to protect their
land rather than make money off this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meed also thinks the most recent episode could spark a new round
of violence along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix writer John Alba came across accounts of the Fimbres
Apache Expedition while researching a novel set during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   He also sees a link between the two calls for vigilantism along
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a parallel there as to how some Anglo people view
dark-skinned people as less than human,'' Alba said. ``At that
time, in the 1930s, it was the Apaches who were viewed as animals
to be hunted down and exterminated. Now it's common to hear in
various places along the border these expressions that the illegals
are a plague, a vermin, an invasion that has to be stopped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
