<SLUG> BC-LEXX-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 `LEXX' EXPLORES SCI-FI's LUSTIER SIDE  
 (Includes a color slide of a scene from ``Lexx.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by STARBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 By CHRISTOPHER BLAND  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before June 11. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)   &HT;    It has understandably been called ``Star Trek's'' evil twin. In
the sci-fi series ``Lexx,'' there are no final frontiersmen
selflessly rescuing alien kittens from trees. Along the darkly
humorous edge of ``Lexx,'' lust exudes and life is cheap. Against
the greater fabric of television, ``Lexx'' is certainly different.
 &HT;    Even against today's few offerings of relatively exotic sci-fi,
``Lexx'' is a siren of distinction for its black comedy, skewed
take on the human condition and open sexuality _ qualities that act
as counterpoints to contemporary sci-fi sensibilities, according to
Lex Gigeroff, co-writer of the show, along with Jeffrey Hirschfield
(voice of the show's lust-struck robot, 790) and executive producer
Paul Donovan.
 &HT;    Perhaps some of its unique style comes from the fact that the
series is filmed in a remote area of Canada _ Halifax, Nova Scotia.
And the people behind the show are all dedicated to taking a
low-key, unassuming approach to the genre.
 &HT;    ``Science fiction has a tendency sometimes to be very pompous
about itself,'' Gigeroff says, speaking from his office at Salter
Street Films in Halifax, which co-produces ``Lexx'' with Germany's
TiMe Film und TV Produktion.
 &HT;    ``We're really dealing with weighty issues here,'' he adds,
``but there's all sorts of ways of doing that. You can do that in a
heavy-handed way, or in a bit more of an ironic or off-center way,
and I think that's the trick, trying to find the outside edge of
science fiction.''
 &HT;    Gigeroff realizes that ``Lexx'' is not the first show to walk
sci-fi's fringes. ``There were things like `The Prisoner,' which
was certainly dark at times,'' he says of the 1967 series starring
Patrick McGoohan, ``and also things like `Dark Star,' John
Carpenter's dark 1974 space comedy.''
 &HT;    ``Lexx'' debuted in 1996 as four made-for-TV movies called
``Lexx: The Dark Zone Stories'' (now called season one). The movies
came two years after Paul Donovan's 1994 movie ``Paint Cans,''
which featured Gigeroff and Canadian actor Michael McManus, who
plays ``Lexx's'' undead assassin, Kai.
 &HT;    Two years later, in '98, ``Lexx'' returned as a 13-part series,
then returned again this spring with 13 new segments. More than a
Canadian hit, ``Lexx'' is popular in the United States, Britain,
France and Germany. Yet fans exist even farther abroad. Linked to
``Lexx's'' Web site (www.Lexx.com) are a few sites in Russia.
 &HT;    On the simplest level, ``Lexx'' is the story of three space
outcasts _ Kai, Stanley Tweedle (Canadian actor Brian Downey) and
Xev (German actress Xenia Seeburg) _ wandering space in a
cybernetically enhanced insect spacecraft, the ``Lexx.'' Beyond the
familiar backdrop of space, ``it's a show that's not really
connected to Earth in any way,'' says Gigeroff. ``(Kai, Stanley and
Xev) are not colonists from Earth ... So it kind of gives you a lot
of freedom ... a really tremendous latitude to go for it.''
 &HT;    That latitude resulted in a change to this season's story
structure. Where season two was a series of stand-alone episodes,
this year is a narrative centered around an interplanetary war. The
reason is that ``Paul (Donovan) really liked the idea of being able
to take a bit more time with some stories,'' comments Gigeroff.
 &HT;    ``It's sometimes a challenge to create a wholly self-contained
little universe each week,'' he says. ``You can take a bit of time
with some characters, which is what we tried to do with Nigel,''
meaning Nigel Bennett, the Emmy Award-winning Canadian actor cast
as season three's recurring character, Prince.
 &HT;    Another change is Seeburg's costume. Introduced during season
two as a replacement for German actress Eva Haberman, who played
Xev's progenitor, Zev, in the ``Lexx'' movies, Seeburg first
appeared as a savvy, red-haired love slave. The change to Seeburg's
natural blond tresses resulted during production this season.
 &HT;    ``People would see me like I look in real life, even the people
that I worked with, and they would always go, `Oh, Xenia, it's so
good to see you without that horrible red wig,''' says Seeburg from
her home in Dusseldorf, Germany. ``So finally it was like an
all-around agreement,'' which became an on-camera change only after
Seeburg was sure that fans had accepted her as Haberman's
replacement.
 &HT;    A constant of the show has been its stunning digital effects,
created by Filmeffekte GmbH in Germany and CAGE Digital in Halifax.
Yet the effects, too, have evolved. This season was shot using High
Definition technology that was blended with digital imagery, then
treated on video with a film effect. Perhaps the only thing that
hasn't changed is the life-and-death situations in which the
cowardly captain, Stanley Tweedle, routinely finds himself.
 &HT;    ``We really think it's one of our missions in life to put Brian
Downey in as many uncomfortable shooting positions as possible,
just because he's such a great guy,'' Gigeroff says, jokingly.
``Paul and I will be talking about what we're doing, and Brian will
come by and ask, `What are you going to put me in next week?' And
(Brian) does it cheerfully.''
 &HT;    As appealing as ``Lexx'' is to fans, Gigeroff doesn't expect the
show to become universally appealing. ``We've always kind of wanted
to try and get a little cult show,'' he says. ``This is never going
to be a show which everybody is going to like. It was never meant
to be.''
 &HT;    Oddly, some of the stars who've appeared on ``Lexx'' stand as
cult icons in their own right. ``The Dark Zone'' tales themselves
include Malcolm McDowell (an ultraviolent `malchick' in ``A
Clockwork Orange''), Rutger Hauer (tragic antagonist Roy Batty in
``Blade Runner'') and Tim Curry (just a sweet transvestite in ``The
Rocky Horror Picture Show'').
 &HT;    Although ``Lexx'' has had some success, Gigeroff can't speculate
about the future, given the precarious nature of TV. For the
moment, he is content with what he describes as ``an incredible
rocket ride so far'' _ a phrase that perhaps best describes the
impact of the show. As Seeburg says in one of the show's trailers,
it's a ride for you to remember.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Christopher Bland is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada)
 &HT;    
 -0- 
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
<TEXT>
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features. &QL;
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITOR: For further information on ``Lexx,'' consult the
official Web site at www.lexx.com. Or visit the Sci-Fi Channel Web
site at www.scifi.com. And check out The New York Times Syndicate
Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on
StarBeat and other features.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
