<HEADER>
A8743 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-MONEY-GORDON-NYT     05-29 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-MONEY-GORDON-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE ARE ALL SPENDTHRIFTS NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (New York Times OpEd for Monday, May 29, and thereafter.) 
ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By MARY GORDON    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become increasingly difficult to read a newspaper or
magazine without encountering the details of extravagant,
conspicuous consumption, usually on the part of new millionaires,
or billionaires, usually under 30. Stories of $1,000 spent on a
bottle of wine. Reports of a dish of boiled sole and a roasted new
potato that costs $60, not counting, of course, tips and taxes.
Apartments in New York City formerly considered marginally
uninhabitable snapped up at the price of half a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Our imaginations are drawn to these stories; they have the
allure of soft porn, at least for those of us who congratulate
ourselves on not jumping for the bait, those of us who believe
ourselves capable of the statement, ``It isn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   But what do we mean by worth?
</P>
<P>
   When we use the word, we are talking about a system of
equivalencies _ a transaction between the symbolic and the actual
that many people believe is the most real thing there is, but which
is, in fact, a sheer act of imagination. Whose idea was it that a
hard, inedible and unprotecting substance (stones, shells, metal)
could be traded for food, clothing, shelter?
</P>
<P>
   The use of money is the purest act of faith; no anchorite who
has followed a vision into the desert has acted on an idea as
far-fetched as our belief that if we put a dollar in a machine we
will be drinking a Diet Coke in a minute. Of course, we don't think
of this strangeness all the time, but sometimes, when the numbers
seem to have reached the fantastical, we question the idea of
worth: how much should be handed over for what things?
</P>
<P>
   These decisions are often based on personal history or
biography. My mother's sense of worth, for example, was much
different from mine. She had been a young woman during the
Depression and was always haunted by the specter of real poverty,
even during the prosperous 1950s and '60s. She supported us on a
secretary's salary, so we were never able to live luxuriously, but
she suspected all expenditure, almost for its own sake.
</P>
<P>
   She saved wrapping paper and tinfoil and Saran wrap. Closets and
drawers were full of discolored papers and crinkled squares of foil
and ill-smelling plastics. She usually waited for someone to die
before replenishing her wardrobe: wearing the clothes of the dead
seemed to her a superior choice to a purchase in a store. She
deprived herself of the real pleasures of consumption: we never ate
in restaurants or stayed in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   My cousin and I (he was the son of her sister) feel that every
time we buy something that gives us pleasure, we are undoing an old
curse. We refer to such activities as ``mental health purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   The flexibility of a sense of worth was brought home to me last
week when my oldest friend and I sent our children shopping in
Harvard Square. Thirty years ago, we had spent the summer in
Cambridge, she studying physics (she later became a doctor), I
working as a secretary in an insurance company (I later became a
novelist). That summer, we made a weekly decision about whether we
would share a frankfurter at a German restaurant, or a piece of
apple cake.
</P>
<P>
   Half a lifetime later, we dropped our teen-age daughters off,
shoving bills at them through the car window.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did you give them?'' my friend asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty dollars,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me too,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of us believed we had been extravagant, but we noted the
difference 30 years and increased prosperity had made. Fifty
dollars was liberal, it made us happy that we could offer our
children an ease we hadn't had ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   But what if we had given them $500? Is there ever a point at
which it is important to say, ``this far and no further''? Isn't
there a moment when we question the relationship between what we
paid and what we got?
</P>
<P>
   Was the plate of sole really worth $60? Was the studio apartment
really worth $500,000?
</P>
<P>
   We use the word ``disposable income,'' but shouldn't we consider
what's being disposed of?
</P>
<P>
   Is it only hypocritical or absurd to question what the poor
could do with the money?
</P>
<P>
   The fact that I have to fear that mentioning the poor will
induce only yawns or groans, as if I'd questioned the propriety of
sleeveless dresses, tells us something about what seems important,
even discussable, to us now.
</P>
<P>
   In these times, there seems to be a gap between price tag and
worth. Shouldn't we consider, without fearing that we've turned
into Puritans or killjoys, taking a deep breath before speaking
sentences whose language is made up of numbers that seem
incomprehensibly distant from what once seemed reasonable?
</P>
<P>
   Is this a real question, or just my version or my mother's
shouted admonition: ``Don't rip that wrapping paper off that box so
fast! Do you think I'm made of money?''
</P>
<P>
   (Mary Gordon is the author, most recently, of ``Seeing Through
Places'' and ``Joan of Arc.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
