<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-TECHNOLOGY-LIFEBEAT-1070-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE TECHNOLOGY IN YOUR GARAGE
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Paul Ingrassia is a contributing editor of ``Smart Money''
magazine.
 &HT;    
 By PAUL INGRASSIA 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   Now all you grown-up kids can play Tank Commander while you're
driving home at night: The 2000 Cadillac DeVille sports an optional
night-vision system that detects critters (human or otherwise) in
the dark and projects their images in ghostly form onto the lower
windshield. ``We've brought Desert Storm to the family garage,''
Cadillac executives boast. Did somebody say road warrior?
</P>
<P>
   A host of high-tech gadgets, many based on defense technology,
are finding their way into new cars these days. Besides night
vision, for example, the DeVille has an ultrasonic device that
chimes when you're about to back into something. A slew of luxury
cars are being outfitted with navigation systems, as either
standard equipment or options. Soon cars will have wireless
Internet service and will even read your e-mail aloud to you. (On
second thought, I'll stick with my Eagles Greatest Hits CD
instead.)
</P>
<P>
   General Motors has had enough success with its OnStar in-car
communications system, which combines global positioning with a
pushbutton, cell-phone concierge service, that it's negotiating to
provide OnStar to Toyota and perhaps other car companies as well.
</P>
<P>
   It was the General (military allusion intended) that started the
combat-gear trend. In 1985, GM bought Hughes Aircraft with the
avowed purpose of adapting defense technology to autos. Four years
later, the strategy got its first, modest adaptation: a ``heads-up
display'' system, developed for fighter planes, that projects
information onto the lower windshield. More recently, GM honchos
have declared that cars are really mobile platforms for serving up
a whole host of technological services to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   They may be onto something, but there are a couple of caveats.
First, new technological features will have to be truly useful
instead of just flashy gimmickry. The heads-up display, called
EyeCue and available on the Pontiac Bonneville and some other GM
models, is pretty much the latter. Seemingly aimed at Top Gun
wannabes, it projects your speed, turn signals, headlight beams,
low-fuel indicator and radio station onto the windshield, allowing
you to keep your eyes on the road. I found the turn-signal display
moderately useful, but the rest was distracting.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat two: High-tech gadgetry will be no substitute for getting
a car's fundamentals absolutely right. In short, it's pointless to
consider technological features apart from the car itself. So
here's how a couple of new cars that tout their whiz-bang gizmos
stack up overall.
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC DEVILLE
</P>
<P>
   When I decided to test-drive the new 2000 DeVille, I was more
interested in the night vision than in the car itself. My age being
well south of 60 _ in fact, slightly south of 50- _ I figured I
would dismiss the Caddy but like the night vision. It ended up sort
of the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   The night-vision system sees through a camera mounted on the
DeVille's front grille. But this camera senses heat, not light. The
resulting images have the ghostly look of a photographic negative,
with hot objects in white and cooler ones in black. These images
are projected onto the lower windshield. You can turn the system
off. And to a degree, you can adjust the location and size of the
projection.
</P>
<P>
   Using the system on a busy road produces a host of bobbing round
images. They are the hot mufflers of the cars ahead of you. It's
mildly distracting. But on dark country roads, night vision may be
worthwhile. Hitting a deer can be dangerous, and the system does
let you spot animals earlier than your headlights do.
</P>
<P>
   The DeVille's other techno-gadget is Ultrasonic Rear Parking
Assist. It sends out ultrasonic waves when you're backing up at
slow speeds and starts chiming when you get within a
yard-and-a-half of an object. It got on my nerves a bit when I was
squeezing into a tight parking space.
</P>
<P>
   If the DeVille's technology proved less than compelling, though,
the car itself was a pleasant surprise. The 2000 DeVille is three
inches shorter and two inches narrower than the previous version.
The styling, while hardly daring, is quite handsome. The DeVille's
ride is comfortable and even a bit cushy, but far from the
``floating sofa'' feel of its predecessor. The steering should be
tighter, even on the DeVille Touring Sedan (DTS), which is designed
to appeal to younger (i.e., 40s to mid-50s) buyers. But the DTS's
standard V-8, 32-valve Northstar engine pumps out 300 horsepower;
it's wonderfully responsive and powerful. All in all, I rather
liked the DeVille.
</P>
<P>
   The DeVille DTS I drove carried a base price of $45,370 with
destination charges. Options, including $1,995 for night vision,
$400 for a security package with Ultrasonic Rear Parking Assist and
$5,520 for other goodies, made the final sticker $53,285. I'd skip
the night vision, haggle and get the price below $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ACURA 3.2 TL
</P>
<P>
   The best way to evaluate any new piece of electronic automotive
technology is simply to try to use it, without pulling out the
owner's manual. Amazingly, the Acura Navigation System passes this
test with ease. It is remarkably user-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, my wife and I hopped in the Acura to drive from New
Jersey to Brooklyn. We just entered our destination address on the
touch-sensitive screen.
</P>
<P>
   The display is intuitively clear. You can select the most direct
route or specify that the route should avoid freeways, use
freeways, etc. The system shows your location with great accuracy,
and it tells you where to make your next turn and how far it is
until the turning point.
</P>
<P>
   If you miss a turn, it just flashes a message that it's
``recalculating'' and quickly maps the new route.
</P>
<P>
   It still can't see traffic conditions ahead and plot the route
with those in mind. Should that capability be added someday, this
would be a home-run device.
</P>
<P>
   This time, I liked the gadget better than the car. The 3.2 TL
has a smooth, powerful engine (a 3.2-liter, 24-valve V-6 with 22S
peak horsepower) _ the hallmark of all Hondas. The steering is
tight and precise.
</P>
<P>
   But the styling also is a Honda hallmark, which is to say,
nondescript. My major problem with the 3.2 TL, though, is that it's
simply too small. Even a young child won't have much room in back.
</P>
<P>
   The base price is a reasonable $28,855 including destination
charges, and the only option is the navigation system, which costs
$2,000. The electronics are great, but there are other ``near
luxury'' cars with more personality.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
