<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-PARENTING-ANXIETY-LIF     05-29 2162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTING-ANXIETY-LIFEBEAT-1731&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOTING PARENTS OF HARD-WON CHILDREN OFTEN CAN'T BEAR TO LET GO 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Monika Guttman is a contributing editor to ``Child'' and the
mother of two.
 &HT;     &HT;    
 By MONIKA GUTTMAN 
 c.2000 Child Magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
<P>
   Although their twin boys, Allan and Stephen, are almost 4, Diane
Morancie, 34, of West Orange, N.J., and her husband Craig, 34,
don't roughhouse with them the way some parents do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where most dads fling their children into the air, we just
want to safeguard their existence,'' says Diane. If that sounds
overprotective, she adds, it's nothing compared to when the couple
brought the boys home from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Back then _ haunted by the idea that the babies might die of
Sudden Infant Death Syndrome, also known as ``SIDS'' _ they made a
pact: One of them would always stay awake to keep an eye on the two
children. After a few weeks of watching the new parents stumble
around in exhaustion, ``our mothers sat us down and said we had to
stop this,'' Diane recalls. ``They basically told us we had to
trust that the babies would be all right. That wasn't easy for us
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Take normal new-parent anxiety. Add years of effort, expense,
dashed hopes and loss on the road to childbearing. Throw in a dose
of disbelief that the long process is finally over, that the little
bundle in your arms is really yours. What you end up with, say
experts, is a parenting style unique to parents of ``hard-won''
kids _ children who arrive after infertility, multiple miscarriages
or a long adoption process.
</P>
<P>
   The Morancies, who went through six years of infertility and one
unsuccessful in-vitro attempt before having their children, are
part of a growing group of such parents. That's partly because
infertility rates are rising: From 1988 to 1995, the percent of
reproductive-age couples experiencing infertility rose from 8.4
percent to 10.2 percent, or one out of 10 couples.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption, too, is on the rise _ international adoptions by
American parents, for example, more than doubled between 1990 and
1998, according to the Evan B. Donaldson Adoption Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Couples whose children did not come that easily start parenthood
with a ``special kind of legacy,'' says Ellen Sarasohn Glazer, a
licensed social worker who lives in Boston and the co-author of the
book, ``Experiencing Infertility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who've gone through infertility have a stack of
losses,'' she says. ``The losses live on, and even the arrival of a
child doesn't erase the impact.'' The losses may be obvious, such
as a miscarriage, or can include those that aren't socially
recognized, such as a failed in-vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   The most subtle issues, says Dr. Kevin Leman, the Tucson-based
author of ``The New Birth Order Book,'' arise from a
``specialness'' attached to a child born of so much emotion and
endeavor. Leman can relate: When he and his wife had their first
child, who was born after two previous miscarriages, he was
extremely overprotective. ``I turned the heat up in the house so
high you could have raised gardenias in the place,'' he says. ``I
said, 'My daughter is not going to be cold.'''
</P>
<P>
   But after going through emotionally and physically wrenching
procedures, spending incredible amounts of money, or traveling
overseas, parents are so happy the child has finally arrived, Leman
says, that they want to be perfect. That puts enormous pressure on
them, and ``what happens is you create a child who is the center of
the universe,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Such focus goes well beyond normal, Leman maintains, and can
lead to problems. ``When you hand a child everything he wants and
give in to his every need, you end up not with a responsible child
who has developed an age-appropriate independence but a child in
full control of adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, there have been some huge strides in recognizing
post-infertility parenting issues, says Dr. Joyce Maguire Pavao,
founder and director of the Boston-based Center For Family
Connections, which provides counseling for parents before and after
adoption. Being aware of some of the following issues before they
occur, she says, can make the parenting of hard-won children less
stressful:
</P>
<P>
   Doubts About Parenting Skills:
</P>
<P>
   Before her successful pregnancy, Linda Carbone, 44, of
Irvington, N.Y., suffered through hormone injections and 10
surgical procedures, including in-vitro fertilization. Her husband,
Ed Decker, 47, underwent an operation to correct misshapen sperm.
For nine years, nothing worked. ``Getting pregnant became a medical
process for me,'' says Carbone. ``I almost lost sight that at the
end of it there was going to be a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, without assistance, one day she found she was pregnant.
``I didn't believe it was real, and I was halfway through the
pregnancy before I read any books about parenting,'' she says. ``I
think parenting is a lot harder than either of us expected. In some
ways we were not prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coping With New Parenthood Challenges:
</P>
<P>
   Simply acknowledging that they are tired because the baby was up
all night _ a common complaint for any new parent _ can be harder
for moms and dads who talked only of how much they wanted a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any new mother will tell you that handing the baby to her
husband when he comes home and then going off to the supermarket
feels like a day at the spa,'' says psychotherapist Harriette
Rovner Ferguson, a licensed social worker who lives in Smithtown,
N.Y., and is co-author of ``Experiencing Infertility.'' ``But so
many mothers of much-awaited children say they are full of guilt
for feeling this way. Or if they do complain about parental stress,
their family and friends say, 'But you wanted this baby so much.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson says parents of hard-won babies should know ``it's
really OK to say 'I can't do it all.''' You may find it harder than
others to ask for help and have more difficulty accepting that
you're still good parents if you take a break. It's even more
important to ``ask friends or relatives for help and for both
physical and emotional support, such as finding baby-sitters, ''
advises Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing Loss:
</P>
<P>
   Some parents of hard-won babies say they live in genuine fear
that somehow their child will either be taken away or not survive.
``I think it took about a year before I could finally breathe
easily,'' recalls Rebecca Gold, 38, a Los Angeles-based children's
book author who adopted her second daughter, Camila, three years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gold, who 13 years earlier had had her first daughter without
any problems, spent seven years going through infertility
treatments and unsuccessful adoption attempts. ``I remember always
putting my hand on Camila's back to make sure she was breathing. I
would immediately take her to the doctor when she got sick because
I kept thinking it could be something I didn't know about in her
genes.''
</P>
<P>
   Letting go of this fear, says Glazer, begins with accepting the
fact that ``there's nothing crazy or irrational about it. Anyone
who has had a brush with a risky situation has similar fears.''
Acknowledge that, as the parent of a hard-won child, you will
probably go more slowly and cautiously than other parents.
</P>
<P>
   Never Saying No:
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it's easy for these parents to give in to the child
they worked so hard to have. Dodie Hoffman, 38, of Valencia,
Calif., started in-vitro fertility treatments in 1994 and gave
birth to her daughter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I was a mom, all I wanted to do was hold her all the
time,'' she recalls. Now that her child is a toddler, ``I noticed
that I'm more tolerant than some of my 'normal' friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for parents of hard-won kids, the parenting challenge
is drawing the line. Dr. Alix Casler, a pediatrician in Orlando,
Fla., and the host of the Parenting Community at
TheHealthNetwork.com, says, ``if you say yes all the time, then
there's nothing for the child to strive for, and that's not to
their benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   If your knee-jerk reaction is always to concede to your child,
such as buying her a new toy every time she wants one, stop and ask
yourself whether her demand is appropriate before automatically
saying yes. Tying the toy treat to good behavior, such as cleaning
up each night for a week before dinner or helping clear the table
during that same period, will show the child that the toy is a
goal, not a given.
</P>
<P>
   Being Overprotective:
</P>
<P>
   Parents of hard-won kids sometimes try too hard to protect their
children, which arises from the sense that their child is all the
more precious because of the ordeal they went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents do so much for them that the children don't learn
to help themselves,'' says Diane Clark Johnson, director of A
Family Resource, a parent-education center in Oakland, Calif.
``They lose important opportunities for achieving independence.''
This happens, for example, when you hover worriedly or hold your
toddler instead of letting him climb unassisted on jungle gym at
the park.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson suggests ``giving your child more autonomy in small
steps.'' With the jungle gym, for instance, stand next to it rather
than holding on to your child the whole time. Set him up for
success.'' Johnson also suggests doing a reality check with other
parents in your play group or preschool. ``As you look at what
other parents are able to let their children do, and what is
reasonable, gradually try to do it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the Marriage:
</P>
<P>
   When a much-awaited child arrives, most couples shift their
focus from one another to the baby. But for parents of hard-won
kids, marital stresses can be even more acute. Decker and Carbone
learned this the hard way _ after their daughter Julia arrived,
they only did things as a threesome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been together for 16 years before Julia came along, and
when you've been together for that long, you're really not prepared
for that kind of change,'' says Carbone. ``I feel as if it's very
easy to lose your marriage that first year or two.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember some infertile couples who proudly said, 'We never
leave the children with a baby sitter,''' says Glazer. What they
don't realize, she says, is that years of infertility may have
robbed their marriage of time and romance, and ``they need to tend
to that now. Just as the child is an entity, the marriage is also
one.''
</P>
<P>
   It is critical, she says, to carve out some special time to be
together, whether it's going to the movies or even just dinner,
although it may be harder for these parents.
</P>
<P>
   Leman agrees. While support groups can be useful, he says, new
parents shouldn't worry too much about which ones they should join.
What he believes is even more helpful is ``just to commit to
staying close as a couple.''
 &UR; WHERE TO GO FOR SUPPORT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most people, say experts, these worrisome issues begin to
die out as parents become confident in their childrearing skills
and begin interacting with other moms and dads in play groups,
preschools, and kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Today, especially, there is increasing awareness and
understanding of the important issues these parents face. Chat
groups on the Web are picking up on this topic and churches,
temples and even hospitals are starting to offer classes for
parents of hard-won babies that address many of these topics.
</P>
<P>
   Some useful organizations and Web sites include:
</P>
<P>
   Resolve, the national infertility support organization, has
groups for parents of hard-won kids in some of its local chapters.
For information, log on to www.resolve.org or call the national
headquarters, 617-623-0744.
</P>
<P>
   www.childofmydreams.com has weekly live chats on parenting after
infertility as well as news and basic information on infertility
issues.
</P>
<P>
   www.adoption.com provides support for parents in all stages of
the adoption process. Among their message boards is one called
Adoptive Parent Support Group.
</P>
<P>
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
---
</P>
