<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-VARICOSEVEINS-LIFEBEAT-579-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEN WAYS TO BEAT VARICOSE VEINS
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by LIFEBEAT clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (tlk) 
 &HT;    Michael Castleman is a contributing editor of ``Country Living's
Healthy Living.'' &HT;    
 By MICHAEL CASTLEMAN 
 c.2000 Hearst Communications Inc. 
<TEXT>
 &UR; World rights &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features
<P>
   1. Exercise: Movement is important in controlling varicose
veins. The action of the thigh and calf muscles helps pump blood
upward toward the heart; one-way valves in your leg veins open to
encourage this. If you sit or stand for long periods, however,
these valves weaken and cannot seal properly. Blood then pools in
your veins, stretching them. The bulging results _ visible through
the skin _ are known as varicose veins. Though they generally do
not pose a health problem, they can be unsightly. To prevent them,
take regular stretch-your-legs breaks when you're sedentary, or
elevate your legs after spending the day on your feet. In addition,
Dr. Anne Simons advocates brisk 30- to 60- minute walks daily.
</P>
<P>
   2. Weight control: Though varicose veins can plague women of
varying shapes and sizes, carrying excess weight puts pressure on
the legs, impeding blood flow to the heart and causing veins to
swell. Drop unwanted pounds through a balanced diet-and-exercise
regimen.
</P>
<P>
   3. Herbs: Numerous studies have proven the effectiveness of
horse-chestnut-seed extract in treating varicose veins. A safe dose
for adults is 50 milligrams three times daily in capsule form. This
herb, however, should not be used by children or pregnant or
lactating women.
</P>
<P>
   4. Compression hose: ``Support hose help relieve discomfort by
exerting gentle pressure on the calves, which facilitates proper
functioning of the valves in your veins,'' says Dr. Alan Gaby. If
regular support hose don't do the trick, try thicker elastic
versions available at medical-supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   5. Diet: Feast on blueberries, blackberries, cherries and
bilberries, which are rich in anthocyanosides, a type of flavonoid
that strengthens veins and valves.
</P>
<P>
   6. Homeopathy: ``Healthy Living's'' homeopathy expert, Dana
Ullman, M.P.H., says taking hamamelis (witch hazel) in the 12c
potency three times a day for no longer than a week is a reliable
treatment for varicose veins.
</P>
<P>
   7. Supplements: People with this condition have difficulty
breaking down fibrin, a substance that aids with bloodclotting.
It's deposited in the tissue near varicose veins, making the
surrounding skin hard and lumpy-looking. Bromelain, or pineapple
enzyme, dissipates the fibrin, thus improving the vein's
appearance. Joseph Pizzorno, N.D., recommends taking 500 to 750mg
three times a day between meals.
</P>
<P>
   8. Essential oilS: Massaging rosemary essential oil into the
legs can dilate capillaries near the surface, which may discourage
varicose veins. If you already have them, rub cypress and chamomile
oils into the skin to soothe swelling and relieve pain.
</P>
<P>
   9. Acupuncture: TCM practitioner Efrem Korngold, L.Ac.,
recommends being treated on several acupuncture points, including
Lung 9, on the thumb side of the inner forearm, in the hollow above
the crease of your wrist; and Spleen 6, on the inside of your lower
leg, four finger-widths above the top of your anklebone in the
muscle just behind your shinbone.
</P>
<P>
   10. Ayurveda: Combine equal parts ginger powder, ground black
pepper, coriander, nutmeg and the Indian herbs pippali (or long
pepper) and ajwan (substitute cloves if you can't find this at
Asian markets), says Ayurveda expert David Frawley, O.M.D. Take 1
to 4 grams of this herbal mixture _ which helps rev up circulation
_ three times a day. If you have a kapha constitution (you are
large-framed and deliberate), mix it with honey; if you're pitta
(with a medium build and a type-A personality) or vata (you're thin
and you love change), dissolve it in water.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
