<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ATTENTION EDITORS: The articles described below moved THURSDAY,
MAY 25, 2000, in the 'l' news file. The material was filed by The
New York Times Syndicate for use by LIFEBEAT clients.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement
with the Syndicate. For purchase information, see end of text. &QL; 
 &UR; (tlk) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE TECHNOLOGY IN YOUR GARAGE
</P>
<P>
   CARS-TECHNOLOGY-LIFEBEAT _ A host of high-tech gadgets, many
based on defense technology, are finding their way into new cars
these days. Look for night vision, for example, or for an
ultrasonic device that chimes when you're about to back into
something. Many luxury cars are being outfitted with navigation
systems as either standard equipment or options and cars will soon
have wireless Internet service and will even read your e-mail aloud
to you. However, don't be too dazzled. High-tech gadgetry is
fascinating and even fun, but it's no substitute for getting a
car's fundamentals absolutely right. By Paul Ingrassia.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ UP YOUR HAMBURGERS WITH SEARED AVOCADOS
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BARBECUE-LIFEBEAT _ Today Americans are barbecuing with
fresh zeal, and along with the old standbys _ hamburgers and
chicken _ are adding adventurous side dishes. Just in time for
Memorial Day, the traditional start of summer, here are some
unusual but simple barbecuing ideas from Kevin McCarthy, chef of
The Point, a luxurious Adirondack resort. To the traditional fare
he adds such fruit and vegetable accompaniments as table grapes
with venison or fish; seared avocados with hamburgers and sausages;
and that tart Italian chicory, radicchio, with beef or chicken.
WITH PHOTO. By Jane Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   DOTING PARENTS OF HARD-WON CHILDREN OFTEN CAN'T BEAR TO LET GO
</P>
<P>
   ANXIETY-PARENTING-LIFEBEAT _ Take normal new-parent anxiety. Add
years of effort, expense, dashed hopes and loss on the road to
childbearing. Throw in a dose of disbelief that the long process is
finally over. What you end up with, say experts, is a parenting
style unique to parents of ``hard-won'' kids _ children who arrive
after infertility, multiple miscarriages, or a long adoption
process. Recently, there have been some huge strides in recognizing
such post-infertility parenting issues as anxiety and
overprotectiveness. Being aware of some of the issues before they
occur can make the parenting of hard-won children less stressful.
By Monika Guttman.
</P>
<P>
   TEN WAYS TO BEAT VARICOSE VEINS
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-VARICOSEVEINS-LIFEBEAT _ Varicose veins aren't
life-threatening, but they can make people very self-conscious.
Normally, thigh and calf muscles help pump blood upward toward the
heart; one-way valves in leg veins open to encourage this. However,
if you sit or stand for long periods, these valves don't seal
properly. Blood then pools in the veins and stretches them. The
bulging results _ visible through the skin _ are known as varicose
veins. Exercise, weight control, certain herbs and the use of
compression hose can improve circulation and diminish varicose
veins. Dietary changes can also help. Blueberries, blackberries,
cherries and bilberries, which are rich in anthocyanosides, a type
of flavonoid, are said to strengthen veins and valves. Other
remedies for the problem include homeopathy, dietary supplements,
acupuncture, Ayurveda and rubdowns with essential oils. By Michael
Castleman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
