<SLUG> BC-INTERNET0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lab tests supplements' content
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Though the world of natural supplements is confusing
and frequently contentious, it is home to a few advocates who are
consistently reliable, responsible and clear. One of the most
notable is Mark Blumenthal, founder and director of the American
Botanical Council, an independent nonprofit group, and editor of
the peer-reviewed journal HerbalGram.
</P>
<P>
   Now Blumenthal has lent his expertise to a new Web enterprise,
and it looks like a winner. Consumer Lab (www.consumerlab.com) is
conducting privately financed tests of vitamins, herbs and other
nutritional supplements to determine whether the content of the
products matches industry standards and the manufacturers' label
claims. Brands that hold up under scrutiny are listed on the site
and receive the right to display the trademarked CL seal.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the site has reviewed various brands of gingko biloba,
vitamin C, the antidepressant SAMe, the osteoarthritis supplements
glucosamine and chondroitin sulfate, and the prostate support herb
saw palmetto. The findings are provocative: Significant numbers of
the supplements lacked key components or did not contain the
advertised percentages of active ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Chief personnel for Consumer Lab are William Obermeyer, formerly
a high-ranking natural products chemist with the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration, and Dr. Tod Cooperman, founder of a group that
rated consumer satisfaction with managed care companies.
</P>
<P>
   This site is worth bookmarking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
