<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SPINE0530-COX     05-29 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPINE0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cure for paralysis closer
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The cure for paralysis from a spinal injury is
closer than ever, but that only means there's no longer a consensus
that it's impossible. Not only is it too soon to predict when
people will walk on formerly paralyzed legs, it's still impossible
to predict how medical science will make that happen, say
researchers for the prominent Miami Project to Cure Paralysis at
the University of Miami, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The optimistic view is that we're looking in years or decades
rather than centuries,'' said anatomy professor Robert Fyffe, who
directs the biomedical sciences Ph.D. program in the School of
Medicine at Wright State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to find out how all the different parts
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyffe's WSU program is one of the leaders in drawing that map
and user's guide for the central nervous system. It is providing
sophisticated imaging data to construct the first large-scale
computer model of spinal cord cells with thousands of functioning
synaptic connections, through which motor signals pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The connections are mind-boggling,'' Fyffe said, with a single
motor nerve cell receiving 20,000 to 50,000 signals in order to
control just a few fibers in a single muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's these thousands of connections that are lost when there's
a spinal injury,'' Fyffe said. ``So we're trying to figure out how
things are working at the single cell level. What are the important
aspects of the connections? How are these systems organized? How
are things altered when there is an injury?''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the basic research at WSU and other centers, research
focuses on enhancing the lives of the 250,000 paralyzed Americans
with spinal cord injuries and on what the Miami Project calls the
five steps to a cure, according to W. Dalton Dietrich, the
project's scientific director.
</P>
<P>
   They are identifying which injuries are most responsive to
treatment, limiting the early damage from an injury, regenerating
nerve growth, enabling regenerated nerves to pierce the body's
fortress protecting the central nervous system and rehabilitating
control over newly mobile limbs.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical spinal injury, Fyffe said it is the axons of the
neurons that are damaged. The axons extend as far as several inches
away from a neuron's cell body, passing down the spinal cord to
stimulate the nerves that control the muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can protect these cells from dying off because their
axons have been damaged,'' Fyffe said, ``and then facilitate the
ability of the axon to regrow past the injury site, that's really
what regeneration or recovery of function in spinal cord injuries
is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The neurons on both sides of the injury still work, he said.
``What they're losing is all the inputs. So if only we could get
the connections back, we could get them working under voluntary
control again.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in spinal cord research was rekindled locally last week
with the news that Dayton police officer Mary Beall was paralyzed
below the waist after she was shot in the neck May 15. Considerable
progress has been made even in the 13 months since activist-actor
Christopher Reeve merged his foundation with the American Paralysis
Association to form the Christopher Reeve Paralysis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _ London researchers were able to regrow and reconnect nerve
fibers in the damaged spinal cords of laboratory rats with the help
of neurotrophin proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Neurotrophins are growth factors that help the central nervous
system develop, Fyffe said. They already had shown promise in
limiting what's called secondary damage, which spreads from the
site of a spinal injury in the hours following the injury.
</P>
<P>
   _ By injecting paralyzed rats with embryonic stem cells,
researchers at Washington University in St. Louis restored movement
to their legs nine days after their spines were injured. Stem cells
are the undeveloped cells that have not yet committed themselves as
specialized parts of, say, lung tissue, heel bone or arm muscle,
but their use is controversial because they come from human embryos
after abortions or miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   _ A surgically implanted electrical device, with a computer chip
in the abdomen wired to 15 electrodes on nerves and muscles in the
legs, helped a paralyzed Belgian man walk with special crutches in
March. Although scientists cautioned the device was effective only
for certain types of paralysis and only for short distances, it was
seen as an early step to artificially replicating motor signals
from the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll take a combination of therapies,'' Fyffe said.
``I don't think there will be a day when someone stands up and
says, 'We've got the cure now.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
