<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Can you please provide a mailing address for Erin Brockovich?
</P>
<P>
   _ G.A.L. A: Catch a glimpse of the real Erin in her cameo movie
role as a waitress? Erin Brockovich persuaded attorney Ed Masry to
employ her for $800 a month after hiring him to represent her after
an automobile accident. Brockovich still works with Masry. Send
missives to Masry &AMP; Vititoe, attention Kathy Brown, 5707 Corsa
Ave., 2nd floor, Westlake Village, Calif. 91362. Q: Is there a
difference between a tornado watch and a tornado warning? My boss
thinks they are the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rick Y.
</P>
<P>
   A: Time to enlighten the boss. A tornado watch means the
possibility of storms turning into a tornado exists. These
favorable conditions may be hard to believe, says KXAN's
meteorologist Jim Spencer, since when you hear the watch you may be
looking at a nice blue sky. A warning means action is required
since severe weather, such as a tornado, is imminent. In the case
of a warning, a tornado has been sighted on radar and may in fact
be on the ground. Time to seek shelter. How to remember which is
more serious? Warning (more imminent) has more letters than watch.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a nonprofit organization called Jupiter Index that
supposedly helps people with literacy, mainly writing and
composition? A group was doing door-to-door solicitations claiming
the above. Questions concerning their goals were answered vaguely.
If this is a scam, the public needs to be warned, as their story
sounds plausible. Was I correct in not giving a donation?
</P>
<P>
   _ Martha R.
</P>
<P>
   A: When in doubt, demur. The Better Business Bureau maintains a
file of information on charities and is developing a Web site with
the data (e.g., percentage of raised funds going to programs or
administration). Jupiter Index has not filed any information with
the BBB. While charities are not required to file information, they
are encouraged to do so, says BBB President John Etchieson. Next
time you are approached by the group, ask for printed material and
contact information.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for the bonnet-style hair dryer, Dazey brand if
possible. Who sells them?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.T.
</P>
<P>
   A: Dazey Soft Bonnet Hair Dryers are available on the Web at
www.earthcommerce.com ($36.80 plus S &AMP; H).
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's already starting! Last summer, my trash can turned into
the fly factory. It was impossible to keep flies from laying eggs
(maggots, yuck!) by the hundreds, thousands, in my trash. I cannot
keep the trash inside. I have scrubbed the can with bleach, tried
spraying it (daily) with a flying-insect bug spray, had my pest
control treat the area around it with pesticide and used kitty
litter/baking soda on the bottom of the can. How do I keep my trash
can from being the local fly pick-up bar?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: What's a nice tse-tse like you doing in a can like this? It
may not be you; it may be your neighbors, notes Jimmie Roach, chief
sanitarian at the Texas Department of Health. Check the can lid. If
the can has a tight fitting lid and is kept clean, the problem
could be nearby open areas. Are you close to a farm, ranch or
poultry operation? Are your neighbors as conscientious as you are
about bagging refuse and keeping containers clean? Is the
neighborhood rife with large dogs creating a manure problem? Roach
advises checking within a one- to two-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to see where I can get a copy of the film that was
shown at the Washington Press Club dinner (I think) of Clinton in
``The Final Days.'' I saw part of it on the ``Today'' show, but
it's so funny, I'd like to have a copy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Amy Brees
</P>
<P>
   A: The White House Correspondents Dinner has become a highlight
of political entertainment. C-SPAN is hawking this political video,
currently priced at $24.95 (plus shipping and tax). President
Clinton's tongue-in cheek presentation wooed the usually cynical
crowd with vignettes of what life at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue is
like for a president looking at retirement (delivering his wife's
brown-bag lunch, etc.). To order, call (877)662-7726 or visit
www.c-spanstore.com. The cast of NBC's ``The West Wing'' also did a
spoof at the correspondents' dinner, which is not available for
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I cannot afford to use air-conditioning. When it gets humid,
I drown my body in talcum powder to sleep. I even sprinkle it on my
sheets and pillows. Will the powder absorb oil, not just
perspiration on my skin? I am afraid of doing something that would
make me more wrinkled. And will the talc on my pillow, if I inhale
some, harm me?
</P>
<P>
   _ B. Evans
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, the talcum powder will absorb oil and, no, it is not a
good idea. Dermatologist Steven Zimmet warns the powder could lead
to overdrying of your skin. If untreated, the dry skin contributes
to wrinkling and could develop into a skin disease such as xerotic
eczema. In addition, Dr. Zimmet warns there may be a link between
talcum powder use and ovarian cancer. Cornstarch powder may be a
better selection for perspiration control. Inhaling it? Excessive
amounts could cause respiratory problems, reports Doug Borys of the
Central Texas Poison Control Center. Problems have been reported
with chronic use of powder, although using small amounts is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have recently acquired a collection of antique knives, some
as much as 100 years old. Some show age marks and discoloring. What
can I do to keep them from deteriorating more? At first I put a
light coat of oil on each after they were handled, but I've since
been warned that the oil will seal in moisture and make things
worse. Short of putting them in a vacuum, what is best?
</P>
<P>
   _ Ron Brown
</P>
<P>
   A: Veteran custom knife maker Scott Costa (830-693-3431) says it
is difficult to know what is best for your knives without seeing
them. However, most older knives are high carbon steel that need
some protection to retard tarnishing. His suggestion? Put the oil
away, and pick up a silicon-impregnated gun rag, which coats a
blade with a protective film. Always wipe blade after handling.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a recent convert to Diet Mountain Dew from Diet Coke, and
was told that the ``Dew'' has twice the caffeine. Is this true? Is
that why I'm typing this e-mail so quickly?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not twice, but a whole lot more. Diet Coke (12 oz.) contains
46 milligrams of caffeine; Mountain Dew, 55. Caffeine is a bitter
white alkaloid and a mild stimulant. Dew is a lemon-lime beverage
of unusual color concocted by soft drink salesman Bill Jones in
Marion, Va., in 1961. It is the preferred beverage on long-distance
drives. Q: Do you know where I can purchase a ZIP code directory?
</P>
<P>
   _Belinda Sandoval
</P>
<P>
   A: ZIP is ``an acronym for Zone Improvement Plan.'' ZIP codes
for specific addresses can be obtained online at www.usps.com.
Directories are available in hard copy ($31.50) at local post
offices or from the National Customer Support Center, United States
Postal Service, 6060 Primacy Parkway, Suite 201, Memphis, Tenn.
38188-0001. Obtain order forms from your local post office and
include payment. Shipment will take up to four weeks. Q: I observed
The New York Times is published in Texas, but the format is
practically identical to that published in New York. How does this
come about?
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul G.
</P>
<P>
   A: The New York Times is printed in 12 locations around the
country. The information is electronically transmitted via
satellite to these locations. The Times' own fleet of trucks
distributes the papers to each region.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX, 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
