<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medical advances at the bottom of the mug
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I do not take my health news full
strength. I take it with the milk and sugar of wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   I am selective. I ignore the salubrious medicinal effects of
Brussels sprouts, squid brain and exotic teas made of powdered
pumpkin seeds, orange rinds and just a touch of power-steering
fluid. I concentrate instead on the health-giving qualities of red
wine, select food preservatives and the orange powder on cheese
curls.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Journal of the American Medical Association
released a study that was just my kind of scientific research. The
kind that justifies habits I already have. The kind that quiets
criticism from the opinionated and conspicuously healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that coffee-drinking prevents Parkinson's
disease. Or at least that people who drink buckets of coffee are
less prone to the disease. This is not precisely the same thing but
close enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 8,000 Japanese-American men in Hawaii found
coffee-abstainers were five times more likely to develop
Parkinson's disease than people who drank four-and-half to
five-and-half cups a day. A lot of coffee, but the scientists were
counting dinky little six-ounce servings as a cup. Not a healthy
10-ounce cup of Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Abstainers were two to three times more likely to be afflicted
by Parkinson's than those who merely drank one or two dinky cups.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers believe caffeine is the key to this. That means
highly caffeinated sodas and other health foods could have the same
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Parkinson's disease involves deterioration of nerve cells that
produce a chemical the body needs to control muscle movements.
That's why head and hand tremors are associated with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   How does coffee and caffeine work to inhibit this? Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   It may be something in the way caffeine works to stimulate the
nervous system. Or the way it works on the brain stem. It may even
be that the kind of people with nervous systems that demand coffee
have other things working in their body chemistry that fight off
Parkinson's. Can't tell.
</P>
<P>
   The article ends, unsurprisingly, with a plea for more research.
</P>
<P>
   What's surprising is not that a chemical that prevents serious
disease can be found in so pleasant a substance.
</P>
<P>
   Nature should work that way. Coffee feels as though it is doing
something good when it works its magic on your morning neural
chemistry. Why should we assume our bodies lie to us?
</P>
<P>
   What is strange is that after 600 years of drinking the stuff,
people are only now finding this out.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes right down to it, we really don't know that much
about a lot of our intake.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what would happen if coffee were only being introduced
now.
</P>
<P>
   How would you feel going to a Food and Drug Administration panel
and explaining that your company has just developed a liquid that
somehow works to quicken mental processes?
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't know quite how it works. No, you don't know its
side effects. Further, the effects you have documented differ
wildly from person to person.
</P>
<P>
   No, you are proposing distributing it without prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   And no, there would be no recommended dose. Actually, people
will never know how concentrated any cup of the substance is until
they sip it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is addictive. The withdrawal effects _ including a
headache that can feel like aliens hatching from the front of your
brain _ are short-lived and not life-threatening. And not to worry:
we will develop a massive distribution system that will ensure that
no American would ever be more than 1,000 yards from the product.
</P>
<P>
   No, it didn't seem to hurt the lab rats. It merely made them run
around in quick little circles.
</P>
<P>
   No, we do not plan on warning labels. Besides, we wouldn't know
exactly what to warn folks about.
</P>
<P>
   This would not be a very strong presentation.
</P>
<P>
   The regulatory panel would need to get back to you. Approval
might have to go through a few more hoops.
</P>
<P>
   More research is called for. And I, for one, am willing to
redouble my efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at mark.lane(at)news-jrnl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
