<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This is not your mother's microwave
 &HT;    By Shaun Conlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If ``computerized oven'' sounds like an oxymoron
or something out of ``Star Trek,'' take a look at The FlashBake 120
($1,700, www.flashbake. com), an oven as revolutionary as the
microwave, which seemed so very sci-fi just a few decades ago. The
stand-alone or wall-mounted unit utilizes a high-energy halogen
light controlled by a microprocessor. The oven is pre-programmed to
apply energy at different times during the cooking cycle to
penetrate and cook from any or all angles, depending on the food
and cooking mode chosen. The technology involved can bake, broil,
steam, grill, roast and even saute. Cooking with light as opposed
to microwaves or raw heat provides maximum flexibility and
versatility _ and there's no preheating required. ``Cooking with
light is the wave of the future,'' said Henry Colleti, president of
Vulcan-Hart, a supplier of commercial FlashBake ovens, which have
been in use since 1993. ``We're excited that this advanced
commercial cooking technology is now available to the chef at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
