<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quick View offers virus protection
 &HT;    By Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sue and Jacki:
</P>
<P>
   Using one of the free services, I want to set up a Web site for
my civic organization from which just the 25 members might access
information, such as bylaws, meeting notices, minutes, etc. Who
offers these services?
</P>
<P>
   _ Cheryl Smith, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Sounds like what you need to do is set up an intranet. It's
a bit different from the Internet, which is a huge, global computer
network. An intranet is a space on the Web where a group can easily
access and share documents, calendars and information. Intranets
are usually password-protected, which gives your group control over
who has access to its information.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: Give Intranets.com (intranets.com) and MSN.com
Communities (msn.com) a look-see. These intranet sites are FREE!
They'll help you every step of the way: From setting your site up
and designing it, to hosting and support.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Intranets.com is mostly geared toward small businesses, but
it could work for your organization too. They provide 25 megabytes
of space on their servers, you'll exist in their domain
(groupname(at)intranets.com), and you'll have control over who
visits your site. They offer scheduling, messaging, discussion,
document management, contact directory, instant messaging, news and
finance information. You can save files for others to download,
have a real-time conference with members of your group and use
e-mail to keep everyone in the loop on events.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: MSN Communities works like Intranets.com, except it is
geared more toward clubs, organizations, personal sites, photo
sites, family and communities. You'll exist in its domain, and each
member can have up to 30 megabytes of space. That's a good bit more
than Intranets.com. What's cool about MSN is that you can subscribe
to public community sites and see what everyone else is up to. But,
if you need privacy, you can create a private site. The public will
not be able to access your information. Access is by invitation
only.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Another way people are coming together is through community
Web sites. AtHomeNet.com, an Atlanta-based company, touts its
intranets for communities, associations and subdivisions. There is
no set-up or design fee. They do charge a monthly fee, depending on
the number of members.
</P>
<P>
   Jacki: The idea is to improve and promote communication within
residential communities. You pretty much get the same features
we've described. The difference with AtHomeNet is that you can
purchase your own domain name. You can decide the exact name of
your intranet. For instance, if you live in a subdivision called
Cambridge Park, you could name your intranet cambridgepark.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sue: Community intranets can display their own advertisements
ranging from home sales to finding a baby sitter. Ads can be
designated as public or private. We thought this was a great
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Cleere and Jacki Rudd write for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail questions to techsavvy(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
