<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lord, he's _ a Pibber?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Youthful rebellion takes many forms. My first
coming-of-age rebellion was to hide in the ditch when the piano
teacher came. It was the beginning of the end of lessons I
detested.
</P>
<P>
   My wife, who didn't want to take swimming lessons in seventh
grade, defied her mother and got a two-piece suit to protest.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest son chose rebellion of a fashion as a middle-schooler.
He dyed his sandy hair auburn.
</P>
<P>
   None of this guaranteed, we told ourselves, that our youngest
son, now in the autumn of age 12, would ever fall to said
condition. Sure, he would disobey on occasion and act like a kid.
But he would never make some sort of kooky symbolic statement that
tossed convention out into the slop, or denounced his heritage. Not
him.
</P>
<P>
   Then a few days ago he made the most jarring announcement ever
made in an ever-tranquil home.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Dr Pepper. Mr. Pibb.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Pibb? This cannot be so. My son and Dr Pepper have been
linked almost since birth, sharing the same birthplace: Waco. On
steamy summer days, they were more than 10, 2 and 4. They were
every half hour.
</P>
<P>
   As one who loved Dr Pepper long before wings of fate delivered
me to its holy land, my heir's love affair touched me. Now his new
dalliance pains me.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could bite off ``c's'' and ``t's'' he was requesting
Dopper Pepper. Waco being the nation's per-capita Dr Pepper
consumption capital, he was contributing to the cause almost before
he consented to solid food.
</P>
<P>
   TWO ONE-SODA GUYS
</P>
<P>
   Just like his dad, my son, whose initials are RC, would never be
caught with any but DP. It was there for him in good times and bad,
for richer or poorer, for pizza party or Amoxycillin.
</P>
<P>
   And then what happened in his sixth-grade year but a flirtatious
vending machine at school that caught his eye. It had no DP. Based
on a handsome promotional contract, Waco schools vend Coke products
exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was at school that he tried this Dr Imposter. At first I
know it was in protest (I'd seen him turn up his nose at Mr Pibb in
restaurants). Then it came with less resistance. Then he was under
its spell.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who loves Dr Pepper is wise to the crafty attempts of
competitors in the industry to copycat the formula Charles Alderton
whipped up at the Old Corner Drug.
</P>
<P>
   FIZZY FORGERIES
</P>
<P>
   The Dr Pepper Museum has an occasional display on these efforts,
showing all the Dr Fauxes and Dr Fakes. Attempts at matching the Dr
Pepper formula were made way before the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to present, the first mass-consumed effort was the late,
not-great Dr. Wells. Museum director Joe Cavanaugh blames Dr. Wells
for a misimpression Dr Pepper still must deal with. There's no
prune juice in Dr Pepper. None. But the imitator had it.
</P>
<P>
   Mr Pibb was Coke's venture into the field of Pepper imposters, a
field which continues to grow as super stores and grocery chains
introduce their own attempts. Cavanaugh estimates that the world
has 20 to 30 attempts at it.
</P>
<P>
   And now my son has been seduced by one of them. When I sent him
away to school I figured all sorts of influences might change him.
He'd probably find girls, and interests to which I'd not exposed
him. He'd probably find new foods on the cafeteria that appealed to
him. But I never imagined that his schooling would lead him into
the arms of another soda.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I should refuse to play along. Maybe I should ignore his
request for the 2-liter Pibb at the store. The indignity of it all.
To think that some of my hard-earned cash is underwriting rank
fakery of a national treasure, here in Pepper heartland.
</P>
<P>
   I'll do it. The next time he requests Mr Pibb from me, I'll show
him. I will hide in a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8773 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECH-GAMER0530-COX     05-29 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-GAMER0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   As a revamp of a bona fide classic, Excitebike 64 ($60;
www.nintendo.com; for Nintendo 64) faithfully pays tribute to its
heritage while bringing the simple side-scrolling dirt bike game up
to speed with the 3-D gaming era. Not to be confused with a
sophisticated motocross simulation, Excitebike 64 is all about
mud-mucking motocross mayhem while suspending disbelief. A great
selection of decently animated bikes and riders, each with specific
strength and weakness, race around more than 20 handsomely designed
indoor and outdoor tracks. As with the original, the excitable
bikes come equipped with a finite amount of ``turbo,'' which will
overheat and stall a motor if overused, making for some
strategically selected high-speed overthrusting. Aside from
farcical lateral control during ``Whaaahooo!'' airtime, Excitebike
does have a fairly accurate physics model that offers enough
realism within its larger-than-life premise to make it the best
``arcade'' dirt bike racer to be found on the N64.
</P>
<P>
   Are you the kind of acquisitive, collective person who proudly
displays ``complete sets?'' Do you scour every inch of game levels
seeking ``secrets?'' Do you count the cracks in the sidewalk and
make certain that at the end of each walk equal numbers of cracks
have been crossed with right and left feet? Do you think you're
clever? In short, Alundra 2 ($40; www.activision.com; for Sony
Playstation) takes obsessive-compulsive disorders, burns them onto
a Playstation disc, then spins them round and magnifies them to a
power of two. It's intricate and ornery, a puzzle-ridden
action/adventure role-playing game of ludicrous proportions.
There's no artificial intelligence to be seen as everything is
pattern based, but the sheer exploratory extremis gameplay should
keep any gamer into these sorts of games happy for a long, long,
long while.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Thief II: The Metal Age ($40, www. eidosinteractive.com; for
Windows PCs) tiptoes the same path as its predecessor, adding a
handful of new features but, for the most part, succeeding as an
expansion rather than a true sequel. The original first-person
sneaker, ``Thief: The Dark Project'' was the surprise breakthrough
hit of 1998, a thinking-person's shooter emphasizing stealth,
timing and cold calculation over brute force. As master thief
Garrett, you creep through the night, hiding in the shadows,
awaiting the proper moment to pick a pocket, dash into an alcove
or, if you must, strike a blow. The game's graphic engine hasn't
been updated, the enemies still tend to be blocky-looking and not
too bright, and there's no multiplayer game. Yet the sinister,
gloomy experience as a whole remains immersive, tense and fun.
Thief II offers new weapons, great voice acting and 3-D sound
effects, challenging new enemies, a variety of missions, plus 16
large, interesting and beautiful levels. It remains an innovative
concept and the new installment is a solid successor to the
groundbreaking original, worth many hours lurking in the shadows
and scurrying across the rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
