<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growth of online grocery services says something about our
society
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The city of Atlanta is under siege. Invading armies of
vans and trucks are everywhere, driving up and down our streets,
stopping at any house that will let them in, bribing our children
with Pokemon cards and us with fresh produce and free delivery.
Like they say on ``Star Trek,'' ``Resistance is futile.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is the invasion of the online grocery stores. WebVan
(www.webvan.com) has already marched through town and HomeGrocer
(www.homegrocer.com) will follow on June 14. The addition of
HomeGrocer will make Atlanta one of the few two-online grocery
towns in America. (Three, if you count online convenience store
Kozmo.com.) We only have one newspaper but a variety of online
delivery services. We can get stamps, Starbucks, Krispy Kremes and
cola delivered right to our homes with a click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, New York.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Atlanta's wealth of online delivery services says
something about the changing world we live in. It probably says
something deep and profound about the increasing impact of the
Internet on daily lives. It also probably speaks volumes about the
increasing number of ordinary people using the Internet to
accomplish the routine tasks of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly I think it says people are tired of lugging cases of
soda and 10-pound bags of cat box litter out of the grocery store,
into their cars and then into their homes. Why spend your precious
spare time waiting in milelong checkout lines and then dragging
groceries around in those paper-thin plastic bags, when some
pleasant grocery courier will happily do it for you, refuse to take
tips and charm the kids with pockets full of goodies.
</P>
<P>
   You can't swing a cat in metro Atlanta without seeing a WebVan
truck on its way to or from some household that's probably giddy
with excitement that the grocery guys are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Our grandmothers used to have groceries delivered, too, but it
was never front-page news. But remember, for a generation that
lives with do-it-yourself checkout lines, automatic bank tellers
and self-service gas stations, ordering groceries online and having
them brought to your door whenever you want and deposited exactly
where you want seems downright revolutionary. Online grocery
shoppers are more than eager to tell you about their adventures.
</P>
<P>
   They do it with a mix of awe and wonder that makes old-fashioned
grocery shoppers want to log on and order a loaf of bread, some
peanut butter, three oranges and a box of cornflakes _ even if they
don't need any.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at WebVan and HomeGrocer both say a little competition
in the online grocery business is a good thing for everybody. They
claim it will help people to think of alternative ways to shop for
groceries. WebVan spokesman Bud Greeby says just because we've been
shopping at the supermarket for decades doesn't mean it's the best
way to shop for groceries. He could be right and he could be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Our fascination with online grocery shopping could be a fad that
will fade once the novelty of it all wears off. Or it could be a
huge hit with time-crunched families who still have to pick up dry
cleaning they dropped off three months ago, never mind find time to
get to the market.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, even the most computer-phobic people in town are
putting WebVan through its paces. Business is so brisk, the company
has literally run out of trucks and is using plain old unmarked
trucks to make deliveries. This is not to say that WebVan is
problem-free.
</P>
<P>
   Delivery areas are determined by ZIP code, and residents in
several suburbs both north and south of the city report heated
online and offline debates with WebVan representatives insisting
they do live where they say they live. While the selection is
extensive, you get every last box of cereal or flavor of ice cream.
And as addicted as we may become to online grocery shopping, there
will always be those double coupon days at the local market when
boneless chicken breasts are on sale for 99 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes online shopping doesn't make sense, and stopping off
for a bottle of milk on the way home actually is easier than online
ordering. But of course, 20-pound bags of dog food are another
story altogether as any pet owner will tell you.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a WebVan truck or a UPS delivery man hopping out
of his truck with a pile of boxes that have the Amazon.com logo
stamped all over it speaks volumes for how wired a city and its
residents are. Those trucks mean that somebody inside the houses
they're headed for has computers or access to a computer and is
using them to make purchases to save time, to save money or just
because they think it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a Harris Poll or a batch of Internet pundits to
tell you the Internet is everywhere. Just keep an eye out for those
online delivery trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
