u l BC-ILLUSTRATORS0530-COX     05-29 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLUSTRATORS0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Illustrators gather to promote positive images of
African-Americans
 &HT;    By Rachel Kipp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRBORN, Ohio _ The pictures in a simple children's book speak
a thousand words to Willis ``Bing'' Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a visiting professor in the African and African-American
Studies program at Wright State University, sees the images of
African-American people and culture in children's books as part of
the key to how children perceive themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-esteem is partly sourced by how the society views and
portrays them,'' Davis said. ``By putting forth positive images,
images that look realistic and show people in positive way can help
influence positive image and self-concept.''
</P>
<P>
   As he prepares to finish his year-long stay at WSU, Davis is
giving the public a change to get to know the life and art of three
book illustrators who are promoting realistic images of
African-Americans. ``Reading Images: African-American Fine Artists
as Illustrators'' is the theme of symposium Thursday at the WSU
Student Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept came as a result of wanting to share the
creative efforts of a couple of African-American artists working in
an arena where they sell and paint and work the gallery scene but
also do work illustrating books as a means of trying to get out to
the general public more positive images of African-Americans and
the African-American experience, while at the same time encouraging
more involvement in reading,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The participants are Tom Feelings, an artist and retired
professor from Columbia, S.C.; Jon Onye Lockard, a professor at the
University of Michigan, and Dayton native Tyrone Geter, who also
lives in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The three illustrators will create a sequence of
African-American history through children's books. Feelings book,
``The Middle Passage,'' represents 20 years of research into the
persecution of Africans captured and transported under horrible
conditions to be sold as slaves in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to tell a very adult subject matter using the form
of a children's book but expanding it by using elements from black
culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The illustrators will progress from facts to folklore starting
with Lockard's for ``Ebony Sea,'' written by Irene Smalls-Heltor.
In the book, a man recounts the legend of a group of slaves
transported by way of the Middle Passage who choose to follow a
woman back into the sea rather than become slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said ``Irene and the Big Fine Nickel,'' also written by
Smalls-Heltor completes the cycle by telling the story of an
African-American girl living in Harlem in the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Geter said he thinks the works he did for Irene are some of his
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every book I've ever done I've tried to make (the
illustrations) say something positive about black people and people
in general,'' Geter said. ``(Irene) is about a time when Harlem was
actually safe. When people sat on stoops and actually communicated
with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said each illustrator has worked to create positive
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping to be able to gather a variety of things,'' Davis
said. ``No. 1 to interact and applaud highly skilled and highly
recognized African-American visual artists; No. 2 to get an insight
into the function and role of illustrations in books that will
depict people in a positive light; and the third would be that (the
audience) will recognize the contribution artists can make to the
positive development of all young people both inside the culture
and outside the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
