<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nothing but the truth of contrite reviewer
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Comes now the plaintiff, J.G. Warner, who makes these
representations to this honorable court:
</P>
<P>
   1. Plaintiff states that on or about April 5, 2000,
representatives of Plantronics, a California firm, sent him one of
the company's Model CT10 cordless headset telephones to use in the
hope he would review it in his newspaper column.
</P>
<P>
   2. After using the Model CT10, and carefully studying the user's
manual (Exhibit A) included with it, plaintiff did write a review
of the CT10 which was published on or about May 14.
</P>
<P>
   3. While using the Model CT10, plaintiff noted that if the
telephone box was clipped to the user's belt as instructed, the
telephone's keypad was upside down. Before mentioning this in his
review, he again carefully perused the manual (Exhibit A) for some
explanation. Finding none, plaintiff mentioned this in his review
(Exhibit B), writing that the keypad was upside down for ``reasons
that escape me.''
</P>
<P>
   4. On May 16, plaintiff received an electronic communication
(Exhibit C) from a reader who stated: ``The phone clips upside down
so that when you look down to dial, it appears right side up.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Plaintiff was made to feel slow-witted and stupid, and his
reputation as a wide-awake newspaper columnist was severely
tarnished, as a result of his failure to note this fact in his
review of the Model CT10. Plaintiff submits that Plantronics is the
proximate cause of his emotional and professional agony, because it
failed to explain its purpose for the upside-down dialpad in the
instruction manual (Exhibit A).
</P>
<P>
   6. Defendant will no doubt suggest that had Plaintiff clipped
the box to his belt, he would have needed no explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Such a defense would be meritless, however, since Plaintiff is
one of a large class of potential users of the Model CT10 unable to
see their belts due to overlapping anatomical projections.
</P>
<P>
   7. Plaintiff states his mortification is so great that no amount
of monetary damages could allay it. Instead, he prays this
honorable court will punish defendant, so as to deter any future
attempts to embarrass reviewers of its products, by making its
executives spend an hour a day for one week dialing 900 numbers on
their CT10s while taking tango lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
