<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TECHNOBUDDY0530-COX     05-29 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine calling your favorite automobile mechanic and
first explaining that your Toyota is making a ``plunka plunka''
sound as it climbs hills. Then you ask him to diagnose and fix the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think would happen? Most likely he would ask you to
bring the car in. A lot of different problems can result in that
same sound. Even if he has a good guess about what the problem is,
he'd probably need to actually open the hood to fix it.
</P>
<P>
   But it's natural to think that _ with computers _ there is some
magical incantation that can be said over the phone, or some file
that can be deleted, to fix any problem. It just isn't so.
Computers aren't just gadgets made up of hardware, they're a
magical mix of hardware and software. And since each computer has
different components, different programs installed too, what would
fix one computer might not help on another.
</P>
<P>
   So, unless you're a computer guru, you need to face the reality
that _ when something goes wrong _ you need to be able to either
find and fix the problem yourself or bring it in to an RE (real
expert) to get it fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will help to learn a little about how you can diagnose
a problem. So today we'll open the hood a little and take a peek
inside.
</P>
<P>
   First, you need to know that most computer problems are caused
by the most recent change you made. If your computer was working
perfectly yesterday and stops working today, it's smart to think
about any changes you've made. So, at the first sign of trouble,
look back and try to find what you've changed and consider that
last change to be the main suspect for your problems. (Obviously
there are exceptions. Sometimes hard disks fail, components burn
out but start by assuming that your problem comes from software or
a new device.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're lucky enough to remember a change that you've made,
then try undoing that change. For instance, if you've just
installed new memory, take it out and return the computer to the
way it was before and see if it works. Or if you've hooked up a new
modem, take it out and replace it with the old one. If you've added
software, uninstall it (using the uninstall feature that you'll
find on the Control Panel in Windows) and see if that returns
things to normal.
</P>
<P>
   Never make two changes at the same time. For instance, if you
realize that you've recently installed a modem, added some software
and also changed the way you log on to the Internet, don't reverse
all those changes at one time. If you do and the problem goes away,
you won't know which of the many changes caused the problem in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Next, if things are still wanky, go through what may seem like a
silly exercise. Take my word, it's not silly at all. Start
searching for the obvious. Make sure that all the cables, including
the power cable, are plugged in tightly. I remember getting a call
from someone here at the newspaper about a modem that didn't work.
I spent 20 minutes checking all sorts of complicated things before
I noticed that the telephone line to the modem had become
unplugged. I fixed the modem by plugging it back in. So don't
ignore the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't solve the problem, consider opening up the
computer _ only if you feel comfortable doing so _ and reseating
all accessory cards (video card, sound card, etc.). Sometimes the
heat inside the computer can cause metal to expand and a poorly
seated card can get loose enough to cause intermittent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also remember to go to the Web sites for the programs you run.
Look for technical hints there. You may find a note from another
user, or from the company itself, that explains a glitch that could
be causing your problem.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, don't be afraid to get professional help. I know that a
lot of your friends are computer geniuses. You know it too because
they've told you that. Some of them are, no doubt about it. But
some aren't. Unless you are really sure of your friend's skills, go
ahead and spend the money to get professional help.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a lot of computers that were fixed so well that they
needed major surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
