<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-HANDWRITING0530-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can you write well?
 &HT;    By Keith Still
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nine-year-old Nicholas Le can, and his penmanship has
earned him more than respect from his teacher and classmates. It
impressed handwriting experts so much that they named Nicholas the
national handwriting champ for third-graders.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas was one of about 100,500 kids who submitted a
handwriting sample to the National Handwriting Contest sponsored by
Zaner-Bloser. The company publishes handwriting books that teach
children the proper way to form letters. Entries came from 47
states, the U.S. Virgin Islands and the Department of Defense
School in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put 218 percent of my effort into handwriting,'' said
Nicholas, who attends St. John the Evangelist Catholic School in
Hapeville, Ga. ``I've been doing cursive since the first grade. I
practice a lot at home and at school _ but mostly at school.''
</P>
<P>
   As National Grade Level Champion, Nicholas won an engraved pen,
an award plaque and a $500 U.S. savings bond. Though his friends at
school have asked him to split the bond with them, Nicholas said he
plans to use the money for college.
</P>
<P>
   To enter the contest, students in grades 1 through 6 wrote two
short sentences. First- and second-graders wrote in manuscript,
although some second-graders chose to submit a cursive entry.
Third- through sixth-graders wrote only in cursive. A panel of
Zaner-Bloser handwriting judges reviewed each entry and selected
state champions. Then Zaner-Bloser's master penman, Clinton
Hackney, chose national champions for each grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students' handwriting was judged on legibility,'' said
Georganna Harvey at Zaner-Bloser. ``The judges looked at the shape
of each letter, the slant, the size and the spacing between the
letters and between the words.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaner-Bloser began holding the contest nine years ago to
emphasize the importance of good penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handwriting is a vital skill that students will use for a
lifetime,'' Harvey said. ``Despite high-tech communication devices,
every business still depends upon pen and paper.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first year Nicholas entered the handwriting
contest, and it doesn't appear to be his last either. He's eligible
for three more years, and he's already practicing for the
fourth-grade competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win again next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
