<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. warming up to China
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The United States last week took the first step toward
becoming better friends with China. The U.S. House of
Representatives voted to grant China permanent ``normal trade
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   If the bill becomes a law, China will have full access to sell
its products to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate will vote on the bill in June.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate agrees, the U.S. Congress no longer will vote each
year on China's trading status.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, Congress has decided once a year whether
China has behaved well enough to be granted the privilege of
trading with America.
</P>
<P>
   The United States watches closely how well China treats its
citizens. Part of the bill requires a group to monitor China's
actions. China protested that section of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA WIN IS ERITREA LOSS
</P>
<P>
   The people of Ethiopia celebrated a major victory over the
country of Eritrea last week. The Ethiopian military broke through
Eritrea's central front, taking back the town of Zalembessa.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries on the Horn of Africa have fought for two
years over land along their 620-mile shared border. Eritrea
declared independence from Ethiopia in 1993. In 1998, Eritrea
claimed more land along the border.
</P>
<P>
   After losing Zalembessa, Eritrea's government declared it would
withdraw from the disputed land. Eritrea said it was leaving
voluntarily, but Ethiopia said Eritrea was forced
</P>
<P>
   to retreat.
</P>
<P>
   SPEARS' `OOPS!' SETS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Forget Madonna, Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston. Britney Spears
has beaten them all.
</P>
<P>
   The teen pop star set a one-week sales record for a female
artist with her second album, ``Oops! . . . I Did It Again.'' In
its first week, it sold 1.3 million copies,
</P>
<P>
   according to Soundscan.
</P>
<P>
   Spears' ``Oops!'' is the second-fastest-selling album ever. 'N
Snyc's ``No Strings Attached'' sold 2.4 million copies in its first
week earlier this spring. The Backstreet Boys'
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium'' holds the third spot. It sold 1.1 million copies
in its opening week.
</P>
<P>
   All three artists _ Spears, 'N Sync and the Backstreet Boys _
are on the Jive Records label.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
