<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ The government has put former
President Suharto under house arrest as it tries to bring him to
trial for corruption and abuse of power. The house arrest, which
comes almost exactly two years after Suharto stepped down after 32
years, carries strong symbolism in a nation that is struggling to
convert itself to a democraacy. By Seth Mydans. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PRISONERS (Tel Aviv) _ A court ruled Monday that two
jailed Lebanese guerrilla leaders, whose release has been demanded
by Hezbollah and urged by a U.N. envoy, should stay in jail until
their case is decided on July 12. By Joel Greenberg. (700 words0
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-CHINA (Yanji, China) _ Chinese police have dramatically
increased their efforts to forcibly expel North Koreans living in
China in recent months, creating a climate of fear along the border
_ and a potentially explosive international refugee crisis. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   PERU-POLITICS (Lima) _ Developments after President Alberto
Fujimori won a third consecutive five-year term. By Clifford
Krauss. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ALTHORP (Great Brington) _ It is spelled simply enough,
in just two syllables, with no strange or gimmicky combinations of
letters. But for centuries, it has been grievously mispronounced by
everyone who is not anyone. Why would the average person know that
the word Althorp is supposed to be pronounced AWL-trupp? Now Earl
Spencer, the owner of Althorp, the family's ancestral estate, is
changing that. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-POLITICS (Dateline to kum) _ George W. Bush and Al Gore
hold Memorial Day events in Fort Hood and in western Pennsylvania.
Gore appears with an Amry buddy. By James Dao and Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FOREIGN-POLICY (Washington) _ As the chief foreign policy
adviser for Gov. George W. Bush, Condoleezza Rice is widely viewed
as the most likely choice for national security adviser if Bush
makes it to the White House. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the world of politics.
</P>
