   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHILD-WELFARE (New York) _ In poorer neighborhoods across New
York City, where the child welfare agency is regarded as a potent,
ubiquitous presence, there is a real fear that a momentary crisis
can become something worse, that a parental mistake can lead to an
investigation. That in the nightmare case, a difficult child can
become a child removed from the parents by the agency. By Somini
Sengupta. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-WAITERS-RACE (New York) _ One reality has dominated the
city's enormous inventory of distinguished restaurants: a scarcity
of black waiters. Interviews with dozens of restaurant owners and
waiters, and with state, city and labor leaders reveal an industry
that acknowledges a dearth of black waiters, but offers several
reasons for their absence. By Glenn Collins with Monte Williams.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MICROBREWERS (Boston) _ The great beer awakening of the
mid-1990's suddenly jammed store aisles with fanciful brews like
Laughing Skull Bohemian Pilsner, Long Trail Double Bag Ale, Rogue
Shakespeare Stout and Pig's Eye Pilsner. For consumers used to
basic names like Coors and Bud, it was too much, too soon to
stomach. Some microbrewers collided head-on with distributors who
refused to carry their products and financiers who clamored for
profits even as sales growth slowed. Last year, for the first time,
more microbreweries in the United States closed than opened, and
more bottles will head for the clearance shelves this year. But
those craft brewers that lived through the shakeup _ and there are
many _ are telling a tale of leaner, more economical brewing, more
conservative growth, and more thoughtful business plans. They are
taking a breath before making another run on the American beer
market that is 80 percent controlled by Anheuser-Busch, Miller
Brewing and Coors. By Julie Flaherty.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE-SEARCH (Undted) _ Within a few weeks this spring, J.C.
Penney, Sears and Kmart all announced they were looking for new
chief executives. These separate recruiting drives have essentially
created a referendum on which of the ailing businesses is the
sickest. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   SUV-LIABILITY (Detroit) _ Looking at whether makers of sports
utility vehicles may someday face liability issues in the wake of
Ford Motor's admission that it is concerned about SUV's impact on
safety and the environment. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-INSURANCE (Shanghai) _ A look at foreign wrangling to grab
a piece of the untapped insurance market in China, and how that
might change after the country joins the World Trade Organization.
The Chinese have granted six of seven foreign insurance licenses to
American International Group, the financial services conglomerate
that was founded in China in the 1930's. But the favoritism shown
to the company has angered other foreign insurers, who contend that
China won't be able to behave that way once it joins the WTO. By
Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLLUTION (Baikalsk, Russia) _ Environmentalists in
Russia and abroad have accused the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill of
polluting Lake Baikal in Siberia, the world's largest body of fresh
water. The issue goes beyond the lake. Throughout the former Soviet
Union, industry has turned the nation's waterways into
environmental catastrophes. By Russell Working.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-COFFEE (Sao Paulo) _ Borrowing a page from OPEC's
successful pricing strategies on oil, major coffee producers led by
Brazil are hoping to exert more influence on what consumers pay by
keeping more coffee beans off the market. By Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Founded in 1920 and probably best
remembered _ at least by baby boomers _ for its role during the
anti-Vietnam war protests of the '60s and '70s, the American Civil
Liberties Union is taking a classic consumer marketing approach to
build new awareness and support for its causes. By Patricia Winters
Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, U.S. equity and financial markets are closed for the
Memorial Day holiday.
</P>
