<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OLYMPHOMA0530-COX     05-29 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPHOMA0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Treating cancer with radioactive antibodies
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When researchers over the past generation or so
have talked about looking for a magic bullet to attack cancer
cells, the drug Joan Martindale took last week was what they had in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to find some molecule on the cancer cells and
make an antibody to it,'' says Dr. Basel Yanes, the medical
director of oncology at Miami Valley Hospital. Antibodies attack
specific molecules, so if researchers could manufacture the
antibody and attach a radioactive element to it, they would have a
dedicated assassin for a particular cancer cell.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two decades of working on it, this is really the first
treatment we have with radioactive antibodies,'' Yanes says. Where
radiation and chemotherapy have traditionally attacked cancer cells
with a machine-gun spray, killing healthy cells in hopes of
destroying the cancer along with them, Yanes says, ``This is the
first treatment available where we can target the treatment
directly to the cancer cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Martindale's antibody attacks the cells of a slow-growing
lymphoma for which there has been no satisfactory treatment. In
preliminary research over two years, doctors said last week that
the tumors shrank in 97 percent of patients using the new drug,
Bexxar, and apparently disappeared in 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bexxar is six months to a year from approval for commercial use.
But it's available in clinical trials at eight hospitals from
Pennsylvania to Illinois, including Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was apprehensive,'' says Martindale, a Centerville woman who
pronounces her first name Jo Ann. ``It's virgin territory. You
don't know what you're getting yourself into. But I have a lot of
faith in Dr. Yanes, and if the research is positive, it will be a
great step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami Valley's trial is for patients who have tried chemotherapy
unsuccessfully, but the Dayton Clinical Oncology Program has a
similar trial for newly diagnosed lymphoma. Bexxar consists of two
doses a week or two apart and generally has side effects no worse
than a brief bout of flu, as opposed to chemotherapy's many weeks'
duration ravaging the whole body.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new concept in cancer therapy,'' Yanes says.
``We hope these new drugs will be more targeted and less toxic and
more effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with destroying cancer cells is that they are very
good at hiding from the natural immune system, which is why science
has turned to the laboratory for creating synthetic antibodies.
Bexxar is attracted to a particular protein that is on the surface
of virtually all lymphoma cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another approach is to target molecular defects at the genetic
level and find the drug that targets these enzymes or these certain
areas that control the growth of cancer cells,'' Yanes says.
``We're getting much smarter now because we understand how the
cancer cells grow. We have all these genetic abnormalities
identified.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining task is to make drugs that block the chemical
signal that stimulates cancer growth, or that shut down the enzyme
that helps a tumor grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' Yanes says. ``In the next
decade, we're going to have many of these new drugs. Many of them
are now available in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just joined a trial for pancreatic carcinoma. In another
trial that's not here, they've literally targeted drugs for
leukemia. All these drugs do the same thing. They identify the
defect that causes cancer cells to grow, and they attack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
