<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following  &UR; Science
Times &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, May 30:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRIZZLY-BEARS (Undated) _ This summer, the United States
Fish and Wildlife Service is expected to adopt a controversial plan
to put grizzly bears back in the Bitterroot region. A 15-member
committee will be charged with finding a way for the bears to
flourish and exist with humans, particulary those engaged in
backcountry recreation, logging, mining, and ranching. By Mrk Derr.
(1525 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FASTER-THAN-LIGHT (Undated) _ The speed at which light
travels through a vacuum, about 186,000 miles per second, is
enshrined in physics lore as a universal speed limit. Nothing can
travel faster than that speed, the textbooks say. But now, two new
mind-bending experiments have demonstrated how wrong that
comfortable wisdom is. By James Glanz. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELL-IMPLANTS (Undated) _ Hope is growing that neural cells
implanted into the brain can replace cells and restore functions
lost to stroke, spinal cord injury or neurological diseases like
Parkinson's and Alzheimer's, most of which have no effective
treatments. And some cases to date are showing startling results.
By Andrew Pollack. (1975 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELL-THERAPY () _ Stem cells, the master cells from which
all other cells in the body develop, might be used to replenish
many other tissues in the brain. Companies are already trying to
harness the cells to rebuild hearts, bone, blood and other tissues,
part of a field coming to be called regenerative medicine. At Geron
Corporation, scientists have already turned embryonic stem cells
into heart muscle cells that spontaneously beat in the test tube.
Studies in mice have shown these cells stably integrate into the
heart. Eventually stem cell therapy might be used to rebuild hearts
after a heart attack, since heart muscles do not regenerate
themselves after they are killed. By Andrew Pollack. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MILLER-EVOLUTION (Undated) _ A conversation With Geoffrey F.
Miller, an evolutionary psychologist at University College, London.
As Dr. Miller sees it, the most outstanding features of the human
mind _ its creativity, its consciousness, its moral sense, its
artfulness and its love of a good punchline _ were shaped, not by
natural selection, as most biologists have assumed, but by the
other strong evolutionary force called sexual selection. In this
view, which he lays out in a newly published book called ``The
Mating Mind,'' humans are imaginative, artistic, humorous, and
relatively amiable for the same reason that peacocks fan their
fancy tails and cicadas thrum through the summer: to attract mates
and hence increase their so-called reproductive success. By Natalie
Angier. (1745 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SWALLOWED-CAMERA (Undated) _ They haven't figured out how to
squeeze Raquel Welch into it, but scientists with an Israeli
company have made a pill-sized videocamera that takes a fantastic
voyage of its own, traveling through the digestive tract and
transmitting pictures along the way. The device, which consists of
the camera and light source, radio transmitter and batteries within
a sealed capsule slightly more than an inch long and less than half
an inch wide, is intended as a less invasive way to examine the
small intestine. By Henry Fountain. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SEADRAGONS (Undated) _ Normally, the sea dragon is the most
popular exhibit at the Long Beach Aquarium of the Pacific, but
lately its even more excitement is buzzing around its tank: one of
the weedy males is pregnant, with about 100 bright pink eggs
hanging prominently onto his tail. What has the aquarium world
watching so closely is not that the mother is a male: sea dragons
are among one of two fish groups whose males incubate the eggs.
Rather it is the hope that this notably sensitive species might
actually reproduce away from its natural habitat. No one has done
it before. By Rachel Uslan. (740 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on a
species of ant that thrives on a lack of diversity, distribution of
trees in forests and public suggestions for aiming the Hubble. By
Henry Fountain. (690 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIVING-WILLS-II (Undated) _ A Special Report, the second of
two parts: Planning for Death. Life doesn't have to end badly, and
families and patients can often get around painful treatments, but
it takes effort. Now, more and more doctors are learning how to
deal with such cases, and patients and families are becoming better
educated. By Denise Grady. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-THERAPY (Undated) _ Researchers are looking in
unexpected places for treatments and cures for cancer and are
turning up some interesting and possibly promising results from
novel forms of therapy. The results were unveiled at a recent
oncology conference. By Lawrence K. Altman. (1030 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Health myths today abound even more
than before, largely because of the power of the Web. The Personal
Health column explodes these myths. By Jane E. Brody. (1130 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Two recent studies _ one animal, one vegetable _ reported
progress in turning nature's stings toward healing purposes. The
tarantula and the hot pepper may have medicinal values. (215 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ The first controlled study of Viagra's ability to help women
with sexual dysfunctions has found that the drug did no better than
a placebo. (185 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Life spans of 195 umpires, born from 1836 to 1945, were
compared to life-expectancy data from actuarial tables. No
statistically significant deviation was found. The most likely
explanation, the researchers wrote, is that the job's stress is
offset by other benefits: after all, they noted, the workday is
rarely longer than four hours. (150 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Some experts now suggest keeping CPR therapy simple: only
chest massage. (285 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ On the relationship between a child's age and sleeping
patterns. (220 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Why does paper,
especially newsprint, turn yellow as it ages? By C. Claiborne Ray.
(295 words)
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
