<P>
   HOLIDAY-BOX-OFFICE (Hollywood) _ The holiday weekend, spurred by
a spectacular opening for Tom Cruise's ``Mission: Impossible 2''; a
solid debut for Jackie Chan's comic Western, ``Shanghai Noon''; and
strong holdover business for May hits like ``Dinosaur,''
``Gladiator'' and ``Road Trip,'' has seen a Memorial Day record of
$174.7 million in ticket sales for the top 12 films. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-ALAMO-MYTHS (San Antonio) _ The tension between mythology
and revisionism in the story of the Alamo meant that Stephen
Harrigan's new historical novel, ``The Gates of the Alamo,''
required as much historical research as imagination. By Jim
Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   ARMOR-RESTITUTION (Undated) _ In an unusual agreement that
extends beyond the normal barriers of restitution, the Philadelphia
Museum of Art and the State Art Collections in Dresden, Germany,
will announce Tuesday that five works of armor that had been in the
Philadelphia collection since 1977 have been returned to the State
Art Collections, which claimed ownership of the pieces five years
ago. By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   HELLER-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Like such embarrassing Hemingway
works as ``The Garden of Eden'' and ``True at First Light,'' Joseph
Heller's ``Portrait of an Artist, as an Old Man'' is one of those
posthumously published books that form a sad coda to a
distinguished career. Reviewed by Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-MODELS-REVIEW (Undated) _ On AMC, ``Reel Models.'' Reviewed
by Neil Genzliner.
</P>
<P>
   TV-CLERKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ On ABC, ``Clerks,'' a new animated
series. Reviewed by David DeWitt.
</P>
