<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      05-29 1419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE CAUTION ON RETIREMENT ACCOUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problem: Alternative to Massachusetts Deferred Compensation Plan
</P>
<P>
   Age: 38
</P>
<P>
   Deferred compensation savings: $224,000
</P>
<P>
   50 percent Fidelity Growth Company fund
</P>
<P>
   25 percent AIM Weingarten fund
</P>
<P>
   25 percent Vanguard Industrial Index
</P>
<P>
   Contributions: $8,000 annually
</P>
<P>
   Q. I invest in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts' Deferred
Compensation Plan, where the investment management will change in
June. Instead of going with the new manager, I am considering
rolling my account into a plan offered by IMCA Retirement Corp.,
which focuses on Vantagepoint funds, although other funds are
available. What do you see as the pros and cons of this plan? How
much might I expect to have by ages 55 and 60?
</P>
<P>
   D.E., Dunstable, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you plan to focus on the Vantagepoint funds featured in
the four model portfolios offered in the literature that you sent
along, the chief con is their youth. Given your current
investments, the only portfolio that might serve your goals is
Long-Term Growth, which holds shares in seven different
Vantagepoint funds.
</P>
<P>
   All of these funds are less than a year and a half old, and
while a couple of them have produced respectable results so far _
the Aggressive Opportunities fund has a 26.69 percent one-year
record as this is written, and the Vantagepoint International fund
has an 18.69 percent one-year record _ I think there is just not
enough data to evaluate these funds.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, with a 20 percent position in Vantagepoint's Core Bond
Index fund, the long-term growth prospects are automatically dimmed
by a considerable factor. (Although in fairness, the bond fund is
the only one of the seven offerings that is above water in
year-to-date results, with a 1.17 percent year-to-date return.)
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons, I suggest you look to the 13 funds from other
families that are offered through IMCA. Looking at that list, you
might select Fidelity Blue Chip Growth fund as a reasonable proxy
for AIM Weingarten fund, and select either Fidelity Magellan or
Fidelity Contrafund to serve the slot in your portfolio formerly
held by Vanguard Index 500. American Century Ultra fund might then
take the place of Fidelity Growth Company fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to keep saving at an $8,000 annual rate and achieved
10 percent average total returns, you would have $1,542,108 at age
55, and $2,638,212 in the deferred compensation plan at age 60.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Selling a rental property
</P>
<P>
   Rental: $1,000 monthly
</P>
<P>
   Value of house: $165,000
</P>
<P>
   Q. I own a house that I rent, and I use part of the rentals to
cover living expenses. The tenant wants to buy the house, and if I
sell it, I would need to invest the proceeds to replace the rental
income. What investment would you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   W.D., Winchester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a solid plan, especially once you calculate the
taxes, insurance, and maintenance costs you are paying out of your
$1,000 monthly rental income.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, since you presumably would not be going through a real
estate agent in arranging the sale, you would net almost all of the
$165,000 gross proceeds, less the amount of your legal and closing
costs.
</P>
<P>
   You should, of course, explore your potential tax liabilities
resulting from the sale, but it seems likely that you would be well
ahead of the game in selling.
</P>
<P>
   Entering this week, the nation's best rate from a five-year
jumbo CD was 8.06 percent. (A jumbo is a CD for $100,000 or more;
the best rate on a CD of less than $100,000 was 8.05 percent.) At
the higher rate you would need to have a little less than $147,000
invested in such a CD to produce an income stream of $12,000 a
year. Your after-tax proceeds from a sale probably would exceed the
current net income from the property _ the gross rental minus
taxes, insurance, and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   If you do go along with the CD plan, keep in mind that interest
from an out-of-state bank is taxed at a higher rate on your state
income tax than interest from a Massachusetts bank.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Retirement income
</P>
<P>
   Age: 59 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Savings: $801,320
</P>
<P>
   25 percent bonds
</P>
<P>
   65 percent stocks and stock funds
</P>
<P>
   10 percent cash, CDs, and money market holdings
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have no debt except a 15-year mortgage of $115,000. I spend
about $50,000 a year in today's dollars. I stopped working at the
end of January and would like to continue to be retired.
</P>
<P>
   As of April 1, I had the investments outlined. If I start
collecting Social Security at age 62, I will collect $11,400
annually; I will get about $16,000 a year if I wait until age 65.
</P>
<P>
   I have set out a spreadsheet projection that includes an average
portfolio return of 8 percent, a 20 percent tax rate, and inflation
running at 3 percent. This showed that I would have enough money to
last until I am about 88 years old _ actually probably not enough,
since my mother lived to be 89.
</P>
<P>
   What suggestions can you make so that I can achieve my goal?
Since the market is so bad right now, I feel I have enough cash to
leave everything as it is. Nevertheless I do worry as the market
gets worse and worse, and wonder if I shouldn't change the
distribution a bit. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   R.M., Watertown, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I would be more than a bit nervous about this plan if I were
you.
</P>
<P>
   First, as you point out, your money would run out before you
died if you lived to the age of 89 _ and that's not dealing with
the prospect that the wonders of modern medicine will make
nonagenarians a good deal more common in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Second, your assumption of a 3 percent inflation rate is giving
yourself the best of it. I usually use 3.5 percent as a projection
against inflation, and sometimes I get nervous about even that
number.
</P>
<P>
   Third, when you include the state tax liabilities along with the
federal tax bill, that expense might go beyond 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the major thing that makes me worry about your plan is that
huge chunk of the portfolio that's in stocks and stock funds. With
only 35 percent of your portfolio in bonds and cash instruments,
you can count on the fixed-income portfolio to produce only about
$18,000 as an income stream.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, that means you will be looking to your stock
portfolio to bring in the other $32,000. It's unlikely the dividend
stream from your stocks and funds would represent much more than
$10,000, and it's probable that the figure is less. But at best,
you are looking for the stock portfolio to generate about $22,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Is this reasonable? Certainly it seems to work on paper, since
that $22,000 represents a market return (exclusive of the yield) of
only about 4.2 percent. But plans such as this can go awry quickly
if the stock market delivers not gains but losses in the early
years of the going. I am not predicting doom, but I do suggest that
you would be in a better situation if you reduced your reliance on
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what to suggest. As I said, I'd like to see the
fixed-income side of the portfolio beefed up a bit. In addition, I
suggest you rework your outline in several ways. One would be to
plug in the higher level of Social Security beginning at age 65,
letting you see whether that change improves the long-term outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Another change I'd suggest is to plug in 3.5 percent as an
estimate of inflation. And you might want to consider the
possibility that your total tax liabilities might run closer to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   With these results in mind, you could then consider a couple of
other options, both of them viscerally unpleasant. One would be to
take on some part-time work for the next few years _ perhaps
setting a goal of earning enough money so that you could live on
the actual portfolio yield plus your part-time income. Another
approach would be to try to rebudget so that you would be spending
a bit less.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one factor works in your favor. Unless I am misreading
your spreadsheet, I don't see a calculation of the effect that
paying off your mortgage after 15 years will have on the question
of how long your money will last. If you reduced the amount you
would be withdrawing from your savings by about $12,000 a year at
that point, the figures would look considerably better.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
