<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sick buildings make unhealthy working world
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The World Health Organization estimates that one of
every three workers is toiling in a workplace that makes them sick.
The culprit, says Business Week (June 5), is ``a stew of largely
undetected dangers, from the carbon monoxide and other contaminants
sucked into a building ... to volatile organic chemicals seeping
out of building materials.''
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Health and Safety Administration has standards
that are supposed to protect workers against individual
contaminants, but the standards were set for industrial workplaces
and have been ``force-fit to apply to white-collar offices.''
</P>
<P>
   An OSHA official tells Business Week, ``There is no federally
guaranteed protection from exposure to unhealthy air indoors.''
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE RICH ARE
</P>
<P>
   A million dollars isn't what it used to be in America's richest
towns, Worth (June) discovered in researching its fifth annual list
of the nation's 250 richest communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a fully loaded house _ a kitchen befitting a four-star
chef; bathrooms as big as the Ritz; top-of-the-line media rooms;
marble fireplaces and cherry paneling _ home buyers are plunking
down much more than a mere million, and often in cash,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   This year's top rich town is Jupiter Island, Fla., population
601, and median home sale price _ the unit by which the rich towns
were ranked _ of $1.98 million.
</P>
<P>
   Worth counted 76 rich towns in California, 46 in New York, 25 in
New Jersey, 18 in Massachusetts, 17 in Illinois and 12 in Florida _
and none in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The closest rich towns to Georgia were Kiawah Island, S.C., and
Biltmore Forest, near Asheville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   RICH, BUT NOT SPOILED
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of wealth, Forbes (June 12) devotes its 13th annual
investment guide to raising your kid in an age of wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handwringers say being born with a silver spoon will doom your
children's chances for success. Nonsense,'' says Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when a booming economy is producing unprecedented
wealth, the way to bring up kids so they won't be spoiled is to
teach them how to make their own money, the magazine advises.
</P>
<P>
   As for the investment guide itself, the magazine recommends that
everybody overhaul their investments to adjust to new tax laws and
lower the tax take on savings.
</P>
<P>
   AS FOR THE POOR...
</P>
<P>
   There's no disputing the fact there is a desperate labor
shortage among small businesses. But Inc. (June), a small- business
magazine, says this situation also has opened the doors for people
who wish to get off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt the transition from welfare to regular work can
be extremely trying for both employer and employee, the magazine
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But CEOs are quickly finding that with the right training,
employees fresh off the welfare rolls can become valuable and
dependable parts of any business,'' the magazine adds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
