<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TRADE-IMPACT-BOS &LR;      05-29 1777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-IMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNERS AND LOSERS IN THE TRADE BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Wednesday's congressional vote granting
China permanent normal trade relations, of PNTR, the tension that
defines the next chapter of our economic discourse was clear:
</P>
<P>
   Proclaimed President Clinton, ``Today the House . . . has taken
an historic step toward continued prosperity in America, reform in
China, and peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered AFL-CIO president John Sweeney, ``Without protections
for workers' rights and human rights and the environment, it is
certainly going to speed up the race to the bottom. . . . Good jobs
are bound to chase bad standards.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to sympathize with Sweeney, for when it comes to
trade, few interests are treated as cavalierly as those of
working-class Americans rightly suspicious of trade deals with
countries who find their competitive advantage not in productivity
or innovation but rather in low wages, repressed workers, and a
ravaged environment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when unions protest that Americans shouldn't be forced to
compete on that basis, they are rebuked as protectionist and
scolded that free trade with China is indubitably in the best
interest of America.
</P>
<P>
   But which America? That is the question underscored in the wake
of labor's big loss. The trade deal will have strikingly different
ramifications depending on one's place in the economic order. And
in the United States, unlike in parts of Scandinavia and elsewhere,
little attempt is made to ease the sting to workers by offering
them offsetting social benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just talking about the rich getting richer and the
poor getting richer at a slower rate,'' says US Representative
Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat who opposed the deal and is
a leader in the fight for fairer trade. ``We are talking about the
rich getting richer and the poor getting poorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who support the permanent status for China
acknowledge that the differential impact of that commerce will
likely reward US workers with higher skills and more education
while increasing pressure on lesser-skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any economist would agree that the effect is there,''
says William Cline, chief economist at the Institute of
International Finance, whose own work shows that trade pressures
work to impede blue-collar wages in this country.
</P>
<P>
   So who will suffer? ``If you are working in an automobile plant
or an electronics factory, if you are making steel, and certainly
if you are making apparel or toys or anything like that, all of
those are going to be directly threatened by PNTR for China,'' says
Robert E. Scott, international economist for the progressive
Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   If the most visible casualty will be lost jobs for some workers,
a second insidious effect is lost bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``When workers go into contract negotiations, time and again
they are told, `Hey, are you crazy, we will go and make this
somewhere else,' '' Frank says.
</P>
<P>
   Given the media's fascination with entrepreneurs, dot.coms, and
all things Internet, it is increasingly easy to lose sight of
working-class Americans. But in their new book, ``America's
Forgotten Majority: Why the White Working Class Still Matters,''
Ruy Teixeira and Joel Rogers contend that many more Americans than
is commonly realized work on the lower-skilled side of what the
writers term the ``great divide'' separating those who have
prospered in the new economy from those who have not.
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira and Rogers say the group tracked in their book, which
they identify as America's ``forgotten majority,'' makes up as much
as 55 percent of the US adult population.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of this group will face increased pressure from China,
says Teixeira, a senior fellow at The Century Foundation. ``For
people with less than a four-year degree, people who work in the
tradeable-goods sector, people who are more blue collar, the
competition is going to be stronger,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That group has already felt its standard of living under siege,
something highlighted by wage data in the book.
</P>
<P>
   From 1979 to 1998, college-educated whites saw their real
(inflation-adjusted) median wage grow by 12 percent, while
working-class experienced an 8.6 percent real wage decline. High
school dropouts, meanwhile, suffered a real wage loss of an
astounding 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it a coincidence that the era of declining real wages for
many Americans has also been an era of increasing international
trade, says economist Mark Weisbrot, codirector of the Center for
Economic and Policy Research in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Weisbrot says the effect is best seen by comparing two eras.
From 1946-1973, the median US hourly wage increased by about 80
percent in real terms. But from 1973-1999, a period during which
the share of Gross Domestic Product devoted to trade has doubled,
the real median wage has not grown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a drastic change from the previous 27 years,'' says
Weisbrot. ``And everybody admits trade has had a significant
effect.'' Exactly how significant is hard to say. Some estimates
say trade has caused 25 to 40 percent of the rise in US wage
inequality, while others put the effect as low as 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, as some assume, has trade proved a net creator of jobs.
While it's true that rising exports created about 4.1 million jobs
from 1992-1999, rising imports cost us about 7.3 million jobs in
the same period, for a net loss of 3.2 million actual and potential
jobs, according to an analysis by Scott, of the Economic Policy
Institute. His general findings are seconded by others in the
field, though with the caveat that domestic growth at a pace that
created another 3.2 million jobs might well have nudged the Federal
Reserve toward earlier interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   These losses have hit disproportionately in the sectors that
employ less educated and less skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, says Cline, the rising flow of cheaper imports
from abroad clearly kept inflation low and allowed for lower
interest rates. On the other hand, a trade deficit the magnitude of
ours is clearly unsustainable over time and thus will eventually
put downward pressure on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the perverse logic that lets free trade with
developing countries justify a race to the bottom rather than a
rise to a minimum set of standards also works to undercut
meaningful efforts at international environmental progress.
</P>
<P>
   Frank cites as an example the Kyoto Protocols on reducing
industrial emissions that contribute to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a perfect Catch-22,'' the congressman says. ``The people
who say give China PNTR without conditions cite the fact that China
is industrializing as a reason we can't ratify the Kyoto
agreements. But if we say, let's make China worrying about global
warming as part of PNTR, they say that is an interference with free
trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly a tougher ``fair trade'' agenda has widespread
support; in the last several years, a variety of public opinion
polls have shown that US citizens overwhelmingly favor including
labor and environmental standards in trade deals _ and penalizing
countries who fail to abide by those standards.
</P>
<P>
   Classic free-trade theory would say that even with all the ill
effects, we would still be better off trading openly with countries
like China because even with the lost jobs and eroded income, those
who have gained could subsidize those who have lost and still leave
the country as a whole better off.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just the sort of argument that economic theorists offer
to assuage concerns that trade with low-wage countries catalyzes a
growing inequality here. But though some Scandinavian countries
have crafted welfare states that attempt to do just that, this
country has made little attempt beyond retraining to redress
trade-based displacement.
</P>
<P>
   One reason, of course, is that most tangible and easily
identified benefits of such a deal will go to companies that open
operations in China, while the more general advantage _ cheaper
consumers goods _ are spread so broadly it is hard to measure, much
less to redistribute. (Access to those less expensive goods, Cline
argues, is a benefit that softens trade's impact on the
less-skilled workers here who have seen their real wages stagnate
over the last quarter-century.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, says Bluestone, ``the argument ends up as, `Well, there
are going to be some losers, but it is up to them to get more
skills or retraining so they can do better, and if they don't,
that's the price they pay.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Frank says he and other liberals would be more inclined to
support something like PNTR status for China if some sort of
compensation for American workers _ say, universal health care _
came as part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But absent any compensatory benefits, it's hard not to conclude
that the totemistic devotion to free trade no matter the partner
leaves an important Democratic Party constituency increasingly in
the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   The political question is obvious: Will the trade deal with
China lessen support for Democratic nominee-to-be Al Gore among
working men and women? After all, the United Auto Workers, fed up
with the administration's trade posture, are now flirting with
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sweeney says the AFL-CIO will stick with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have differences with him on trade . . . but he has assured
us that labor standards, workers' rights, and environmental
concerns are going to be part of our trade negotiations when he is
elected president,'' the labor chief told the Globe in an interview
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet others aren't so sure the working-class center will hold for
the Democrats without a trade policy that more clearly defends
their economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira says that if his ``forgotten majority,'' already
vaguely suspicious of government, comes to conclude the Democratic
Party is no longer concerned about their economic interests, they
may migrate to the Republicans on other issues, even though the GOP
is even more enthusiastic about China trade than the Democrats.
(White male voters have already started that journey; a recent
Washington Post/ABC poll showed Bush leading Gore 58 percent to 35
percent among that demographic.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is pretty clear that a lot of these people view these trade
deals as not being in their interest,'' Teixeira said. ``For people
for whom George W. is not unattractive to begin with, it may help
push them further in a direction they are already willing to
contemplate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
