<HEADER>
A8860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TRADE-HISTORY-BOS &LR;      05-29 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-HISTORY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN DIPLOMATIC, COMMERCIAL INTERESTS COLLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The very month the Continental Congress accepted
Thomas Jefferson's draft declaring America's freedom from Great
Britain, it asked John Adams to draft a second important document _
a model treaty the new nation would use to win free trade
agreements with other nations.
</P>
<P>
   That document, drafted in 1776 with the assistance of Benjamin
Franklin, established the United States from the start as a trading
nation committed to open markets.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, the United States has practiced that
philosophy in a broader way than its authors probably envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   American presidents have often used trade policy to promote
diplomatic and political goals, just as they have often used
diplomatic policy to promote trade goals. And while some of the
earthquakes that have rumbled through American history _ the Civil
War, for example, or World War II _ have been predominantly moral
conflicts, even they have had important trade elements.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of lobbying, last-minute deal-making, passionate
pleading, and agonized balloting on the House floor last week _
probably the only vote of enduring significance for the entire year
on Capitol Hill _ shed light on a little-appreciated aspect of
American political culture: the notion that our diplomatic
interests and our commercial interests are often more intertwined
than presidents, lawmakers, and lobbyists acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been strong voices and votes for protectionism
in the United States. The Smoot-Hawley Tariff, for example, raised
trade barriers in 1930, and although it also provoked retaliation
against US exports, many historians no longer include it among the
causes of the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Though the economic historian Alfred E. Eckes Jr. argues that,
at the end of the 19th century, ``a protectionist America and a
protectionist Germany both outperformed free trade Britain,''
American policymakers in the modern era generally have favored
free-trade policies. Overall, they have endorsed a view expressed
by New Deal-era Secretary of State Cordell Hull, a former Tennessee
congressman and senator who hailed, not insignificantly, from Vice
President Al Gore's hometown:
</P>
<P>
   ``Toward 1916 I embraced the philosophy I carried throughout my
12 years as Secretary of State,'' Hull said. ``From then on, to me,
unhampered trade dovetailed with peace; high tariffs, trade
barriers, and unfair economic competition, with war.''
</P>
<P>
   Tariffs have been at the heart of American political debate from
the very beginning. The first tariff, providing for duties on some
30 commodities, was enacted on July 4 of the first year of the
Constitution, 1789. Two years later, Alexander Hamilton's famous
``Report on Manufactures'' called for tariff walls to foster
American industry.
</P>
<P>
   Take away slavery and Reconstruction, and much of 19th- century
American history can be distilled down to a debate over trade; the
first angry breath of true states' rights sentiment came not over
slavery but over an 1828 tariff that Southerners considered so
onerous that they called it the Tariff of Abominations. American
sentiment constantly shifted between two poles, one holding that
foreign trade and foreign capital provided the engine of American
growth, the other that the US internal market was big enough to
sustain enormous growth on its own.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept of opening other nations to American goods was
seldom disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, nothing raises American hackles more than the idea that
American goods can't win a fair shake in the world market.
</P>
<P>
   The undeclared war with France between 1798 and 1801 was
triggered by a dispute over neutral rights and the seizure of
American vessels in the West Indies. The War of 1812 was prompted
by restrictions on American traders, and though national honor and
the impressment of American sailors were important elements in the
struggle, so was the idea that the British were excluding Americans
from continental markets.
</P>
<P>
   The United States joined the first great moral war of the 20th
century, World War I, after Germany embarked in January 1917 on a
policy of unrestricted submarine warfare, endangering the full
neutral trading rights that Woodrow Wilson pledged to protect. In
his War Message on April 2, 1917, Wilson said that ``the right is
more precious than peace,'' and though he enumerated several of
what he called ``the things we have always carried nearest our
hearts'' _ and though he fought the war for important moral
principles _ American entry into the war was provoked in large
measure by trade questions.
</P>
<P>
   The parade of business factors through American diplomatic
history is long and loud: the role of the cotton trade in Civil War
diplomacy. The lure of Asian commerce in the War of 1898, commonly
called the Spanish-American War. The attraction of Latin commerce
in 1898 and again in the 1940s and 1950s, when American money and
arms propped up convenient dictatorships in our own hemisphere. The
high stakes of oil politics, which led to strains with Japan in the
1930s, with Iran in the 1950s, and with Iraq in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout American history, an ungainly coalition of free
traders has claimed the high ground in domestic politics and in
diplomatic debates. The free-trade doctrine was established firmly
as US policy in modern times with a 1962 trade law that reduced
tariff barriers substantially. The lower American tariffs generally
encouraged lower barriers worldwide and set the stage for dramatic
acts such as the 1993 North American Free Trade Agreement, which
removed virtually all trade walls among the United States, Mexico,
and Canada, and allowed free-traders to dream of hemispheric
free-trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But while the free-trade mythology marched from triumph to
triumph, other domestic factors were shifting, and as a result the
traditional political alliances have been altered dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats and their allies in the union movement, once
reliable apostles of free trade, grew wary of environmental and
workplace practices in developing countries and grew worried about
the security of American workers in a world market full of cheap
labor. More of them came to oppose international trade agreements.
The Republicans and their allies in business, once determined to
protect American industry behind tariff walls, became intrugued by
the potential of larger markets for American goods and less
expensive workers for American companies. More of them came to
support trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, much of the support for the just-passed China
legislation, backed by a Democratic president, came from Clinton's
party rivals. Republicans voted by a 3-to-1 margin for the trade
bill. Democrats voted against it by about 2-to-1. In the end, it
took 164 Republicans and 73 Democrats to pass the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a new era for trade politics, but also a new era in
American diplomacy. With the Cold War over and with no dictators
providing the sort of threat to Western democracy that Fascism and
Nazism posed in the 1930s and 1940s, trade questions now are far
more openly a part of American power calculations than they were in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policy makers have stepped back and realized the two are
inseparable, and that they have been insparabale,'' said Susan C.
Schwab, dean of the School of Public Affairs at the University of
Maryland. ``America has always been a commercial nation and has
always used the economic and commercial tools in its foreign-policy
basket. Right now those tools are being used openly both for
traditional foreign-policy ends and for economic and commercial
ends. And now that the Cold War is over, the economic interests and
economic tools are clearly in the ascension.''
</P>
<P>
   They are, in fact, reclaiming the position they held in 1776,
when John Adams's draft treaty called for nations to provide
Americans with all the ``liberties, priviliges, immunities and
exemptions in trade, navigation, and commerce'' that they provided
to their own citizens. The open door beckons to us still.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
