A8863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-NEWSSTAND0530-COX     05-29 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time spotlights drugs in Georgia county
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In a troubling cover story on the illegal drug
Ecstasy, Time ($3.50) correspondent John Cloud reports that the
elixir best-known for powering ``raves'' is now readily available
from Georgia to Michigan. He begins his article with a scene from
an unnamed Cobb County high school as 18-year-old ``Karen'' and
five friends skip class and go into the woods to take the pills.
That night they'll go out and drop more Ecstasy, he says. ``The
cliques are pretty big in my school,'' Karen says, ``and every
clique does it.'' Users believe the drug is safer than heroine or
cocaine, but researchers are still studying its long-term effects
on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Real TV: Undaunted by the failure of Fox's ``Who Wants to Marry
a Multimillionaire,'' CBS is airing ``Survivor,'' a 13-part
``reality'' show in which eight men and eight women are dropped on
a remote island. The last one who survives the whims of Mother
Nature and the TV audience gets $1 million. Newsweek ($3.50) talked
with four of the participants about their experiences and found
that one of them had resorted to eating roasted rats. They tasted,
of course, ``like chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   Cyber rich: More than 150 years ago, the American West was
changed when the forty-niners struck gold. Now the West has been
changed again by another group that has struck it rich with
something even more precious than gold: computer chips. Town &AMP;
Country ($4), the magazine that keeps tabs on the wealthy, examines
the new millionaires of Silicon Valley to see how they're living
and spending their money. Some have become passionate
philanthropists, while others have flocked to the Pacific Northwest
in search of adventure. In the Puget Sound area alone, there are
more than 60,000 households with a net worth of $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Eye of the storm: Batten down the hatches. With George Clooney
and his crew heading to theaters this summer in ``The Perfect
Storm,'' Outside ($3.95) goes behind the scenes to explain how the
best-selling book by Sebastian Junger became Hollywood's next great
adventure epic. The $120 million movie is loaded with special
effects, but Clooney says the unexpected appearance of Hurricane
Floyd allowed them to save about a million dollars. ``You can see
it in the movie _ it's real weather, and it makes a difference.''
And, adds Clooney, don't expect a Hollywood ending.
</P>
<P>
   Style and substance: There's no question that Architectural
Digest ($4.95) has wonderful photography, but the glossy magazine
is more than just pretty pictures of elegant houses and expensive
antiques. In the June issue, author Tobias Wolff (``This Boy's
Life'') tells a tongue-in-cheek cautionary tale about the woes of
owning a second home. ``I quickly learned that you don't own houses
_ they own you,'' he writes. Other articles of interest include a
visit with Michael J. Fox and his wife, Tracy Pollan, at their
80-acre New England estate and a look at a trend in weekend homes:
tent cabins.
</P>
<P>
   Green peace: Rolling Stone ($4.95) talks with MTV's Tom Green
about how he's dealing with life after testicular cancer. At first
it was embarrassing, Green says, but then he and his girlfriend,
Drew Barrymore, decided to treat it like everything else in his
life _ with humor. Elsewhere in the magazine, Dan Baum takes aim at
the proliferation of gun shows. Since a law was passed in 1986
making it legal for gun dealers to sell firearms at these shows,
more than 4,400 such events are held every year.
</P>
<P>
   House of rock: All right, so you're never going to get your
picture on the cover of Rolling Stone. You can, however, be a rock
star _ briefly _ at Seattle's Experience Music Project. Smithsonian
($3) explores the new high-tech museum where visitors can perform
in an ``onstage'' exhibit complete with billowing smoke and crowd
noise, watch videos of Bo Diddley, teach themselves chords on
keyboards or guitars using computer tutorials, or get close-up
views of Jimi Hendrix's hat, Janis Joplin's boa and Eric Clapton's
guitar. The museum opens June 23.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
