<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT     05-29 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SLAM THE DOOR ON SECRET EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suppose you were arrested and charged with a serious crime, but
the prosecutor refused to tell you or your attorney the nature of
the crime or the evidence against you. Doing so, according to the
prosecutor, would jeopardize national security. You don't know who
your accusers are; you don't even know the accusation against you.
</P>
<P>
   Sound crazy? Such Kafkaesque scenes are occurring in our nation
right now _ in the United States, not some South American
dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Congress passed the Anti-Terrorism and Effective Death Penalty
Act in 1996. It authorized the setting up of special Immigration
and Naturalization Service courts and the use of classified or
secret evidence against an accused that he and his attorney cannot
view. Only the special court judge can.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has used secret evidence in 75 cases against
non-citizens. There are currently 25 cases pending in INS special
courts which rely upon secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those accused using secret evidence are Arabs or Muslims
_ a kind of government-sanctioned racism.
</P>
<P>
   In any criminal trial in the United States, no matter how
serious the crime, a defendant has the right to see all the
evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Classified or secret evidence was not even permitted in the
trials of the bombers of the Oklahoma City federal building and New
York City's World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   Use of secret evidence that the accused cannot confront or
dispute is against our nation's sense of justice and our
Constitution. Secret evidence, which cannot be balanced against
counter evidence, perpetuates a sham justice. It denies defendants,
who are the targets of that secret evidence, due process of law.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Amendment states unequivocally: ``No person shall be
... deprived of life, liberty, or property without due process of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Notice that the Fifth Amendment does not say ``No United States
citizen shall be ... .'' It says ``No person.'' That means
non-citizens also have the protection of the Fifth Amendment's due
process clause.
</P>
<P>
   But not according to the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
nor according to the anti-terrorism act. That act gave the agency
the power to arrest, detain and deport non-citizens on the basis of
secret evidence. Any non-citizens arrested by the INS can be denied
an opportunity to even confront the government's witnesses against
them or be told who they are.
</P>
<P>
   A few of those arrested non-citizens have spent as long as three
years in prison awaiting the final outcome of their cases. And when
their cases were finally taken out of the special INS courts and
into federal courts through appeals, the INS lost both on the
constitutional issue of denial of due process and on the flimsy
nature of the evidence presented against those accused.
</P>
<P>
   And strangely, although the INS could have appealed these cases
_ involving potential terrorists, according to the agency _ it did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even the agency could see their accusations were based
upon flimsy evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Congress, both the FBI and the INS claimed
that secret evidence used in all cases is ``substantive and
credible'' and ``is subjected to rigorous review.'' However,
neither the federal courts, nor even some INS special court judges,
who have the right to review the secret evidence, have found that
to be true. Most of this secret evidence turned out to be
inflammatory gossip and hearsay by those who had grudges against
the accused.
</P>
<P>
   Hany Kiareldeen was born in Gaza. He came to the United States
in 1990 to attend college. He was arrested in 1998 and accused of
terrorist activities, based upon a false accusation by his ex-wife.
He spent 19 months in prison before being released. The so-called
evidence against Kiareldeen was his former wife's accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Mazen Al-Najjar, of Palestinian descent, has been in an INS
prison for three years. He taught at the University of South
Florida until he was arrested. He now faces what appears to be an
indefinite sentence. No criminal charges have been made against
him. And Al-Najjar cannot view the evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser Ahmed, from Egypt, spent more than three years in an INS
prison, most of it in solitary confinement, before his release last
November when the Board of Immigration Appeals ruled that he did
not pose a threat to national security. The secret evidence against
him was a sham.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., introduced the Secret
Evidence Repeal Act (HR 2121) to end this abomination against the
constitutional rule of law. The legislation now has 90 co-sponsors
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The act would strike down the use of special courts and secret
evidence against non-citizens. The proposed legislation states in
part: ``The alien shall have reasonable opportunity to examine all
the evidence against the alien, to present evidence on the alien's
own behalf, and to cross-examine all witnesses presented by the
Government.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House Committee on the Judiciary held hearings on
HR 2121. At that hearing, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., a co-sponsor
of the bill, made it clear in his testimony that HR 2121 ``would
not require the government to release dangerous terrorists. It
merely requires the government to choose whether to reveal the
evidence against a non-citizen whose liberty is in jeopardy, or
keep that information fully secret and outside immigration
proceedings and determinations.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cole, professor of law at Georgetown University Law
Center, testified before the House Judiciary Committee. He has had
long experience dealing with the INS and secret testimony. He
defended 13 Palestinians against INS charges that they posed a
threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Cole said in his testimony: ``But it is not simply years of
human beings' lives that have been lost. More broadly, America's
image as a country that cares about fairness, openness, and due
process has been seriously tarnished. Secret evidence is a tactic
one associates with totalitarian regimes and military juntas, not
free democracies. A remedy is needed, and HR 2121 is it.''
</P>
<P>
   The damage, however, isn't only to our nation's image. The use
of secret evidence poses a significant threat to constitutional
constraints. If the anti-terrorism act can carve out an exception
to the due process clause of the Fifth Amendment, what other
exceptions will be carved out during times of perceived danger?
</P>
<P>
   Congress should pass the Secret Evidence Repeal Act.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot protect America by hacking apart our Constitution. If
we attempt to do so, we're in danger of becoming the despotic enemy
we so despise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
