u k BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE BILL A BITTER PILL _ AND DEMOCRATS BEST SWALLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is a dilemma for organized labor in this fall's
election, it is this: What to do about the Democrats in Congress
who voted to grant China permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   These Democrats, many of whom depend on labor's support, deeply
disappointed and even angered top labor officials, who have been
campaigning vigorously against the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 73 Democrats joined with 164 Republicans to give the
China deal _ and its main backer, President Clinton _ a victory
Wednesday. Both parties, as well as labor, expect the bill to
easily pass the Senate next month.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of organized labor, Democrats who voted for the bill
are guilty of selling out to big business, and as a spokesman for
the United Steelworkers of America said, ``Our members won't
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   While AFL-CIO president John Sweeney said members will decide
for themselves what they will do in November, he assured that
``they'll be holding candidates accountable.'' Teamsters president
James Hoffa said his union would reassess its support for
candidates in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Democrats' probable presidential nominee, Al Gore, has
not escaped the anger of organized labor for supporting the China
trade bill. Although Sweeney stated that Gore will still benefit
from the AFL-CIO's endorsement, the United Auto Workers union said
it may endorse Green Party candidate Ralph Nader over Gore.
</P>
<P>
   If a large number of disappointed union members who opposed the
bill decide to stay home on election day, as Sweeney warned they
might, Democrats and organized labor may lose two more key battles
more important perhaps even than the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   One is the Democratic Party's effort, with the early pledge of
help from organized labor, to regain control of Congress. The other
is to elect Gore the next president.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt organized labor has good reason to be angry at
defecting Democrats and Clinton. By waging a vigorous campaign and
lobbying effort for passage, Clinton apparently put his legacy as a
an achiever of monumental trade agreements _ he also engineered
passage of the NAFTA trade bill _ over his loyalty to the union
members who helped elect him.
</P>
<P>
   But if workers decide to punish him by staying away from the
polls on election day, they would only be helping Texas Governor
George W. Bush, the probable Republican nominee, move into the
White House. And a Bush presidency, especially combined with a GOP
majority in the Congress, could spell labor's defeat in a variety
of upcoming legislative battles.
</P>
<P>
   Whether workers withhold backing _ in the form of money or votes
_ from congressional candidates, or actually work against some
candidates, remains to be seen. Sweeney said it would be up to
local unions and rank and file members to decide which to do in
their local congressional contests.
</P>
<P>
   Some union officials, such as Teamster official Mike Mathis,
said he does not think his union will be working for any Democrat
who voted for the trade bill, and ``There may even be places where
we actively go against someone,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   As Sweeney and other union officials know, Democrats must take
six seats from the Republicans this fall to win control of the
House, adding that ``there have to be six good candidates out there
to achieve majority in the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   What the nation's union leaders and key Democrats need is a
summit meeting aimed at putting the trade bill vote behind them and
focusing on electing Gore and taking back the House.
</P>
<P>
   They also need to include in this effort President Clinton, who
is still the most popular Democrat and the party's biggest
fund-raiser. Clinton, of course, must do whatever he can to mend
fences with labor and Democrats who opposed the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats, organized labor, and Clinton working together,
they will have a better chance of winning the House. Labor can, as
Sweeney suggests, look to the 2002 elections for candidates who
strongly support its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But for this election, avenge, not revenge, should be the theme.
Once organized labor retakes the House, and holds on to the White
House, there will no longer be any doubt that it is a force to be
reckoned with _ and listened to.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
