<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-ONEYEAR-BOS &LR;      05-29 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ONEYEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REWRITING HISTORY IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELA CRVKA, Yugoslavia _ If Sabri Popaj could read the current
revisionist writing about NATO's war with Slobodan Milosevic, he
would learn that the war that allowed him to come home to his farm
was a sham.
</P>
<P>
   He would be told that when his two teenage sons, Agon and
Shendet, his only children, and 63 other civilians from this small,
dusty village in Kosovo were massacred by Serb gunmen the day after
NATO began bombing Serbia, it was NATO's fault _ a reasonable
reaction to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's decision to
bomb a sovereign country.
</P>
<P>
   He would read that the war was probably not worth the effort,
that Milosevic didn't deserve the wrath the US air war rained on
him.
</P>
<P>
   As the anniversary of NATO's victory in its 78-day war against
Milosevic approaches, revisionism, second-guessing, and opposition
to the war are all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it has legitimate underpinnings _ such as a recent
Newsweek magazine cover story that reported that while the Pentagon
initially claimed to have hit 120 tanks, 220 armored personnel
carriers, and 450 artillery pieces, a suppressed US Air Force
report put the true figures at 14, 18, and 20. Thus, the magazine
concluded, it was the morally dubious bombing of civilians and
infrastructure, not the exaggerated decimation of the Yugoslav
Army, that forced Milosevic to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   But much of what is being offered in hindsight is far less
informed.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the right-wing press and commentators, which a year
ago led the war-mongering and demonization of Serbs, now routinely
claim the war a failure, using it as evidence that Prime Minister
Tony Blair should be tossed from office.
</P>
<P>
   William Pfaff, the Paris-based syndicated columnist who last
year cheered on the war, recently questioned the basis for military
action. ``Did the ethnic cleansing inside Kosovo really begin
before NATO's attacks started?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emilio Perez Pujol, a Spanish forensic scientist, complains that
NATO had wildly exaggerated the numbers of civilians murdered by
Serb forces. He said ``as few as 2,500'' civilians were murdered.
(Investigators at the International Criminal Tribunal for the
former Yugoslavia at The Hague believe the final toll will be
closer to 5,000.)
</P>
<P>
   The revisionism is based on a narrow view of history. Some of
the same people who are saying Milosevic did not deserve to be
attacked have loudly defended the arrest and attempted prosecution
of Augusto Pinochet, the Chilean former dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Over 17 years, Pinochet's regime killed about 3,000 people; in
about half that time, Milosevic has started four wars that have
killed a hundred times as many and displaced millions.
</P>
<P>
   Janine di Giovanni, a foreign correspondent for the Times of
London, recalled that a year ago she was sitting in a trench with
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army, and that NATO's mistaken
bombing of them shows how senseless the war was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what we know now about the KLA's corruption, and the
behavior of the Kosovan Albanians against Serb civilians, the NATO
campaign seems even more senseless,'' Di Giovanni said.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that the KLA killed Serb policemen and
civilians in an attempt to goad the Serbs to commit the atrocities
that led to NATO's intervention. The KLA ranks are littered with
gangsters and bigots. But while the postwar killing of Serb
civilians in Kosovo is inexcusable, and even scandalous given that
there are 40,000 international peacekeepers there, it is absurd and
disingenuous to compare it _ as some are now doing _ to what
Milosevic has done over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   There wouldn't be a KLA if Milosevic had not decided that
Kosovo, while 90 percent ethnic Albanian, was not Serbian enough.
Ethnic Albanians were thrown out of government jobs, relegated to
official second-class citizenship. Just as the Irish Republican
Army could not have reestablished itself 30 years ago without the
British government's clumsy and heavy-handed treatment of Roman
Catholics in Northern Ireland, the KLA would never have been born
without government oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionists maintain that NATO not only inflated the number of
military targets it was hitting, but the number of civilians the
Serbs were killing. A look back at an event in the middle of the
war is instructive: It is true that when the NATO spokesman, Jamie
Shea, and US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen announced that some
100,000 young ethnic Albanian men could not be accounted for, they
were implying that some, most, or all of those men could have been
murdered by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   But while revisionists see what Shea and Cohen said as a
bald-faced lie, it was certainly within the realm of possibility
that the Serbs were indeed rounding up young men and killing them.
For the two years before the war, the Serbs had been routinely
arresting young ethnic Albanians for no reason. Given that track
record _ not to mention the fact that Milosevic had launched three
previous wars, destabilizing the region and flooding Europe with
more than a million refugees _ fears that they had detained (or
worse) the missing men were legitimate. The revisionists are being
disingenuous by not acknowledging that.
</P>
<P>
   The revisionists point to Chechnya, saying that NATO's failure
to do to the Russians what it did to Milosevic is proof that Kosovo
was not a moral war, as President Clinton and other Western leaders
declared, but only bullying.
</P>
<P>
   That reasoning, however, employs a logic that would suggest that
because the police can't arrest all murderers, they should arrest
none. And if the charge is that NATO acted in Kosovo because the
Serbs don't have nuclear weapons and will not act in Chechnya
because the Russians do, so what? What the revisionists call rank
hypocrisy would be judged by others to be political pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   Those who criticize the Western powers for not moving more
forcefully against Milosevic years earlier, or for trying to
appease rather than coerce him to abide by international standards,
have a strong argument.
</P>
<P>
   What NATO did, however imperfectly, was show anyone who might
want to emulate Milosevic's tactics for crushing dissent that there
could be a heavy price to pay for such cavalier attitudes toward
human rights. Britain did the same when it detained Pinochet for
more than a year before sending him home on humanitarian grounds.
Criticizing such actions on the basis that the West looks the other
way when Russia and China kill their civilians while rooting out
rebels sounds more self-righteous than realistic.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the revisionists are right about is the unacceptable
number of Serb civilians killed by NATO bombs. Most died because
the Pentagon refused to allow American pilots to fly low enough to
avoid mistaking civilian targets for military ones. But to compare
what NATO did to the premeditated murder of civilians is to engage,
with imperfect hindsight, in a dangerous form of moral relativism.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who says the war was a sham ought to explain it to Sabri
Popaj and his village neighbors who still grieve for their dead.
Revisionist history has not changed his view; Popaj remains certain
about who was at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO didn't kill my sons and my neighbors,'' he said. ``The
Serbs did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SUMMER-BOS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     05-29 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUMMER-BOS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... for a few minutes.' ''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Burnett, who built up to ``Survivor'' as the creator and
producer of ``Eco-Challenge'' on the Discovery Channel, doesn't
believe that his show is harmful to viewers, or that it panders to
voyeurism. Indeed, he views it as ``a crash course in life,'' one
in which viewers can learn which human traits _ cleverness, the
ability to manipulate others,likability, intelligence _ are most
relevant to survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more like a mirror,'' he says. ``What went on on that
island is just like most offices all over America. There are people
trying to get ahead and win. In the office environment, that means
getting promoted and not getting fired. And people are politicking
and there's a little back stabbing and duplicity now and then. And
there's also hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett planned the show as a sort of microcosm, making sure
that his 16 castaways were from diverse backgrounds. They include a
72-year-old retired Navy SEAL, a 30-year-old neurologist, a
38-year-old truck driver, a 22-year-old student, and a 62-year-old
musician. ``I didn't want 16 survival nuts who run around in the
woods in camouflage paint on weekends,'' he says. ``That would be
completely boring. I was trying to simulate if there was a cruise
ship that went down and a fair smattering of American society got
washed up onshore.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett also feels that the ``Survivor'' experience was a
positive one for the participants. He says that, more than the
desire for money and celebrity, they joined the production in
search of a Robinson Crusoe-like experience. Exhibitionism took a
back seat to the thirst for adventure.
</P>
<P>
   He says he made sure the 16 were well cared for. Despite a few
sand-flea-bite infections, a stingray incident, and a diet that
often included rat, they were physically unharmed during their
island stay (as was verified by checkups with the show's medical
director every three days). And psychologically, he says, they were
solid coming in and solid upon departure. The casting of the show
included a written psychological exam and a two-hour psychological
evaluation that was geared to predict ``if they are likely to be
able to accept the rejection of being kicked off the island, if
they are violent, or if they have a propensity to hurt others on
the island.'' There was one psychologist on the island, and another
waiting for the castaways upon their return to the States, one by
one. And once the episodes begin airing, ``Survivor'' will provide
follow-up counseling. ``They're all so balanced,'' Burnett says.
``They're getting together for parties to watch the damn thing.
Even the first people voted out are laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallout
</P>
<P>
   But the psychological effects of ``Survivor'' were called into
question a few weeks ago, when one of the finalists was arrested on
second-degree child-abuse charges shortly after his return from the
island. Richard Hatch, a 38-year-old management consultant from
Newport, Rhode Island, was accused of bullying his 9-year-old
adopted son during an early-morning jog because the boy had gained
approximately 20 pounds during Hatch's absence. For some, the
incident recalled the demise of ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?'' a show that was tainted by the assault
accusations that trailed Rick Rockwell, the groom Fox had chosen
for the show.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett says he feels Hatch is being wrongly accused by the boy,
and that ``Survivor'' is not affected by the conflict. ``I really
like Richard,'' Burnett says. ``And most people on the island felt
the same way. He never made a secret that he was a single gay man
who adopted a problem child. And as a West Point graduate, Richard
has a disciplinarian nature to him, and he decided that, as the
eighth family this kid has been in, this kid needed tough love in
some way. He'd regularly taken this kid on these 4:30 a.m. runs
long before he came to the show. I feel very, very sad for the kid.
Richard is probably the best chance for this poor child, who grew
up in a terrible environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Murray, one of ``The Real World'' producers, likewise
says he feels confident about the psychological screening that
precedes the filming of the ``Real World'' seasons. And he always
makes counseling available during the airing of the show, when a
cast member may have a problem with the instant celebrity, or with
the way they have been portrayed in the final edit. As ``EDtv''
conveyed so vividly, making yourself into a TV show can be more
traumatic than you expected. ``We've found that the greatest
resource they have is each other,'' he says. ``Only they can
understand what it's like to have these cameras follow you and have
your life put up for the enjoyment of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, MTV would like to distance ``The Real World''
from ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' and Murray was reticent
about discussing any series but his own. And indeed, next to the
newfangled shows, ``The Real World'' looks like a harmless pioneer.
It offers no cash prizes, for one thing, and it doesn't encourage
competition by requiring the roommates to continually vote against
one another. ``We all love to listen in on other people's
conversations,'' says Murray, ``and here we've made it easy for you
by shooting it all and putting it together into nice little
22-minute stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossroads
</P>
<P>
   As ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' marry exhibitionism and
voyeurism to the sort of get-rich-quick, day-tradingesque mania of
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' they bring American TV to yet
another crossroads. Will we give up more of our privacy and
modesty, and more of others' privacy and modesty, with each passing
season? Will Andy Warhol's prediction that ``In the future everyone
will be famous for 15 minutes'' turn out to be the understatement
of the 20th century?
</P>
<P>
   Will Big Brother, the once-feared icon of oppression, make it
into Entertainment Weekly's Cool Issue?
</P>
<P>
   Burnett scoffs at the thought that a show like ``Survivor''
represents a subtle erosion of our dignity. ``Some writers aren't
maybe so great at their writing jobs and they're looking for the
easy thing to hang their hat on, and not really cerebrally thinking
it through,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be involved in a crass thing. That, of
course, may mean the ratings (will) suck. It seems like on TV, the
more crass and violent things are, the better the ratings. I think
dramatically it's very good, but I've tried to keep it highbrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
