<HEADER>
A8873 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT &LR;      05-29 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: A Toast to Stingers, and to Your Health
</P>
<P>
   Two recent studies _ one animal, one vegetable _ reported
progress in turning nature's stings toward healing purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In an article this month in The Journal of General Physiology,
researchers from the State University of New York at Buffalo
described isolating a factor from the venom of a Chilean rose
tarantula that appears to block the action of the chemicals that
determine when the pores in cell membranes open and close. This
action plays a poorly understood role in a number of bodily
functions, including the sense of touch and the regulation of blood
pressure, and it is associated with a number of diseases, among
them congestive heart failure and brain tumors.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published last week in The Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences, researchers from Seoul National
University and Finch University of Health Sciences in Chicago
reported isolating a substance that is able to turn on the same
switch in the brain that is thrown by capsaicin, the ingredient
that makes hot peppers painfully hot.
</P>
<P>
   Products of enzymes that help speed up the burning of fat, they
found, are able to activate the same receptor cell in the brain,
and one of them has the exact same three-dimensional structure,
opening up possibilities of developing a new class of pain
inhibitor, the researchers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS: Viagra and Women: A Frosty Reception
</P>
<P>
   The first controlled study of Viagra's ability to help women
with a broad range of sexual dysfunctions has found that the drug
did no better than a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra works in men with erectile dysfunction by increasing
blood flow to the erectile tissue, and since its introduction there
has been widespread speculation that the same effect might be of
benefit to women, since researchers have wondered whether
inadequate blood flow to women's erectile tissue plays a role in
some female sexual dysfunctions as well.
</P>
<P>
   In research presented last week at a conference of the American
College of Obstetrics and Gynecology, researchers studied 577
European, Australian and Canadian women.
</P>
<P>
   About half of them had low levels of arousal as their primary
complaint, the problem most comparable to male erectile
dysfunction. The other primary complaints were low levels of
desire, inability to achieve orgasm or painful dryness during
intercourse. The women were randomly assigned to take Viagra or
dummy pills an hour before intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   After patients recorded the effects in logs and questionnaires
over 12 weeks, the researchers, led by Dr. Rosemary Basson of
Vancouver General Hospital, found no statistically significant
difference in their reports. Most women were able to tolerate the
drug, but some reported side effects that included headache,
flushing and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Basson, a professor in psychiatry and
obstetrics and gynecology, said the findings confirmed ``that
sexual dysfunctions in women are complex,'' more so than in men.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do women tend more than men to suffer from multiple
dysfunctions, Basson said, but ``when women talk about problems
with arousal they are often talking about different things,'' from
genital arousal to ``mental excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   LONGEVITY: Long Live the Umpire! But How Long?
</P>
<P>
   When an umpire collapsed and died behind home plate minutes
after the opening pitch of the 1996 Major League baseball season,
questions were raised about whether the combination of high stress
and relatively low physical fitness associated with the position
posed a health risk. Now a demographic analysis has provided an
answer: no.
</P>
<P>
   In an article published this month in The Physician and Sports
Medicine, researchers from the Upstate Medical Center in Syracuse,
N.Y., and Bloomsburg University in Pennsylvania, the life spans of
195 umpires, born between 1836 and 1945, were compared to
life-expectancy data from actuarial tables. No statistically
significant deviation was found.
</P>
<P>
   The likely explanation, the researchers wrote, is that the job's
stress is offset by other benefits: After all, they noted, the
workday is rarely longer than four hours.
</P>
<P>
   OUTCOMES: A Simple Plan for Heart Attack Care
</P>
<P>
   A new study has found that giving heart attack victims just
chest compression is as effective as combining compression with
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, leading the researchers to suggest
that the simpler method should be made the standard.
</P>
<P>
   The study, from the University of Washington in Seattle,
involved 241 people who collapsed outside a hospital. If the person
who called 911 did not know cardiopulmonary resuscitation
technique, which alternates the two methods, emergency dispatchers
randomly instructed them in using chest compression alone or full
CPR.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers followed the patients' progress and found no
statistically significant difference in survival rates between the
two groups. The body's bloodstream usually contains enough oxygen
to keep the brain alive until an ambulance arrives, if the blood is
``pumped'' by chest compression, the researchers explained.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Al Hallstrom, the lead author, wrote that given the lack of
a clear benefit from resuscitation, chest compression alone could
be the better method.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it takes an average of 2.4 minutes for an
emergency services dispatcher to instruct a bystander in the full
cardiopulmonary resuscitation technique, time that would be better
spent keeping the blood flowing. For another, some people shy away
from mouth-to-mouth resuscitation out of fear of infection.
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom noted that the results of the study, which appeared
last week in The New England Journal of Medicine, could be skewed
by the unusually short response times of emergency personnel in
Seattle; after a few minutes, the blood's oxygen is exhausted if
not replenished.
</P>
<P>
   STAGES: On the Trail of Sleepy Sixth-Graders
</P>
<P>
   Every child knows that when you get older you can stay up later.
Now a study from Israel has confirmed what many parents know:
Children get sleepier as they get older.
</P>
<P>
   The study, reported last week in the journal Developmental
Psychology, used motion monitors worn on the wrist to track the
sleeping patterns of 140 second and sixth graders. The children and
their parents filled in logs and questionnaires on levels of
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the sixth graders, on average, went
to bed an hour later than the second graders, and got eight hours
sleep, on average, instead of nine. They also reported much greater
morning drowsiness. The study also found that later bedtimes were
more likely in families with older parents and in families that
reported higher levels of stress.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's lead author, Dr. Avi Sadeh, a psychologist at Tel
Aviv University, says there is no simple rule for parents to follow
about how much sleep is enough _ other than being aware of whether
the child is sleepy.
</P>
<P>
   The key to judging whether a child is sleeping enough is daytime
functioning, Sadeh said. ``If the child is alert during the day and
doesn't suffer from daytime sleepiness, irritability, severe mood
disturbances of attention problems, then he or she probably gets
enough sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
