<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-SUMMER-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      05-29 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SUMMER-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVING UP EXHIBITIONISM-VOYEURISM COCKTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Darva Conger makes her journey up the celebrity ladder, from
the Woman Who Wanted to Marry a Multimillionaire to teary fixture
on ``Entertainment Tonight'' to Playboy model, the infinitely
resourceful medium of television is about to provide us with a
whole new population of Darvas.
</P>
<P>
   Because Darva, the woman who is famous for exchanging wedding
vows before a nation of TV viewers, is the way of the future. Darva
and Big Brother, that all-seeing dude with the fancy cameras _ they
are the twin rising stars in American culture, the duo poised to
change the face of TV or destroy civilization as we know it,
depending on whom you ask. Together, the forces of Darva and Big
Brother are preparing to turn prime-time TV into a place where
striptease and spying and eavesdropping are little more than
escapist fluff.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, two controversial new CBS series will serve up a
potent mix that is already one of the defining elements of the
Internet. Both high-profile network shows, they will give what is
known as ``reality programming'' _ a genre usually identified with
extreme fodder like ``When Animals Attack!'' _ its most legitimate
entree into the mainstream so far. Called ``Sur-
</P>
<P>
   vivor'' and, yes, ``Big Brother,'' they feature real people
willingly giving up weeks of privacy to be filmed constantly for TV
viewers, who are more than happy to watch. There may not be any
teeth-baring on the new reality shows, but backbiting and
blackballing will certainly be on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' a 13-week series that premieres on Wednesday,
spies on 16 people who have been left to their own devices on a
remote tropical island off the coast of Borneo. Every three days at
a ``tribal council,'' one of them is voted off the island, until
the last remaining person wins$1 million. (When two are left, the
last seven kicked off the island vote for the winner.) It's
``Gilligan's Island'' meets ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' meets
``Lord of the Flies,'' with an emphasis on the primitive behavior
of the novel. The show's producer, Mark Burnett, says that while
``Survivor'' has the trappings of a game show, it is ``mostly a
psychological story.'' He says he thinks of the ``Survivor'' genre
as ``dramality'' because it's ``drama meets reality'' (and not, of
course, because of the pun on ``malady''). Like ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' ``Survivor'' was originated by a British company.
</P>
<P>
   The provocatively titled ``Big Brother'' promises to be more
incendiary than ``Survivor.''Due in July, the series confines 10
people in a
</P>
<P>
   REAL, Page P6 &QL; 
house for 100 days of 24/7 surveillance, with viewers and roommates
voting every two weeks on which member gets kicked out. The last
remaining person wins a cash prize of $500,000. It's ``The Real
World'' meets ``Millionaire'' meets ``1984,'' and it's the closest
TV has ever come to mimicking the Internet's Web-cam phenomenon,
whereby a person airs his or her own mundane home life on a public
Web site. Already a hit in the Netherlands, ``Big Brother'' was
developed by a European company named Endemol. If it succeeds here,
Endemol may import another of its far-out reality products,
``Chains of Love,'' which literally chains four men to one woman at
the wrists and ankles. Each day, she cuts one of them loose, with
the last remaining man winning a date and a cash prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' join a TV lineup whose fringes
are already peppered with the ``dramality'' genre. ``The Real
World,'' which returns for its ninth season on June 13 in New
Orleans, is a longstanding ratings favorite on MTV. About seven
young people living together as roommates, it is a snappily edited
youth-market fishbowl. UPN's ``Blind Date'' follows young couples
through the awkward minutes of the title event, embellishing the
developments with humorous thought balloons. It's the contemporary
iteration of ``The Dating Game.'' And ABC's ``Making the Band,''
from the producers of ``The Real World,'' chronicles the daily
lives of a group of young men competing and training to be part of
a boy band. After breaking for a few weeks, the series returned to
ABC's lineup last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Real nightmare?
</P>
<P>
   To some, the reality trend promises to take our culture in an
undesirable and even frightening direction. When he programmed
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother,'' CBS Entertainment president Les
Moonves acknowledged, ``There are a lot of people (at CBS) who
think we should not be doing this. But I think it could be
interesting.'' The dangers awaiting a TV-addicted country when it
plays with real lives were most recently underscored in the movies
``The Truman Show'' and the underrated ``EDtv,'' which captured
both the allure and then the horror of giving up your privacy to
the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already a celebrity-obsessed society,'' says Stuart
Fischoff, professor of media psychology at California State
University, Los Angeles. ``Now what were doing is taking people's
normal lives, or even artificially normal lives, and making that
another reason to sit there and be a voyeur. It increases the
passivity of our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischoff says the trend is destined to find increasingly lower
lows, in order to keep viewers interested. ``People become bored
and so you have to escalate the stakes to get them back. At that
point you have high-risk enterprises where people run the risk of
dying, or you have public executions, or you have snuff movies _
anything that will keep the audience interested and spike the
ratings, even if it's another nail in the coffin of civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischoff also says that these reality shows, along with the
popularity of Web cams, make us eerily comfortable with the
phenomenon of surveillance. ``Everybody is getting used to having
the public and the private line obliterated _ my life is for
viewing and if you're interested, great.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cities already have cameras directed at problematic traffic
areas, he says, and this ``sets the stage for a worst-case scenario
in which a tyrannical government keeps tabs on everybody.''
Fischoff says the process is an insidious one, more Aldous Huxley
than George Orwell. ``Orwell foretold that we would be enslaved by
forces that we fear. Huxley predicted that we'd be enslaved by
forces that we love, and I think that's what you have here. We
become so enamored of seeing ourselves or other people on
television that our sensibilities begin to flag, and we say, `Hey,
what can I do to become a celebrity for a few minutes?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
