<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0530-CO     05-29 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are the good old days gone?
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The closest I ever came to knowing the joy of
living in a small town, before I moved to this one, was the
neighborhood I grew up in. It was neither a suburb nor a planned
community. It was a tree-lined street of
</P>
<P>
   modest homes and an endless variety of folks living on it. At
the corner we had Bader's Pharmacy, a bakery, a small grocery
store, and Hodap's Butcher Shop _ not because of some municipal
visionary's blueprint, but because they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   We also had a neighborhood post office. I remember it because
the man behind the counter helped me with my first official
purchase _ one stamp to go on the envelope of a letter I had
written to my Aunt Edna thanking her for the box of fancy bath
soaps she had sent for my birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Then we moved and I lost that happy neighborhood _ the one where
I'd known which yard had the best sour cherry tree or the sweetest
Concord grape vine, and who would let me pick and who wouldn't. Now
the nearest post office was a bus ride away and nobody there knew
my name.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how it was before I moved to this village almost 17
years ago. After my first visit, Postmaster Reed was greeting me by
name: ``Morning, Elizabeth,'' he'd smile and ask what he could do
for me.
</P>
<P>
   The folks in the blue shirts and I have done a lot of business
together and they've been mighty good about it. Letters vaguely
addressed: To The Newspaper Writer, Gibsonburg, Ohio, make their
way to my mail basket without any fuss, since of the 2,000 souls in
our village, I'm the only one who gets her name in the paper
without dying.
</P>
<P>
   Then a couple of years ago, Mr. Reed retired and a stranger rode
into town to take his place. The new man doesn't know our names and
sometimes I'm not even sure he likes us. Or maybe it's just our
post office he doesn't like; it's not very big. He's polite, in a
smarmy sort of way, but I suspect he thinks we're all a little
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other morning when I shambled in with a tissue-wrapped
dress under my arm to send to a friend for her yard sale. I picked
up a large mailing envelope from the rack in the lobby and, since I
was the only customer in the
</P>
<P>
   place, laid the envelope and dress on the counter and busied
myself stuffing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be $1.25,'' the voice said. I looked up. ``For the
envelope,'' he said and pointed. I stooped to pick up the belt I'd
dropped and explained that I didn't want just the envelope _ that I
intended to mail it as well. ``It's still
</P>
<P>
   $1.25 - now.''
</P>
<P>
   I stood up, blinked, and said I'd have it ready to go in just a
few seconds and then I could pay for the envelope and the postage
at the same time. ``Can't do that,'' he said. ``You have to pay for
the envelope now, and then you pay the
</P>
<P>
   postage.'' I was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you suggesting I might be intending to steal your
envelope?'' I asked in disbelief. He assured me that was the case _
that it had happened a couple of times. I didn't ask where.
</P>
<P>
   But you know me, I wanted to say. You've seen me in here a
hundred times and you know where I live. Why are you acting like
I'm a fugitive from one of the posters on your ``Wanted'' wall. I
wanted to say that, but I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I walked next door to the library. ``Hi, Elizabeth,''
Naomi greeted me from behind the counter. ``The books you've
ordered are in.'' I thanked her and said I'd like to browse the
stacks a bit before I checked out. ``Just let me
</P>
<P>
   know when you're ready,'' she said, turning to busy herself
elsewhere and not even asking for my watch as collateral. Guess she
hasn't heard about my attempted envelope heist yet.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still annoyed with the postmaster, but I wish him well. So
well, in fact, that I hope he soon might be promoted to a really
big post office _ one littered with hard-core envelope thieves
trying to mail dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH, 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
