<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-BOBOS-BOS &LR;      05-29 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BOBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOURGEOIS BOHEMIANS SET THE TONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOBOS IN PARADISE &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; The New Upper Class and How They Got There &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; By David Brooks. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 256 pp. $25. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Brooks has written a smart, funny book about the new
meritocracy, the information-age elite whose members _ he calls
them Bobos, short for bourgeois bohemians _ set the tone of our
time.
</P>
<P>
   The word Bobo may bring to mind ``bozo,'' or ``boob,'' or
``bimbo,'' but Brooks's coinage is not meant to be negative, not
entirely at least. To some observers, Bobos may appear to be a lot
of latte-swilling, SUV-wielding, fitness-obsessed, self-centered
overachievers. Brooks, a senior editor at The Weekly Standard, a
conservative magazine, sees them differently. He's a Bobo himself.
While his tone is self-mocking and often critical, it is not really
disapproving. He writes incisively, and hilariously, about Bobo
follies, excesses, and self-indulgences, but he believes Bobos
essentially are an impressive bunch who have the potential to be a
positive force.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks uses the wedding page of The New York Times to good
effect to show how The Bobocracy has supplanted the old WASP (and
WASP-ish) establishment. He compares the lineup of the late 1950s,
when pedigree prevailed, to today's, replete with ``Resume Gods''
with impressive degrees and ambitious career paths. ``You can
almost feel the force of the mingling SAT scores,'' he writes of
the more recent unions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet these marriages are not all intellect and achievement.
Each week the Times describes a particular wedding in detail, and
almost inevitably the brainy pair are described by friends as
``enchanting paradoxes . . . grounded but berserk, daring yet
traditional, high-flying yet down to earth, disheveled yet elegant,
sensible yet spontaneous.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the Bobo ethos. They've somehow managed to combine
1960s-style counterculture with 1980s-style achievement. ``This is
an elite that has been raised to oppose elites,'' Brooks writes.
``They are affluent yet opposed to materialism. They are by
instinct antiestablishmentarian yet somehow sense they have become
a new establishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobos may be in the minority, but their tastes and attitudes
have a disproportionate impact on American culture. They are
leaders, opinionmakers, trend setters: ``Wherever they have settled
they have made life more enjoyable (for those who can afford it).''
And what about those who can't? You won't find many references to
the poor and struggling classes in the pages of ``Bobos in
Paradise.'' The book covers the Bobo waterfront, from buying habits
to political style to attitudes about sex, but there is very
little, almost nothing, about the Bobo social conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks shines when he's writing about Bobo taste and lifestyle.
He observes that Bobos take a utilitarian view of pleasure that
synthesizes bourgeois self-control and bohemian emancipation. For
example, women may jog in public places wearing next to nothing _
but ``any erotic effect of their near nudity is counteracted by
their expressions of grim determination.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``serious,'' he writes, is the highest compliment Bobos
use to describe their leisure activities. Bobos cannot simply go on
vacation; they must spend their time off torturing themselves in
ways that will be intellectually and spiritually enhancing,
``hiking on a forced march across some glacier or trekking thorugh
arid deserts along the path that Alexander the Great's soliders
were induced to follow only by threat of death.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bobo fun is serious, Bobo work is more like play, ``an
extended hobby.'' Brooks contends that Bobos are reshaping the
working world by applying the creative energy of bohemianism to
business. The new ideal organization isn't a machine, it's an
ecosysytem. CEOs talk about trying to promote creativity and wax
enthusiastic about the corporate social mission. Bobo moguls
embrace the notion that work isn't about making money, it's about
doing something you love. ``And the weird thing is that when
employees start thinking like artists and activists, they actually
work harder for the company,'' Brooks concludes, without citing any
evidence. (In his introduction, he notes that his book does not
have a lot of statistics. It is more of an extended essay, a work
of what he calls ``comic sociology.'')
</P>
<P>
   Brooks's chapter on Bobo buying habits is sharply observed and
entertaining, and should strike a chord with anyone who has ever
paused at Starbucks or browsed at Pottery Barn or Restoration
Hardware. Brooks writes that the Thorstein Veblen era is over; that
is almost true. Bobos have managed to meld bohemian disdain for
material objects with bourgeois conspicuous consumption. This means
that marketers must invent ways of selling to people who dislike
marketing. The results may be seen in pre-distressed furniture and
clothing in Bruise Tones, in ice cream companies with their own
foreign policies, and in catalogs that attempt to sell tweed
jackets with a text that traces the history of tweed back to the
14th century. ``If T. S. Eliot were alive today, and of a mind
to,'' Brooks writes, ``he'd open a chain of home furnishing stores
called Objective Correlatives, and each object in them would be the
physical expression of some metaphysical statement.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain autobiographical edge to a chapter on Bobo
intellectual life. Brooks contrasts the intellectuals of the 1950s,
who shunned the marketplace and bourgeois values, with the current
ideal, personified by Henry Louis Gates Jr., Harvard professor and
multimedia star. Today's intellectuals, he writes, see their
careers in terms of market niches. Indeed this book is a good
example of how one Bobo intellectual succeeded in finding his niche
and exploiting it for all it is worth, and it may be worth a lot.
We will probably be talking about Bobos for a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Bobos are essentially conservative, Brooks writes, not
necessarily politically conservative, but conservative in the
old-fashioned sense, i.e., prudent, restrained, community-oriented,
``epistomologically sober.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobos have learned from the example of Vietnam and the fall of
European communism that revolutions usually backfire. They believe
that steady reform is best. Their political project, he writes, is
to correct the excesses of the bohemian '60s and the bourgeois '80s
by fusing the best features of both. They seek a Third Way, beyond
left or right. The Clinton administration, he writes, embodies the
Bobo spirit of compromise.
</P>
<P>
   In the final chapter Brooks drops the cheeky tone and expresses
an earnest hope that Bobos will be able to transcend their
narcissism and their cynicism about politics and develop a
public-service ethos. If they can, he writes, fervently, ``they
have the ability to go down in history as the class that led
America into another golden age.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems a little mushy, coming as it does at the very end of
a book as witty and trenchant as this one. But maybe it is not such
a surprising turn: As Brooks observes, beneath the Bobo's
microfleece vest beats the heart of a cautious idealist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
