<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      05-29 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Invasion of the Ants
</P>
<P>
   In Stanislaw Lem's 1961 science fiction classic ``Solaris,'' a
group of scientists encounters a world covered by a sentient ocean,
a single, giant organism that invades every nook and cranny of the
planet (and, unfortunately for the scientists, every nook and
cranny of their minds).
</P>
<P>
   Nothing quite that creepy is going on in California, but the
state has been overrun by a species of ant that, researchers say,
has essentially formed a single giant colony from San Diego to San
Francisco and beyond. The researchers, from the University of
California at San Diego, discovered a lack of genetic variation in
the insect, the Argentine ant, which has allowed the species to
spread to nooks and crannies up and down the state, particularly in
coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   Individual ants are so close genetically, the researchers report
in The Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, that they
consider all their fellows to be close relatives and thus do not
engage in the kind of fierce intercolony death matches that limit
the ants in their native Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of genetic diversity is normally considered bad for a
population, making it vulnerable to disease, among other problems.
The ants are unusual: Their lack of variation is beneficial,
allowing them to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   The sameness results from the insects' having gone through a
genetic bottleneck _ all of them having descended from a relatively
small group. That makes sense given the ants' history. They are
believed to have entered the United States aboard ships that were
carrying coffee and sugar from Argentina in the 1890s.
</P>
<P>
   Patterns in the Forest
</P>
<P>
   Creamy or chunky? That's a thorny issue among children, and also
among ecologists who study the distribution of trees in tropical
forests. Are forests creamy, with trees of the same species
dispersed randomly, or chunky, with the trees clumped together? As
with peanut butter, each side has strong opinions on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A new report in Science appears to have settled the question.
Researchers from the Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute and
other institutions surveyed six forest plots of 60 to 130 acres in
Asia and Central America, noting the location of all trees. They
found that almost all the species, numbering more than 1,700, grew
in clumps.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that the results were the same both for
smaller trees and for those with trunks larger than four inches in
diameter. And at all but one site, rare species were substantially
more clumped than common ones. The highest degree of clumping was
found among crape myrtles in a Thai forest, where 51 of 59
specimens grew within about 20 yards of one another.
</P>
<P>
   The work should help conservationists develop forest reserves
and determine harvest patterns that will sustain, not destroy, a
forest.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Point the Hubble
</P>
<P>
   The Hubble Space Telescope needs some help getting pointed in
the right direction. It's not that its gyroscopes are shot _ they
were just replaced, after all, by a shuttle maintenance crew. No,
the Hubble just needs to be told what to look at, and the public is
invited to make suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubble Heritage Project, an educational group at the Space
Telescope Science Institute in Baltimore, is conducting an online
vote to help select the next object to be observed. Visitors to the
project site (heritage.stsci.edu) can make suggestions until June
6, with the final decision being made by the heritage team. The
observation will be made in August.
</P>
<P>
   The site has guidelines for the kinds of objects that can be
suggested (nothing in the solar system is acceptable for this
project, because of the complexities involved in training the
Hubble on a close moving object), as well as a link to astronomy
education resources for those who do not know the Milky Way from a
Mars bar. Votes to focus the instrument on your neighbor's house
will not be counted.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
