<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      05-29 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NICE EXCEPTION TO THE PROLOGUE CANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roughly half of all mystery novels these days begin with a
prologue, a writer's device to provide background for a reader and,
to my taste, one of the lazier ways out of the writer's dilemma:
how to grab a reader in the first page with some unexplained action
that will be given meaning only far into the novel, by which time
the reader is hooked. The notion that crime fiction needs a grabber
on Page One is a sign of the times, putting instant gratification
ahead of careful development. Now! I'm glad to have got that off my
chest.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner propound a critical canon, and it is challenged. Dana
Stabenow is a professional whose rise to mastery of both prose and
plot can be traced through her books, and she gives us a prologue
in ``Midnight Come Again'' (St. Martin's Minotaur, $23.95) that
launches her best-ever book. The prologue is set in St. Petersburg
(Russia, not Florida), two years before the main story begins, and
it is a fine piece of writing in itself. We then move to Alaska,
home of Kate Shugak, Stabenow's Aleut Native Alaskan investigator,
who has worked her way into our imaginations in eight previous
encounters. Shugak has virtually disappeared, in mourning for her
murdered lover and her own life, and an important part of the
novel, which functions as a second prologue, details finding her.
This done, she and we are propelled into a fine account of the
linkage between Russia and Alaska, smuggling, and some beautifully
evoked Alaskan landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this exception, my bias against prologues is nicely
supported in two other books this month. K. J. A. Wishnia's ``The
Glass Factory'' (Dutton, $23.95) gives us Filomena Buscarsela,
ex-NYPD officer from Ecuador, who is handed a diagnosis that she
has cancer and, at best, eight months to live. This happens on the
day her 2-year-old daughter shows her own detective talent by
concluding that Fil takes cough syrup in order to make her cough
and, as any bright 2-year-old would, wants to know why her mother
likes coughing. There is a needless prologue that uses seven
sentences to get us to a killing, and some other padding, but
mother and daughter are so appealing, and the case against an
unscrupulous businessman who is polluting great swatches of Long
Island is put together so compellingly, the tale keeps one reading
to its bittersweet end.
</P>
<P>
   Another clumsy prologue draws us into ``Shut Down'' by R. J.
Pineiro (Forge, $24.95), which opens with a killing in Japan, moves
on to a railway accident in Florida and an industrial disaster in
Texas, and then settles down to the interesting business of how
computer programs are sabotaged. From this point on, Pineiro's book
grows in its bid to command the reader's undivided attention, and
in the end proves that Pineiro is now professional enough as a
spinner of high-tech thrillers to give up his need to escape from
the search for a compelling first sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the best writers have long since overcome their
insecurity about how to start. Jane Heller is feisty, funny, and
fully in control in ``Name Dropping'' (St. Martin's Press, $24.95),
perhaps because as a literary agent she has helped so many insecure
writers onto the path to success. Her heroine is Nancy Stern, a
preschool teacher who begins to receive $10,000 American Express
bills and invitations to ambassadorial parties because she learns
(in the skillful equivalent to a prologue) that another Nancy Stern
has moved into her apartment block. The first Nancy's phone
messages entice her into accepting a blind date with a man who
thinks she is the second Nancy, and from here everything proceeds
with amusing complications until the second Nancy is murdered. It's
a great story with much wry comment about how trendy parents
deposit their trophy offspring at nursery school and what they
expect of teaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Harlan Coben also knows how to begin a story without hesitation
marks, and ``Darkest Fear'' (Delacorte, $23.95) is a terrific novel
about a young boy who must have a bone-marrow transplant, the
search for a donor who, having surfaced, has disappeared, and the
efforts of Myron Bolitar, ex-Duke basketball star and now sports
agent, to come to terms with the strong possibility that he is the
father. Bolitar is rather immature, and Coben doesn't trouble
himself about making him very attractive, but Coben's
professionalism is clear from every paragraph in the book.
</P>
<P>
   When one thinks of professionals, one thinks quickly of K. C.
Constantine, whose ``Grievance'' (Mysterious Press, $23.95)
completes the transition from Mario Balzic to Ruggerio ``Rugs''
Carlucci as the top cop of Rocksburg, Pa., as decaying a city as
one could hope not to visit. Constantine has a wonderful ear for
how we speak, and he shows the complex home life of his characters
through the angry, despairing way they talk, while never forgetting
that there is also a killing to be investigated: of J. D. Lyons, a
steel magnate found in the trunk of his Jaguar, the man most
responsible for the steady decline of an already grim steel town,
for whose murder nearly everyone in town must be a suspect. I have
admired Constantine for a long time, not least because he gets
right to it, no prologues or epilogues, and he rides the tiger to
the end. I think this is the best Constantine novel ever.
</P>
<P>
   Robin W. Winks reports from Oxford, where he is teaching for the
year, and is hungry for American-based books and the rhythms of
demotic American speech. He returns to Yale in September, and will
probably long for the interrogative voice of Inspector Morse once
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
