<HEADER>
A8882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS &LR;      05-29 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRAUSCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE DREAM, WILL TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN TRAUSCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tony Tjan, 29, and Kaming Ng, 36, cofounders of Zefer Corp.,
might seem to be cliches _ successful, rich, Internet geniuses. Are
there any other kind?
</P>
<P>
   A person walking into their reception area on the sixth floor of
their office and seeing the purple pool table in front of the
silver desk might think: ``Typical dot
</P>
<P>
   .com decor. Too cool to stand. I'm out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many young entrepreneurs, they have rocketed into the
financial stratosphere riding an idea at Internet speed. In just
two years Zefer, a private company, has attracted $102 million in
venture capital and generated more than $18.3 million in revenues
selling Net business strategies to clients. Their motto might be:
Way beyond the Web site. Last week the company announced a $12
million deal with Citizens Bank to expand online services and
internal systems.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a half-dozen determined souls sleeping on
the floor of Tjan's loft in Central Square when he was a Harvard
Business School student is now 750 employees in six cities.
</P>
<P>
   But who are those guys? Beneath the numbers and behind the
sleek, fast corporate culture that would seem to typify a business
generation, there is always a human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents came over with $100,'' says Tjan of the journey his
father and mother made from Indonesia to Newfoundland in the late
1960s. ``They had no notion of what they were getting into _ they
just knew what they were getting out of. They barely had a
language. They landed in Gander in the middle of winter. My mother
cried for two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tjan's parents were first-generation Chinese in Indonesia, part
of a persecuted minority who found a new life in Canada. His
father, who studied at McGill, is a doctor. Tjan was born in
Montreal and grew up in St. John's, Newfoundland. He came to
Massachusetts to attend Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Ng and his parents left Hong Kong in 1994, also for political
reasons, and settled in Toronto. His father is a choreographer who
studied at the Royal School of Ballet in Hong Kong. His mother was
a dancer who later became a costume designer. Ng majored in
mathematics at the University of Ulster in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who has had contact with some immigrant history has an
appreciation for entrepreneurship,'' says Tjan, who met Ng in 1995
when they worked in the Toronto office of McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
management consultants. Tjan was a consultant. Ng worked in visual
aids. He is now the design honcho at Zefer.
</P>
<P>
   Their immigrant roots sparked their friendship and continues to
shape their passion for their work, allowing them to have what Tjan
calls ``a greater belief in the possibilities. We've seen what a
person has to do to overcome adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The April stock market dive didn't panic them much. Zefer had
been scheduled to go public but pulled back. They still had their
champagne party, though, celebrating growth instead of an IPO.
</P>
<P>
   They're philosophical. Ng quotes Confucius: ``If you find
something you like to do, you'll never work another day in your
life.'' The days are long, sometimes starting at 6:30 a.m. The
travel is intense. ``When people ask my address, I give them a seat
number on United,'' says Tjan.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a job. ``If I thought this was a job, I'd be gone
by now,'' says Ng. ``I don't want a job. That's 9 to 5 and boring.
I want a challenge. I do this because I love problem solving. It's
not about pixels on a screen. It's not about color. I love
technology. I want to express the best way to navigate through
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Accumulating wealth is as boring to them as a job. Ng rents a
small apartment in the South End. He loves to cook and play the
guitar. He has no car. Tjan owns a one-bedroom in the Back Bay that
is smaller than his student loft. He drives a Saab. He enjoys good
food and French and California wines. But mostly what he does is
work.
</P>
<P>
   Tjan hopes their footprint in time will be this: ``When people
think of the Net, they will say we were the people with the insight
and smarts to guide them through the space.'' He hopes the world
will think big about information-age ethics and ask: ``What is the
digital soul?''
</P>
<P>
   Is he ever scared? ``Some nights you wake up feeling like you're
building a plane while learning to fly,'' he says. ``Other times
you're a 7-foot-2, 8-year-old kid.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably doesn't get much better than that.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Trausch is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at trausch(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
