<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MONEY-TRADING-BOS &LR;      05-29 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TRADING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE STOCK TRADES HAVE TRADE-OFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free stock quotes are everywhere. Costless Internet connections
were news a year ago. And gratis e-mail accounts? They're downright
pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably inevitable that somebody would dangle free stock
trades in front of online investors, too.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Boston-based Brown &AMP; Co. slashed commissions to $5 on
some trades back in 1998. Longer ago than that, brokers began
blanketing the Web with offers to buy and sell shares for as little
as $7 or $8 per trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making almost nothing on each trade as it is,'' said
Robert Sterling, an analyst at Jupiter Communications in New York.
``What's another $5, or even $8?''
</P>
<P>
   It may not mean much to them, but three online brokerages hope
the extra money matters a whole lot to investors.
</P>
<P>
   One, American Express Brokerage, first offered free trades to
high-roller clients in November. Two others introduced a limited
form of no-cost trading this month, both targeting less monied _
and more active _ investors.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, all three services sound great. But free trading
isn't without its detractors.
</P>
<P>
   Unless an investor does a fair amount of trading each month, the
argument goes, $5 just isn't that significant. On a $10,000
buy-and-hold investment, few people will care whether they have to
hand over one more Abe Lincoln to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   And reduced commissions typically come at a price in other
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, you have to ask yourself what you need
from (an online) broker,'' said Jaime Punishill, an analyst at
Forrester Research in Cambridge. ``We've found that commissions are
often well down the list of priorities for people.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But few are going to turn down free trades, as long as
their other priorities are addressed.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you need to take a close look at the tradeoffs each
site forces on you in exchange for zero commissions.
</P>
<P>
   --www.americanexpress.com offers a relatively robust brokerage,
along with a number of other financial services.
</P>
<P>
   There's just one catch: To get free trading, you need to keep a
six-figure account with American Express. (Actually, stock
purchases are commission-free with $25,000 in your account.
Commissionless sales require a $100,000 minimum.)
</P>
<P>
   If your account dips below the threshold, trades are $14.95
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presumably, people who qualify for free trading have more
money than the average bear,'' said Dan Burke, an analyst at Gomez
Advisors in Lincoln. ``Free trading for them isn't the deciding
factor in choosing a broker, but it's a little bonus on top.''
</P>
<P>
   American Express spokesman Dave Kanihan agreed, saying investors
attracted to free trades are likely to be interested in the
company's other services, too.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage is substantial in its own right, though, offering
the ability to trade stocks on all the major exchanges (but not
over the counter), buy and sell 2,000 mutual funds, and trade all
kinds of bonds. It also features online bill payment, and peddles
options, certificates of deposit, and some insurance products.
</P>
<P>
   The site's investment tools include real-time stock quotes and
some charting. And, of course, American Express financial planners
stand ready to give you advice _ for an additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty thorough service,'' said Sterling, of Jupiter
Communications. ``You just have to be able to pony up $100,000 to
get the free transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   --www.freetrade.com is at the other end of the Internet-broker
spectrum. The no-frills end.
</P>
<P>
   A subsidiary of Ameritrade, freetrade.com tells investors up
front that the type of trading it offers isn't for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only survive with special types of accounts and a
special type of operation,'' the site explains. ``Therefore, we can
only service a special type of customer, a customer that will
qualify and agree to our type of operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is strictly bare bones and completely electronic,
with no phone support, no research, and no screens full of
real-time trading data.
</P>
<P>
   You can't transfer money from another account to freetrade.com
(wire transfers only, please). You can't open an IRA, or trade
bonds, options, or mutual funds (stocks only, thank you). And you
can't do anything other than simple market orders if you want free
trading (limit orders cost $5 each).
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, freetrade.com differentiates itself from competitors
by cutting back on expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The home page also discloses freetrade.com's sources of revenue:
Advertising, interest from loans to investors, and ``payment for
order flow,'' or the cents per share that stock clearing firms pay
to process your trades (they profit by selling those shares for a
smidgen more than they paid).
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers, though, are skeptical of the site's chances
for long-term survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freetrade is just floating something up there, to see if it
sticks,'' said Burke, of Gomez Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 10 guys in the world that want this kind of
trading,'' said Punishill, of Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody from freetrade.com or its parent company is defending the
site at this point, either. Ameritrade quietly launched the service
a few weeks ago, and won't comment publicly on it now.
</P>
<P>
   --www.thefinancialcafe.com began taking buy and sell orders less
than two weeks ago, and is the most difficult of the free-trading
sites to peg.
</P>
<P>
   Like freetrade.com, it eliminates commissions on basic market
orders. (Most other stock trades cost $16.95, plus 1 cent per
share. If you have to speak with a live broker, it will cost you
$30.95, plus 1 cent per share.)
</P>
<P>
   Like American Express, thefinancialcafe.com provides a
relatively full slate of brokerage offerings. Mutual funds, bonds,
and options are included, and IRAs are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Thefinancialcafe.com also offers a split trading screen, which
allows investors to track their stocks on one side and pull up
research on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we won't make you wire money to us to open an account,''
joked Andrew Koslow, chief operating officer of The Financial
Cafe.com LLC, based in San Francisco. ``A check or a transfer will
do just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The site tries to provide both low-cost trades and high-value
service by partnering with firms such as Morningstar.com and
IPO.com. It gives the firms part ownership in thefinancialcafe.com,
or promises to send business their way in exhange for no-cost or
low-cost tie-ins for brokerage customers.
</P>
<P>
   Koslow said more partnerships are in the works, which will
expand the number and type of services available.
Thefinancialcafe.com also has its own editorial staff, cranking out
investment-related articles for clients.
</P>
<P>
   The information clearly eclipses what's available on
freetrade.com. But it isn't (yet) on par with the offerings at
full-service brokerages.
</P>
<P>
   Punishill said that if he was a typical investor and it was his
money, he'd probably take a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you're trading dozens of times per month, you won't
spend that much on commissions,'' he said. ``Is that really worth
betting that a new brokerage will stick around, that you won't have
to transfer your account later, or that you'll get bad service or
executions?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get so much more for $8 or $10 a trade, most people
will decide it's not worth it to be an early adopter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
