<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE QUESTION AND ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By C. CLAIBORNE RAY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yellowing Paper
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why does paper, especially newsprint, turn yellow as it ages?
</P>
<P>
   A. The paper is oxidizing, one of several destructive processes
that affect paper. Newsprint is high in lignin, one of the main
structural components of wood. When lignin is in contact with
oxygen, a highly reactive chemical, the reaction changes the way
the fibers reflect light, discoloring the paper. Oxidation also
produces more acid, a major culprit in the breakdown of many modern
papers.
</P>
<P>
   Older paper was usually made from linen or cotton fibers, which
required little treatment to offer a good writing surface. Wood is
much cheaper, but manufacturers found they had to use a thin
chemical layer called sizing on the paper surface to make it less
absorbent and prevent blurring when ink is applied.
</P>
<P>
   A commonly used sizing is a compound of alum, or aluminum
sulfate, and when exposed to warmth and high humidity, alum
molecules split up and form an acidic solution. Cellulose fibers,
which are made of molecular chains of carbon atoms, are easily
split by even weak acids. The strength of the fibers is destroyed,
and the paper becomes fragile.
</P>
<P>
   The acid problem affects nearly half the books published since
1850, conservators estimate, and it was not until the 1950s that
publishers began to abandon alum sizing for alternatives to make
some paper acid-free. Conservators are also working on treatments
to de-acidify paper.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-29 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE ABORTION BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By coming out forcefully in support of the
Republicans' current anti-abortion plank, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
may have avoided another bitter abortion fight at the party's
convention in July.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed his capitulation to the GOP's far right during a
joint appearance with Gen. Colin Powell, who is widely admired and
mentioned as a possible secretary of state but who would like to
remove the plank. This means that moderates who had hoped for a
more tolerant convention position on abortion might as well give up
now. Bush will control the convention, and what he wants he will
get.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican platform is a grass-roots document, and I think
the plank ought to stay the way it is,'' Bush said last week. The
comment reflects the retreat he has been making from his previous,
more woman-friendly stand.
</P>
<P>
   Before his primary scare in the South Carolina primary and his
embrace of the Christian right, Bush used to say that while he
supported an anti-abortion constitutional amendment, he favored
exceptions for the life of the mother and in cases of rape and
incest.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 GOP platform endorses ``a human life amendment to the
Constitution'' and ``legislation to make clear that the Fourteen
Amendment protections apply to unborn children.'' It does not
mention any exception. The language treats a fetus in a womb as a
person entitled to equal protection of the laws with rights that
are identical to those of a living, breathing, pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   The plank also supports ``the appointment of judges who respect
traditional family values and the sanctity of innocent human
life,'' which is the GOP code for a fetus. Bush has never been
clear about how he views this section of the anti-abortion plank,
but in his remarks last week he did not back away from it.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that he will not apply an anti-abortion litmus test
to his Supreme Court and other judicial appointments, as the plank
demands. But he coyly declares that he wants to name ``strict
constructionists'' and lists Supreme Court Justice Anthony Scalia,
who strongly favors overturning the Roe v. Wade decision, which
legalized abortion, as the jurist he most respects.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party platform was pro-choice until 1980, when
the nominee, Ronald Reagan, insisted on reversing that position.
Since then, anti-abortion activists within the GOP have grown
steadily more demanding, kicking up a fuss when subsequent nominees
George Bush, the governor's father, and Sen. Bob Dole tried to
reach out to pro-choice Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 President Bush talked about making the party ``a big
tent'' encompassing all views on the subject. He personally
supported an exception for the life of the prospective mother. But
his words turned out to be hollow. He couldn't overcome pressure
from the religious right. Outnumbered and intimidated, moderates
abandoned their threats of a floor fight in the interests of party
unity. The platform remained intolerant and the tent tiny.
</P>
<P>
   Again in 1996, Dole, needing desperately to appeal to
independents and moderates, tried to soften the offending GOP
plank. Polls show that most voters want abortion to be limited but
do not want it outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   Dole wanted to include a mild reference to abortion as a matter
of ``personal conscience.'' But his modifying language was
immediately rejected by abortion opponents, and he too gave up in
order to avoid a bitter internal party fight.
</P>
<P>
   The best Dole could do was to say that he had not read the
platform and to indicate that he would ignore it because nobody
paid any attention to it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was right in a sense. Party platforms are instruments of
interest mostly to political wonks. But the documents do set forth
the political philosophy of a party and as such can be a useful
guide to the direction a newly elected president might take.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has ample reason to work for a peaceful convention that
buries the divisions within his party. A nominee who presides over
an unruly pack of delegates does not inspire confidence in his
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Given that reality, it is unlikely that Bush will have the
courage to select a running mate who is pro-choice although he is
trying to win over moderates by pretending to consider one. The
religious right objects as strongly to that heresy as to changing
the abortion plank.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have signed onto the Bush campaign mostly as the
lesser of two evils. Many of them are willing to live with his
low-key approach to abortion (he seldom mentions it) so long as
they know he is really in their corner.
</P>
<P>
   Picking a pro-choice vice president would confuse and anger
them. It would also be inconsistent with the unambiguous signals of
unwavering opposition to a woman's right to choose that he is now
sending.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
