<HEADER>
A8896 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ESSAY-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      05-29 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSAY-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOURNALIST AND THE SERIAL KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN YEMMA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a bright spring morning not long ago, two state troopers
showed up unannounced in the lobby of my office. One was tall, one
was short. Both were wearing windbreakers. They wanted to talk to
me and ushered me over to a side area. Immediately, I raced through
recent memories to see if there was something I did, someone I knew
. . . but I came up empty. I live a quiet life _ work, home, a
little excessive speed in between, maybe, but nothing more daring
than that. I have no ongoing feuds, no felonious friends.
</P>
<P>
   In 25 years as a journalist, I've talked with law enforcement
officials many times. Usually, it's a situation involving someone
whose life has just been intruded upon by violence, craziness,
turmoil. Usually, I'm asking the questions, weighing the answers
for that elusive quality, truth. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelly, one of the troopers, pulled a file folder out of his
briefcase and showed me a four-page letter he had received, via
Interpol, from a police department in Scotland. Keeping his voice
low so as not to be overheard by my co-workers strolling past,
Kelly explained that a slip of paper with my name on it had been
found when police raided the apartment of a suspected serial killer
in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that moment. Imagine it in slow motion: s-e-r-i-a-l
k-i-l-l-e-r.
</P>
<P>
   The man's name is William Ian Beggs. The crime for which the
36-year-old Beggs had been arrested was the killing and
dismemberment of an 18-year-old grocery store worker. Parts of the
young man's body were found in Loch Lomond. The cavalier Scottish
tabloids have reduced this awful crime to a sound bite called the
``limbs in the loch case.''
</P>
<P>
   Scottish authorities wanted, first, to confirm my ``safety and
well-being.'' That being clear, Kelly then showed me three pictures
of Beggs taken over a 10-year-period, progressively more fleshy
through the decade. Had I ever seen him? I have a good memory for
faces. And I have done a lot of traveling in my career. He didn't
register as anyone I had met.
</P>
<P>
   There's one other thing, and saying this will be a little
awkward: Beggs preyed mainly on men, most of them gay.
</P>
<P>
   I am not gay. I don't lead a secret life, either. But a possible
Jeffrey Dahmer-type serial killer had my name. How? Why? I've never
even been to Scotland. It's been five years since I've traveled
abroad. Could Beggs have come to the United States?
</P>
<P>
   I puzzled over it. There are two other John Yemmas in the world
that Internet searches have turned up, but the actual information
that police pulled from Beggs's apartment was linked to me:
``Boston Globe 00-1-617-929-2000. John Yemma. PO 2378 Boston
02107.'' I can never remember the post office box number, so the
fact that he had it (it's on my cards) was a clue of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   I thought back to a talk I had given during a fellowship at
Oxford University in 1994 and to a conference I had attended in
Belfast that same year. Could I have run into him at either of
those places? There are always mysterious faces on the edges of
crowds. Some background research indicated that at one time Beggs,
who hails from County Down, was active in Ulster Unionist circles.
Could he have been in an office when I handed out a business card?
There is always a low-level functionary in a back room compiling a
list of journalists for bureaucratic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   So was he stalking me? On calling the police department in
Strathclyde, the city where Beggs's last victim lived, I was told
by a sympathetic policewoman that while my name was found on a
scrap of paper, many other names were found on other scraps of
paper and in address books throughout Beggs's litter-strewn
apartment. There was no clue to his intentions with those names,
but police are investigating a string of disappearances. Neighbors
spoke of screams and sawing sounds coming from his apartment at
various times.
</P>
<P>
   Beggs, I learned, was a computer specialist at a local
university. Could that be how he got my name and the Globe's post
office box? Possibly, said policewoman Kate Jackson: ``We're seeing
more and more of that sort of thing with the Internet.'' But the
Internet is such a forest of names and information. Why pick a
minor character like me?
</P>
<P>
   Or could someone who knew me have been using my identity to mask
his own as he cruised the gay bars of Scotland? That could be the
case as well, Jackson agreed. Five years ago, my wife found that an
acquaintance had appropriated her name and was using it on an
Internet chat room, having cooked up a story about being a
paraplegic who was consulting with my wife, a psychiatrist. The
acquaintance is able-bodied. My wife is an illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someone did the same with my name. Trooper Kelly told me
this happens more often than you might think. Or maybe some third
party just dropped the name while talking with Beggs in a dark bar
somewhere. But it just as well could have been in broad daylight in
a perfectly innocent setting. Even a serial killer must have a
normal side, must sometimes sit in the next seat on an airplane,
buy a cup of coffee at the same counter as you, show an interest in
activities other than murder and dismemberment.
</P>
<P>
   I'll probably never know. Jackson assured me I have nothing to
worry about. I have signed a sworn statement saying that to the
best of my recollection I've never met or seen Beggs and know no
one who has. If this creep, currently jailed in Amsterdam, has a
string of crimes to his name, that is where the tragedies lie, that
is where investigative energy should be spent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a lesson for me: Over the years I have had the
unpleasant task of talking with people whose private lives, because
of some event _ a war, an accident, a controversy _ have been
penetrated by the merciless public gaze. I've met some of you when
you were at your most vulnerable, when your good name, your very
identity, was under suspicion, when you worried about the
skepticism with which your story was greeted _ worried that you
were somehow guilty because you were inadvertently connected. I've
always imagined it was awkward for you. I've never known how
awkward until now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
