<HEADER>
A8897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-HARRINGTON-BOS &LR;      05-29 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-HARRINGTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A CRUSADER   AGAINST POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE OTHER AMERICAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Life of Michael Harrington &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Maurice Isserman. PublicAffairs. &UR;  &LR; 449 pp. Illustrated.
$28.50. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the most influential American books of the last 50 years
was ``The Other America'' by Michael Harrington, subtitled
``Poverty in America'' and first published in 1962. Not only did
this eloquently compressed book (it ran fewer than 200 pages)
influence public policy, beginning in the Kennedy administration
and continuing with the Johnson administration's War on Poverty,
but it inspired tens of thousands of young Americans to join VISTA
or the Peace Corps and try to change the world Harrington had raged
against.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington died almost 11 years ago, and a full-scale biography
is most welcome. In Maurice Isserman, he has found an admiring, but
critical, biographer. It is a tribute to his skill that Isserman, a
leading historian of the American left and a history professor at
Hamilton College, is as understanding of Harrington's ``discovery''
of poverty in the Catholic Worker movement as he is of Harrington's
efforts to find a solution through socialism.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington (born Edward, in 1928) came out of a comfortable
middle-class, Roman Catholic background in St. Louis and went to
Holy Cross. There followed a year at Yale Law School, then one at
the University of Chicago to pursue poetic yearnings.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home, having recast himself as ``Michael,'' his middle
name, he landed a job as a welfare worker for the St. Louis public
schools. Brief though his stay was, he still recalled years later
the day he visited a derelict tenement. ``The cooking smells and
the stench from the broken, stopped-up toilets and the murmurous
cranky sound of the people were a revelation. It was my moment on
the road to Damascus, (and riding home) I realized that somehow I
must spend the rest of my life trying to obliterate that kind of
house and to work with the people who lived there.'' Isserman takes
Harrington's memory at face value, perhaps because such
impulsiveness was so very much in his character.
</P>
<P>
   At the Catholic Worker, Isserman writes, Harrington was more of
a scholar than a ``mercy-giver.'' He ``did not often serve food on
the bread line, and when he did, it was not with any great sense of
fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   But there Harrington fell under the spell of the saintly _ and
autocratic _ Dorothy Day. He would remember years later that it was
considered a ``perfectly rational and legitimate thing'' to say
that one was there because they wanted ``to be a saint.'' For her
part, Isserman writes, ``Day appreciated the intellectual luster''
that Harrington brought to the Catholic Worker's penny-a-copy
newspaper and ``also appreciated the social graces'' _ opening the
door and pulling out the chair for her _ he brought to scruffy St.
Joseph's House.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, it is Day, not any of his socialist allies
and enemies of later years, whose inspiration Harrington
acknowledges in ``The Other America.'' Through her and the Catholic
Worker movement, he wrote, ``I first came in contact with the
terrible reality of involuntary poverty and the magnificent ideal
of voluntary poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington left the Catholic Worker _ and the Roman Catholic
Church _ after a year, reassuring the straight-laced Day that it
was because of ideology, not a woman. The ideology was socialism
and Harrington spent _ perhaps ``squandered'' is the appropriate
word _ many ensuing years fighting one factional battle after
another. Isserman chronicles this in some detail, but recognizes
that it all pales against the signal accomplishment of ``The Other
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The book grew out of two articles Harrington wrote for
Commentary magazine. The timing, Isserman writes, ``was remarkably
good,'' the second appearing after US Senator John F. Kennedy,
campaigning in West Virginia for the 1960 Democratic presidential
nomination, had exposed the region's desperate poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Harrington who became known as ``the man who
discovered poverty.'' As Isserman writes, Harrington wanted his
readers to understand ``that despite the apparent national
consensus about the arrival of the `affluent society,' widespread
poverty continued to exist'' in an ``invisible land'' of rural
isolation or urban slums. Beyond that, poverty was not just a lack
of income but a distinct culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creative achievement,'' writes Isserman, was to present
these findings in a tone that was ``modest, reasonable and calm,
and . . . at the same time idealistic, impassioned, and
inspiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington spent his final years in efforts to promote a
socialist ideology within the Democratic Party. He died, in July
1989, of cancer, still hopeful _ even against the evidence that
that ``other America'' of poverty had not been vanquished _ that
``there are signs that we are, without really having planned it
that way, marching out of the desert.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other America'' is still in print (though not with the
ironic red-white-and-blue cover of the paperback that once tumbled
out of activists' backpacks). It is still powerful in the
rereading. It might even hold the power to influence the children
of those thousands who read it while at their long-ago
poverty-program postings in Harlem or Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kenney is a member of the Globe staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1532EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
