<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-SEADRAGONS-NYT &LR;      05-29 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SEADRAGONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WEEDY SEA DRAGON PLAYS A STARRING ROLE AS `MR. MOM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
 By RACHEL USLAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Normally, it is the most popular exhibit at the Long Beach
Aquarium of the Pacific, but lately, the weedy and leafy sea dragon
tank is surrounded by more expectation than the usual school-age
visitors provide. One of the weedy males is pregnant, with about
100 bright pink eggs hanging prominently onto his tail. That 8-inch
creature is an international star.
</P>
<P>
   What has the aquarium world watching so closely is not that the
mother is a male. Sea dragons are actually among one or two fish
groups whose males incubate the eggs. Rather it is the hope that
this notably sensitive species might actually reproduce away from
its natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mom,'' as he is called, is the first captive weedy sea
dragon in the United States, and only the third in the world, to
carry its eggs effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tense times'' are expected around the aquarium until the sea
dragon gives birth, said Sandy Trautwein, the curator of fishes and
invertebrates. The gestation period is six weeks and the birth is
expected the week of June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since no one has done it successfully before,'' Trautwein
said, ``there is no recipe. I'm going by instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The sea dragon, a relative of the sea horse, has a reputation
for being particularly delicate, both in captivity and in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Endemic to the seaweed beds where the Southern Ocean meets the
South Pacific, these famously fragile swimmers essentially rely on
their camouflage to survive. They look almost exactly like a small
piece of seaweed that has broken off the mother plant and has
quietly sprouted eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Often the victims of habitat destruction, sea dragons have
become a protected species in Australia. Trautwein said that only
two people have permits to collect them. The sea dragons'
precarious situation and delicate nature make the potential
aquarium birth all the more significant to naturalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely jealous,'' said Bob Burhans, the curator of the
Birch Aquarium in La Jolla, Calif. ``I've had weedy sea dragons for
four years and have never gotten to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   When Trautwein does one of her several checks a day, she looks
to see if any of his eggs have dropped. The reproduction of a sea
dragon relies on the transfer of eggs from the female to the male's
``brood patch,'' a section of blood-rich indentations on the
underside of his tail. When the males are ready, the patch widens
and releases a fluid that helps the eggs stay attached for four to
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past, aquarium males have not been ready to commit.
At Germany's Stuttgart Aquarium, the male dropped a few eggs each
week until only five were left. At Tokyo's Sea Life Park, several
eggs hatched but survived for only eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So far Mr. Mom has dropped a few eggs, but not at a very fast
rate, ``So I feel it's a tremendous success,'' Trautwein said.
</P>
<P>
   In order to ensure that Mr. Mom's eggs can endure the breeding
process, the Long Beach aquarium is trying to mimic the seasonal
changes of the sea dragon's typical environment. But Burhans notes
that maintaining the correct length of daylight hours is often
impossible to achieve because visitors may want to see the exhibits
at the same time the fish would prefer darkness.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Trautwein will try to keep Mr. Mom
comfortable in his usual tank for as long as she can. About a week
before the birth, she plans to move him to a holding tank within
the same water system but with controlled lighting and temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Mom is still in the exhibit, where visitors can note how
weighed down he looks by his cluster of eggs. Yet when mysids, the
tiny shrimplike crustaceans that he feeds on, are dropped into the
tank, he suddenly moves with the ease of all the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely eating more than he used to,'' said Trautwein,
who is reassured by Mr. Mom's appetite.
</P>
<P>
   ``His nutrition helps the health of the eggs so it's a good sign
that he's eating,'' Trautwein said. At the other aquariums, the
males had stopped eating.
</P>
<P>
   Trautwein explained that whatever happens, the Mr. Mom
experience has given her hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a dream last night that one of our leafy sea dragons had
also laid eggs on the male's tail during the night,'' she said. ``I
drove to work this morning thinking that it might be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a leafy was releasing some eggs by the time
Trautwein arrived, though there was no male ready to accept them.
Perhaps Mr. Mom will show one of them the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
