<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-JACKSON-BOS &LR;      05-29 1436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL JACKSON'S LEGACY LIVES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael Jackson anointed himself King of Pop nine years
ago, he had already missed his cue by several beats. It was 1991.
Grunge was brewing. The emerging alternative rock loudly condemned
the glitz and commercialism of good-time fare like Jackson's. A new
radical fringe was, in time-honored tradition, rearing its unruly
head, and the sound of music was changing _ fast. Jackson's
self-coronation was more a desperate gesture from a suddenly
outdated icon than a timely assessment of Jackson's reign, which
had already begun its long, strange decline into dark eccentricity.
</P>
<P>
   His prodigious artistic accomplishments during the phenomenal
run that spanned 1979's ``Off the Wall,'' 1982's ``Thriller,'' and
1987's ``Bad'' paled _ like his skin color _ with each new
revelation about his bizarre lifestyle. Jackson's morphing
appearance was the most distressing quirk of all. In the process of
obliterating his race, neutralizing his gender, and erasing his
sexuality, Jackson managed to expunge his musical identity as well.
</P>
<P>
   But time has a way of twisting itself inside out when it comes
to cultural trends. While the art may have been eclipsed by his
hellish life story, Michael Jackson's musical legacy is alive and
well. In terms of influence, Jackson is, in fact, the King of Pop,
circa 2000. His pioneering fusion of dance, rock, pop, and soul,
his merging of black and white sounds, and his highly stylized
phrasing and tautly controlled dancing are at the heart of the
music sweeping today's charts _ from Backstreet Boys and Britney
Spears to LFO and 'N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   The commodified assembly-line look and sound of today's teen
acts is the direct descendant of a look and sound that was, at its
inception two decades ago, a pop-culture breakthrough. In 1979,
then-21-year-old Jackson and veteran producer Quincy Jones
collaborated on ``Off the Wall.'' It did more than just present the
former Motown boy wonder as a mature artist. Songs like ``Don't
Stop 'Til You Get Enough,'' ``Rock With You,'' and the title track
introduced a blend of slick disco rhythms, Motown soul, and
pop-radio sweetness that cut a clean swath through genre and color
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Thriller,'' released in 1983, Jackson and Jones ensured
that their vision, the glamorous new dance-pop, became a global
phenomenon. The album's masterful artistry is easily obscured by
its staggering commercial success: 46 million sold, eight Grammy
awards, an unprecedented seven Top 10 singles. But the album's real
significance was crystallized in Eddie Van Halen's searing rock
guitar solo on ``Beat It.'' It was a resounding shout-out for
Jackson's blanket crossover, emblematic of an invigorating new
sound that was embraced by lovers of soul, pop fans, the burgeoning
hip-hop nation, and rock enthusiasts. ``Beat It'' became the first
video by a black artist to spin into heavy rotation on MTV. With
the subsequent elaborate song-and-dance videos for ``Billie Jean''
and ``Thriller,'' Jackson helped pioneer the video medium, which
would become the lifeblood of the next generation's glossy
dance-pop stars.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it didn't take two decades for the impact of
Jackson's sound to reverberate in the industry. The poster boys of
1980, New Edition and (especially) New Kids on the Block, both
Boston bands, were influenced as much by the bubble-gum soul of the
Jackson 5 as by Jackson's sophisticated solo work. A decade later,
the teen band Hanson seemed to be channeling the Jackson 5 on its
breakthrough song, ``MMMBop.'' But what's striking about those '80s
powerhouses is the fact that impresario Maurice Starr, who created
both groups, essentially substituted white kids for black kids in
the identical musical mold.
</P>
<P>
   Lines erased
</P>
<P>
   The line between traditional black and white sounds had for all
intents and purposes been erased _ ironically enough by a man who
had literally scrubbed himself free of color. It paved the way for
a group composed entirely of white middle-class boys who sang a
hybrid of new jack balladry, hip-hop R &AMP; B, and sentimental pop.
Even the quintet's name, the Backstreet Boys, evoked a mixture of
urban cool and mild-mannered youthfulness _ a study in
contradictions purveyed by Jackson, as well. The world hadn't seen
the sort of mass cross-cultural hysteria inspired by the Backstreet
Boys since Michael Jackson's heyday.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync _ yet another grouping of five young male singers _
followed in short order. The band's second album, ``No Strings
Attached,'' which sold a record-setting 2.6 million copies its
first week out in March, owes still more to Jackson's legacy with
its meticulously crafted mixture of hard beats, breezy pop, techno
flourishes, and lush ballads.
</P>
<P>
   Take the band's current single, ``Bye Bye Bye'' (although one
could conduct the same exercise with just about any of the current
hits in the genre). Held notes on electronic strings start the
song; the anticipatory mood is shortly punctured by a young man's
tenor, loosing a cry of ``hey, hey.'' A wall of beats kicks in, a
wave of synthesizers swells _ merging into restless, rhythmic
bedrock for the singer's compact vocal lines and tight harmonies.
It's driving, melodic, and funky. You can practically see the guys'
synchronized, cookie-cutter dance moves.
</P>
<P>
   That musical arc, while not an explicit copy, is a direct
descendant of ``Thriller.'' On ``Beat It,'' for example,
keyboard-generated bells toll for a few brief bars, then drums drop
in with a steady stream of robotic beats, followed in short order
by a towering groove built from banks of synths and scathing power
chords. The young tenor unleashes taut vocal lines and layers of
harmonies over the churning, jittery rhythms. It's driving,
melodic, and funky. You can practically see the singer's signature
syncopated dance moves.
</P>
<P>
   Today's teens execute slick routines like the advanced
dance-class graduates they are. At his zenith, Jackson merged song
and dance into a seamless whole. And while no one since has matched
Jackson's jaw-dropping instinct for maneuvering his body in the
slivery spaces of a song, the highly stylized movement pioneered by
Jackson has become a ritual component of contemporary pop.
</P>
<P>
   Lather, rinse, repeat
</P>
<P>
   One simply never sees a stage or video performance that doesn't
feature a battalion of choreographed urban warriors. Teen queen
Britney Spears has incurred the wrath of critics by choosing to
lip-synch upbeat numbers in concert, but she has to in order to
conserve lung power for her nonstop dance routines. There's really
no alternative, considering Spears's generic dance-pop singles
function much like window dressing for the herky-jerky body
language that's become common currency in the teen dance-pop
market.
</P>
<P>
   Spears's vocal register, like Jackson's, is tight and narrow,
and on the new ``Oops! . . . I Did It Again'' she has co-opted
Jackson's clipped, tic-strewn phrasing as an effective way of
asserting style over substance. A symphony of synthesizers straight
out of ``Thriller'' cushion Spears's little growls and cries, and
the tune's massive beats. Her remake of the Rolling Stones'
``Satisfaction'' is anchored on the high end by ethereal synths
nearly identical to those on ``Billie Jean,'' and on the low end by
urgent, clamping breaths and rhythmic ``ughs'' _ trademarks of
Jackson's blockbuster hits that surely weren't lost on Spears's
producers. (Spears's new CD sold 1.3 million copies in its first
week of release, second only to 'N Sync for an out-of-the-box sales
performance. In third place: the Backstreet Boys.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Michael Jackson is in the studio _ actually 10
different studios with nearly as many producers _ working on his
next album, which Sony hopes will be ready for release later this
year. The stakes are high for Jackson, 41. Now that the dance-pop
he crafted at the highest level has been watered down, filtered
out, and recycled as fossil fuel for the next generation, Jackson
must reinvent the wheel one more time. He needs to record songs
that are more compelling than sordid tales of consorting with
children. He'll have to summon the courage to leave Neverland and
reenter the real world if he hopes to transcend a decade of his own
tired, bloodless music _ the sad product of his self-imposed
isolation. Otherwise, Jackson's legacy will be reduced to a
synthesizer arrangement here, a spunky dance move there, a
high-pitched cry in a pop song.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
