<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CURRENT MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``M:i-2'' It's big, noisy, explosive, and
marginally more coherent than the first ``Mission: Impossible.''
But it's also pretty labored. Tom Cruise's heroics are too clenched
and intense, and John Woo's direction is too driven, to allow for
much fun in this big pop comic strip. In this nominal chase after a
deadly virus, Cruise's sunglasses are cooler than he is. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS) 1/2 ``Passion of Mind'' A softer, more appealing Demi
Moore, back after a hiatus of several years, as a woman leading a
split life, trying to figure out whether her life as a single mom
in the French countryside with lover Stellan Skarsgard is the real
thing, or whether it's her glam existence as a Manhattan literary
agent with William Fichtner's doting accountant. Glossy stuff,
recalling Hollywood's discovery of Freud in the '40s, but not very
passionate. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (FL) (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Shanghai Noon'' Jackie Chan again, giving us
the film ``Wild, Wild West'' wishes it was. A kidnapped Chinese
princess is all the pretext the movie needs to plunk Chan into the
Old West to unleash another outbreak of his exuberant, inventive
acrobatics. Owen Wilson makes a droll foil, handling the
smart-mouthing with aplomb. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   (BS)(BS)(BS) ``Welcome Back, Mr. McDonald'' Koki Mitani's
outrageously funny show-business comedy illustrates, in a most
amusing fashion, the destructive power of the ego. In Japanese with
English subtitles. (Unrated) (Michael Blowen)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
