<SLUG> BC-ETHIOPIA-ERITREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHIOPIA BOMBS AIRPORT IN ERITREAN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ Ethiopian fighter planes bombed the airport
here Monday, targeting a military airstrip in the first air raid on
Eritrea's capital since the opening blows of the war between the
two nations in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The raid was carried out even as the nations' foreign ministers
prepared to open a new round of peace talks in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrage,'' said Yemane Ghebremeskel, a spokesman
for the Eritrean government. ``The timing is inexplicable.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials from Ethiopia, which began a major offensive two
weeks ago, repeated their intention to continue fighting while
talking about peace. In Addis Ababa, Ethiopia's capital, Lt. Gen.
Tsadakan Gebretensae, the armed forces' chief of staff, said the
airport was a legitimate military target.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to incapacitate the Eritrean air force, and this
operation was conducted in line with this objective,'' he said at a
news conference Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No one was killed in the attack, just three miles from the
capital, though officials here said two civilians were wounded.
Four Ethiopian MiG-23s dropped the bombs Monday morning on the
military section of the airport, which also handles civilian air
traffic. One bomb apparently hit a control tower, but most of the
bombs seemed to have landed in the grass, setting off brush fires.
At least one bomb also hit the road leading to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said two Eritrean MiG-29s, which were parked at the
airport, were not damaged and chased the Ethiopian planes.
</P>
<P>
   Talks were scheduled to begin Monday in Algeria between the
nations' foreign ministers, Seyoum Mesfin of Ethiopia and Haile
Woldensae of Eritrea, though the Ethiopian delegation only arrived
in the afternoon. Last week, Eritrea agreed to withdraw from the
disputed areas along the 620-mile border, after significant
military gains by Ethiopia in the last two weeks. Only minutes
before the bombing, a plane carrying reporters and foreign
diplomats took off from the airport on a trip organized by the
Eritrean government to prove that its troops had withdrawn from the
town of Bure, near the port of Assab on the Red Sea. The plane was
turned back.
</P>
<P>
   The airport is the main portal for food arriving in Asmara to
feed the hundreds of thousands of people displaced by the war in
the last two weeks. Lindsey Davies, a spokeswoman for the U.N.
World Food Program, said none of the three flights of food
scheduled for this week have been canceled. But they may be halted
if there are more attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game of cards at moment,'' she said. ``We really have
to see how the situation pans out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
