<HEADER>
A8908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTEREST-ONLY0530-COX     05-29 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEREST-ONLY0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest-only loans ease rate burden
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Steadily rising mortgage interest rates not only have
prospective home buyers scrambling to find the best rates, they
also have the lending industry busy looking for new ways to attract
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Home-loan interest rates have risen 2 percentage points since
this time last year, practically drying up the refinancing market.
Many current homeowners remain satisfied with interest rates well
below what the market is charging now.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, only 13 percent of a typical lender's portfolio
comes from refinancing, compared with half of its loans just a few
years ago. Overall, mortgage applications are down 10 percent from
12 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The lending industry is turning to interest-only loans with
lower monthly payments than conventional mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   It is just starting to catch on with certain local consumers and
is so new that most home-loan banks don't even offer it on first
mortgages. But HomeBanc, which started developing its HomePower
Classic loan product four years ago, is now writing $65 million a
month in interest-only loans. They account for 25 to 30 percent of
mortgage originations, said spokesman Mark Scott.
</P>
<P>
   The loan is made to order for people who want a lower monthly
payment in a time when interest rates around 8.5 percent can add
hundreds of dollars a month to a conventional loan payment.
</P>
<P>
   The lower monthly payments that resulted from the lower interest
rates that refinancing accomplished two years ago, an interest-only
loan can accomplish now.
</P>
<P>
   The loan is what it says it is _ a mortgage on which buyers pay
interest, but no principal, for a period of eight to 10 years.
After that, the loan reverts to a conventional form, and the
borrower repays the balance of interest due, plus principal, for
perhaps 20 more years. A customary down payment is required, but
monthly payments are lower.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the interest rate is generally lower than for a
conventional loan.
</P>
<P>
   For buyers who stay in their home less than seven years, a
common occurrence in metro Atlanta, the payments on principal may
not make that much difference.
</P>
<P>
   In the first years of a mortgage, a substantial amount of the
payment goes toward interest and very little toward principal. In
an area where home prices are rising, owners could see their equity
increasing faster through appreciation than by paying down the
principal by the time they sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get more bang for your buck with this product,'' said
Charles Wagner, HomePower brand manager. ``You may want to take the
saved money and invest it in your 401(k) plan, to bring you up to
the maximum contribution. You might pay off the high-interest
credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people, like Mary Catherine Doering, want a lower payment
for more personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Doering, an Atlanta obstetrician/gynecologist, recently took out
a HomePower Classic loan that will require her to pay the interest
only on her loan for eight to 10 years. After that, the instrument
converts to a conventional, 15-year mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Doering wanted a lower-payment loan that would allow her the
flexibility to reduce the principal payment as opportunity arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 10-year-old daughter and am trying to structure my
life to take care of her, be with her and be there for her. That
means working less,'' said Doering, whose real-estate agent
suggested the interest-only mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stretches her financial flexibility,'' observed Doug
Perry, senior vice president of California-based Countrywide Home
Loans' consumer marketing division.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, cash-strapped professionals expecting big salary
increases or bonuses in the next few years will also find
interest-only mortgages appealing, said Wayne Fuller, a loan
officer at Tucker Federal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are your own banker. You can pay the home debt down
quickly or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tucker Federal does not offer interest-only on first
mortgages, it does offer them on seconds and equity credit lines.
</P>
<P>
   Both Perry and Wagner warned that there is one major drawback to
this loan: careless use of the monthly savings. People who fail to
save the difference, or who do not put it to a use such as reducing
principal, are missing the point, which the bankers said is to
diversify financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do this strictly for cash flow, you will not maximize
the benefits of this program,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
