<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-PRISON-0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELEASED, BUT WOUNDS FROM NOTORIOUS PRISON HARD TO HEAL
 &HT;    With Two Photos placed on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ While her nation rejoices, Cosette Ibrahim
tries to piece together a life interrupted by the most notorious
element of Israel's occupation of southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Nine months ago, the promising journalism student was
inexplicably snatched from her house by the South Lebanon Army, the
Israeli-allied militia.
</P>
<P>
   They took the young Lebanese woman to the Al-Khiam prison. It
sits high on a hill wrapped in walls and rolls of barbed wire, but
was the dungeon of the occupation.
</P>
<P>
   There, Ibrahim faced a month of interrogations and beatings, and
eight more months of incarceration. Like the other prisoners, she
had no trial or lawyers. ``Here,'' she said her captors told her,
``You defend yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, as the SLA and Israel gave up their two-decade
occupation, nearby residents cut open the locks of the prison,
setting Ibrahim and about 140 other inmates free.
</P>
<P>
   The prison is open to inspection now. Its cells, originally
built as horse stables by the French in 1933, are strewn with the
old clothes, books and wall graffiti of the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The corduroy hoods that prisoners were forced to wear litter the
courtyard between the small, detached cellblocks. Solitary cells,
about the size of a large closet, sit locked and dank.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say that at least four prisoners died in
Al-Khiam since 1985, when the SLA began using the prison. Torture
included beatings, dowsings with freezing and scalding water, and
electric shock. Rights advocates have called for both Israel and
Lebanon to prosecute those who violated human rights in Al-Khiam,
and in general.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon now celebrates the end of the Israeli occupation _ and
the disintegration and flight of the SLA. Ibrahim is bitter and
tired.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a Beirut cafe on Friday, the tired 25-year-old began
her mission to describe conditions in the prison. It was just three
days after her release and her tension and exhaustion were still
evident. Ulcers she had before were aggravated by the prison stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I feel,'' she said. ``In the end, I was
happy that I was released, but I am shocked at some of the things
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said the prison was run independently by the
SLA. But, the SLA was paid, trained and supplied by the Israeli
government _ and Israel's overall control seems clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli human rights group B'Tselem(CQ) notes that Israel
ordered 50 inmates released from the prison in 1998 to trade for
the body of a dead Israeli soldier held by Hezbollah guerrillas.
Israelis made frequent visits to the jail to pay the guards and
sometimes dropped off prisoners there.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim is Christian and the SLA was lead by Christians. She
said that, and the international attention her case received, won
her ``lenient'' treatment compared to the Muslim prisoners around
here.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim was a graduate student from a town in the occupation
area, about an hour from the prison. She had written articles
against Israel and the occupation in her university newspaper and
she had a brother-in-law involved in one of the resistance groups.
Otherwise, she can think of no reason she was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Her first day, Ibrahim was interrogated for five hours, with a
hood over her head. Two men took turns hitting and kicking her,
while the 120-pound woman was handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, 'We're not going to tell you what it is, but you
have something to tell us and you know what it is,''' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of four women in the prison. They were forced to
submit to medical exams that prison officials said were meant to
show if they were virgins. They claimed it would be used to refute
any claims of rape later.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim said one inmate was raped repeatedly while she was
there.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim passed time reading books provided by the International
Committee of the Red Cross. She said she distrusted the Old
Testament and its description of the Jews as ``chosen'' by God.
</P>
<P>
   Her cell, a square room about 12 feet across that she shared
with three others, was open last week. Ibrahim's pencil-drawn
self-portrait was on the wall, with her inscription in French,
``Sometimes it is easier to dream life than to live it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be contracted at larryk9at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.amnesty.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
