<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8924 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMO     05-29 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMONT-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENT CAL'S HOME SPEAKS VOLUMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.D., Vt., Mass.)   (Editors: a 250-word box appears at end of story.)  
 (For release Sunday, June 4)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For anyone weary of the glitz and spin of modern presidential
campaigns and longing for a quieter time when American presidents
wore hats and spared the electorate their confessions, it may be
time to repair, as my wife, Jaqueline, and I did, to Plymouth
Notch, the Vermont birthplace and home of Silent Cal, as Calvin
Coolidge was nicknamed by contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge, the 30th president of the United States, said he could
not recall that any presidential candidate hurt himself much by not
talking. When a woman bet a friend that she could pry more than two
words out of Coolidge, he told her, ``You lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories about Coolidge and his thrifty, taciturn clan abound in
Plymouth Notch, a community of tidy white clapboard farmhouses and
weathered barns that look unchanged since Coolidge was sworn in
here as president in 1923. That's another good reason to visit
Plymouth Notch, for it is a near-perfect model of a Vermont village
almost a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated in the rugged heartland of the Green Mountains,
Plymouth Notch has been called Vermont's Brigadoon, after the
imaginary Scottish village that appears and vanishes in the mists.
Because the major highways and their attendant filling stations,
convenience stores and strip malls bypassed Plymouth Notch, it
never needed restoration, explained William Jenney, a museum
historian who administers the Calvin Coolidge State Historic Site
on behalf of the Vermont Division for Historic Preservation. ``The
village was not restored, but preserved,'' Jenney said.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled in a pocket of farmland under a panorama of wooded hills
rising to 2,200 feet, Plymouth Notch is accessible by Route 100A, a
secondary road winding between the resort towns of Ludlow and
Woodstock in the ski country of central Vermont. Plymouth Notch can
be seen in two hours or less, but it would be a shame to leave
before lingering for a picnic and a walk along trails through the
meadows.
</P>
<P>
   Jaqueline and I cheated on the recommended itinerary for
Plymouth Notch by driving directly to the final stop: the cemetery
containing the graves of six generations of Coolidges, including
the president. The grassy cemetery, typical of Vermont, was carved
into a hillside too steep for farming. Coolidge was one of two
American presidents born in Vermont (Chester Arthur was the other),
yet Coolidge's gravesite modestly omits any mention of his five and
a half years in the White House, noting merely his birth on July 4,
1872, and death on Jan. 5, 1933. The only clue is a small
presidential seal etched into the granite headstone. Beside him lie
his wife, Grace Anne Goodhue, from Burlington, Vt., and his younger
son, Calvin Jr., whose premature death from blood poisoning at age
16 in 1924 plunged the president into depression.
</P>
<P>
   The road that Coolidge traveled from Plymouth Notch to the White
House led through Massachusetts: he graduated from Amherst College
and became a lawyer in Northampton, where he was elected mayor. His
political career took him to the state legislature and the
governor's mansion. In 1921, he moved to Washington as vice
president in the new Republican administration of Warren G.
Harding.
</P>
<P>
   From the cemetery, we drove through the village and passed Piney
Hollow Brook, which was stocked with trout to assure a catch
whenever Coolidge went fishing on his summer holidays. When a
stranger was spotted angling in the brook, Coolidge reportedly
dispatched his Secret Service men to retrieve the catch. ``Those
are my fish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of Plymouth Notch is the Coolidge Homestead, a
two-story clapboard house where time has been wound back to 2:47
a.m. on Aug. 3, 1923. That was when Coolidge was sworn in as
president by his father, a notary public, by the glow of a kerosene
lamp, after word of Harding's death arrived from San Francisco.
When John Coolidge was asked later about his authority to
administer the presidential oath, he said, ``I didn't know that I
couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Coolidge became president, his father put off
installing electric lights in the homestead because his
housekeeper, Aurora Pierce, distrusted electricity, fearing that it
would burn the place down. A tour of the homestead offers other
intriguing windows on rural life in old Vermont: a sturdy antique
sleigh in the horse barn; an 1838 poster in the tool room
advertising ``gargling oil'' for horses; the kitchen where the
family ate (Calvin's only sibling, Abigail, died at 15, his mother
when he was 12), and where Calvin and his father shaved from water
heated on the wood stove.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich House, around the corner, belonged to Ruth Aldrich, the
daughter of the village's first cheesemaker. Hand-wrought nails and
other early hardware date the original house to the 1820s. The age
of old Vermont houses, we learned, tends to be imprecise, because
the ``continuous'' style of New England architecture involves the
adding on of barns, chicken coops and other outbuildings to avoid
stepping outside in snow and rain.
</P>
<P>
   In the house, we found plates and menus of the tearoom operated
by Aldrich, which she called Top of the Notch, an allusion to the
V-shaped valley leading up from Ludlow. She did the cooking with
the help of two girls, serving deviled ham sandwiches for 20 cents
and creamed chicken on toast for 50 cents, catering to the summer
White House staff, reporters and tourists. Coolidge ate chicken
dinners for $1 in an adjacent private dining room, which was
converted into a bathroom in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich also kept a diary. ``Had a great crew for breakfast,''
notes one entry posted in the dining room. ``Fed a great many. Have
15 secret service men.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to put Miss Aldrich's house in condition for
visitors, a closet yielded a score of woven Abenaki Indian baskets
intended for sale. Folks in Plymouth Notch seemed to save
everything, down to brown paper bags and string in the kitchen
drawers. The Coolidge family donated many of the president's more
valuable objects on display.
</P>
<P>
   Before air-conditioning made Washington bearable in the summer,
the president and Congress fled the heat and humidity for cooler
climes like Plymouth Notch, where Coolidge's summer White House
administrative staff in 1924 consisted of two: a secretary and a
stenographer, both men. Compare this with the retinues that dance
attendance on a president nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   We paused to watch an old Pathe newsreel reporting silently on
Coolidge's return to Plymouth Notch in the summer of 1924. It
included footage of the president, deadpan as ever, deftly
gathering hay with a pitchfork, and of four eminent visitors, Henry
Ford, Harvey and Russell Firestone and Thomas Edison.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge's summer office can be found in the community hall, an
austere room with vaulted ceiling and plank floors on the second
floor above the general store. Telegraph and telephone lines were
brought in to keep the president in touch with the rest of the
country. The hall also contained a piano and other musical
instruments played by the Plymouth Old Time Dance Orchestra, which
traveled to Washington in 1926 to serenade Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1622EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMO     05-29 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COOLIDGE-VERMONT-$ADV04-2NDYAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PLYMOUTH NOTCH, Vt.: serenade Coolidge.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The general store has a wood counter built by Calvin Coolidge
and his father in 1890 from bird's-eye maple and cherry. The
store's top shelves display goods available in 1923. Lower shelves
offer handcrafts made in Vermont for sale today. We saw painted
birdhouses, wooden toys and a child's red sled, but my favorite,
for $16.50, was a bell sewn on leather to wear during hikes to shoo
away bears. The store's filigreed antique cash register no longer
rings up sales because it can't compute Vermont's 5 percent sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   The Plymouth Cheese Factory down the street still produces
granular curd cheese made from an old recipe. The factory, which
Coolidge's father helped start in 1890, was purchased last year by
the state of Vermont and will reopen to tourists this month
following interior repairs. Across the street, the steepled Union
Christian Church, first built in 1840, is open to the public for
services on the first Sunday morning of each month. It has also
become popular for weddings.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to see. The Wilder Barn, thought to date back to
about 1875, holds a marvelous collection of horse-drawn wagons and
old farming implements. Wilder House, once a 19th-century tavern
where Calvin Coolidge's grandmother lived as a child, has a summer
cafe offering light breakfasts and lunches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, Plymouth had 29 residents. The population has grown to
about 450 today, including the adjacent communities of Plymouth
Union and Tyson. Plymouth Notch draws about 40,000 tourists a year.
Many come to view the flaming foliage of the Vermont autumn; the
village is seldom crowded in early summer. Still, back in the
1920s, when Coolidge's home village seized the public's curiosity,
an estimated 10,000 visitors showed up one summer day to see him,
judging by a rough count of 4,000 to 5,000 parked cars.
</P>
<P>
   We left Plymouth Notch feeling that Coolidge deserves more
credit than history accords. When Coolidge occupied the White
House, more than 90 percent of Americans paid no federal taxes, yet
he trimmed the national debt by a third. Although renowned for
keeping his mouth shut, Coolidge held regular news conferences and
he delivered more speeches than any of his 29 presidential
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   When his elected term ended, Coolidge returned quietly to
private life, having declared, ``I do not choose to run for
president in 1928.'' The homespun philosopher Will Rogers caught
the spirit of Plymouth Notch when he told Coolidge, ``You put horse
sense into statemanship.''
</P>
<P>
   TURNING BACK THE CLOCK
</P>
<P>
   It is best to begin a visit to Plymouth Notch at the visitors
center, the town's only new structure, built in 1972 in the form of
an early Vermont stone house. Admission to its exhibits and other
buildings around the village costs $6. Children under 14 get in
free. For information, contact President Calvin Coolidge State
Historic Site, Post Office Box 247, Plymouth, Vt. 05056; (802)
672-3773; www.historicermont.org.
</P>
<P>
   From May 27 to Oct. 15, the Coolidge historic site opens 10
buildings to the public every day, generally from 9:30 a.m. to 5
p.m. Coolidge's birthday is celebrated on July 4, with a procession
to the cemetery. On July 15 and 16, there will be a show of antique
gas and steam engines. Plymouth Old Home Day on Aug. 5 will feature
a chicken barbecue and bake sale and, in the evening, fireworks and
a concert by the Vermont Symphony Orchestra. The village's cheese
and harvest festival comes on Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   A summerlong exhibit of artifacts and graphics will look at
other summer retreats used by Coolidge, including places in
Swampscott, Mass., and Rapid City, S.D. Fishing equipment used by
the president and some fine examples of American Indian beadwork
will be among the items.
</P>
<P>
   There is an on-site restaurant, serving lunch, and the adjacent
Wilder House, offers a light breakfast and lunch from 10 a.m. to 3
p.m., featuring homemade muffins and country fare like chicken pot
pie. Lunch for two costs about $14. Information: Echo Lake Inn,
(800) 356-6844.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1623EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
