u e BC-ARMOR-RESTITUTION-NYT     05-29 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMOR-RESTITUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMOR IN PHILADELPHIA IS RETURNED TO DRESDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unusually collaborative act of restitution, the
Philadelphia Museum of Art and the State Art Collections in
Dresden, Germany, were to announce Tuesday that five works of armor
that entered the Philadelphia collection in 1977 had been returned
to the State Art Collections, which claimed ownership of the pieces
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than just having the Philadelphia museum return the rare
ceremonial armor, the agreement between the institutions provides
for a series of exchange loans, including three major examples of
armor from Dresden that have just been put on display in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Dresden museums have also agreed to let four colletins, or
neck defenses, made for Johann Georg and other Electors of Saxony,
remain in Philadelphia through 2004 before being returned to
Dresden.
</P>
<P>
   The Dresden museums will also lend three other pieces from their
collection to Philadelphia through 2004: field armor, gilded
tournament armor, and a shield matching an armor in Philadelphia
used for jousts celebrating the marriage of Prince Elector Frederic
August II of Saxony to Archduchess Marie Josephe of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In return the Philadelphia Museum will lend Dresden five
paintings from its collection: Courbet's ``Waves,'' Cassatt's
``Woman With a Pearl Necklace in Loge,'' Monet's ``Morning Haze,''
Braque's ``Still Life With Fruit Dish'' and Matisse's ``Still Life
on a Table.'' The Matisse will go to Dresden for five years, and
the other paintings for six months.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 the Dresden museums formally requested the return of
five works of armor. After studying their provenance, the
Philadelphia concluded that they had been put on the market without
the knowledge of the State Art Collections, museum officials said.
Originally part of the armory of the Electors of Saxony, the pieces
disappeared from a remote storage site to which they had been sent
by the Dresden museums for safekeeping during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1950s the objects were on the open market. They
were purchased by Carl Otto Kretzschmar von Kienbusch, an
internationally known collector who bequeathed his entire
collection of arms and armor to the Philadelphia Museum in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the loans because we've made a good
relationship with a distinguished museum,'' said Anne
d'Harnoncourt, director and chief executive of the Philadelphia
Museum. She said that the idea of exchanges had grown out of years
of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums are born to collaborate with each other,'' she added.
``We all have the same mission: to connect great works of art with
our public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
