<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COKE-LAWSUIT0530-COX     05-29 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola plaintiffs delay filing key brief
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With settlement talks under way, plaintiffs' attorneys
are not going to file an important document by today's deadline in
the racial discrimination lawsuit against Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about the settlement talks, but I can confirm
that tomorrow we are not going to file the class certification
brief, and I cannot say anything more at this time,'' plaintiffs'
attorney Cyrus Mehri said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge in the case is likely to grant a two-week
extension to give negotiators more time to try to reach a
settlement, according to former Coke manager Larry Jones, who is
the chief organizer of a boycott of company products aimed at
pressuring it to settle the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The class certification brief is a key document in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In it, plaintiffs' attorneys are supposed to lay out a detailed
analysis of why they believe the case should be expanded from four
plaintiffs to include about 2,000 current and former black
employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The suit alleges that the company has discriminated against
African-Americans in pay, promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which has denied the allegations, would be able to
respond to the certification brief if it eventually gets filed.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones said the settlement talks, which are being facilitated
by a mediator, apparently have become a priority. Attorneys for
both sides are prohibited from publicly talking about the
settlement negotiations, which began in mid-April. They can,
however, talk about the filing of legal briefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I understand the reason for the delay is that both
parties want to continue mediation without the motion being
filed,'' said Jones, who was laid off as a human resources manager
in February. ``However, I am deeply concerned that this is simply
another delaying tactic by Coca-Cola Co.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke, which declined comment Monday, has repeatedly said it
wants a speedy and fair settlement. And the delay in filing the
class certification brief could not have happened without
plaintiffs' attorneys agreeing to it in hopes of making more
progress at the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   But the issues are complex. They include a possible monetary
settlement for the plaintiffs and the prospective class members, as
well as proposed changes in the company's diversity practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said his group will be protesting outside Coca-Cola's
headquarters this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1648EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GINGRICH-BUSINESSMAN0     05-29 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-BUSINESSMAN0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Away from politics, Gingrich takes on the world of technology
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tucked away in a back offfice in the
PriceWaterhousCoopers space of the Wildwood office park one can
find Newt Gingrich the businessman hard at work.
</P>
<P>
   It's far from the pomp and circumstance of Washington D.C. where
at one time Gingrich commanded the center of the country as Speaker
of the House and architect of the Republican takeover of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gingrich's mind is as active as ever. Over the course of an
hour-and-a-half, Gingrich has mapped out a historical model of
technology and economic forces in the past century and foreshadowed
how he sees the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a scale of total change,'' Gingrich said. ``We will
experience as much development in technology in the next 25 years
as we did in the last 100. You will never stop this age of
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich talks about S curves, carbon nanotubes, hydrogen fuel
cells and solar energy, explaining complex concepts, much as a
professor would talk to a student. He then applies his ideas to
education, public policy, the Internet and, more importantly, their
implications for business.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, Gingrich jumpstarted the Gingrich Group, a
management consulting firm that specializes in new technology and
its applications to society. He works with both the companies
offering technological advances and enterprises that can take
advantage of those new developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picking and choosing is one our biggest challenges,'' Gingrich
said. ``I look for two things when considering clients. I want a
dramatic decline in cost or a dramatic increase in capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   He receives consulting fees and ``success fees.'' But he takes
no fees from the U.S. government or for lobbying. He doesn't serve
on any company's board of directors, preferring a role as an
advisor to enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   His client list includes NetSchools, an Atlanta-based company
that offers a combination of laptop computers for students to use
at home and at school, access to the Internet and links between the
student and a school's computer system _ primarily in low-income
areas. Because Gingrich is such a believer in NetSchools, he
accepts no fees from them.
</P>
<P>
   Other clients are: Intelysys, a New York-based company that
developers online software for business purchases over the
Internet; InsiderAdvantage.com, a 50-state website for information
on business opportunities and political knowledge; MindArrow, a
Silicon Valley company that provides interactive sales and
marketing for the Internet; AcclerateIT.com, now called World2One,
a Norcross-based Internet company specializing in electronic
business cards; and Uniscape, a Redwood Shores, Ca. company that
provides business to business translations in multitude of
languages allowing people of all languages to interact with the
same site.
</P>
<P>
   He has a strong association as a consultant with
PriceWaterhouseCoopers, and he also is on the business advisory
board of Fleishman-Hillard, Forstmann-Little and Hollinger
International.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how being in business differs from his political career,
Gingrich is contemplative. ``Working with business is a lot
harder,'' he said. ``If you learn in an environment where you have
to make something work, it's a lot harder than having a theory.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich is not your traditional businessman. He said that
about three-fourths of his consulting work he does for nothing. And
he spends at least half of his time learning. He will tour the
National Science Foundation, Georgia Tech, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, MIT, Stamford Medical School _ anywhere he
can learn about what is coming down the pipe in technology and the
transformation of society.
</P>
<P>
   Then he brings his learning to the Gingrich Group, which has a
total of five employees in two offices: Atlanta and Washington D.C.
While he wouldn't disclose his first year revenues, Gingrich said,
``We made a good profit. It's doing quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Gingrich remains opinionated about the state of the
world and its future. He refers to claims that there are limits to
growth as ``garbage.'' For all practical purposes, we are 18 to 20
years away from hydrogen fuel cell technology, where hydrogen is
stored in carbon nanotubes _ ``100 times as strong has steel but
weighs one-sixth as much.'' The byproduct of hydrogen fuel cells is
not carbon monoxide, but water. ``You solve the water problem at
the same time,'' he said. ``It's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also sounds little like a conservative Republican when
he calls for subsidies and universal coverage of the Internet to
every U.S. citizen. ``We are a rich enough country for every one to
have a computer. In six years, we need to have everyone
connected,'' he said. ``It is cheaper to give every four-year-old a
computer than to hire a Title One teacher or pay for prisons. I
list creating a digital connection as a top three national security
issue.'' (The other two are overhauling math and science education,
and dramatically increasing the federal government's research and
development budget.)
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that Gingrich's mind has not stopped working when
he resigned from Congress in January, 1999. In his new role as
businessman/consultant, Gingrich does not fit a prepackaged mold.
And he seems even freer to take on independent public policy
positions. Take rural development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to actively rethink the rural communities from an
Internet basis. We should wire every house and wire every
community,'' Gingrich said. ``People are big on concrete and
asphalt because that's where the lobbyists are. But the Internet
will provide distance learning, distance shopping, distance work
and distance health. It can transform our rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
