<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REIT0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMB Property remains focused on Atlanta
 &HT;    By Tony Wilbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite the lure of seemingly unlimited land in
Atlanta's far-out suburbs, AMB Property Corp. sees no reason to
alter its Atlanta strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The company will continue to develop warehouse and distribution
center space in two submarkets, the I-85 corridor in Gwinnett
County and the area around Hartsfield Atlanta International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very focused,'' AMB Chairman and Chief Executive Hamid
Moghadam said during a recent visit to Buckhead. ``It's not like
we're randomly developing around Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   With a market capitalization of $1.84 billion, San
Francisco-based AMB ranks as the second-largest industrial real
estate investment trust in the country behind ProLogis Trust. AMB
entered the Atlanta market with a small presence in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Atlanta is one of its six core markets. AMB has nearly
5.5 million square feet of space and is the largest owner of
industrial space in the airport submarket, Moghadam said. Southern
Co., at one time AMB's largest investor, remains a major
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   The company has no employees in Atlanta. It prefers to develop
through alliances with local companies such as Seefried Properties
and Southeast Investment Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Moghadam knows that a competitor, Duke-Weeks Realty Corp., has
decided to follow I-85 into Hall and Jackson counties, where it is
developing a business park in Braselton.
</P>
<P>
   However, he feels no pressure to follow the Indianapolis REIT.
``We attempt to be a little more infill-oriented,'' he said.
``We're not going to be pioneering.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also does not feel obligated to jump on the
bandwagon of developers who are building huge speculative
warehouses and distribution centers in Henry County. The gamble has
paid off for First Industrial Realty Trust, a Chicago-based REIT
that signed Amazon.com to an 800,000-square-foot lease in
McDonough, Ga. last year.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Amazon seek locations in places like Henry
County because of the cheap land and labor, Moghadam said. AMB
would rather develop in locations based on their strong real estate
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   He offers as evidence the Webvan facility, which AMB bought from
Atlanta developer Industrial Developments International. Even if
the technology start-up fails _ and Moghadam said AMB wants to help
Webvan succeed _ the REIT will not be stuck holding an
underperforming property.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proper underwriting (of a dot-com company) is to get back
the building,'' he said. ``If this tenant doesn't work, there are
plenty of others that will.''
</P>
<P>
   AMB will not lease a property to a company with no credit
history ``unless we're comfortable owning the building as an empty
spec building in a competitive market,'' he said. AMB further
lowers its risk by not financing improvements tenants make to
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   AMB has completed deals with Webvan in Seattle and northern
Virginia. Moghadam said the company is ``the ultimate tenant for
our strategy'' of focusing on high-volume distribution facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of serving customers in high-speed
logistics,'' he said. ``Our goal is to make Webvan successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
