<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AH, TO BE IN ENGLAND, NOW THAT ALL THE GREEN IS THERE  

</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   I knew the drought was bad here on
the Gulch Coast, but I had no idea how bad until I looked out on my
patio the other day and saw a couple of love bugs stop snuggling
long enough to smack a palmetto bug out of his lounge chair and
steal his jug of Gatorade. Man, that's dry.
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm fairly new to rapidly growing Florida, so I've been going
over the local water regulations with my attorney this past week to
make sure I'm not risking prosecution when I turn on the spigot.
I've asked him to decode the directions for my automated sprinkler
system, too, but he says the billable hours would make me weep a
fountain of tears, so I ought to just think about his charging me
and sop the lawn that way.
</P>
<P>
   My wife's been out of town, and she left me with the delicate
task of watering her plants. As if it wasn't bad enough to live in
fear of killing off the potted whatchamacallit, I now endure
nightmares that feature me in a prison bunk, staring forlornly at
the ceiling as I listen to the conversations of fellow inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate One: ``Psst. What are you in for?''
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Two: ``Malicious flushing. Unlawful rinsing of a
toothbrush. You?''
</P>
<P>
   Inmate One: ``Possession of ice cubes with intent to
distribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Two: ``Fellow in the next cell got caught watering
bromelaids.''
</P>
<P>
   Inmate One: ``What a prevert.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure the rest of you are also having trouble finding a
cloud, let alone a silver lining, in this extended dry spell. So,
at the risk of sounding overly sunny, I offer up this bit of good
cheer _ in lush landscapes, true evil lurks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as we survey our withered lawns and gardens, we should
be grateful that no one's going to try to filch the greenery _ er,
brownery _ from our yards. Some people are not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Over in England, it seems, folks with green thumbs are coming
down with a bad case of itchy fingers. Gardening thieves are
running amok, swiping anything that isn't bolted down or buried
deep.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today reports that the Mother Country is caught up in a
cultivation craze right now. Gardening is a $5-billion-a-year
industry, and gardeners have become national celebrities. One show
on the BBC draws 12 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Gardening is so popular that there's now an underground market
for plants. Marauding bandits are roaming the countryside, digging
up unusual or hard-to-get varieties to sell to shady gardeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most expensive items are stolen to order,'' an insurance
agency spokesman told USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the garden is safe. One poor lady in Bristol lost
flowers, trees, stone ornaments, a 3-feet-deep artificial pond and
all of the goldfish contained therein.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big business and highly lucrative,'' says Steve
Parnwell, a law enforcement officer who heads a 20-member task
force _ yes, 20 _ focused on plant snippery.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1 million people in England have green stuff stolen
each year, according to USA Today. At least one insurance company,
faced with the prospects of paying out pots of money in claims,
stopped offering policies for gardens. It later reintroduced
coverage after so many customers demanded it.
</P>
<P>
   A drought like ours obviously would dry up this crime wave, but
unfortunately for England, that's not in the forecast. I suspect
the gardeners themselves will have to nip this problem in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   An army has already been mustered. The Royal Horticultural
Society _ or the Royal Hort, as it's known in the trenches _ is a
quarter-million strong.
</P>
<P>
   That's not quite as large or fiercesome as, say, our National
Rifle Association, but _ trust me on this one _ gardeners are a
tough lot and know how to fight dirty.
</P>
<P>
   So, as we watch our grass and flowers die, let our spirits be
lifted by the good and noble battle now under way across the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   At this very moment, mad-dog Englishmen, armed with the trowels,
are bravely preparing to defend their home turf.
</P>
<P>
   May they hoe a righteous row. May justice rain down upon the
heads of their tormenters.
</P>
<P>
   Should the tide turn against the gardeners, we Americans should
stand ready to lend a hand. I'm thinking love-bug bombs might do
the job nicely.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0160 </DOCNO>
