<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MITROVICA-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS WARY OF MORE SERB-ALBANIAN VIOLENCE IN MITROVICA  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ The French commander of this volatile
town, Gen. Pierre de Saqui de Sannes, told a visiting U.N. Security
Council delegation recently that the place was calm. Minutes later,
before the visitors had even left town, the first stones were
thrown in a weekend of street violence that left six French
soldiers and one U.N. policeman injured, several buildings burned
and dozens of foreign cars damaged.
</P>
<P>
   It is the nature of Mitrovica, the last town in Kosovo with a
significant presence of Serbs, to explode without warning, and no
one knows better than the general. In February, on his second day
on the job, this town exploded in the worst night of rioting that
the NATO-led peacekeeping force, known locally as KFOR, has seen
since foreign troops arrived in Kosovo last June.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, as he prepared to hand over the job to
another French general, de Saqui de Sannes said that the situation
remains extremely ``delicate'' and that there is no guarantee
against further violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot stop another attack occurring in north Mitrovica,''
he said in a recent interview. ``There are a number of extremists
on both sides. It could happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners working in Mitrovica complain that despite some 2,000
troops, including a contingent from the French Foreign Legion, and
several hundred international police, the peacekeepers are still
not in control of either the Albanian-dominated southern part of
Mitrovica or its northern Serb enclave.
</P>
<P>
   ``KFOR and the U.N. have been unable to become the ruling power
here,'' said a senior officer working for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe. ``They have never been the
governing authority except on paper.'' Former members of the now
disbanded Kosovo Liberation Army rule the Albanian side, and the
Serbs are in charge in the north, the officer said. ``There is a
climate of complete impunity here that has to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some changes since the violent months of
February and March, with the arrival of troop reinforcements and
the appointment of a retired U.S. general, William Nash, as the new
regional administrator. Nash, who has experience as a peacekeeper
in nearby Bosnia, has injected a certain dynamism into decision
making. After the recent violence, he had a stream of people attend
meetings in his office and reintroduced joint police and military
patrols, recognition of the poor cooperation to date.
</P>
<P>
   From the street, Mitrovica's divisions look uglier than ever.
The boundaries between the Serb northern district and the Albanian
areas are now defined by coils of razor wire and sandbagged
military checkpoints. In the name of security for both communities,
the troops have reinforced the divisions between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Albanians expelled from their homes in February have
returned home to a designated zone around the Ibar River that
divides the Serb and Albanian districts, but they came under armed
protection and now live behind armor and barbed wire. The U.N. High
Commissioner of Refugees estimates that 60 percent of the estimated
2,000 people who fled in February have yet to return.
</P>
<P>
   Izet Jaha, a 72-year-old Albanian, has French soldiers watching
over him from an observation post in the house next door. ``While
KFOR is up there, we can take our socks off while we sleep,'' he
said. ``If they were not here, none of us would be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs also feel insecure, distrustful of both the
peacekeepers and the United Nations, and fearful of a mass influx
of Albanians into their district that would force them to flee.
Dusko Prodanovic, a Serb bank manager who lives just one block from
the dividing line, said the increased security was ``just a
charade,'' and he saw little prospect for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Albanians hate us so much that they do not want to
live with us,'' he said. ``The Americans are just waiting to expel
us,'' his wife, Bosanka, blurted out in agitation.
</P>
<P>
   If the Albanians suffered more directly from the February
violence, the Serbs have lost out overall, said a member of the
OSCE office in Mitrovica. ``The Serbs have lost a lot in these last
three months,'' she said. ``They managed to expel a few hundred
Albanians, but the reaction of the international community was very
strong against them.''
</P>
<P>
   After trying to negotiate with the Serbs to return the Albanians
and establish a safety zone, de Saqui de Sannes did that by force.
He also used force to push back from one bridge the Serb thugs who
kept watch to deter Albanians from crossing to the north side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed that we will not accept partition, and the Albanians
feel that,'' the general said. ``Now we must show that we will also
not accept that Serbs be pushed out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Nash arrived in April his assignment was to prevent
partition of the city and the northern Serb-dominated part of
Kosovo. His goal has already shifted to bringing back the Serbs to
Kosovo. ``The issue we now face today is not partition but the
prosperous and safe return of Serbs to their homes,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But violence simmers on. After the April 29 violence that
followed the Security Council visit, an elderly Albanian couple was
evicted from an apartment in northern Mitrovica. And the Serb
bridge watchers remain in charge on the main bridge, threatening
Albanians and sometimes foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The international police force and peacekeepers have so far
failed to arrest anyone for the killings during the February riots
and the damage done on April 29. Police cells are full of petty
criminals and drug addicts, but the general admitted that arresting
the real troublemakers ``could spark a bigger problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach has raised questions about the French peacekeepers'
determination to enforce order. In the smaller Serb enclave of
Gracanica, by contrast, Swedish troops immediately move in
forcefully to arrest troublemakers when there is any commotion. A
Swedish soldier recently shot one man in the leg to deter an
attack, and several men have been expelled from the settlement for
a period of three months, according to one Swedish officer. ``You
have to show them force, otherwise they don't stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a working judiciary is another danger. A number of
Serb detainees, some of them alleged war criminals, staged a hunger
strike recently demanding trials, and relatives began daily street
demonstrations. U.N. officials admit they have delayed the
potentially explosive trials in Mitrovica, although they did start
this month, and serious cases are due in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
