<HEADER>
A8947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOLIDAY-BOX-OFFICE-NY     05-29 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOX-OFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`M:I-2' LEADS TOP FILMS TO A RECORD FOR WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The holiday weekend, spurred by a spectacular
opening for Tom Cruise's ``M:I-2''; a solid debut for Jackie Chan's
comic western, ``Shanghai Noon''; and strong holdover business for
May hits like ``Dinosaur,'' ``Gladiator'' and ``Road Trip,'' has
seen a Memorial Day record of $174.7 million in ticket sales for
the top 12 films.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge; it's amazing,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman
of Exhibitor Relations, a Los Angeles company that monitors
box-office performance. ``Typically, Memorial Day is totally
dominated by one film, but this shows a real depth at the box
office that you don't normally see.''
</P>
<P>
   It also smashes the record of $148 million _ for the top 50
films _ set over the four-day Memorial Day weekend in 1997, when
``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' opened with $90.2 million.
Exhibitor Relations charts only the performance of the top 12 films
in its initial estimates, released Monday, but when the numbers are
compiled for the top 50 in coming days, Dergarabedian said, the
2000 Memorial Day cumulative box office could well rise above $190
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing how big the smiles are around our business this
weekend,'' said Chuck Viane, president for distribution at Disney.
``It really sets everybody up for the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie landscape may be shifting, as many here believe, with
audiences demanding offbeat stories, studios pushing for lower
costs, and rapidly changing technologies constantly rattling the
firmament. But when the weather gets hot and schools begin to let
out, audiences apparently want what they have always craved: big
stars doing big stunts in big movies and, of course, dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the course of the year we will seek out movies that are
a little bit different, but when it comes to the holidays, when you
want to be with your family, you look for star-driven vehicles or
technological vehicles or comedies or something that you are sure
is going to work,'' Viane said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise's film, whose title stands for ``Mission: Impossible-2,''
earned an estimated $71.8 million in 3,653 theaters over the
four-day weekend, making it the second-biggest opening ever, after
the ``Jurassic Park'' sequel, stronger even than last year's
holiday weekend showing for the heavily hyped ``Star Wars: Episode
1 _ The Phantom Menace.'' The original ``Mission: Impossible''
film, released on Memorial Day weekend in 1996, earned $56.8
million in its four-day opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly this record was spurred by the success of `Mission:
Impossible 2,''' said Robert G. Friedman, vice chairman of the
Paramount Motion Picture Group, which is distributing the film.
``What's amazing is that the good will left over from the first
film combined with the enormous popularity of Tom Cruise and the
adoration toward director John Woo from some in the movie audience
came together to create this tremendous opening.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, after the disappointing box office performance of
Cruise's previous two films _ Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut''
and Paul Thomas Anderson's ``Magnolia'' _ there was some
speculation in Hollywood that the actor's star might be dimming.
All that will be forgotten now.
</P>
<P>
   ``M:I-2'' should pass the $100 million mark on Tuesday or
Wednesday; it has already earned $92.8 million since its opening on
Wednesday. Early estimates are that it will be the first of what
may be several $200 million movies this summer. Last summer a
record number of films earned more than $100 million and, based on
the early box office strength shown this year, studio executives
are predicting a repeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what's out there already,'' Viane said. ``It will be
hard for me not to believe there will be a dozen, if not more, $100
million movies this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming potential blockbusters include Nicolas Cage in ``Gone in
60 Seconds,'' an auto-theft thriller; Mel Gibson in ``The
Patriot,'' a Revolutionary War epic; and George Clooney in ``The
Perfect Storm,'' an adaptation of the nonfiction best seller about
fishermen fighting a raging storm in the North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's computer-animated ``Dinosaur'' finished in second place
over the weekend, earning $33.5 million for a cumulative total of
$81.9 million since its May 19 opening. The newcomer ``Shanghai
Noon,'' another Disney film, finished third with $19.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' ``Gladiator'' was fourth with $17.3 million and a
cumulative total of $127.2 million since its May 5 opening. ``Road
Trip,'' another DreamWorks film, was in fifth place with $14
million and a cumulative total of $35.8 since its May 12 debut.
</P>
<P>
   The box office estimates are for the four-day holiday weekend,
meaning that it includes actual ticket sales from theaters on
Friday, Saturday and Sunday, plus each studio's estimates of ticket
sales for Monday. Adjusted final figures, including actual ticket
sales Monday, will be released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the news for studios was good, though. ``The Flintstones
in Viva Rock Vegas'' did not click with family audiences in May and
has already dipped to 11th place at the box office, while John
Travolta's ``Battlefield Earth'' has tumbled out of the top 12
after only 18 days of release.
</P>
<P>
   ``This weekend's box office sort of flies in the face of what
everybody thought was a sea change in terms of summer blockbusters,
especially in light of `The Blair Witch Project' and `The Sixth
Sense' last summer,'' Dergarabedian said. ``Typically, popcorn
movies are what rules the summer and that hasn't changed. This is
just what people want in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
