<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Tuesday, May 30 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Washington) _ The wildfire that swept through Los
Alamos, N.M., earlier this month is setting off alarms across the
mountain West, where more and more Americans have chosen to live on
the forest's edge. Experts say those housing shifts have multiplied
the danger that other fires could kindle similar disasters
elsewhere. They lie behind an urgent new congressional quest for
millions of dollars in emergency money to try to ease the risk.
Across the country, the damage caused by wildfire to homes and
property increased sixfold between the 1980s and 1990s, to a total
of $3.2 billion over the last 10 years, federal officials say. In
an average year over the past decade, 1,200 homes have burned. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-POLITICS (Undated) _ Organized labor may have suffered a
bruising setback when the House of Representatives approved the
China trade bill last week, but there is widespread agreement, even
among labor's opponents, that the nation's unions are growing
stronger after years of decline. After steadily losing influence
for two decades, the labor movement has begun to rebound under John
Sweeney, the AFL-CIO's president, by reversing its membership slide
and by throwing its weight around far more in elections and on
Capitol Hill. Thomas Donohue, president of the U. S. Chamber of
Commerce, said it would be foolish to dismiss labor's power because
of the China trade vote. ``Labor has a lot of money. Labor has a
lot of forces on the ground. Anyone who wants to declare them weak,
just look out for the next fight.'' By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS-CAMPS (Ain el Hilweh Camp, Lebanon) _ For the
300,000 Palestinians who have lived for half a century in squalid,
supposedly makeshift refugee camps in Lebanon, the Israeli troop
withdrawal last week proved a bittersweet experience. For them, the
moment was distinctly powerful: from the newly opened border area,
they could gaze on the hills of what they consider their land. For
an entire generation of Palestinians in Lebanon, it was the very
first glimpse, and suddenly, painfully, they felt both closer and
farther away than ever. By Deboarah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-OLINE (Undated) _ The race is on to transform visits to
the doctor by providing a wealth of clinical information online for
physicians. Several top medical schools, including the latest entry
from Stanford, are preparing sites of their own, and there are
several commercially operated sites as well. These Websites
reinforce a doctor's knowledge, suggest diagnoses, and provide
on-the-spot answers to patients' questions about their symptoms. In
the process, the new Websites and the other medical information
online have the potential to alter the relationship between patient
and doctor. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BABY-BOUNTY (Tokyo) _ While other Japanese companies give
congratulatory bonuses to child-bearing employees, the Bandai
Corp., a major toy maker, is offering to pay employees $10,000 for
every baby they have after their second child _ the largest baby
bounty ever in Japan, which is struggling to reduce record-low
birth rates that are threatening the country's long-term viability.
By Calvin Sims. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SOUTHHAMPTON-TAX (Southampton, N.Y.) _ Behind the privet
hedges that shield the many monstrous mansions in this village by
the sea, something semi-revolutionary is brewing. The rich folks
who summer in the Village of Southampton are up in arms, in an
understated, law-abiding kind of way, about an American principle
for which colonial patriots tossed tea into Boston Harbor: taxation
without representation. This village has been floating in a deep
green sea of property tax money since the 1890s, when plutocrats
like W.K. Vanderbilt began to erect gargantuan houses that they
called cottages. Since then, more and more summer people have
bought their way into Southampton, and they pay about
three-quarters of the property taxes. The justice that summer
people seek is the right to vote on village matters while still
keeping their permanent residence back home. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
</TEXT>
