<HEADER>
A8951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HELLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     05-29 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELLER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH HELLER'S VALEDICTORY HOLDS A MIRROR TO HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like such embarrassing Hemingway works as ``The Garden of Eden''
and ``True at First Light,'' Joseph Heller's ``Portrait of an
Artist, as an Old Man'' is one of those posthumously published
books that form a sad coda to a distinguished career. Fans of
``Catch-22'' and ``Something Happened'' can only regret that
``Portrait'' was ever published.
</P>
<P>
   Completed before Heller's death last December at 76,
``Portrait'' tells the story of an aging novelist named Eugene Pota
who is having difficulty writing another novel. It reads like one
of those magazine profiles in which a reporter never manages to get
an interview with his subject and so resorts to recounting his own
travails in trying to get the story. The entire book consists of
Pota's complaints about not being able to write, intercut with
outtakes from novels he has decided, for good reason, to abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these abortive efforts are simple testaments to Pota's
failure of imagination. There are weary attempts to rewrite classic
works of literature: Tom Sawyer as a would-be novelist, Tom Sawyer
as rich yuppie with a law degree from Yale, Gregor Samsa as a Wall
Street accountant. Pota contemplates rewriting ``The Iliad'' from
the point of view of the Trojans, toys with writing the biography
of a human gene as a witness to history and proposes a novel
organized as a ``biological map'' of the human body. He has Hera,
the Greek goddess, do a monologue about her philandering husband,
Zeus; and he has Zeus recount a practical joke he played on Hera.
</P>
<P>
   There is something perfunctory about each of Pota's efforts, as
though he couldn't really be bothered fleshing out his characters
or stories. ``Descriptive details of place and character take time,
deplete energy, aren't always necessary,'' Heller writes. ``Worst
of all, we have never been much good with them. Or much good with
intricate plots propelled by swift-paced action.'' In another
chapter he writes of Pota's wife: ``I could develop her easily, but
it's much too hard. It's painstaking and time consuming, and Pota
was short of patience. The generation of writers after him, and the
generation of newer novelists and short story writers following
that one are better at it now and have the gusto and the time. Let
them do it. They can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The skills Heller did possess in abundance at the height of his
career are also sorely lacking in this novel. There are few
glimpses in ``Portrait'' of his bravura satire or zany,
improvisational humor, and while familiar preoccupations surface in
this volume, they are addressed with none of Heller's old ferocity
and swagger. For instance, the obsession with mortality that
animated so many of his books from ``Catch-22'' through ``Closing
Time'' lies very much at the heart of this novel, but as filtered
through Pota's story it feels less like a terrifying reality or
great existential dilemma, than an old man's narcissistic rant
against declining book sales and a diminished sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Pota goes on at tiresome length about wanting to recapture the
success of his youth: how he wants to write another best seller
that will be ``a natural for the movies,'' how he has a sure-fire
title for a novel (``A Sexual Biography of My Wife'') but doesn't
want to go through the hassle of actually writing it. Though some
of Pota's complaints are vaguely amusing _ he's angry that Nabokov
already wrote ``Lolita,'' instead of leaving the field to him _ his
remarks too often devolve into rationalization or self pity.
</P>
<P>
   He writes a dreary story about the unhappy lives of American
authors _ how the likes of Mark Twain, Jack London, Bret Harte and
Stephen Crane were all beset with financial or medical woes _ and
then delivers an equally dreary, listlike speech about the
declining years of writers like Hemingway, Tennessee Williams and
Truman Capote.
</P>
<P>
   Pota's own name, the book baldly points out, is an acronym for
Portrait of the Artist, and he clearly bears more than a passing
resemblance to his creator. Like Heller, he wrote a memoir about
``his childhood and family life in Coney Island and had interwoven
segments of his war and life experiences afterward into almost all
his novels.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Heller, he achieved fame with a novel based on his service
in World War II and like Heller, he later wrote a novel based on
King David. No doubt the reader is also meant to take Pota's
difficulties in writing another novel as a kind of comment on the
difficulties Heller faced himself: always worrying about repeating
himself, always being compared to his younger self.
</P>
<P>
   There is something sad about Pota's dilemma, _ ``a well-known,
aging author'' struggling so painfully ``to close out his career
with a crowning achievement, with a laudable bang that would
embellish his reputation rather than with a fainthearted whimper.''
Unfortunately it's even sadder that Heller should cap his own
inspired _ and sometimes brilliant _ career with ``Portrait of an
Artist, as an Old Man,'' an anticlimactic book that is, at best, a
poor imitation of a novel.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PORTRAIT OF AN ARTIST, AS AN OLD MAN' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Joseph Heller &QL;
</P>
<P>
   233 pages. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $23. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An online reading group's appraisal of ``The Making of the
Atomic Bomb'' by Richard Rhodes and other literary discussions are
available at The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com/books
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
