<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-LIVING-WILLS-CASE     05-29 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LIVING-WILLS-CASES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT PATRICK WOULD WANT  
 A PEACEFUL DEATH WITHOUT TUBES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The two short case studies reported here accompany
SCI-LIVING-WILLS-II.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What happens to people who have no health-care proxy or living
will, and who wind up being kept alive by machines with little or
no hope of recovery? In New York at least, for life support to be
withdrawn, state law requires ``clear and convincing'' evidence
that the patient would not want such treatment. That requirement
can in effect punish people who never put their wishes into
writing.
</P>
<P>
   But one hospital has made a special effort to help patients who
lack written advance directives. Navah Harlow, director of the
Center for Ethics in Medicine at Beth Israel Medical Center in New
York, said, ``If a patient has told his loved ones what his wishes
would be, and has lived life in a certain way so there is no doubt,
can't we find a way to honor his wishes, to listen to his oral
advance directive, as related by family and friends?''
</P>
<P>
   She and others at the hospital have created a system in which
friends and relatives can meet with her and tell her what they
think or know the patient would have wanted. Then, the case is
presented to an ethics panel.
</P>
<P>
   The process is not fast, and patients sometimes die before it
can be completed. But, Harlow said, it is imperative to go slowly.
``I tell the families, `Let's go through this process, because two
or three months from now you'll be lying in bed, wondering if you
acted too fast, and in the long run this will give you added piece
of mind.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will then ask family members to write me a letter giving me
clear and convincing evidence that this is what they know the
patient would want. This is for the patient's wishes, not the
family's wishes. We honor these oral advance directives. I have
binders full of the most beautiful statements, from people of every
level of education, in many different languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Patrick Bedford, a 67-year-old actor from Dublin,
Ireland, who performed on Broadway and in films, was treated for
cancer at Beth Israel and eventually was put on a respirator.
Bedford had no living will or health care proxy, but at Harlow's
suggestion, friends and relatives wrote letters on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford had been an uproarious fellow, a singer and dancer and
storyteller who loved to give parties. One friend said that Bedford
had declared he knew he had a tumor and wanted to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he never wanted to be hooked up to any kind of
machines,'' the friend wrote. ``Let him go to heaven to spin his
tales and tell his stories, to be with all the other cast of
partygoers the way he was meant to be and has not been for the last
couple of weeks and will never be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Another wrote, ``We are certain that a man like Patrick would
not want to be forced to live artificially.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we also want to respect his life,'' she continued, ``how
he lived it and how he would like to have it end.''
</P>
<P>
   The letters were clear and convincing, Harlow said. But Bedford
died before doctors could act on them.
</P>
<P>
   A PEACEFUL DEATH WITHOUT TUBES
</P>
<P>
   On a crisp, sunny morning a year ago, in the Queens, N.Y.,
apartment that had been her home for more than 40 years, death came
gently for Phyllis Finocchio. Gazing into her husband's eyes, she
squeezed his hand, and then let go of it for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``She died very peacefully, the way we wanted it,'' said her
daughter, Bettina, who had helped care for her since 1988, when the
family first learned that Finocchio had Alzheimer's disease. ``And
so as a family, we're at peace.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era of high-tech medicine, a quiet death like Finocchio's
may be harder to arrange than one encumbered by tubes and
machinery, and attended by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   After their decision to care for her at home, one of the
family's most important and most difficult choices came when
Finocchio began to have trouble eating, like many people with
Alzheimer's. Four million Americans have dementia, and most lose
the ability to feed themselves and eventually cannot eat at all,
because of difficulty swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   They begin wasting away, and some doctors and many nursing homes
recommend feeding tubes, which are inserted through the nose or
through an incision in the abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Families are sometimes pressured into consenting because they
are told that without a tube, their loved ones will die painfully,
from thirst, starvation or choking.
</P>
<P>
   But the Finocchios learned from the Alzheimer's Association,
other medical groups and a hospice program that dying people who
can no longer eat do not suffer from hunger and thirst, and can be
kept comfortable with ice chips and swabs to moisten the mouth and
lips.
</P>
<P>
   The cessation of eating is often a natural part of the process
of dying, and most patients are more comfortable without fluids,
which can cause nausea and increased lung secretions. Dehydration,
described by one doctor as ``nature's anesthetic'' in dying
patients, leads them to lapse into comas and die peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, tube feeding can cause suffering in dementia
patients. It has not been proved to prolong their lives, and it can
cause diarrhea, bloating and infections. It does not prevent
choking, because patients still choke on their own secretions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, demented patients often try to yank out the tubes,
leading to the patients' being placed in restraints. Most then find
the restraints so upsetting that they become agitated and wind up
being sedated.
</P>
<P>
   Bettina Finocchio had seen her mother try to pull out
intravenous lines when she was hospitalized, and knew she would
pull out a feeding tube.
</P>
<P>
   The family decided there would be no tube. They fed Finocchio
when she could no longer feed herself, and froze broth into cubes
to help keep her mouth from becoming parched when she had trouble
swallowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a selfish act,'' Finocchio said. ``It was not an
easy way out. It's very painful to watch someone die like that. But
we just felt it was the best thing for her. I think she would have
wanted it that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SPOLETO0530-COX     05-29 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO0530-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spoleto puts on brave face
 &HT;    By Tom Sabulis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Amid the acclaimed opera, the edgy musical
theater, the midnight cocktail parties in cobblestoned alleys and
the breeze-buffeted brunches at historic homes on the Battery,
you'd find it difficult to think of Spoleto Festival USA as
snakebit.
</P>
<P>
   But if ever there was a year for Spoleto sympathy, this is it.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the inaugural weekend kicked off Friday with rebounding
ticket sales and what Spoleto board Chairman Joel Smith III called
``probably the largest crowd at opening ceremonies I've seen,'' the
festival was dealing with the NAACP's tourism boycott of South
Carolina triggered by the Confederate flag issue, which already had
prompted the cancellation of three events starring African-American
performers. And more trouble was around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night on nearby Folly Beach, Antoine Rigot, the
co-founder and artistic director of the French circus Les
Colporteurs, sustained a severe neck injury, forcing the
cancellation of Sunday's and Monday's performances of the troupe's
show ``Filao,'' an aerial fantasy inspired by Italo Calvino's novel
``The Baron in the Trees.'' (``Filao,'' pronounced FIL-ow, is a pun
on the French term for high wire.)
</P>
<P>
   More critical than jeopardizing the show's tour to the North
Carolina Museum of Art and New York's Lincoln Center in coming
months, the accident threatens the career of Rigot, a former Cirque
du Soleil star who helped form Les Colporteurs with Agathe Olivier,
his highwire partner, four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A tightrope phenom, Rigot apparently was hurt ``playing around,
doing circus tricks'' on the beach after a performance Saturday,
said festival spokeswoman Marie Lawson. He underwent surgery early
Sunday at Medical University of South Carolina to relieve pressure
on his spine. Doctors said Rigot's prognosis was good, but it was
too early to predict recovery. The injury was not life-threatening,
but a second surgery will be needed this week in order to fuse two
vertabrae injured in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Circus management was not releasing other details.
</P>
<P>
   Rigot's accident poses ``a huge problem'' for the festival, said
Spoleto General Director Nigel Redden, who also organizes the
Lincoln Center Festival each summer. Spoleto staff members were
waiting to hear if the circus could restage the 10-person show and
continue performances without Rigot's leading-man presence. Les
Colporteurs has 12 performances left at the festival. Lawson said
all the performances would have sold out by showtime _ that's a
total of 6,600 tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, Spoleto put on a brave face on its opening
weekend. As of Monday, ticket sales remained steady for its
carefully curated mix of live cutting-edge creations and vivid new
productions of standards _ the Verdi opera ``Luisa Miller,'' for
instance _ all within walking distance of each other in
Charleston's timeless postcard setting. Some events like the
chamber music concerts, the Colla Marionettes and the circus were
sellouts. Some like Les Grands Ballets Canadiens de Montreal played
to half-full houses.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences were a mixed bag, too, seemingly split between
comitted fans and tourists who showed up for, say, a puppet show,
only to leave upon discovering that the Colla Marionettes'
performance of ``Aida'' was over two hours and in Italian with no
supertitles. (It does, however, pack a sensational special-effects
ending right out of Andrew Lloyd Webber.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the delighted audience members was Marcia Cohen,
professor of painting at the Atlanta College of Art, a self-avowed
``puppet freak'' who drove to Charleston for a day of performances.
She plans to return this weekend to catch the Colla production of
``Around the World in Eighty Days (June 3-11).
</P>
<P>
   Boycott or no boycott, the festival was intent on waving its
diversity flag high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I now understand why the world comes to Spoleto,'' David Henry
Hwang, the Tony-winning playwright (``M Butterfly'') said during
Friday's opening ceremonies, where he filled a prominent spot on
the City Hall balcony. Hwang was at Spoleto for the first time,
having written the libretto for ``The Silver River,'' the 65-minute
chamber opera composed by Shanghai-born Bright Sheng and
choreographed by Muna Tseng. (Its entire run, which ends Sunday, is
sold out.)
</P>
<P>
   A New Yorker, Hwang hailed Spoleto's role as artistic incubator
and its commitment to adventurous work like ``The Silver River,''
based on a 4,000-year-old Chinese legend about the love of a god
for a mortal and the origins of night and day. ``The festival
offers wonderful support without a whole lot of interference,''
Hwang said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about performing during the boycott, Tseng, born in Hong
Kong, said: ``My personal view is that we change things through
dialogue, meeting and discussion. Silence is death. Absence is
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Hunter, star of the Shared Experience Theatre's
production of Bertolt Brecht's ``Mother Courage and Her Children''
(through June 11) said the boycott presented her London-based
company with ``a Brechtian dilemma. He asks you to make choices and
they're difficult. But Spoleto is such an extraordinary
bringing-together of people. Anything that threatens it is a
pity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother Courage'' cast member Nicholas Bailey is one of the few
blacks performing at Spoleto this year. ``I had no real
reservations about coming,'' he said. ``I'm thinking more about the
implications of doing a political piece. I recognize the
significance of the flag _ I have //right?//some relatives here. As
a black from England, though, my experience over there is very
different from being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Racial politics and the artistic juxtaposition of old and new
were not the only constants running through Spoleto's opening days:
The air-conditioning was on the blink at various venues. ``Another
little theme of this year's festival,'' a stoic Redden said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Hunter was battling a chest infection brought on, she
said, by the temperamental cooling system in her guest quarters on
Folly Beach, and by the stifling weather, in general. ``I had
forgotten how much you perspire,'' she said, as she downed flu
medicine and tried to preserve energy for the three-hour ``Mother
Courage'' performance. Still, she refused to cancel an interview.
Instead, she wondered aloud about making her British accent more
accessible to Spoleto audiences. And she couldn't stop talking
about the ``magical'' Colla Marionettes, whom she saw on her day
off.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unticketed treats of Spoleto is running into artists
at performances other than their own. If it's not Mother Courage
herself at the marionettes, it's dancers at the opera, or opera
singers at the ballet. In the words of festival board member Eric
Friberg, Spoleto's opening weekend has become ``like one gigantic
house party'' _ which is exactly what Friberg will throw next
weekend for Atlanta friends in his Revolutionary War-era home on
Legare Street. ``Some folks just go from mimosas to cocktail party
to cast party,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friberg is a director at Mckinsey &AMP; Co., the Atlanta-based
consulting firm that has done pro bono planning work for Spoleto,
as well as for the Atlanta Opera and the High Museum of Art, whose
boards he oversees? He was confident that a
less-than-recordbreaking year at the box office will not damage
Spoleto's future. ``We'll get through it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you wonder about the festival's future considering the
economic pressure, the mostly outdated venues and the nagging sense
that after 24 years, the local populace is growing a bit
complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spoleto is good for business,'' said Phil Slotin, owner of
Birlant &AMP; Co. antiques on King Street, who had a ``Spoleto Sale''
poster in his store window. ``I'm not badmouthing it at all, but I
think it has lost some of its glitter in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you'd be hardpressed to find others to agree with
that this weekend. As playwright Hwang said, ``During Spoleto,
Charleston is the artistic crossroads of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
