<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, May 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Sizzling heat will broil the Southwest and southern Plains
Tuesday as a broad, warm ridge of high pressure several thousand
feet aloft expands east toward the Mississippi Valley. Temperatures
will soar to 100 degrees in parts of western Kansas and southern
Nebraska as heated breezes descending the Rockies supplement heat
associated with the warm ridge.
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms will erupt near the Big Bend of Texas as
moisture invades northward from Mexico. Save for isolated
thunderstorms associated with the sea-breeze front near the coast
of south Texas, the rest of the region will be shielded from
thunderstorms by a layer of very warm air at altitudes near 5,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of potent thunderstorms, some approaching severe
levels, will erupt over parts of eastern Wyoming and western
Nebraska later Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TORRID TALLAHASSEE
</P>
<P>
   The mercury soared to 100 degrees in Tallahassee, Fla., on
Sunday. Late spring and early summer mark, on average, the city's
warmest period. By midsummer, the burly Bermuda high has
established firm footing over the eastern Atlantic. In turn, its
persistent air circulation keeps southerly winds over the Florida
panhandle, boosting humidity and fostering flocks of cumulus clouds
that keep high temperatures mostly in the 90s.
</P>
</TEXT>
