<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8974 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-LABOR-POLITICS-ART-2T     05-29 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES(1100)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YEARS OF DECLINE, LABOR IS BACK AS A POLITICAL FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the American labor movement's loss in the bruising
battle over the China trade bill, supporters and opponents say that
after years of decline, it has once again become a powerful
political force.
</P>
<P>
   It provided important political muscle that helped Vice
President Al Gore become the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, and will likely by a major force for the Democratic Party
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   After many people wrote off labor as an irrelevant, toothless
dinosaur, the AFL-CIO has displayed considerable muscle on Capitol
Hill by stopping fast-track trade legislation and by helping push
through a higher minimum wage and the Family and Medical Leave Act.
</P>
<P>
   In other signs of promise, white-collar workers, including
doctors and psychologists, are flocking into unions as never
before, and labor registered its biggest organizing victory in 60
years by unionizing 74,000 Los Angeles home-care workers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this rebound has been engineered by John J. Sweeney, who
was elected president of the AFL-CIO four-and-a-half years ago on a
platform of reviving labor after its membership and clout had
slipped steadily for two decades. To rebuild labor, Sweeney has
focused on attracting new members, and as the foremost evidence of
a turnaround, he points to last year's 265,000 jump in union
membership _ by far the largest increase since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
said it would be foolish for anyone to think that labor was weak
because the House of Representatives defied labor last week and
approved permanent normal trade relations for China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who stands up and says, `We won this thing by a couple
of votes and therefore labor is weak,' they don't know how to
count,'' said Donohue, who led the corporate fight for the trade
bill. ``Labor has a lot of money. Labor has a lot of forces on the
ground. Anyone who wants to declare them weak, just look out for
the next fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the 13-million member labor federation has pledged to
put together its biggest army of of campaign volunteers _ tens of
thousands who will distribute literature at work places and make
millions of get-out-the-vote phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO's endorsement of Gore gave him a much-needed boost
in the Democratic presidential primaries, with union foot soldiers
helping him trounce former Sen. Bill Bradley in the Iowa caucuses
and capture a much narrower win in the New Hampshire primary.
Political experts give labor much of the credit for accomplishments
ranging from Gray Davis' gubernatorial victory in California, to
Charles Schumer's triumph over Alfonse D'Amato for New York's
Senate seat, to the Democrats' surprising success in gaining House
seats in the 1998 mid-term election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like night and day comparing the AFL-CIO's political
operations today with those in the 1994 elections,'' said Charles
Cook, who publishes a nonpartisan political report. ``It's like
comparing a Model T with a Ferrari.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor has a long way to go to regain the economic might it
had in the 1950s. Back then, 35 percent of the nation's work force
belonged to unions; compared with 13.9 percent today. The sectors
where unions have been strongest traditionally, like steel,
automobiles, mining and apparel, have been losing jobs the fastest,
while the sectors where unions have had the least representation,
like high technology, finance and fast food, are those growing the
fastest.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor is losing about half the elections where workers
vote on whether to unionize, as many corporations mount aggressive
and expensive campaigns that pressure workers not to join unions.
As a result of such corporate tactics, unions now represent less
than one in 10 private-sector workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The labor movement has done very well in the public sector,
organizing government employees, but in the private sector, it is
still very difficult,'' said Richard Hurd, a labor relations
professor at Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Labor faces some other problems _ the occasional embarrassing
episodes of union corruption, repeated Republican efforts to weaken
unions, and internal feuding among union leaders over political
strategy and trade. Businesses contribute 15 times as much in
campaign money as does labor and many Democrats still keep their
distance, fearful of accusations that they are in Big Labor's
pocket. And for all their efforts, they lost the fight they had
cared the most about over the past few years _ the China trade
bill.
</P>
<P>
   With union membership falling by nearly one fourth between 1979
and 1995, Sweeney has made attracting more members his No. 1
priority. He often cites studies showing that labor's declining
power is a major reason that after-inflation wages have declined
for most workers over the past quarter-century.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has advocated more militant tactics for labor, like
those used by thousands of striking janitors in Los Angeles who
repeatedly blocked traffic last month to draw attention to their
meager wages. He has also worked to reduce labor's unwanted
reputation as a ``special interest'' by having it focus more on
helping low-wage workers and by forming alliances with religious
leaders, environmentalists, immigrant groups and college students
who oppose sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Sweeney has a commitment to reach out to those who have
been largely bypassed by the labor movement,'' said the Rev. Howard
Hubbard, the Roman Catholic bishop of Albany, N.Y., who has helped
lead efforts to rebuild the clergy's once-strong ties with labor.
``He's reached out to the forgotten workers _ child-care workers,
nurses' aides, janitors, people at the low end of the scale. He's
made a commitment to show solidarity with the poorest workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has used his bully pulpit to urge the AFL-CIO's 68
member unions to hire more organizers and to spend millions of
dollars more each year on recruiting. Nonetheless, in his first
three years at labor's helm, union membership slid by 150,000 as
many unionized workers retired or companies closed unionized
factories and moved operations overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeney's ambitions seemed to pay off last year when the
Bureau of Labor Statistics announced that union ranks grew by
265,000.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders say they hope those gains are not a one-time blip,
but the start of a long-term upswing, although many labor experts
say the jury is still out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're starting to turn the corner,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we've had significant progress in terms of organizing,
we still have to do a lot more. We can't rest on modest growth.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His ambitious _ some say unrealistic _ goal is for unions to
organize 1 million new members each year, meaning there might be a
net gain of 500,000 members after layoffs and retirements.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a huge obstacle. Only a handful of unions, most
notably the Service Employees International Union and the Hotel
Employees and Restaurant Employees Union, are operating on all
eight cylinders to attract more workers. Sweeney wishes that more
unions copied the union he once headed, the Service Employees,
which devotes 45 percent of its budget to organizing _ 10 times the
percentage of many unions. That union recruited 155,000 workers
last year, many of them janitors and hospital employees, the most
any union has attracted in one year since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still tremendous inertia among certain unions,'' said
Kent Wong, a labor relations professor at the University of
California at Los Angeles. ``The level of activism among some
unions has changed dramatically, but many unions are having
tremendous difficulties changing.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to woo immigrant workers, Sweeney has gotten the
labor movement to reverse its long-held position and embrace,
rather than oppose, the wave of immigrants. In the 1980s unions
were convinced that immigrants were driving down wages so labor
backed a law that punished employers who hire illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the AFL-CIO has called for ending such employer
sanctions and granting amnesty to millions of illegal immigrants.
Labor changed direction because it views immigrants as a natural
audience for its message and because it sees many employers taking
advantage of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   One welcome development for labor is the surprising surge in
interest shown by white-collar workers. With managed care squeezing
their incomes and professional freedom, thousands of doctors are
joining unions; in New York state, 3,000 psychologists have
unionized. So have 10,000 podiatrists and more than 20,000 customer
services workers at United Airlines and U.S. Airways.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of IBM workers showed interest in unionizing last year
after their company sought to cut their pensions. And even a few
dozen workers at Microsoft called for a union because they were
angry about being long-term temporary workers, with few benefits,
rather than permanent staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of industries, because of the way things are
changing, people realize they need some form of collective voice,''
said Sweeney. ``People are seeing the problems they're confronted
with are too big to resolve by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the China trade battle, one of Sweeney's biggest
problems is that many political and business leaders have pegged
him as protectionist and anti-trade. These critics misunderstand
his position, he insists.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that past trade accords have helped business but not
labor, he said he told the Clinton administration that the AFL-CIO
would oppose any trade agreement that did not protect workers
rights. So when Sweeney saw that the administration's trade deal
with China contained no worker protections, he saw no choice but to
oppose it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think trade is good for our country,'' Sweeney said. ``It's
important to our successful economy. We recognize that
globalization is here to stay, so the question is, How do workers
around the world share in the fruits of globalization?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
