<HEADLINE>
MICROBREWERS STRUGGLE TO SUCCEED OUTSIDE THEIR HOME AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After 14 years in the beer-making business, Richard
Doyle, a founder of the Mass. Bay Brewing Co., no longer pays much
attention to the humid, bready scent of barley malt and yeast
bubbling over into foam-topped buckets. But the smell is still
comforting, reminding him that the brewery is running all out,
producing nearly 2 million gallons of Harpoon beer a year.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle recently added a sixth 24-hour production day to the
brewery's workweek. Indeed, business is as good as it ever was at
the height of the specialty beer boom in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   But some of his colleagues in the Massachusetts microbrewing
industry have not been so fortunate. Local brewers like Bristol,
Middlesex, Pilgrim and Old Newbury have all closed their doors.
Thinking back on the boom, Doyle, who is also chairman of the
Brewers Association of America, described the rush to market as a
busy intersection without a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much product going through, it was just
crashing,'' he said. ``We needed time to kind of tow it all away.''
</P>
<P>
   The craze in the 1990s for craft-brewed beers with a variety of
interesting tastes (and names) suddenly jammed store aisles with
fanciful brews like Laughing Skull Bohemian Pilsner, Long Trail
Double Bag Ale, Rogue Shakespeare Stout and Pig's Eye Pilsner. For
consumers used to basic labels like Coors and Bud, it was a bit too
much. Some microbrewers collided head-on with distributors who
refused to carry their products and financiers who clamored for
profits even as sales slowed.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, for the first time, more microbreweries in the
United States closed last year than opened. And more bottles will
head for the clearance shelves this year.
</P>
<P>
   But those craft brewers that lived through the shake-up _ and
there are many _ are telling a tale of leaner, more economical
brewing, more conservative growth, and more thoughtful business
plans. They are taking a breather before making another, more sober
run on the American beer market, which is dominated by three
companies _ Anheuser-Busch, Miller Brewing, a unit of Philip
Morris, and Coors _ that have 80 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, these independent beer makers say, they are paying
more respect to their roots. The craft beer industry grew at a
euphoric rate of 50 percent in both 1994 and 1995, spurring some
regional brewers _ heady as prom queens with their local popularity
_ to rush their products into new markets. But when growth stalled
in 1997 and 1998, many retreated to their home states and the
comforting loyalty of customers in their own backyards.
</P>
<P>
   Deschutes Brewery of Bend, Ore., stopped shipments to Colorado
and San Diego. Pyramid of Seattle and the Breckenridge Brewing Co.
in Denver cut back on their out-of-state attempts as well.
</P>
<P>
   What they found, said David Edgar, president of the Institute
for Brewing Studies in Colorado, is that beer drinkers in Oregon
have a special affection for their Black Butte Porter, and
Alabamans stick with their Red Mountain Red Ale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry will always be primarily about local beers,'' he
said. ``The lesson was learned that just because you were the cat's
meow in Portland doesn't mean that automatically consumers are
going to embrace your brand as strongly in Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shipyard Brewing Co. in Maine, for one, began on the
Kennebunk River in 1992, but within a few years expanded into New
York, New Jersey, Maryland, Chicago, Florida and parts of Virginia.
Then sales slumped. Shipyard retrenched to New England, where it
currently sells 75 percent of its product. Fred Forsely, its
co-founder, hasn't given up thoughts of going national, but
meanwhile he is coping with ``being able to accept a small piece of
a very loyal market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we go to Chicago again,'' he said with humility, ``we won't
expect to sell three trailer loads a month again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
