<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROBREWERS-ART-2NDT     05-29 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROBREWERS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: month again.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been a handful of closings in New York as well. In
upstate New York, where the trend was slow to dig in, there are
about a dozen working microbreweries, including Brewery Ommegang in
Cooperstown, which opened in 1998, and Flying Bison in Buffalo,
which began brewing last year. All have set their sights on the
local market, which gives them good odds of succeeding, said Bill
Metzger, a trade publisher in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Many brewers call New York City a hard market to break into. But
the Brooklyn Brewery built a loyal following by handling its own
distribution. Sales have grown consistently since it began in 1988,
said Stephen Hindy, president and co-founder. Last year, Brooklyn
Brewery sold 32,000 barrels, 80 percent of them in the metropolitan
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slow way to grow, but owning our own trucks and doing
our own deliveries has taught us a lot about the beer business,''
Hindy said. ``We know a lot about what our customers are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Sunset Grill &AMP; Tap in Boston, which offers about 60
American craft brews from its 112 taps, beer enthusiasts still
sample the occasional seasonal Summer Wheat Ale or Octoberfest
brew. But instead of jumping on the new brand of the month,
drinkers generally stick with established products from Sam Adams
(made by Boston Beer and the biggest and best-advertised craft beer
in the country), Sierra Nevada (a best-seller from California), and
New England makers like Vermont's Magic Hat and the Tremont
Brewery, a tiny Boston producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it, at this point, is just credibility,'' said Marc
Kadish, the bar's owner. ``Breweries change and the owners change.
Or it's simply not fresh. Somebody takes a chance, tries an
interesting microbrew and is disappointed. Why do people go to
McDonald's? It's consistent and people know what they're going to
get.''
</P>
<P>
   Even very good beer makers ran into problems. Some, expecting
the euphoria of the beer craze to continue, poured borrowed money
into beer-making, and were caught with a lot of shiny equipment to
make too much beer for too few drinkers. Catamount, Vermont's first
microbrewery, completed a $5 million dollar plant just as growth
began to top out. It closed last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Frederick Brewing company of Maryland found itself in a
similar predicament in 1997. It built an $8 million beer-making
plant with a 100,000 barrel annual capacity, but wound up producing
only about 32,000 barrels there. Last year, Frederick was purchased
by Snyder International Brewing Group of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Firmat, a founder of Oregon-based Full Sail, has seen
several brewers in her region merge or consolidate. Others continue
to struggle with whether to go public, stay private or form a
partnership with an industry giant. Her own company faced the same
question when two of her partners recently wanted out of the
business. Full Sail employees bought them out in 1999, and the
brewery is now worker-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Firmat credits Full Sail's survival, in part, to the Pacific
Northwest's taste for better beer. ``Craft beer is part of the
consciousness of the region,'' she said, pointing out that special
brews account for about 10 percent of beer sales in her area, as
opposed to about 3 percent nationally. ``That helps a lot to buffer
the changes in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   One change was increased competition from imported beers. If a
customer was willing to spend a little more for a six pack, it
turned out he was more likely to buy a brand that had been around
for 50 years than 50 days. East Coast brewers in particular felt
the competition of brands like Heineken, Corona and Bass, which
helped push consumption of imports to 9.2 percent of the American
market last year.
</P>
<P>
   The craft beer promoters have themselves to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, tastes have definitely developed,'' said Kadish,
the bar owner. ``People were so scared of the imports and the dark
beers, and now IPA is a household word.'' As with India Pale Ales,
customers barely sputter when they order a Bitburger, Warstiener or
Hackerphscorr.
</P>
<P>
   To further erode consumer confidence, the megabrewers played an
awkward role in the specialty beer field. The large beer makers
answered the call for unique beers with their own homespun-sounding
labels, including Anheuser-Busch's Red Wolf, Coors' Killian's Red
and Miller's Red Dog. As if that scarlet trio were not confusing
enough, consumers were unsure whether they were drinking a hometown
favorite, or a quaintly packaged version of a megabrew.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some smaller companies, eager for expansion money,
became megabrewer protectorates. Miller, the Milwaukee-based giant,
bought a 50 percent stake in fast-growing Shipyard in 1995. In
exchange, Shipyard gained access to Miller's laboratories, and
probably most important, its distribution system. But Miller
apparently lost interest when Shipyard's barrel production dropped
from 39,500 in 1996 to 25,300 in 1998. Last month, Shipyard
announced it was taking on some debt to buy those shares back.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent doldrums, industry analysts are optimistic.
Beer sales increased by 1.6 percent last year, primarily because
the prime beer drinking population, considered to be people (mostly
men) in their 20s and early 30s, is also up. Beer prices, which
have lagged behind inflation for some 15 years, have climbed.
</P>
<P>
   There are still over 420 small brewers in the United States _ up
from about 200 in 1994 _ and their stories are as varied as their
labels. Together, sales at the four of the largest specialty
brewers _ Boston Beer, Pete's Wicked, Redhook and Pyramid _ fell 24
percent between 1996 and 1999. Yet half of the top 50 craft brewers
had double digit sales growth last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some have been blissfully unaffected by the turmoil. New Belgium
sales were up more than 40 percent last year. Sierra Nevada, the
second largest craft brewer in the United States, has grown right
along since its founding in 1981, increasing its sales nearly 15
percent last year and 26 percent the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, the beer association chairman, said resisting the
temptation to go for maximum growth helped his Harpoon Brewery keep
its footing as others around him slipped. ``We were not leveraged,
we're not highly leveraged now,'' he said. ``Our focus was making
sure that we were very profitable at the size we were, to store up
resources for the time when the industry thawed again.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, most of the specialty brands have reported an
upturn in sales, said Frank Walters, the director of research for
the trade newsletter Impact. ``A lot of the streamlining, getting
rid of the dead-wood brands, we think was probably completed in the
last half of 1999,'' he said. ``Things are starting to grow
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakeouts have their advantages. At the National Craft Brewers
Conference in Milwaukee last month attendees were mostly
experienced brewers more interested in seminars like ``Hopping to
Perfection'' and ``The Biodiversity of Yeast'' than newcomers
looking to hop on a bandwagon. ``These events used to be full of
tire kickers,'' said Gary Fish, president of the Deschutes Brewery.
``There's not so many of those people any more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
