<HEADER>
A8995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-RUSSIA-POLLUTION-900(     05-29 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLLUTION-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL WORKING  
</HEADLINE>
  
 ENVIRONMENTALISTS FEAR DEVASTATION IN VAST SIBERIAN LAKE   By c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAIKALSK, Russia _ Near the outlet where the Baikalsk Pulp and
Paper Mill discharges chlorine into the world's largest body of
fresh water, Oleg Dolgov has dropped a line to fish.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists accuse the mill of polluting Siberia's Lake
Baikal, a mile-deep cleft that contains one-fifth of the planet's
fresh water. But Dolgov, who has already snagged a dozen small
fish, shrugs off the danger of contamination. A cargo handler at
the company store, he regularly eats what he catches, and has never
noticed ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployed come down here all the time in the summer and
catch fish with nets,'' Dolgov said.
</P>
<P>
   Locals may be insouciant, but among environmentalists in Russia
and abroad, the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill symbolizes the abuse
of an ecological treasure. An international campaign is seeking to
close the plant, and Greenpeace has begun nationwide television
advertisements blasting the factory. But even as critics say the
mill threatens this gem of a lake, the management says the demands
for a complete shutdown are blocking efforts to clean the plant up.
</P>
<P>
   The issue goes beyond the lake. Throughout the former Soviet
Union, industry has turned the waterways into environmental
catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Vladivostok pumps raw sewage into its bay, the Aral
Sea has been gradually emptied and polluted by agricultural runoff,
and the navy dumped radioactive waste into the White Sea and the
Sea of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have long had trouble making their case in a
nation predisposed to heavy industry. This time around, the
Baikalsk mill is attempting to blame environmentalists themselves
for the pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, Greenpeace and all the environmental
organizations prevent us from improving the environmental situation
of the lake,'' said Anatoly Steinberg, president of the mill.
</P>
<P>
   Baikal is 5,370 feet deep and contains 5,500 cubic miles of
water. Believed to be 25 million years old, the lake floor's
sediment is 5 miles deep, recording eons of life. Buried in its mud
are traces of magnolia pollen, deposited when this northern lake
had a subtropical climate.
</P>
<P>
   Today Baikal is filled with rare species such as freshwater
sponges and seals. Sixty percent of the lake's life forms are
unique, biologists say.
</P>
<P>
   The lake's pure water and the virgin forests around it helped
draw the Baikalsk mill here in the 1960s, a decision that critics
say is a relic of the Soviet Union's central planning. .
</P>
<P>
   ``They put a factory here because there is a lot of forest
here,'' said Vladimir Fialkov, director of the Russian Academy of
Sciences Lake Baikal Museum. ``Then they passed a decree
prohibiting cutting the woods around Baikal, to protect it.'' Then,
he said, timber had to be shipped in from some 600 miles away, in
Chita.
</P>
<P>
   Baikalsk itself is a typical Siberian village _ rows of block
apartments and neighborhoods of log houses with heaps of coal or
wood in back. There is a monument to World War II veterans and a
Soviet-era sculpture of youths reaching for the heavens, as if
grasping for a socialist future. The air is permeated with the
rotten-egg smell of pulp making.
</P>
<P>
   The plant annually produces 160,000 metric tons of high-quality
pulp for domestic and foreign markets. Some of the chlorine,
despite filtration, is discharged into the lake. But Jennie Sutton,
an Englishwoman who lives in the nearby town of Irkutsk and is a
leader of a local group called Baikal Environmental Wave, says the
chlorine is converted to deadly dioxins in the bodies of seals and
other animals. Although the pollution is in only a tiny part of the
lake, the impact is disproportionate, she said. Animals flock to
the warm outflow from the mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual management of the mill is irresponsible
economically,'' Sutton said. ``They have found ways of hiding their
profits to avoid paying for the damage they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of answering reporters' questions and watching
environmentalists hang banners from his mill's smokestacks,
Steinberg has little patience for the topic of pollution (``Why are
foreigners so primitive?'' he pondered aloud in an interview. ``Why
do they ask such stupid questions?'').
</P>
<P>
   He insists that the mill causes only a minute amount of harm
that the vast lake is capable of handling. ``This is the best
quality of water coming from any paper mill in the world,''
Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists agree that the damage to Baikal has been minimal
and the pollution is restricted to a small portion of the south
part of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Steinberg says he has plans for reducing pollution
to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Another lakeside mill in the town of Selenginsk, about 120 miles
away, produces an inferior grade of paper in a plant that recycles
waste water, so that, theoretically, at least, it discharges
nothing into the lake. The shareholders of the Baikalsk mill have
decided they will follow suit. They plan to convert the mill to
producing a cheaper grade of pulp that does not require bleaching
and will use a closed filtration system. (Steinberg refuses to
state the cost of remodeling or say where the money will come
from.)
</P>
<P>
   But Steinberg is bitter that, rather than embracing this plan,
environmentalists are, in his view, blocking any solution short of
complete closure. ``Some critics,'' he said, ``have built entire
careers around closing his plant. They are being parasites on the
problem,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But some environmentalists believe that the plant's management
simply can't be trusted. And, they say that even mills with
supposedly closed systems often discharge pollutants into the
surrounding watershed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people responsible for checking independently are highly
corruptible,'' Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Galazy, an environmentalist, retired biologist and
former deputy in the regional parliament, says the mill is not
needed. Downstream on the Angara River, which flows from Baikal,
two other pulp and paper mills could pick up the slack, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these two factories work at only 30-40 percent of their
capacity, this Baikalsk mill keeps stubbornly contaminating the
lake,'' Galazy said.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists are divided on how serious the damage is. ``In
1989, there were massive deaths in the population of freshwater
seals,'' said Nadezhda Basharova, a hydrobiology professor at the
nearby Irkutsk State University. Autopsies showed that the seals
were abnormally infested with parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe the seals were weakened by toxins from
the mill and less able to resist the parasites, Basharova said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, she does not believe the mill should close. ``If
you close it and go away, it will be worse for Baikal, because
there is a lot of contamination in the soil, and it will find its
way into the lake,'' Basharova said,
</P>
<P>
   Environmental warnings carry little weight with many of Baikalsk
Pulp &AMP; Paper Mills workers. Closing the mill would be devastating
for a 3,500-person workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Baikal Environmental Wave is establishing a small business
incubator to encourage alternative employment.The region could
conceivably attract foreign hikers, boaters and hunters. But a
program with a budget of a few thousand dollars would not have the
resources to help a town full of people thrown out of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The factory was built at the same time as the town,'' said
Dolgov, the fisherman. ``If there was no factory, there would be no
jobs. It would be worse than any village could take. The town would
die.''
</P>
<P>
   But others see dangers of another kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that we could lose the uniqueness of Baikal,''
Galazy said. ``The loss will be irreparable. There is no other lake
like this in the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
