<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SUV-LIABILITY-1055(2T     05-29 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUV-LIABILITY-1055(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS DEBATE FEASIBILITY OF SUING SUV MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ While Ford Motor Co. recently acknowledged that sport
utility vehicles can be hazardous to other motorists, law
professors and plaintiff lawyers say that it remains difficult to
win lawsuits based on the damage that sport utilities inflict in
crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers and automakers say that they are aware of only one
lawsuit so far in which a car occupant has sued the manufacturer of
the sport utility that hit her. That case, against Land Rover, was
summarily dismissed in January by a Superior Court judge in Los
Angeles who concluded that the automaker had no legal duty to
consider what would happen to other vehicles and motorists struck
by its products.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some plaintiff lawyers say that even before Ford's recent
pronouncements, they were searching for cases in which tall sport
utilities overrode cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just waiting for the right case to come along, where
someone isn't sodden with alcohol or going 100 miles an hour,''
said Robert Palmer, a lawyer in Springfield, Mo., who is the vice
president of the Attorneys Information Exchange Group, a national
group of trial lawyers who sue automakers.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars say that while Ford and other sport utility
makers have a strong legal case, liability law can evolve quickly
in response to shifts in public sentiment, as shown by recent
litigation against tobacco companies and gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were the Ford Motor Co., I wouldn't treat this very
cavalierly, but at this point in the development of tort law, they
have the better argument,'' said Roger C. Henderson, a law
professor at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Most legal experts agree that Ford Motor's recent acknowledgment
of the dangers posed to occupants of other vehicles by sport
utility vehicles is unlikely to help trial lawyers. The legal issue
is not whether sport utilities are particularly deadly to other
motorists, but whether that deadliness results in legal liability
for automakers.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers have lost many lawsuits over the years
accusing them of having designed automobiles that inadequately
protect occupants during crashes. Some of these suits have involved
occupants injured or killed when sport utilities rolled over. But
successful suits holding automakers liable for the harm that their
products cause to other vehicles and their occupants are another
matter.
</P>
<P>
   In a corporate ``citizenship report'' distributed at its annual
shareholders meeting in Atlanta on May 11, Ford attributed the
heavy damage inflicted during crashes by sport utilities and other
so-called light trucks to the big vehicles' design, not just their
weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trucks are also built with a more rigid frame and higher
stance _ important for towing and hauling cargo _ but this means
that the stiff parts of the truck may not engage all the parts of a
car designed to absorb impact,'' the company said, vowing to
continue its industry-leading efforts to find solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice president for safety and the
environment, said that sport utility manufacturers and their
customers were not exposed to litigation because the vehicles were
not defective or negligently designed. She depicted the report as
containing a scientific discussion of sport utility safety rather
than an admission of defects or negligence in design.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers have several strong defenses against litigation
involving damage and injuries caused by sport utilities during
crashes. Legal tradition holds that makers of large cars, pickups
and trailer trucks are not liable just because these vehicles
inflict severe damage on small cars during crashes. Trucks and
large cars need to be big to haul freight and plenty of people.
</P>
<P>
   And most state courts allow some balancing of a product's
usefulness with its risk to society, along with the cost of design
changes to reduce those risks.
</P>
<P>
   But a few legal experts suggest that sport utilities may not
pass muster on this balancing of risk and usefulness. Richard
Friedman, a law professor at the University of Michigan, questioned
whether their off-road capability _ for which they have high ground
clearance and high bumpers _ justified the extra damage and
injuries caused when the tall vehicles override cars' bumpers and
door sills during crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments are quite theoretical. In an actual crash, it is
extremely difficult for engineers, much less juries, to distinguish
between the damage caused by sport utilities' height and the damage
caused by their considerable weight.
</P>
<P>
   Large, heavy cars have always done a lot of damage to other
vehicles, although they are far less likely than sport utilities to
kill the other motorist in a crash. The line between heavy cars and
sport utilities has been blurred by the introduction of carlike
sport utilities like the Lexus RX300, which is essentially a tall
Toyota Camry wagon with all-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evidence on the deadliness of sport utilities is
based on national statistics, rather than specific crashes. Midsize
sport utilities are three times as likely as midsize cars to kill
the other driver in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   This is true even though occupants of midsize sport utilities
are also more likely to die in a crash themselves than occupants of
midsize cars. That is because the sport utilities are more prone to
rolling over and have limited crumple zones.
</P>
<P>
   Using such statistics tends to be easier in a class-action
lawsuit than in a specific personal-injury claim, but it is unclear
whether people hit by sport utilities represent what courts would
accept as a legal class.
</P>
<P>
   The usual basis for establishment of such a class is a
contractual relationship between a manufacturer and the people who
are harmed, such as when people buy a defective product. No such
relationship exists between automakers and people who have been hit
by sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently have some courts allowed class-action lawsuits by
people without such contractual relationships, notably by gunshot
victims against gun makers and by people who sue tobacco companies
because they were exposed to colleagues' secondhand smoke. But such
class-action cases remain uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't any clear duty by Ford to other motorists. They
owe a duty to their customers,'' said John C. Coffee, a law
professor at Columbia University.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There are also no federal regulations requiring automakers to
limit the damage that their products may inflict on other
motorists. Sport utilities are specifically exempt from federal
regulations on bumper height, so as to preserve their off-road
driving capability.
</P>
<P>
   Land Rover emphasized the absence of bumper-height regulations
in persuading Judge Jan A. Pluim of the Los Angeles Superior Court
earlier this year to dismiss the lawsuit filed against it by Diane
Y. Diaz de Veer, who suffered brain injuries when her Saab was hit
by a Range Rover. Arnold Schwartz, the woman's lawyer, said he
would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers believe that Ford, by forthrightly addressing sport
utilities' problems now and describing its search for solutions,
may have actually reduced its potential exposure to large verdicts
for punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ford may have transferred some of its liability to
owners of sport utilities. ``It was a very wise statement for them
to make, because they're putting the world on notice that if you're
in a sport utility and drive it negligently, then you could be
responsible,'' said Ralph Knowles, a plaintiff lawyer in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, a particularly gruesome aspect of accidents
involving sport utility vehicles also discourages plaintiff lawyers
from filing lawsuits over their designs.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that the high front ends of sport utilities make
them more likely to hit other motorists in the head, neck and upper
torso and kill them, rather than crippling them with injuries to
the waist or legs. Large liability awards tend to go to people who
are severely injured but survive to provide vivid testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said he had just turned down a sport utility case mainly
because the car driver had died in the crash. Preparing a lawsuit
that breaks new legal ground costs $200,000 to $400,000, he said,
adding, ``A wrongful-death case in most parts of the country is
just not worth a lot of money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
