<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9008 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LADIES-FASHION-ART-NY     05-29 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADIES-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO CAN DEFINE `LADYLIKE?' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT1,2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CATHY HORYN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever since designers and fashion editors started
tossing about the term ``ladylike dressing'' like a threadbare
muffler from Gimbel's, one has had the feeling they don't know what
they are talking about. Oh, sure, they have contacts in the world
of thin women _ what is Vogue if not an illustrated Social
Register? And there's no telling how many designers have set their
speed dials to BUtterfield-8.
</P>
<P>
   But just because the fall collections are loaded with examples
of upper-echelon chic doesn't mean they jibe with the reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any such thing as ladylike dressing,
said Nan Kempner, the Park Avenue hostess and champion
clotheshorse. ``I think you're the lady and the clothes are just a
reflection of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Kempner, who will be 70 in July, is unique, with her
40 years of wearing Saint Laurent couture. ``I mean,'' her friend
Bill Blass said, ``have you ever had the statistics on what Nan has
purchased or seen?'' But as she herself would point out, she isn't
the only socialite with an informed view of the new dressing up.
</P>
<P>
   Here are four women _ Amanda Hearst, Brooke de Ocampo, Kempner
and Brooke Astor, four generations of New York women, age 16 to 98
_ defining what it means to dress like a lady.
</P>
<P>
   Outgrowing Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just at Scoop and I bought a lavender tube top and a
pair of hazel capri pants in linen,'' said Amanda Hearst, the
16-year-old daughter of Anne Hearst and a great-granddaughter of
William Randolph Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is blond and pretty and very poised. A sophomore at a
boarding school, she follows what's in fashion. ``I buy stuff at
Prada, but mostly it's shoes and coats,'' she said. ``That's what
my friends and I do. I also like stuff from Tocca and Katayone
Adeli. Stuff you see on Barneys eighth floor. We really don't go in
for the top labels.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Hearst said, she has noticed a sea change among her
friends, even as they slave away at school. ``Last year the look
was Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch and Ralph Lauren polo shirts and khaki
pants,'' she said. ``Right now, we're into blow drying our hair,
wearing delicate jewelry and clothes that fit, especially skirts.
We're always into makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   But can a tube top be ladylike?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think so,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ladylike Without the Rules
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls who come to us are, for lack of a better word, more
earthy,'' said Josh Patner of the dress house Tuleh. ``The Nan
Kempners of the world, in my imagination, float on clouds. Brooke
very much is putting her heel to the pavement.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Brooke de Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
   With three small children, a busy social life with her husband,
Emilio, and a book in the works with the photographer Jonathan
Becker, de Ocampo, at 33, has a lot on her mind other than clothes.
Yet, every day she gets dressed as if she's going somewhere _ last
Monday, in a white Marc Jacobs peasant top with fuchsia Helmut Lang
trousers and Manolo Blahnik sandals. ``I'm dressed in a way that
helps me get things done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   de Ocampo is part of a junior crowd of socialites, though none
really like the term. Still, it was obvious to her and her friends
that a number of designers, notably Michael Kors, were thinking of
this younger group when they showed their ladylike fall
collections. ``Some of these designers are pals of mine,'' she said
hesitantly, ``but what they were doing looked like a caricature of
all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I feel that if you're going to have a cashmere coat
with fur, then show it with jeans and high-heeled boots. It would
look ladylike without looking stamped.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, what de Ocampo and women her age want is a
put-together look that still says girlishly casual, even sexy. She
brought out a couple of things from her closet: a cinnamon-and-pink
polka dot Tuleh skirt she has worn with a hot-pink sweater, and a
purple chiffon Helmut Lang top she wore with pants to a dressy
Sotheby's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hardly ever wear suits,'' she said. The last time she did
was for a wedding. It was by Chloe, and it fit beautifully, she
said. ``The skirt was practically riding on my hips.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed to Please
</P>
<P>
   To give some idea how crazy Nan Kempner is for clothes, in 1957,
when she was pregnant with one of her three children, she had her
maternity clothes made at Patou in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you love that?'' she said one afternoon in the Park
Avenue duplex where she and her husband, the investment banker
Thomas Kempner, have lived for 42 years.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the clothes were made by Karl Lagerfeld, then
known at Patou as Karl. Kempner shrugged. ``Everybody's got to
start somewhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She had just come from having lunch at Swifty's, which she
treats like a canteen, and she had on a beige sweater with a
20-year-old Saint Laurent python skirt. ``Everything recycles,''
she said. ``So if you keep clothes long enough, you have a good
wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempner doesn't wear only couture, but she buys a lot of it, and
at half price, since the samples fit her. ``Couture is like a
second skin _ it moves with you,'' she said. ``And the more you
wear it, the better it feels. You break it in.'' She added, apropos
of both Saint Laurent and herself, ``If you've got a great look,
you don't really improve it. You master it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempner, who recently bought a cream-colored Saint Laurent
pantsuit and a leopard chiffon blouse (``I'm mad about that
shirt,'' she said), thinks the most important thing about dressing
is to put yourself together _ and then forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dress to be appealing _ to anything and everybody,'' Kempner
said. ``That's a wonderful thing about Brooke Astor. She always
dresses appropriately. And when she goes to these big charity
things, sure, she brings out all the jewelry. Why not? Everybody
wants to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   So dressing is a social grace?
</P>
<P>
   ``You got it. You dress to please people.''
</P>
<P>
   And Don't Forget Your Hat
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in one of a series of articles she has written for
Vanity Fair about modern manners, Astor recalled some advice from
her grandmother: A lady should always leave something on her plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``On looking back,'' she wrote, ``I recognize a philosophy
behind this admonition. To want to enjoy one's dinner is correct,
but greed is not.'' Astor, every bit the lady, has given millions
to worthy causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I dress so extraordinarily,'' she said by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Though feeling a bit under the weather, she was on her way to
her home in Maine. ``Some of my suits I've worn for ages, because
they're taken very good care of,'' she said. ``I have a very good
French maid whom I've had for years. She always sees that all my
clothes are in very good condition. I buy a couple of new evening
dresses every year. I buy Balmain from my friend Oscar. I like
those clothes very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wear a hat _ you see, I was brought up to all that.
Wearing a hat is also good for your eyes. My eyes are marvelous. I
can see right the way across the river. Which at 98, is pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Astor had some plain old wisdom for the new business of dressing
up. ``I think your clothes should be very clean and fresh and
always in good shape,'' she said. ``I think all your things ought
to be in order. Go along that way, and you'll be all right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      05-29 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS EXITS EARLY IN FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It is hardly a surprise to see Pete Sampras bid farewell
to the French Open long before the last blow has been struck. At
this stage of his otherwise brilliant career, it is only a question
of how he will be eliminated, and who will do the eliminating.
</P>
<P>
   The answers came particularly early this year. They came Monday
on the first day of play, and they came under an ever-changing sky
against a younger and more powerful opponent, Mark Philippoussis,
who has given him trouble in the past on surfaces much more
conducive to Sampras' game.
</P>
<P>
   But this was European clay, the red and gritty stuff that sticks
to Sampras' sneakers and sticks in his craw. And though the
second-seeded American performed and served quite well in stretches
on the refurbished center court, he did not play well enough when
it mattered to avoid another bitter five-set experience in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis prevailed, 4-6, 7-5, 7-6 (4), 4-6, 8-6, in a match
that required 3 hours 39 minutes and ended with Sampras losing his
serve at love on a double fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fifth set it comes down to nerves, and he had the
better nerve,'' said Sampras, who also lost the second set and the
sixth game of the final set on double faults.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sampras has won 12 Grand Slam singles titles _ tying him
for the most ever with Roy Emerson _ he has never advanced past the
semifinals at Roland Garros Stadium. He got that far only in 1996,
negotiating a brutal draw before running out of resources on a very
hot day against the eventual champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov. But with
Sampras approaching his 29th birthday, that memorable run now looks
increasingly like an anomaly. In 1997, he lost to Magnus Norman in
the third round. In 1998, he lost to Ramon Delgado in the second
round, and last year, he was beaten in the second round by Andrei
Medvedev, who went on to reach the final against Sampras'
compatriot, Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   All three of Sampras' recent losses came on the Suzanne Lenglen
court, one that he dislikes and contends is considerably slower
than the other showcourts here. But this time, he was beaten on the
center court he prefers, and beaten at his own game by a big server
who likes to push forward to the net and take risks from the
baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I had some chances, but Mark, I give him all the
credit, he served huge,'' Sampras said after watching 23 aces go
by.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Americans fared better Monday. First, Meghann
Shaughnessy upset the No. 12 women's seeded player, Julie
Halard-Decugis of France by 7-5, 6-4. Then Jan-Michael Gambill
ousted eighth-seeded Nicolas Kiefer of Germany, 6-3, 7-5, 6-1,
although it might have been more satisfying if the clearly off-form
Kiefer had not missed most of the last two months because of ankle
surgery. But Jennifer Capriati, still struggling since her split
from her former coach Harold Solomon, fell to Fabiola Zuluaga of
Columbia, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sampras holds a 7-3 career edge over Philippoussis,
Sampras has now lost to him twice in Grand Slam events: the first
time in straight sets at the 1996 Australian Open when
Philippoussis was still a relative unknown. But if Philippoussis,
with his short attention span and penchant for the unforced error,
has not managed to succeed consistently on tour, he has clearly
improved his ability to handle pressure (not to mention short, low
balls). He was the key figure in Australia's Davis Cup victory over
France last year on indoor clay, and if not for a serious knee
injury that forced him to retire with a one-set lead over Sampras
in the Wimbledon quarterfinals last year, he might have eliminated
the American there as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Mark in the first round is certainly a tough draw,''
Sampras said. ``I certainly haven't got the breaks at this event
over the years, but one year hopefully I'll get those breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a perfect world, a perfect career, you'd like to win all
the majors, do everything in the game,'' he added. ``I have a very
high bar that I've raised. It kind of would be disappointing if I
would not win it, but, you know, life will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis would agree and has a great deal more time left
to do so. Traditionally, it is the defending champion who opens
play on center court at Roland Garros, but this year, the defending
champion has retired, which means that Hingis, whom Steffi Graf
beat in last year's final, got the honor of walking on court at 11
a.m. with only a few hundred fans in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   There was not much suspense surrounding the outcome. Hingis had
beaten Sabine Appelmans of Belgium in all five of their previous
matches, and she beat her again, 6-0, 6-4, in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But what was in doubt was how the Parisian fans would react to
Hingis after her histrionics in last year's final, when she
contravened tennis etiquette by crossing the net to question a line
call and later lost her composure and served underhand twice out of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Though she may yet have some public relations work to do over
the next two weeks, the response to Hingis' arrival Monday was
restrained: light applause and a few scattered whistles. Hingis, as
usual, is choosing to accentuate the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here since Tuesday, and I never had so many people
recognize me walking on the streets in regular clothes, never.''
she said. ``So it was real nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, visibly heavier than she was during her resurgence
from last summer to March of this year, has now lost both her
matches without Solomon in her corner, first to Anne-Gaelle Sidot
in the opening round at the Italian Open and to Zuluaga Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harold was great for me and a great coach,'' the 15th-seeded
Capriati said. ``But I took myself back from that point to top 20.
The coach is always just going to be the coach, but the player is
the one that does all the work. I just don't want to make it seem
like he brought me back and now because he's not with me, I'm going
to go down. That's not fair to say.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
