<HEADER>
A9017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-FASHION-NOTES-ART-NYT     05-29 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Designer Shows her Styles
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not long ago, Elisa Jimenez, a flower-power-minded
designer whose answering machine asks callers to ``be well, be
blessed,'' sent some dresses encased in hardened clay to a Los
Angeles shop, Naked. To see just what a dress looks like, you'd
have to crack open the packaging at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a hard thing to sell,'' Steven Russell, an
owner of the store, recalls telling Jimenez. He suggested she send
at least one dress in an open case. Jimenez would not. Buying a
dress is all about taking a risk, she told Russell, and hey, some
risks don't work out.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial instinct is not Jimenez's forte, she admitted the
other day, although she is trying to acquire one. The designer, who
is 35 and lives in Hell's Kitchen, sews one-of-a-kind dresses
directly on her customers, typically dousing the garments with oils
for an aromatherapy effect. Last week, she introduced her first
full ready-to-wear line at Kirna Zabete on Greene Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to make some money,'' she said. She has had a following
among stylists and celebrities like Courtney Love, but few women
with more pedestrian lifestyles buy her clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The collection consists of one-size-fits-all polymorphous items,
like halters that transform into skirts. ``There are about 10
different ways to wear everything,'' said Sarah Hales, an owner of
Kirna Zabete, adding that so far Jimenez's clothes were attracting
``experimental'' customers.
</P>
<P>
   But some pieces are too advanced even for the daring. Last week,
Hales returned a sequined orange cape to the designer. ``I told
her: `Take this home with you. It's scaring customers.'''
</P>
<P>
   Where's the `Beauty' in Beauty Pageants?
</P>
<P>
   Beauty pageants are generally not the sort of spectacles that
draw people with an aversion to camp _ people like the the German
photographer Juergen Teller, who is best known for saturnine
fashion images in magazines like Index and W. But last fall,
Teller, a pioneer of the unglamorous documentary style of fashion
photography of the 1990s, found himself captivated by the 1999 Miss
World Competition in London. He was on assignment from the Goethe
Institute of Caracas to take a portrait of Venezuela. Once there,
Teller photographed all 88 contestants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty much blown away by how determined they all
were,'' he said last week. ``They were just standing in front of my
camera, each one, and smiling. They were not necessarily smiling at
me. When a model smiles at me, I feel she means it to a certain
extent.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Miss World project will be on view starting
Thursday at the Lehmann Maupin gallery on Greene Street, in
Teller's first commercial exhibition in the United States. The show
will also feature images from his ``Go-Sees'' project, candid
photographs of aspiring models who visited his London studio, taken
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at their portfolios,'' he said, ``and most of them
were much sweeter and more beautiful than they looked in their
books.''
</P>
<P>
   From X-Rays to Image Making
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing aggressively groovy in Patrick Li's look _ no
Yves Saint Laurent suit, no glasses that look like German surgical
instruments, nothing suggesting that he landed a job at Interview
magazine in 1990, the day after he moved to New York, or wound up
as a protege of the graphic designer Fabien Baron. ``I wanted to be
a radiologist,'' Li said in his Mott Street studio recently. ``Look
at X-rays, right? They're amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   With two Paris-based partners, Ezra Petronio and Suzanne Koller,
who edit the avant-garde French fashion magazine Self Service, Li,
31, has become a sought-after image maker in the fashion world. He
and his partners have designed ads for Jean Paul Gaultier and
packaging for a Commes des Garcons fragrance, Odeur 71. The team
was recently asked to help reshape the image of the French fashion
house Cacharel, which has just hired the British team of Suzanne
Clements and Inacio Ribeiro as head designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their work is very graphic and clean,'' Annick Gorman,
creative director of Cacharel, said. ``We don't want to be as
romantic as we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Karl Lagerfeld asked Li to produce Chanel's next
in-store catalog, which Lagerfeld has always designed. ``I was,
like, `Karl Lagerfeld _ oh, no!''' Li said. ``But behind the fan,
there's amazingly little pretense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
