<HEADER>
A9019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-MASS-MUSEUM-ART-700     05-29 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-MASS-MUSEUM-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART MUSEUM SPARKS RENAISSANCE IN ONCE-FADING BERKSHIRES MILL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV:  Photos NYT 11 and 12  are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ Of all the dying mill towns in New England,
this was perhaps the deadest.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid 1980s, 70 percent of its storefronts were empty. The
Sprague Electric Co., the city's largest employer and long its
dominant, paternal presence, shut down in 1985, throwing 4,137
people out of work, affecting virtually every family in the town of
18,000. The unemployment rate, the highest in the state, ran from
25 to 30 percent. The local newspaper kept a front-page box score
on plant closings. A developer suggested that the whole town, lying
at the foot of steep mountains, be flooded to provide lakefront
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hit rock bottom,'' recalled John Barrett 3rd, the
city's mayor for the last 17 years. ``We were the butt of jokes.
The Adams Print Works closed, another 2,200 jobs. The hotel went
bankrupt, it was the third time. Everything was bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   But now North Adams is in renaissance, a nascent Soho in the
Berkshires, mainly thanks to a massive new arts complex, the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, known as Mass MOCA.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-thirds of the town's shops are occupied, including
a downtown-slick restaurant, 55 Main, with spotlights and arty
furnishings. Artists have moved into some of the long brick mills,
and one houses a shitake mushroom farm. This month, plans were
announced for a $5 million project to turn a deteriorating stretch
of Victorian houses into a bed-and breakfast to be run by the Red
Lion Inn of Stockbridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful to have an excuse to be doing something
in North Adams. I think it's a great place,'' said Nancy
Fitzpatrick, president of the Red Lion, a favorite with the crowd
that frequents Tanglewood, the nearby summer home of the Boston
Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely catalyst of this change, a gigantic museum in an
abandoned factory featuring trees growing upside down and
sculptures made out of tons of industrial debris, was nearly hooted
out of existence as a $35 million boondoggle before it could be
born.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to understand, everybody laughed at this,'' said
Barrett, who remembers and bristles at every slight his city has
ever suffered from out-of-town writers. Like ``gritty.''
</P>
<P>
   In the year since it opened last Memorial Day weekend, Mass MOCA
has been hailed as a wild success, drawing more than 105,000
visitors to its galleries, 25,000 more to performing arts events,
garnering architectural and preservation awards, and, in an
arrangement that is key to its financial security, renting
commercial space to eight tenants thus far, with 60,000 square feet
scheduled to be occupied by October.
</P>
<P>
   For Mass MOCA, it was a hard, fourteen-year struggle into being,
a cliffhanger of state funding cut-offs, small-scale fund raising,
deadlines missed and extended, plans juggled and changed.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit goes to an odd couple: the blue-collar mayor,
and Joseph C. Thompson, a soft-spoken art historian from Williams
College via Oklahoma, who has devoted most of his working life to
the project. Refusing to give up their dream, Thompson and his
development director, Jennifer Trainer, went for months without
pay, turned down lucrative job offers and, along the way, fell in
love, married and now have an infant son. And an infant museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Joe, this wouldn't have happened,'' said Michael
Conforte, director of the Clark Art Institute in neighboring
Williamstown.
</P>
<P>
   Mass MOCA also owes much to three post-modern phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the tendency of artists to construct works that,
although they are called minimalist, are huge, so huge that art
experts say 90 percent of them cannot be exhibited. Some are so big
and so minimalist they do not even exist; they are just
instructions as to how to build them in the unlikely event there
should be room.
</P>
<P>
   The second phenomenon, as manufacturing is abandoned, is the
existence of big empty industrial spaces. New York's Soho
neighborhood was a manufacturing center, after all, before artists
(and later investment bankers) inhabited its lofts.
</P>
<P>
   The third, which was not foreseen, is the growth of e-commerce
and dot-com companies so fast that this region is being called the
``Silicon Village.'' Web companies are among the museum's main
tenants, including, e.Ziba.com, which markets exotic crafts over
the Internet.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The museum owes much, too, to Williams College, five miles to
the east. Williams gave crucial initial backing to the museum. Some
of its wealthy and well-connected alumni, who bear a fond
allegiance to the surrounding purple hills, invested in the
project. And since the '60s the college's art history department
has spawned a network of museum directors and curators, including
the current director of the Guggenheim, Thomas Krens, who conceived
Mass MOCA after running a more traditional expansion of the
college's art museum.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, when Krens came looking for more display place, Mayor
Barrett showed him the abandoned Sprague plant. It is huge, a third
of the town itself, with 27 buildings scattered around 13 acres,
and it bears a certain resemblance to a walled medieval city,
albeit in rough industrial brick, with a clock tower, courtyards,
passageways and a branch of the Hoosic River flowing through the
middle. The plant was built in 1874 for a then-thriving textile
industry; when that went under in 1942, it was bought by Sprague.
In its heyday, making components for the Gemini moon mission, the
trigger for the atomic bomb, and electronic capacitors, the plant
had its own radio station, orchestra and sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Entranced, Krens spun out a vision for a museum, involving a
luxury hotel, the architect Frank Gehry and the collection of an
Italian industrialist, Count Giuseppe Panza di Biumo, said to have
a villa stuffed with modern masterpieces. Michael Dukakis, then the
governor, bought into the scheme as a desperate economic
development plan for this forlorn corner, which had been bypassed
by the Massachusetts Miracle boom. Krens estimated that the museum
could be opened by 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1988, Krens left for the Guggenheim, Gehry and the
Italian count along with him. Thompson, his protege, inherited the
project, but by the next year the Massachusetts Miracle went bust.
Dukakis was out by 1990, and the Republican administration of the
new governor, William Weld, swiftly cut off the $688,000 in
development money that Dukakis had slipped in the budget at the
last minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe sneered at the plan as ``endive economics'' and
the reviews in other newspapers were equally dismissive, calling it
a pipe dream and a hare-brained scheme. But the sometimes puckish
Governor Weld visited the old factory and, like others, fell under
the spell of its space, saying later that he liked its karma. After
a few Scotches and contemplation of a work by Mario Merz that
resembles a spiral of mismatched tables set up for a hotel buffet,
he gave the go-ahead for a gradual release of state funds. But
there were more crises in store, and at one point even the mayor
said ``I'm all MOCA'd out.''
</P>
<P>
   The project was finally saved when the Jacob's Pillow dance
center came in as a sponsor, as required by legislation. This also
changed the plan significantly, adding dance, movies and concerts
by Patti Smith and others to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   `'We'll get some arts into it, some theater. It's so simple,'''
Barrett said. ``But it was all by accident,'' he added. ``Looking
back at it now, it's just downright ridiculous, absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
