<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EXECUTIVE-SEARCH-730&AMP;     05-29 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXECUTIVE-SEARCH-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE BIG RETAILERS GO SHOPPING FOR CHIEF EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN and DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Within a few weeks this spring, J.C. Penney, Sears and Kmart all
announced that they were looking for new chief executives. These
separate recruiting drives have essentially created a referendum on
which of the ailing businesses is the sickest.
</P>
<P>
   Finding first-rate talent in the retail industry is notoriously
difficult, in part because the best and the brightest are not drawn
to a business that often makes executive prospects do time as stock
boys.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, each company expects its competitors' searches to
increase the difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a shallow pool and three fishermen instead of one,
the one who gets earliest and spots the jumping fish has an
advantage,'' said Gerard R. Roche, the chairman of Heidrick &AMP;
Struggles, which is conducting Sears' search for Arthur Martinez's
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The three-way race ``gives a sense of urgency,'' said Hal
Reiter, chief executive of Herbert Mines Associates, a New York
search firm that is widely believed to be conducting the hunt for
Floyd Hall's replacement at Kmart (neither Reiter nor Kmart will
confirm this). It forces companies to ``play the game I call `head
cheerleader,''' he said. ``Everyone wants to date the head
cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   But on whose arm do the head cheerleaders want to be escorted?
In many ways, the companies are in similar positions. All three are
retail chains with revenues of about $30 billion to $40 billion a
year, which are being squeezed hard between efficient low-price
discounters like Wal-Mart on the one hand and more
fashion-conscious specialty chains like The Limited and the Gap on
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is general agreement among headhunters and retail
stock analysts that Kmart presents the least desirable opportunity.
The discounter, which was fast losing ground to Wal-Mart, brought
in Floyd Hall, a former executive with Museum Co. and Grand Union
in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Hall has gotten the company on a steady train of earnings and
sales growth by introducing private brands such as Sesame Street
Kids and by expanding into Super Kmart formats, extra-large stores
that sell groceries as well as dry goods.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kmart trails its rivals in almost insurmountable ways.
Its real estate is older, its cash flow is weaker and its computer
systems are not as evolved or as integrated into all aspects of the
business. Its stock closed at $7.6875 on Friday, compared with a
52-week high of $17.50.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the Martha factor. Kmart brings in some $1 billion
in annual revenues from the Martha Stewart brand of
200-thread-count bed linens and coordinated pool furniture. The
formidable Stewart has made it clear that Hall has not been as
responsive as she would like and that she would want to work a
little more closely with a new executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``While all our suppliers are important,'' said Kmart
spokeswoman Shawn M. Kahle, ``they do not have a say in the
process. It is a decision to be made by our board of directors.''
Nevertheless, any candidate must know that Stewart and her
penetrating critiques will be constant companions for whoever takes
the job.
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to a particularly challenging package. ``There is
always some reluctance to take on a business perceived as having
problems,'' said Mines. ``The person will have to be smart as well
as courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   The company that might be most attractive to candidates is J.C.
Penney Co. Penney's stock closed Friday at $17.875, compared with a
52-week high of $52.94.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Sears and Kmart have already attempted turnarounds and
made the easiest fixes, like closing the most unproductive stores
and adding more high-margin branded merchandise, there are still
many basic changes to be made at Penney, changes that could lead to
quick payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No outsider has yet come into Penney to cull the low-hanging
fruit,'' said Kirk Palmer, who runs a recruiting firm that
specializes in retail jobs. ``There is much more upside potential.
Plenty of room to hit home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears is in the best shape of the three, as Martinez has closed
more than 100 underperforming stores and slashed 50,000 jobs. Its
shares closed at $35.375 on Friday, compared with a 52-week high of
$51.19.
</P>
<P>
   But Sears has a rough road ahead, especially as Home Depot has
now taken direct aim at its lucrative appliance business. And
Martinez's successor won't find a lot of obvious fat left to cut.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The last time three rivals had such an obvious face-off was last
summer, when Dell, Hewlett-Packard and Compaq were looking for
chief executives. Christian &AMP; Timbers, a search firm based in
Cleveland, came up with the flashiest find, at least in Carleton S.
Fiorina for Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey E. Christian, who ran the search, offered this advice:
``By definition, great leaders are few and far between. You've got
to find the up-and-comer, the person who will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   But even great leaders have their limits, something that Wall
Street is not likely to forget. Richard L. Church, a stock analyst
for Salomon Smith Barney who follows all three chains, said that a
superstar hire could make a difference in the companies' stock
valuations, but he added, ``The long-term issues these companies
face are formidable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
