u f BC-EUROPE-TRADE-NYT &LR;      05-29 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE RIFTS OVERSHADOW CLINTON'S MEETING WITH EU 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the Clinton administration's hope for a
quick resolution to a multibillion-dollar dispute with the European
Union over corporate tax policy, the problem appeared to be
escalating Monday on the eve of President Clinton's meeting with
European leaders in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued here before Clinton's departure, Stuart E.
Eizenstat, the deputy treasury secretary, said he was ``saddened''
and ``disappointed'' by a rebuff delivered Friday by Pascal Lamy,
the European Union's trade commissioner. Lamy said the
administration's proposed revision in the way some foreign sales by
United States-based corporations were taxed would still not bring
the United States into compliance with the World Trade
Organization's rules against subsidizing exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that our proposal is WTO compliant, in fact
and in law,'' Eizenstat said in his statement. He added: ``I am
saddened that the EU has not yet seized this opportunity to
negotiate a solution based on our proposal. We are disappointed
that a chance may be lost to accomplish this goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is over a tax break, worth billions of dollars, that
federal law currently allows exporters through the use of ``foreign
sales corporations,'' subsidiaries set up in places like the Virgin
Islands, Barbados and Guam. Overseas sales channeled through these
subsidiaries escape both sales tax and duties. In 1999, hundreds of
United States companies, including Boeing, Microsoft and General
Motors, saved about $4 billion by using these legally sanctioned
offshore tax havens.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an agreement between the United States and the European
Union not to challenge one another's tax policies, the EU
challenged the policy on the ground that amounted to an illegal
effort to subsidize exports by making them more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals panel of the WTO agreed in a ruling three months ago,
setting off the administration's effort come up with an acceptable
alternative. Eizenstat said Monday that even in the absence of a
negotiated solution, the administration would work with Congress to
enact new tax legislation that in its opinion obviated WTO
objections.
</P>
<P>
   The tax issue is only one of several trade-related disputes,
including skirmishes over bananas, genetically modified products
and aircraft noise, that have cast a shadow over economic relations
between the United States and members of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Under Eizenstat's plan to solve the overseas tax shelter issue,
the United States would repeal the foreign sales corporation plan
and replace it with special income tax rates for both export and
nonexport foreign sales by eligible manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The EU trade officials said, however, the changes meant United
States-based companies would still have to export to benefit _ the
very aspect of the original plan that was condemned by the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The United States proposal also contained two other elements
that the EU considered incompatible with global trade rules _ a 50
percent United States content requirement for products benefiting
from tax breaks and a transfer pricing plan that allocates a
proportion of profits to the foreign sales corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
