<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9037 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-MAINE-WILDERNE     05-29 1467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAINE-WILDERNESS-$ADV04-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAINE, TWO'S A CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4)  
(Editors: a 300-word information box appears at end of story.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The question is, just how deep a wilderness experience can you
get in a long weekend without ever leaving New England?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is: Pretty deep.
</P>
<P>
   The longer answer, reached after three days in the Moosehead
Lake region of central Maine, is:
</P>
<P>
   You can go on an eight-hour hike deep into the North Woods,
passing one roaring churn of a waterfall after another along the
way, and meet nary another soul until you limp back to the parking
lot and run into the nice state wardens who are getting worried
enough to start searching for you.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend the night in a canvas-walled yurt, miles of woods
away from the nearest people, wake up to a view of sky through the
roof and have the euphoria of outdoor sleeping without even lugging
a tent.
</P>
<P>
   You can fly over lake after lake after pristine lake to an
isolated cabin of your own, and know that when you canoe your
territorial waters, there may be moose or deer to challenge you but
no other humans.
</P>
<P>
   And you can fall asleep to such a magically crazy chorus of
clacks and cheeps and peeps and hoots that it seems as sacrilegious
as sleeping through a live symphony concert.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can bring home an old bearskin rug or a stuffed moose
head to go above your mantel if you are so barbarically inclined.
</P>
<P>
   All these were conclusions my gear-laden friend, Stephen Lines,
a photographer, and I reached on a Friday-to-Sunday trip in May. It
took us from Boston to Greenville _ the town known as the gateway
of the Moosehead Lake region _ to nearby Rockwood, to remote
Mooseleuk Lake and back again.
</P>
<P>
   (Please note: The trip was in May, not June. Only the
rhinoceros-skinned would want to visit inland Maine during
black-fly season. But locals say that most of the nasty biters are
usually gone by the end of June, sometimes earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   I'll get to the natural beauty next, but first, my main point
about wilderness: If hell is other people, then shouldn't heaven be
about getting away from them? Have you noticed how, when you
encounter fellow travelers out in a forest or on a mountain or on
an ocean where you want to feel as if you're exploring, you tend to
resent their existence a million times more than if they jostled
you on a city street?
</P>
<P>
   I mention that because our Moosehead trip provided such
satisfying alone-space. No other hikers on the trails _ though
there would likely be a few in summer _ no other cars on the road
to Greenville for nearly a two-hour late-night stretch, no other
kayakers out where we kayaked, no other canoeists where we canoed.
There was more than breathing room; there was the feeling of
dominion captured in the Dr. Seuss book about Yertle the Turtle,
who was king of all he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it was affordable dominion, with cabins advertised
for sale in the Northwoods Sporting Journal at $20,000 or so, your
own little yurt rental running just $55 a night, and your own
little cabin, replete with beds for eight, gaslights and canoes for
$100 a night. Some souvenirs did get pricey: the stuffed moose
heads available at Moosehead Traders on Main Street in Greenville
ran well over $1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Moosehead Lake is a noble old outdoor destination, and its
``camps'' _ Mainespeak for the rustic sites ranging from simple
cabins to fancy lodges _ have drawn hunters, fishermen and nature
lovers for well over a century. Henry David Thoreau described the
region in his ``Maine Woods,'' but anyone writing about the place
always quotes Thoreau, so let's just leave it at that. The lake
itself is about 35 miles long, the largest in Maine and the one of
largest lakes in one single state in New England. It is peppered
with islands, some uninhabited, some housing camps, and it can get
as wild as a sea, with great rollers and gales. (Oh, OK, Thoreau
described it as a ``suitably wild-looking sheet of water, sprinkled
with small, low islands.'')
</P>
<P>
   The region around it is splotched with dozens more lakes, with
Indian names like Nahmakanta and Munsungan and Matagamon. The
Appalachian Trail winds through it, on its way to its northern
terminus on nearby Mount Katahdin, but most of the land is
unprotected paper-company territory, riddled with logging roads,
much of it in various stages of regrowth.
</P>
<P>
   Moosehead is still a major center for the fish and game set, but
it appears to have been shifting a bit in recent years away from
the red-plaid folk and toward the Patagonia purple bunch. Mountain
biking has been taking off here, and kayaking, and ``moose
safaris'' in which the moose survives. Certainly, even for us
gunless, rodless visitors, there was far more to do than a weekend
could encompass.
</P>
<P>
   We flew out of Boston to Bangor on one of the frequent 70-minute
flights run by Business Express, a subsidiary of American Airlines,
grabbed a car in Bangor and reached Greenville in well under a
two-hour drive. There is an unexpected vista as you drive into
Greenville, when the gigantic lake and its islands suddenly spread
themselves serenely out before you.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to proceed immediately to Gulf Hagas, taking the
eight-hour loop hike through what is billed as the four-mile-long
Grand Canyon of Maine. (This lofty claim occasioned some derision
from us as the hike began, but as we proceeded, we shut up. The
walls may be nowhere near as high, and granite gray rather than
ruddy, but the rushing, crashing, warbling beauty at the bottom
demands reverence.)
</P>
<P>
   First, however, we made a lingering stop in Greenville at Auntie
M's, a home-cookin' restaurant whose moderately priced menu ranges
from an all-you-can-eat fish fry to nonalcoholic daiquiris to
nachos. The member of our party who routinely gets to eat as much
as he wants pronounced both the apple crisp and the fried dough
delicious; the member of our party who doesn't get to eat as much
as she wants, even when she hikes for miles and miles, had a
delectable frozen orange milkshake.
</P>
<P>
   From Greenville, the trailhead of the Gulf Hagas hike was
reachable only over miles upon miles of roads so marginally
passable that the locals in four-wheel-drive vehicles we met raised
eyebrows and exclaimed that we must be pretty fancy drivers to get
so far in a mere car. We had followed the directions on a Moosehead
hiking site, but discovered later that access by road was much
easier from Brownville.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, after about an hour of abusing the rental car and
exhorting each other to keep accelerating through the muddy ruts,
we reached a little park service cabin with a sign outside reading,
``One Old Grouch and One Nice Person Live Here.'' I speculated that
the old man who took our $7 per person was the grouch, but he
claimed it was his wife.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was eight hours of challenging, satisfying
footwork, from the initial precarious barefooting across a wide,
thigh-high river to the innumerable viewpoints the Rim Trail
afforded of large, small and middling waterfalls. The hike consists
of several loops, and so can be cut to just two or three hours for
the less ambitious. But we driven types were at it until well after
dark, thanks to my ever-prepared friend's zoom-lens headlamps.
</P>
<P>
   After a pleasant enough encounter _ well, with overtones of
teen-ager-over-curfew sheepishness _ with the wardens who were just
about to come looking for us, we drove to the Birches, which the
guidebooks tend to call the premier resort on Moosehead Lake. From
the Gulf Hagas area near Brownville, it was a good two-hour drive
to the resort in Rockwood, a tiny town north of Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   The Birches, which is known for cross-country skiing as well as
snowless fun, has an old-style central lodge that does the Maine
thing right down to the great stone fireplace, along with 15
hand-hewn cabins strung along the lakeside.
</P>
<P>
   Then, it has the yurts. So why did we stay in a yurt? Well, have
you ever stayed in a yurt? It seemed different. Also, in the quest
to avoid other humans, it doesn't seem to make much sense to fly
hundreds of miles from civilization and then stay in a little
cluster of cabins where you can hear your neighbors cough.
</P>
<P>
   So the yurt it was, and a pleasant little yurt it seemed. The
Birches has three of them on its 11,000 acres of wilderness
preserve, each sleeping four people. Ours had a bunk bed and futon,
plus pillows, linens, a wood stove and a gas stove, plenty of
chopped wood and a five-gallon container of water. Morning in the
clearing where it stands was so serene it brought to mind the
famous Yeats line from ``The Lake Isle of Innisfree'' about living
in a ``bee-loud glade.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Birches was not serving lunch that day, but its managers
were hospitably easy about letting us take a couple of kayaks from
their boathouse, which is super-well-equipped because the resort
also runs wilderness trips.
</P>
<P>
   Against their cautious warnings about possible rough winds, we
paddled the 45-minute route across the temporarily calm lake to
Mount Kineo, a peninsula that is considered Moosehead's most
striking landmark. Its looming granite cliff rises 763 feet from
the lake and, the guidebooks say, was holy to American Indians,
whose legends turned it into the petrified corpse of a giant,
sin-avenging moose. There was, sadly, no time to hike or rock-climb
to the top of Kineo, where the view is reputed to be one of the
best in New England.
</P>
<P>
   We had a plane to catch. Taking to the air is one of the
Moosehead musts, if simply for a 15-minute tourist ride, and with
good reason. Only then, and especially with a well-informed pilot
like ours, does the big picture emerge: the many rivers dammed into
lakes, the lakes expanded and contracted, the river flow reversals,
the timber-harvesting patterns, the rare swaths of untouched
forest, the moundlike mountains and great snowy Katahdin in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   We zipped back down to Greenville to the seaplane base of
Folsom's, one of three air companies on the lake, and took off for
Mooseleuk Lake, about a 45-minute flight away.
</P>
<P>
   Our cabin there was one of a dozen outpost cabins owned by Libby
Camps, whose motto is ``A wilderness tradition since 1890.'' There
are dozens of other camps to stay in around the Moosehead region,
but most seem to be in those annoying little clusters. Libby's
offered cabins isolated not only from the rest of the world but
also from one another. O billed marshy Mooseleuk Lake as one of the
best wildlife-watching areas in Maine. (Which it probably is, if
you get up early. I wouldn't know.)
</P>
<P>
   The one-room cabin was exquisitely homey, from the welcoming
wood stove and the front porch to the 20-seat picnic table and the
polished wooden floor. It slept eight, and seemed to be begging for
a 1950s family whose Mom would stay home and cook flapjacks while
Dad went out after deer. There was even a cookbook of camp recipes.
</P>
<P>
   But its most interesting document was a guestbook full of the
scribblings of a decade of visitors. They ranged from heartless
listings like ``25 grouse, (party of 6) eight moose, six deer, camp
was great!'' to ``Not many fish but bugs plentiful, p.s. saw MANY
moose'' and ``Seem to be a few bugs!?''
</P>
<P>
   My favorite was the entry from a newlywed couple who wrote,
``Here to get off the world for a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   That seemed about right. Who would think you could get this well
off of it, this nearby?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR MORE INFORMATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Moosehead 2000 brochure lists everything from camp rentals,
motels, B&AMP;B's and restaurants to activities like canoe expeditions
and white-water rafting. It is free from the Moosehead Lake Region
Chamber of Commerce, Post Office Box 581, Greenville, Me. 04441;
(207) 695-2702 or (207) 695-2026. By e-mail at moose (at)
moosehead &QL; 
.net or moose (at) mooseheadarea.com. On the Web at
www.mooseheadarea.com or www.mooseheadlake.org.
</P>
<P>
   Hikers can try www.maineguide.com/mooshead/mooshike.html.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom's, (207) 695-2821, offers flights from 15-minute jaunts
($20 a person, minimum of two) to more than $100 a person each way
to distant lakes. Other air services: Currier's Flying Service,
(207) 695-2778, and Jack's Air Service, (207) 695-3020.
</P>
<P>
   June, the peak of black-fly season, is a month to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD AND LODGING &QL;
</P>
