<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-COFFEE-NYT &LR;      05-29 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-COFFEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD COFFEE PRODUCERS' ALLIANCE AIMS TO DRIVE UP PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Borrowing a page from OPEC's strategy book,
the world's leading coffee producing nations have agreed to
withhold beans from the market to raise the price from seven-year
lows.
</P>
<P>
   But since the countries reached that agreement a little more
than a week ago, cracks in the unity of the Association of Coffee
Producing Countries and its allies have already appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The price of coffee, which surged in the days immediately after
the agreement, has since relinquished much of that gain. The price
of the benchmark robusta beans for July delivery, which rose nearly
$50 a ton, to $980, had slumped back by this past Friday to $932.
Prices had recently been trading as low as $890, the weakest since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in London on May 19, the 14-member association, working
with five nonmember coffee producers, said they were prepared to
withhold 20 percent of coffee crops from the market. The producers,
which make up about 85 percent of the world coffee production, said
they would come up with a more detailed plan by June 16 when they
return to London to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Commodities analysts have grown increasingly skeptical, however.
They point to the lack of specifics about how such a plan would
work in the face of an increasing world supply of coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is in a vacuum,'' said Arthur Stevenson, a
commodities analyst at Prudential Securities in New York. ``Only
once we find out how the governments involved intend to effectuate
those plans and how they intend to finance them will we know
whether this whole thing has any real legitimacy and credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about the success of such an agreement started appearing
even before the meeting began, when some of the major world coffee
producers, including leading robusta bean producer Indonesia, said
that they simply lacked the resources to pay coffee growers to hold
back supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that one of the challenges in such a plan is putting
in the financial or economic mechanisms to be able to fund those
within the coffee sectors that would be receiving money to retain
their crop,'' said Robert Nelson, president and chief executive
officer of the National Coffee Association of the United States.
``That is going to be of primary concern to the farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, one of the association's nonmember observers, along with
Vietnam, Honduras, Guatemala and Nicaragua, has said that it plans
to offset the lost exports by stimulating domestic consumption of
coffee. But stimulating consumption, which has been successful in
the United States, as evidenced by the appearance of retail coffee
houses like Starbucks and Caribou among others, is a long-term
process that is unlikely to absorb the excess supply of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which is the world's leading producer and exporter of
coffee beans, will be the pivotal player in the success of the plan
to withhold coffee beans. At the moment, Brazil seems committed to
ensuring the plan's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government wouldn't being doing all of this if it didn't
want the plan to work,'' said David Nahum Neto, the general
secretary of the Association of the Coffee Industry of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Vinicius Pratini de Moraes, the agriculture minister of
Brazil, said after the meeting in London that the country had
already allocated $167 million to finance the retention of about 3
million 60-kilogram bags of coffee from Brazil's total production
of 1999-2000 of about 27 million bags. The country has also opened
up new warehouse space and changed rules governing export
registration.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil's coffee industry, which is expected to expand
sharply in the coming years, is taking an increasingly larger share
of the world market. That is something that experts say the country
will be unlikely to jeopardize by restricting supply over the long
term.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, at least, withholding coffee is akin to the
strategy of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
curtail production of oil. OPEC has been successful over the past
few years in restricting how much each member produces, which has
tripled the price of oil to the highest level in nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But theory may be where the comparison to coffee ends. Coffee,
unlike oil, is not critical to the world economy, so producers have
less influence over the market. To make matters worse for coffee
exporting countries, history does not provide any examples of
successful agreements to keep beans off the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, these types of agreements have proven ineffective
and unenforceable,'' said Nelson, of the National Coffee
Association of the United States. ``Various countries did not
necessarily abide by the plan, and the association has no legal
framework to enforce the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the June meeting of the coffee producing nations, analysts
say that coffee prices will remain vulnerable to speculation about
an eventual agreement. Traders will also be keeping a close eye on
Brazil, where the onset of winter weather in June could affect
coffee crops. A damaging frost in the southern coffee belt of
Brazil could render the export ceiling agreement unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
