<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: BARAK BACKS PERES
</P>
<P>
   Shimon Peres, a former prime minister, was endorsed by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to succeed President Ezer Weizman, who is
resigning in the wake of a corruption scandal. In a secret ballot
in parliament scheduled for July 31, Peres, minister of regional
cooperation in Barak's cabinet, is expected to face Moshe Katzav of
the opposition Likud Party. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: LESBIANS' LANDMARK VICTORY
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli-American lesbian couple won the right here to
register as the two mothers of their 4-year-old son, Matan,
provoking outrage from the country's religious right. Nicole
Berner-Kadish adopted Matan, the biological son of her partner,
Ruti Berner-Kadish, in California. But the Israeli government
fought their petition to have Matan recognized as Nicole's child
until the High Court, in a groundbreaking ruling for gay couples,
said a child may indeed have two mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PLEA ON WALL RULING
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Ministry said it would ask the Supreme Court to
review a ruling last week that permitted women to hold services at
the Western Wall while wearing prayer shawls and chanting from the
Torah. Asserting that the ruling had changed long-standing
tradition at the site, which limits such services to men, the
ministry said the women could hold prayers at an adjacent location
that would not offend Orthodox worshipers.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: JOINT GOVERNMENT
</P>
<P>
   The government that divides authority between the province's
Catholic and Protestant political parties resumes Tuesday when
Britain formally restores powers suspended in February. The Irish
Republican Army has agreed to open its hidden arms caches to
international inspectors, and the Ulster Unionists, the largest
Protestant party, voted by a narrow margin Saturday to accept that
move as reason to return to government with Sinn Fein, the
political allies of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: NO PARDON FOR BERIA
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court rejected a request by relatives to
posthumously pardon Lavrenty Beria, the reviled chief of the NKVD
who sent millions of people to their deaths under Stalin's
dictatorship in the 1930s and '40s. The NKVD later became the KGB.
Beria was executed after Stalin's death in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: PUTIN POSITIVE ON CHECHNYA
</P>
<P>
   President Vladimir Putin suggested he could find common ground
with European critics of the war in Chechnya, saying lawlessness
there will be ``stamped out,'' even if Russian soldiers are the
lawbreakers. After a meeting with European Union officials, Putin
also pledged to cooperate with journalists and rights groups
monitoring the war.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: REBELS ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Chechen rebels have apparently begun a broad offense against
Russian troops, and, by their accounts, killing 40 soldiers in an
ambush in the Grozny suburb of Aldi. Russian forces stand accused
of conducting a killing and looting rampage in Aldi last February,
which residents contend left at least 80 civilians dead. Russian
officials denied rebel casualty reports, but said the situation in
Chechnya is ``tense and difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: FOX SPURNED
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, the leading opposition presidential candidate,
appeared to abandon attempts to enlist the campaign support of
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the other major opposition contender who is
running a distant third. Cardenas spurned a request to step down to
help defeat the governing party. Fox called Cardenas ``a traitor''
to Mexico's democratic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHOPS PROTEST TAXES
</P>
<P>
   As teams of soldiers and revenue officers fanned out in
marketplaces seeking to document how much businesses owe in taxes,
shopkeepers closed their doors in protest. Only 17,500 of the 2.5
million business owners in Pakistan collect sales tax, the
government says.
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: PICKERING TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of State Thomas R. Pickering arrived for talks
about battles with separatist rebels in the north in a visit
government officials have depicted as a way to raise morale in the
embattled army. Pickering last week reiterated American opposition
to a separate homeland for the ethnic Tamil minority.
</P>
