   WEST-FIRES (Washington) _ The wildfire that swept through Los
Alamos, N.M., earlier this month is setting off alarms across the
mountain West, where more and more Americans have chosen to live on
the forest's edge. Experts say those housing shifts have multiplied
the danger that other fires could kindle similar disasters. They
lie behind an urgent new congressional quest for millions of
dollars in emergency money to try to ease the risk. Across the
country, the damage caused by wildfire to homes and property
increased sixfold between the 1980s and 1990s, to a total of $3.2
billion over the last 10 years, federal officials say. In an
average year over the past decade, 1,200 homes have burned. By
