<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9052 &Cx1f; tth-z
r i BC-CANADA-FRONTIER-SPI &LR;      05-29 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-FRONTIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
B.C. RESIDENTS SEEK TO PROTECT THEIR PARADISE FROM PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TATLAYOKO LAKE, B.C. _ A quarter-century ago, Fritz and Sally
Mueller crossed the U.S.-Canada border to settle by a lake beneath
10,000-foot-high peaks of British Columbia's Coast Range.
</P>
<P>
   They also moved back in time.
</P>
<P>
   The Muellers put down roots in a land known as British
Columbia's last frontier, a land separated from Vancouver and the
hurry-up lifestyle of today's urban West by 125 miles of peaks, ice
fields, coastal fjords and mountain lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place reminds me of the West of my youth, of before my
youth,'' said Fritz Mueller, 57, who grew up in Coeur D'Alene,
Idaho. ``We are incredibly lucky to live here,'' said Mueller, a
craftsman who makes classical guitars.
</P>
<P>
   But time may be catching up with a place where pristine
wilderness and a hardy, resourceful human population still coexist.
</P>
<P>
   The clearcuts of industrial forestry, and the luxury resorts
that critics nickname ``industrial tourism,'' are approaching the
remote, sparsely populated hamlets of the Chilcotin Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Author Chris Harris gave the region its nickname with his 1998
book, ``Chilcotin: British Columbia's Last Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Paradoxically, rich in the natural resources of timber,
minerals and spectacular beauty, the area is in danger of being
destroyed by that which has made it flourish,'' Harris wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, in an age when sprawl, congestion and hurry-up
lifestyles have taken hold almost everywhere, the valley of
Tatlayoko Lake remains gorgeous, easygoing and more heavily
populated by animals than people.
</P>
<P>
   Deer and trumpeter swans winter in pastures at the head of the
lake. Wolves and cougars prey on the deer. Black bears are
numerous. Grizzly bear sightings are not infrequent.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 2,000 people live along the south and west edges of
the Chilcotin Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   They are by necessity a hearty few. The coldest winter
temperature ever recorded in Canada, outside the high arctic, was
taken at Alexis Creek on the Chilcotin Plateau. The thermometer
dipped to more than 60 degrees below zero in the winter of 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity and phone service arrived only in the past decade.
Students from kindergarten to grade 10 are bused from as far as 45
miles away to school in the hamlet of Tatla Lake. Fifty-six
students are enrolled this year. Older 11th and 12th graders must
go live 160 miles away in Williams Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Hogs, horses and chickens still have the run of yards at the
head of Tatlayoko Lake. Cattle wander along the road and a
primitive, grassy airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   Indians were the first human inhabitants of the Chilcotin
Plateau. White pioneers began arriving early this century, led by
K.B. Moore from Massachusetts, whose antecedents donated land that
became the Boston Common.
</P>
<P>
   The adventurous still come. Many of the latest pioneers are from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of our children, English is a second language,''
said Dale Kerr, who teaches kindergarten and grades 1, 2 and 3 in a
single room at the Tatla Lake school. ``They're predominantly
German. This area draws Germans like nobody's business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Germans are drawn by open spaces, the affordability of land,
and the freedom to do what they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Germany, you do only one job,'' said Matthias Hoerolt, who
came here with his wife, Sylvia, to start a guest ranch. ``Here, I
do everything _ cooking, guiding, ranching. ... It's easier to live
in Canada, not so many rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The rules may be few, but the visions of the future of this land
are many.
</P>
<P>
   The provincial government has protected much of it by creating
several large provincial parks, sparing the land from development.
</P>
<P>
   But the B.C. Forest Service takes the view that everything not
in a park is fair game for logging. It has come up with preliminary
plans that envision logging deep into valleys of the Coast Range.
</P>
<P>
   The plans don't sit well with Dennis Redford, a former
California aircraft worker who runs Driftwood Resort, a collection
of weathered cabins on both sides of an old, little-used road that
runs down the east shore of Tatlayoko Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Redford left California for three reasons: ``Too expensive, too
many people, not enough space.''
</P>
<P>
   If cutting comes, the sleepy road that passes through Driftwood
Resort would be a thoroughfare for logging trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would forever change the way we live. We are now so out of
the way on a dead-end road, nobody comes here,'' Redford said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the locals say they don't want to halt logging, only to
limit cutting to sustainable levels and keep it away from prime
fishing, wildlife and view areas.
</P>
<P>
   They recently scored their first success at the west end of the
Chilcotin Plateau.
</P>
<P>
   A citizen roundtable in the village of Anahim Lake managed to
forge an agreement that satisfied fishing resort owners as well as
operators of the local mill.
</P>
<P>
   The accord created a 210,000-acre no-logging zone in an area
called The Alplands, which has the highest concentration of
subalpine lakes in British Columbia. Lodges do a flourishing
business flying fly fishermen into the high lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Another local group, the Tatla Resource Association, is working
to put together a land use plan that will shield the region's way
of life and the beauty of the lake-dotted landscape at the base of
the Coast Range.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the association also say they are not on an
environmental crusade, but they do not want to see lakeside forests
sacrificed to supply mills a five-hour drive away.
</P>
<P>
   They also want to preserve the rhythms and feel of living on a
frontier in the face of another kind of change _ the climbers,
rafters, sailboarders and daredevil skiers who are discovering
remote valleys of the Coast Range, sometimes bringing the 21st
century with them.
</P>
<P>
   Valley matriarch Gerry Bracewell, 77, who has lived here nearly
50 years, says some clients of her family's wilderness adventure
business just refuse to let go of the information age. They carry
cellular phones, look for fax machines and get angry that Vancouver
newspapers lying around local cafes are more than a week old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is in such a hurry, and some people are so strung
out with business. ... Heck, you need a week to unwind from city
living,'' Bracewell said. She guides horse trips deep into the
Coast Range despite having recently recovered from a broken hip.
</P>
<P>
   Bracewell laughs at a new generation of outdoor enthusiasts that
expects luxury when the day's exertions are done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need a hot tub that people jump into naked,'' she
said. ``We take people on a raft out into Tatlayoko Lake where they
can swim with the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of attitude that has been around here for a long
time, and still holds sway.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to his parents, Fritz Mueller Jr., a wildlife
biologist, reflected that for now, the frontier life remains
remarkably intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to think of it, I'm amazed at how little this
place has changed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
