<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS ROLLS TO EASY VICTORY IN MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Winning a golf tournament is not supposed to look
as easy as Tiger Woods made it look Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was like a car on cruise control, and he was never forced
to hit the gas pedal. There was a fleeting moment on the back nine
when Ernie Els closed within four strokes, but Woods birdied the
next hole and Els bogeyed to fall six strokes behind again.
</P>
<P>
   Forget drama. Woods prefers dominance. Starting the day with a
six-stroke lead at the Memorial Tournament, Woods (19 under par)
eased to a five-stroke victory over Ernie Els and Justin Leonard in
an event that ended one day late because of rain on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But for Woods, who won $558,000, the wait was worth it.
Finishing at 269 (71-63-65-70), Woods bogeyed the final hole to
fall one stroke short of the tournament record set by Tom Lehman in
1994. But that was hardly a concern for Woods, who captured his
19th PGA Tour victory at age 24, tying Ben Crenshaw for the most
victories among active full-time tour players. Woods also became
the first player to win the Memorial in back-to-back years, as he
successfully defended a tournament for the first time in his
professional career.
</P>
<P>
   Think Woods is ready for next month's U.S. Open at Pebble Beach?
Consider this. He is the only tour player with four victories this
season. He leads the money list with more than $4.1 million. And in
his last 20 starts on tour, he has 11 victories and 18 top-ten
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Woods is looking forward to Pebble Beach. His game is
more consistent than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I've been working toward,'' Woods said.
``That's what you're supposed to do, continue to try and get
better. It doesn't mean you're going to get better, but I'm trying
to get better. I'm trying to give myself chances in every
tournament I play.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was presented the winner's trophy by Jack Nicklaus, the
tournament host, who won 18 professional major championships, the
record Woods covets most. After watching Woods overwhelm the
Muirfield Village Golf Club course that Nicklaus designed, while
averaging 298.9 yards in driving distance, Nicklaus was asked to
compare his game in his prime to Woods'.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was hitting the ball the way I wanted to, I always felt
like everybody else was going to play for second,'' said Nicklaus,
who at age 60 tied for 65th place after a final-round 73. ``I think
he feels the same way. Nobody in golf today can stand there with a
driver and say, `I'm going to hit the ball 295 yards and shape it
the way I want to shape it and put it on that side of the fairway.'
He is the only guy that can do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he manages his game well. I managed my game well. I
think he can play right-to-left, or left-to-right. He probably
plays better right-to-left than I did. He's got a far better short
game than I ever had. His short game is phenomenal. He's got every
shot around the green. He's a terrific putter, but I think I was a
good putter, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods ended any chance for suspense early, with birdies on Nos.
3, 6 and 8 to reach 20 under par. Terrific approach shots set up
each birdie. At No. 3, he hit a pitching wedge shot to six feet
from the hole. At No. 6, he hit a 9-iron to four feet. At No. 8, he
hit a 9-iron to six feet.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, his march toward victory was almost a
formality. Els had the best round of the day, a 65, while Leonard
was solid with a final-round 68. But Els and Leonard were playing
for second place. And when asked what he would do if Woods got even
better, Els had to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 24, I guess he's got to get better,'' Els said. ``In his
own mind, he can get better. In everybody else's mind, he's
probably as good as we want to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Leonard's first top 10 finish this year, and he hoped it
signaled the end to his yearlong slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself that no matter how I played today, I was going
to take some positives from this week,'' Leonard said. ``This is
the first time I even came close to putting four rounds together.
It was much needed in my case.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods does not seem to need much of anything, and no matter how
much he wins, the feeling never gets old. ``It's not easy,
especially how deep the fields are now,'' he said. ``I appreciate
every victory I get.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
