<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OAKLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS WIN, 4-1, DESPITE BEING VICTIMIZED BY UNASSISTED TRIPLE
PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen hours later, it was no longer Roger against
Pedro in front of a spellbound crowd on a memorable night at Yankee
Stadium. Instead, it was Andy against Omar on a more subdued
afternoon. There were different names and a drastically inferior
ring to Monday's two starting pitchers, but Andy Pettitte's
performance was as superb as what Roger Clemens and Pedro Martinez
had done on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte was not as overpowering as Roger and Pedro, and there
was almost no need for a K corner because he struck out only three
batters, but he allowed just two hits in calmly guiding the Yankees
to a 4-1 victory over the Oakland Athletics. Jason Giambi doubled
in the first inning, and Pettitte did not permit another hit until
Randy Velarde, who turned the 10th unassisted triple play in major
league history Monday, homered in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   While Pettitte opposed Omar Olivares, not Pedro or the Red Sox,
he was as dominant in efficient fashion. Pettitte used a sinking
fastball, a cut fastball and precise control to induce 17
groundouts and erase any possibility that the Yankees would
experience a hangover on the day after Boston stymied them and on
the day they received their 1999 World Series rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed that game,'' Tino Martinez said. ``Last night was a
draining game for us. It was a tough game to lose. To come back
today at 1 p.m., we wanted to find a way to win this game. Andy
picked us up big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte was like a frustrating pitching machine to a team that
leads the American League in runs scored. Put in a dollar, watch
Pettitte uncork sinking fastballs and the A's slap grounders. He
uncorked 110 pitches in the complete game and estimated that 65 of
them were sinkers. There were no reasons for Pettitte, who clutched
his three-carat diamond World Series ring after winning his second
straight start, to tinker with what has generally worked for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special day, us getting the rings,'' Pettitte said.
``It reminded us that we are the world champs. I definitely wanted
to go out there and pitch like I was a pitcher for the world
champs.''
</P>
<P>
   The game took 2 hours 30 minutes, and the Yankees appreciated
how quickly Pettitte worked in twirling the first two-hitter of his
career. His speedy pace allowed some of the Yankees to dress,
shower and breeze to Madison Square Garden for the Knicks-Pacers
game.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte also kept the infielders alert, especially the
embattled Chuck Knoblauch, who might have had his best defensive
game as a Yankee with nine assists from second base and a sweet
basket catch of a pop-up along the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   Six days ago, Knoblauch made a terrible throw that bounced about
30 feet from first base against the Chicago White Sox. Afterward,
he hinted at retirement while discussing the stress from the
throwing woes that have hampered him since the 1998 season. But
eight of Knoblauch's nine throws to first against the A's were
solid, and he ranged behind second to field a carom off Pettitte's
glove and complete a snazzy play in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' Knoblauch said. ``The
hardest thing for me to do sometime is give myself credit. Maybe
today I have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's two-out single in the third was the first hit
against Olivares, and he scored when Derek Jeter smashed a double
into the left-field corner. Bernie Williams tripled to knock in the
second run in the sixth, the third run scored that inning on
Velarde's error and Williams added a homer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde followed his error by spearing Shane Spencer's liner
with two runners moving for the 10th unassisted triple play in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this day was mostly about Pettitte. Giambi called it
death to hit grounders at the Stadium because the grass is thick,
so Pettitte used the perfect way to kill the A's. Pettitte was not
Roger or Pedro, there were 41,284 fans at the game instead of the
sellout crowd Sunday night and the opponents were not the hated Red
Sox. But Pettitte, in his own way, dominated like the pitchers who
were on the same mound several hours before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to have a good game,'' Pettitte said. ``Them guys are
in a class of their own. I wanted to go out and get groundballs and
throw strikes. Those are the keys for me. I can't remember feeling
better than I did today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
