<SLUG> BC-FOLATE-WOMEN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLATE MAY HELP REDUCE HEART DISEASE FACTORS FOR OLDER WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DORIS CHANDLER   
 The Gainesville Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The benefits of folate for women of
childbearing age have been known for some time, but a new
University of Florida study is the first to document that this
vitamin reduces a risk factor in heart disease for postmenopausal
women ages 63 to 85.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research has shown that folate _ a B vitamin naturally
occurring in food _ and its synthetic version, folic acid, can help
prevent certain birth defects of the brain and spinal cord called
neural-tube defects. For women of childbearing age, the National
Institute of Medicine recommends daily consumption of 400
micrograms of folic acid, plus folate from a varied diet.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Florida study examined the effect of different
levels of folate on blood levels of homocysteine, an amino acid
that requires folate in order to metabolize. Previous studies of
homocysteine have suggested it is a risk factor for heart disease,
which is the No. 1 killer of men and postmenopausal women.
</P>
<P>
   The study was directed by Lynn Bailey, professor of human
nutrition, and Gail Kauwell, an associate professor of human
nutrition, both at the Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   In the 14-week study, 33 postmenopausal women received low
levels of folate _ 120 micrograms for seven weeks. In the last
seven weeks, women in the study consumed different levels of
folate, some received 200 micrograms, others 400 micrograms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those receiving low levels of folate, homocysteine levels
increased,'' Bailey said. ``The ones on 400 micrograms had a
positive response. Blood folate levels increased, and blood levels
of homocysteine, an amino acid considered a risk factor in heart
disease, remained low.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this study, there was little information available on
folate's effects for older women, Kauwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bailey and Kauwell emphasized that study results indicate
that higher levels of folate may reduce only one of the risk
factors of heart disease, not the incidence of heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can say is that homocysteine is a risk factor in heart
disease, and that adequate intake of folate can reduce homocysteine
concentration,'' Kauwell said. ``We look at it as a way to help
reduce the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Results of the study are to be published in the June issue of
the Journal of Nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Study participants received folate by eating a balanced diet,
with orange juice playing a prominent role. One 8-ounce glass
contains 75 micrograms of folate, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Other major sources of folate are dark green, leafy vegetables;
other fruits, such as strawberries; kidney beans and peas; and
liver, although liver is high in cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
