<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-IRELAND-TOBACCO-650&AMP;A     05-29 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-TOBACCO-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH GOVERNMENT MOVES TOWARD TOBACCO LITIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The spelling ``Micheal'' in the 7th-last graf is correct.) 
 By BRIAN LAVERY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ With bipartisan political support and a
growing national awareness of public health issues, the Irish
government is taking aggressive steps that could result in Ireland
being the first European country to seek damages from tobacco
companies for the cost of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Irish lawyers and members of Parliament traveled to
New Orleans to seek advice from veterans of the landmark U.S.
tobacco settlements, including Hubert H. Humphrey III, the former
attorney general for Minnesota, and Ron Motley, a leading
plaintiff's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   A parliamentary health committee will soon begin investigating
whether three Irish tobacco companies knew about research by their
U.S. parent companies into the dangers of smoking and the addictive
nature of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in November, the cross-party committee
recommended that the Irish government, the eight regional health
boards, the partially state-owned health insurance company, and the
country's private hospitals all should sue the tobacco companies
for damages.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is currently hearing legal advice before
requesting so-called powers of compellability _ the right to
subpoena documents and witnesses. But all the nation's political
parties have already approved such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Batt O'Keeffe, the chairman of the committee, said he wants to
make sure that tobacco companies will not be able to question the
legality of the investigation's findings, based on background
issues like the membership of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the Irish Tobacco Manufacturers' Advisory
Committee said that the industry had seen the committee's report
but would have no comment until a specific government proposal is
made by the Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   While the government's case might not go to trial for several
years, 300 civil suits by individuals claiming personal injury
damages have already been filed and will reach the courts within a
year, plaintiff's lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   Peter McDonnell, a lawyer representing 204 personal injury
claims against Irish tobacco companies, said that Ireland's small
size and relatively simple legal system offer a tremendous
advantage in litigation. Cases begun in Ireland's High Court can be
appealed only once, to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And since tobacco companies here act principally as
distributors, the industry has no local lobbying power to create
opposition within the government, he argued. ``It's like pushing an
open door,'' McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   One of McDonnell's clients, Anne Moloney, had a lung removed in
1996, along with part of her heart lining, after being diagnosed
with lung cancer, she said. Moloney, now 47, started smoking at 13,
she said, claiming that she was unaware of any health risks until
1973. (Warnings on cigarette packages appeared in Ireland in 1978,
10 years after they appeared in the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor advised me to stop smoking, because I would have a
small baby,'' she said. ``It never dawned on me that it would cause
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate of smoking is still highest among teen-age girls, at 40
percent, according to the nonprofit group Action on Smoking and
Health. The smoking population dropped to a historic low of 28
percent six years ago, but has since risen to 32 percent. The
government attributes 6,500 deaths per year to smoking-related
causes, in a country of 4 million people.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe estimates that the Irish government spends between $570
million and $1.15 billion per year on health care for
tobacco-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell argues that the potential damages are much higher:
Based on the damages awarded to Minnesota, he says that Ireland is
eligible for a $23 billion settlement. Only two years ago, Brian
Cowen, then Ireland's health minister, said that the cost to the
government of treating tobacco-related illnesses was just $115
million Irish pounds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Micheal Martin, the current health minister who took office in
January, has helped set the aggressive tone with his calls for
Ireland to become ``a tobacco-free society.'' Recently he proposed
legislation to raise the legal smoking age from 16 to 18 and
sharply restrict smoking in public.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to push the bill through Parliament on a fast track to
approval before this summer. In advance of a deadline called for by
the European Union, he has promised to implement a complete ban on
tobacco advertising in July.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's tobacco industry points out that a ban on print
advertising makes little sense, because British newspapers with
cigarette ads command significant space on newsstands here. ``It's
difficult to see the wisdom in Ireland moving ahead of the UK,''
the spokesperson said. ``The industry feels that the current packet
of regulation, along with the EU directive, is one of the strictest
in the world, and is very adequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Most smokers, of course, resent restrictions on their habit. But
the government's initiatives have not raised much protest. ``I
think Irish people are becoming more aware of their health, and
more assertive of their health rights,'' said Hugh Ward, a lawyer
who is representing 50 bartenders in lawsuits against their
employers. The bartenders claim that extended exposure to
secondhand smoke constitutes dangerous working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's pub culture is where widespread acceptance of smoking
is more difficult to shake. For more than half of Ireland's
pub-goers, a pint glass in one hand is accompanied by a cigarette
in the other. Pubs that have attempted to curtail smoking quickly
reversed the policy after losing business, according to Dick Dunne,
president of the Vintners' Federation of Ireland, the national pub
owners trade association.
</P>
<P>
   ``A blanket ban on smoking would be detrimental to our
business,'' said Dunne, a third-generation pub owner. Such a ban
would be impossible to enforce at small pubs around the country, he
said. Instead, the federation wants the tobacco industry to
subsidize modern ventilation systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because something was taboo overnight doesn't mean we
were irresponsible,'' he said in defense of the pub owners. ``A lot
of pubs had machines for years, but they didn't work properly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
