<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-AIR-POLLUTION-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MORE PARKS, SMOG IS OBSCURING THE VIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 4) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As another smog season begins, it's likely that
some of the country's most popular national parks, especially in
the east, will once again be troubled by haze and smog rivaling the
levels in crowded metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   A booming economy has been increasing production from factories
and power plants whose pollution blows on the wind to distant peaks
in national parks like Acadia in Maine, Shenandoah in Virginia and
Great Smoky Mountains in North Carolina and Tennessee. A hiker
following the length of the Appalachian Trail this summer,
therefore, is likely to encounter some pretty smoggy days.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, monitors in Great Smoky Mountains Park, near the
southern end of the Appalachian Trail, recorded what the park's air
quality officials called extraordinarily early violations of
federal smog standards. Last autumn, the monitors documented heavy
smog unusually late in the year. Usually, the smog season is
concentrated in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Great Smoky recorded 52 days of smog exceeding
federal health standards. Acadia recorded worse smog than Boston
and Philadelphia. Visibility from Shenandoah's heights has been
reduced by a quarter in the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   In a satirical essay in the April issue of Backpacker magazine,
Thom Hogan, the editor, writes of traveling the length of the
Appalachian Trail 50 years in the future _ starting in January in
Georgia to beat the heat and smog on a trip that nowadays typically
begins in March. ``Fortunately, I'm carrying my battery-powered
rebreather, a technology derived from scuba equipment and paid for
and refined by the final tobacco-industry settlements with the
federal government in 2003,'' he fantasizes.
</P>
<P>
   Park advocates say today's reality is grim enough. ``It's a
tragedy when the air is dirtier in the places we escape the
pollution of the city,'' said Jonathan Birdsong, southeastern
regional representative for the Izaac Walton League, a conservation
group of hunters and other outdors enthusiasts, which recently
issued a study of the trends.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency reported last month that in
recent years, the smog trend in some national parks has been
running counter to the overall national picture, which has steadily
improved. Smog concentrations increased at 17 of 24 National Park
Service monitoring sites from 1992 to 1998, the most recent
comprehensive data that is available, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The data measures ground-level concentrations of ozone, a
chemical that forms smog. Ozone damages living cells, and therefore
can harm not only growing plants but also people's lungs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1998 levels were particularly high at two parks in the
eastern United States, Shenandoah and the Great Smoky Mountains,''
the report said. ``Ozone levels at these sites were the highest in
a decade and 30 to 40 percent higher than the national ozone
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Haze _ not the natural bluish vapors that gave the mountains
their name, but the suspended smoky particles that are chemically
different from smog _ is also worsening, the report said. ``Eastern
visibility impairment on the haziest days has worsened from 1997 to
1998, and the Great Smoky Mountains National Park experienced its
worst visibility in more than a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   More than the view is affected, park advocates say. In a study
several years ago by the Appalachian Mountain Club, Brigham and
Women's Hospital in Boston and the Harvard School of Public Health,
hikers climbing to the summit of Mount Washington in New Hampshire
suffered from less efficient breathing as ozone levels rose. The
people who had the worst problems were those with a history of
asthma or other lung problems, but even healthy climbers could be
afdfected, the study found.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in the Great Smoky Mountains park have documented
damage to 30 plant species, including tall milkweed, black cherry
and sassafras.
</P>
<P>
   There are many sources of air pollution in parks. Some are
affected even in wintertime by heavy snowmobile use; Yellowstone
National Park is phasing out snowmobiles, and other parks are
expected to crack down on their use. Cars, of course, crowd many
parks in summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the most persistent problems are caused by industrial
pollution from relatively distant sources, especially coal-fired
power plants, according to pollution experts.
</P>
<P>
   In Great Smoky, for example, air quality scientists have found
strong correlations between emissions from the Tennessee Valley
Authority's power plants and pollution in the park. The National
Oceanographic and Atmospheric Agency, which has been flying
research planes in the area, said pollution patterns are complex
and implicated Ohio Valley plants as well.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has adopted policies that should result in significant
reductions in smog in eastern states, including emissions from the
TVA, in the next several years. The power authority already has
taken steps to reduce the generation of smog-creating chemicals,
especially in the summer. But at the same time, the authority,
which is the largest federal utility in the nation, has been
challenging some of the environmental agency's rules in court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
