<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDIDATES STEER CLEAR OF POLITICS IN HONORING THE COUNTRY'S WAR
DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa.)   By JAMES DAO with FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, Pa. _ Vice President Al Gore commemorated the
nation's war dead Monday by recounting his own military experiences
in Vietnam and the complex web of emotions, from patriotism to
family devotion to guilt, that caused him to enlist three decades
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before several hundred people gathered for a
Memorial Day ceremony here, Gore acknowledged that his five months
in Vietnam as an Army reporter were not the most grueling or
dangerous, saying, ``I know that my service doesn't in any way
match that of the heroes we honor on this day.''
</P>
<P>
   But his time in uniform and near the battlefield had taught him
much about sacrifice, honor and loyalty among soldiers, Gore said
in a speech largely devoid of policy, politics and mention of his
Republican rival for the presidency, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those veterans who are here, whether you served in Vietnam or
Korea, the Persian Gulf or World War II or another conflict, you
have that bond with those you served with,'' he said in this small
town along the Monongahela River, just south of Pittsburgh. ``You
felt the same feelings. You saw the same things. You made the same
sacrifices.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, Bush, who was a pilot in the Texas Air National Guard,
delivered brief remarks that were less personal than Gore's, but
that also steered clear of politics and the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we owe the brave?'' he asked several hundred veterans,
local residents and Army men and women outside the community center
in Killeen, where the Army's Fort Hood is located. ``It is our
first duty to honor what they have done, and that should not be
hard, because it is one of the greatest stories of human history.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, Monday's deeply personal speech fits into a broader
effort by his campaign to reintroduce him to voters through
television commercials, speeches and other events that highlight
his biography. Later this week, he is scheduled to promote cancer
programs by discussing the death of his sister, Nancy, from lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled in a valley of rolling hills and shuttered steel mills,
Elizabeth provided an ideal locale for Gore's speech. The region
not only has large numbers of war veterans, but also union members
and conservative Democrats whose support is seen as vital to Gore's
chances of winning Pennsylvania's 23 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore enlisted in the Army two months after graduating from
Harvard in 1969, even though he opposed the war in Vietnam. Friends
have said he signed up in part to protect his father, Sen. Albert
Gore of Tennessee, from criticism by Republican supporters of the
war. The elder Gore, a vocal opponent of America's involvement in
Vietnam, was running for re-election at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday Gore offered another reason for enlisting, suggesting
that he could not have faced the guilt of knowing that other young
men from his hometown might have gone to their deaths in his place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to Vietnam, I had many misgivings,'' he said.
``But my draft board was in Carthage, Tennessee, and that made a
big difference because, you know, if you found some way not to go,
you would know the person who went in your place. That person would
have a place and a name and a family and a face.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said little about his time in Vietnam. But he described
feeling disillusioned upon returning to a nation that was
ambivalent, and sometimes hostile, toward its Vietnam veterans.
That disillusionment, he claimed, kept him from running for public
office for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember that parade that was waiting for us?'' he said
about his homecoming. ``One of the reasons Vietnam veterans always
say welcome home to one another was, of course, there wasn't a
parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has spent much of this month on the campaign trail
trying to bolster his foreign-policy credentials with proposals
related to national defense and remarks on international affairs,
made only the slightest detour in that direction Monday, calling
anew for the development of a national missile defense. Both Gore
and Defense Secretary William Cohen have recently questioned the
prudence of pushing too aggressively for such a system.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated his own position, placing in the context of a
general plea for strengthening the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who man the lighthouse of freedom ask little of our
nation in return,'' Bush said. ``But what they ask, our nation must
provide: a military of high morale, a military that's well paid and
well housed, a military well prepared and well equipped, a military
respected by those in authority, a military that's got a coherent
vision of America's duties _ a clear military mission in a time of
crisis _ and a modern defense system aimed to protect our homeland
and to protect our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Gore said his time living in a trailer park with his
wife, Tipper, during basic training had taught him about the need
to improve the pay, benefits and housing of active-duty military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   And both men said that while it was important to pay tribute to
war service with monuments and medals, it was even more important
to share the details of those sacrifices with young Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must pass stories of American courage and character to the
next generation, to capture their imaginations, to raise a monument
in their hearts,'' Bush said. ``This is the way our democracy
renews its promise: by celebrating American heroes and American
values without hesitation and without apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting President John F. Kennedy, Gore said: ``Democracy is a
call to untiring effort, to continual sacrifice, and to the
willingness, if necessary, to die in its defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
