<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN PERU, THE ISSUE IS STABILITY VS. DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSs   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ The students have been back in the streets,
throwing Molotov cocktails at the presidential palace, and the
police have been firing back, with tear gas and water cannon. A
journalist was tortured last week after he said he had evidence
that the intelligence chief was conspiring with election officials.
The army called for order.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface it appeared so familiar, as President Alberto
Fujimori rode to a third term on Sunday in an election so full of
dirty tricks that Alejandro Toledo, the opposition candidate,
withdrew from the race, and all the international election monitors
backed off, too, before a single vote was cast.
</P>
<P>
   But this battle actually has a different script. Issues that
were important in Peru before the end of Communism are not the
issues any longer, and the same is true around the region.
</P>
<P>
   The old issues of land, class conflict and resistance to
imperialism that were foremost during the waves of guerrilla
insurrections, university revolts and military coups in Peru from
the 1960s through the early 1990s are no longer setting the sparks.
</P>
<P>
   The new dominant issue facing Peruvians is about whether the
nation is best served by politicians who put democracy first, or
those who put stability first. It is a question that was not
resolved on Sunday, because the election was effectively not
contested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, the issue was survival,'' said Francisco Diez Canseco,
a former congressman and human rights activist. ``Now it's about
whether the virtues of authoritarianism are to be replaced by the
growing desire of people for broader political participation.''
</P>
<P>
   The question crosses class and ideological boundaries. It raises
uncomfortable choices for a country whose few experiments in
democracy have brought corruption, inefficiency, instability and
economic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. policymakers also find themselves in a quandary,
wanting to encourage free elections but also wanting to support a
government that has been a strong ally against terrorism and drug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of characters and alliances would have seemed
impossible in the days before Communism's collapse, when the
political currents flowing across Latin America originated in
Washington, Moscow and Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Take Toledo, whose resume and platform would have been
unthinkable just a few years ago for someone proposing to annul an
election and overthrow a government.
</P>
<P>
   Though he comes from a poor family, Toledo is a former World
Bank employee and business school professor, has a doctorate from
Stanford, and is not too proud to admit that he likes to eat at
McDonald's. He says his first project, if he ever made it to the
presidential palace, would be to create an independent, uncorrupt
judiciary. His core constituency is the urban middle class.
</P>
<P>
   For Toledo, the choice for Peru now is between ``democracy and
dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, moderates like him usually found themselves facing
a Hobson's choice between the right and the left, and they usually
lost out in coalitions with either Marxist guerrillas or right-wing
generals. Today in Peru, the moderates are leading the revolution
and the leftists are following.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is dignity, it makes us creative and productive,''
Toledo told a throng of more than 60,000 dominated by university
students who gathered in Lima on Sunday night. ``When there is
dictatorship, there is no investment.'' Standing beside Toledo _ in
a gesture a previous generation of students would have thought
impossible to stomach _ was Francisco Morales Bermudez, a retired
general and the nation's last military president, who ushered in
civilian rule in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Standing between this rather unrevolutionary lot and power is
Fujimori. The son of Japanese immigrants, Fujimori remains in many
ways the ultimate outsider even after his 10 years in power. He
continues to be the target of nasty racial jokes by the Lima
elites, and he is proud that his core constituency entails the
urban shantytown dwellers and Indian villagers in regions most
severely attacked by Maoist terrorists in the 1980s and early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has a long list of accomplishments, ranging from the
defeat of two terrorist groups and hyperinflation to making peace
with Ecuador after more than a century of border strife. He has
probably built more schools, roads and health clinics to serve the
poor than every other Peruvian president combined.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Fujimori, according to his critics, is he fires
judges when they disagree with him, he uses his intelligence agency
to harass his opponents, he finds ways to put his cronies in charge
of television stations, and he is willing to convict suspected
terrorists without giving their lawyers the benefit of
cross-examination. In short, he does not give democratic rules a
very high priority.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Fujimori said his muscular tactics
may not be pretty but they are necessary. ``In emergency
situations,'' he said, ``I had to take emergency measures that may
have appeared anti-democratic.'' He promised that once he is
inaugurated on July 28, ``there will be certain corrections.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Fujimori temporarily disbanded the Congress and Supreme
Court, saying he needed more powers to defeat the terrorists and
narcotics traffickers. The traditional political parties that
controlled those institutions, he argued, only stood in the way.
Washington and the Latin American democracies were highly critical,
but the Peruvian people went along enthusiastically, and Fujimori
won a re-election landslide in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls suggest that the Peruvian president might well
have won a clean, uncontested election this year again, although by
a much narrower margin. With Peru no longer in crisis, a growing
number of voters appeared ready to give democracy a chance again.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, historians will probably judge Fujimori's rule
positively or negatively depending on whether he leaves Peru in
better or worse shape for an eventual transition to democratic
rule.
</P>
<P>
   What Toledo and Fujimori have in common is their blurring of
ideological distinctions. What does it mean to be conservative or
progressive in Peru anymore when the two candidates _ who otherwise
seem to be at war with each other _ essentially share the same
economic and social goals?
</P>
<P>
   It is much the same in Mexico, where some left-leaning activists
are backing the conservative presidential candidate as the best way
to crack the dominance of a ruling party that has been in power for
more than seven decades. Or in Chile, where the first Socialist
president in a generation has embraced the heart of the free-market
economic policies first put in place by the Pinochet dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Or in Bolivia, where a former military dictator now rules as a
democratically elected president in alliance with former
guerrillas. Or even in Colombia, where guerrillas with Marxist
origins recently took to exchanging views with visiting investors
from Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Political turbulence continues to roil much of the region. But
only the whiff of tear gas remains the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
