<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9081 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BONE-MARROW-KAN &LR;      05-29 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONE-MARROW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY'S FOUNDATION CALLS ATTENTION TO NEED FOR BLACK BONE MARROW
DONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sitting at the kitchen table one day, Walter
Chism turned to his 5-year-old granddaughter, her cheeks bloated
from medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could take this from you,'' Chism told the girl, who
had been diagnosed with chronic myeloid leukemia in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa, you know you can't do that. This is my sickness,'' Bria
Chism said. ``I'll have a story to tell when I get better.''
</P>
<P>
   But she would not get better without a bone marrow transplant.
And Bria was African-American, so her odds were not good.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally a bone marrow donor's six key tissue-typing proteins
match the patient's. A match is more likely when both are from the
same ethnic group, but minorities are underrepresented on bone
marrow donor registries. And genetically it is harder to find
matches for black people than for white people.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Eighty percent of white bone marrow transplant
candidates find a match, according to the Heart of America Bone
Marrow Donor Registry, while only 50 percent of Hispanic candidates
and 20 percent of black candidates do.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month doctors did find a donor for Bria, but they had
to go outside the United States to find a woman who matched five of
Bria's six proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Bria's body rejected the new marrow. Her bladder, kidneys, lungs
and liver malfunctioned. Blood seeped into Bria's lungs, and the
doctors deemed the situation hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   The family hoped and prayed, said Bria's mother, Ayana Chism.
After two operations the little girl got better and the color
returned to her skin.
</P>
<P>
   Then she developed the fungal infection doctors had warned about
early on. The kindergartner was so weak, little could be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to let her leave with dignity,'' Walter Chism said.
``We decided to not let her suffer any longer and (to) unplug
her.''
</P>
<P>
   She died July 2, 1999, in her grandfather's arms.
</P>
<P>
   Bria's death motivated the Raytown, Mo., family to start the
Bria T. Chism Foundation, an organization dedicated to boosting the
low numbers of minority bone marrow donors and to easing the
financial burden of serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On March 25 the foundation registered 33 new donors in its first
minority bone marrow drive. The ultimate goal is a nationwide
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could find a way to make it easier for other people to
go through this thing, her death would not be in vain,'' Walter
Chism said.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Ng, spokeswoman for the National Marrow Donor Program, in
Minneapolis, said black people were at a disadvantage partly
because they donated at lower rates than white people did. Their
genetic makeup also makes it harder to find a match.
</P>
<P>
   Ng explained that antigens, the molecule or protein markers on
the white blood cells, are used to find a bone marrow match. She
said whites had more antigens in common with each other than blacks
had in common with each other, which made it easier for whites to
find a matching donor.
</P>
<P>
   The bone marrow program understands this, Ng said, so it
launched recruitment initiatives aimed at African-Americans,
Hispanics and other minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   She credited the initiatives with helping to triple the number
of minority transplants facilitated by her agency since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to raise awareness and education in these
communities,'' Ng said. ``You know what? This could be your father
(who needs a transplant).''
</P>
<P>
   In a bone marrow drive, a blood sample is taken from each
potential donor. Participants may be called to donate marrow later.
Bone marrow is collected from the donor through the hip bone.
</P>
<P>
   Why the shortage of potential minority donors?
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Woods, chief of pediatric hematology-oncology at
Children's Mercy Hospital, said some African-Americans were fearful
of the government and the medical establishment because of
incidents such as the Tuskegee experiment.
</P>
<P>
   In that 1932 experiment, the U.S. government lured 399 blacks to
Macon County, Ala., with the promise of free health care for their
syphilis. But the government withheld treatment for 40 years,
monitoring the participants as some died of the treatable disease.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, an African-American, said the number of minority donors
had risen, thanks to well-publicized cases like that of baseball
player Rod Carew. Carew's daughter, Michelle Carew, died of
leukemia four years ago while waiting for a donor.
</P>
<P>
   Woods suggests organizations focus on churches, fraternities and
sororities if they want to boost minority representation on the
donor registry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're discussing the possibility of a transplant, you
worry if they'll ever find a donor,'' Woods said. ``And you worry
more with a minority family.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's bone marrow drive was coordinated through the
Heart of America Bone Marrow Registry, which receives a federal
grant that allows the agency to waive the $65 donation fee for
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the Bria T. Chism Foundation has raised $1,200,
most of it in a ``Celebration of Love'' at a Raytown YMCA on April
1, Bria's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The family treated the event like a birthday party, but the 50
to 60 guests brought monetary donations instead of gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Bria's grandmother, LaGail Chism, said family members hoped to
spare other families what they experienced.
</P>
<P>
   LaGail and Bria's mother remember her as a spirited little girl,
though that all changed as her sickness progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching her turn into an old lady _ it was heartbreaking,''
LaGail Chism said.
</P>
<P>
   Donations for the Bria T. Chism Foundation can be sent to P.O.
Box. 18521, Raytown, MO 64133-8521. For information call (816)
353-5934.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
