<HEADER>
A9090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT     05-29 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, MAY 30
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ARSENIC-WATER-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 24,
about proposed regulations to limit arsenic in tap water referred
incorrectly to estimates of the cancer risk under the proposed
standard of five parts per billion. The Environmental Protection
Agency's estimate of risk, approximately 1 in 10,000, pertains only
to bladder cancer, the most thoroughly studied health risk, and
does not reflect other forms of cancer that can also be caused by
arsenic.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred incompletely to environmentalists'
threat of a lawsuit if the Clinton administration did not propose
the new regulations quickly. The Natural Resources Defense Council,
an advocacy group, filed such a suit on May 10 to force the release
of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BUCKLEY-HONORARY-DEGREE-NYT (moved on Thursday, May 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, May 18,
about William F. Buckley Jr.'s return to Yale to accept an honorary
degree referred incorrectly at one point to a history professor
there who taught a class using Buckley's book and is writing one on
the same topic. He is Gaddis Smith, not Gaddis.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PHILIPPINES-TECH-TALENT (moved on Thursday, May 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, May 18,
about the growth of technology businesses in the Philippines
misstated the ages of Mark K. Escueta and Rufino H. Felipe,
classmates who helped found Mp3Manila, an Internet start-up that
allows Web site visitors to download songs. They are 21, not 22.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LIVING-WILLS-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 28,
about obstacles to honoring the wishes of the seriously ill for
peaceful deaths misspelled the given name of a woman who found that
her aunt's living will had been thwarted. And a caption with the
article reversed her identity and that of another niece. The woman
was Sabina Wilensky, not Sabena. She was pictured at the right and
Rosalind Keyes at the left.
</P>
</TEXT>
