<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-UNICOM-500(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PHONE COMPANY HOPES FOR WARM RECEPTION FOR ITS IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Two months after China's largest oil company
staggered onto the stock market here, the country's second-largest
telecommunications company announced on Monday it would seek to
raise as much as $5.3 billion in an initial public offering in Hong
Kong and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The company, China Unicom Ltd., hopes to get a warmer reception
than PetroChina Ltd., a state-owned oil company that was tarred
prior to its offering by charges of labor and human-rights abuses.
China Unicom will probably be spared those brickbats, analysts
said, given that it is an upstart phone company rather than a vast
oil monopoly with operations in Tibet and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``China Unicom is a very different animal than PetroChina,''
said Andrew Look, an independent fund manager here. ``PetroChina is
a typical old-economy company. China Unicom doesn't have that
baggage. It is a technology play, and a play on China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   But Unicom, which was started by the Chinese government six
years ago to challenge the state monopoly, China Telecom, has its
own problems. It recently shelved plans to upgrade its network with
a mobile-phone technology licensed from Qualcomm Corp. And it has
had to unravel joint ventures with more than 20 foreign partners,
whose investments were declared illegal by Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling, China Unicom only has a 14 percent share of the
country's burgeoning cellular market. China Telecom, which raised
$4.2 billion in a stock offering in 1997, has the bulk of the
business _ not to mention the favor of market analysts, who
consistently put it at the top of their recommended lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unicom has yet to prove its mettle in the marketplace,'' said
Rohit Sobti, an Asian telecommunications analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney here, in a report published in February. ``We believe the
company has a long way to go before it can effectively compete''
with China Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   China Unicom said in its prospectus that it would issue almost
2.46 billion shares at a price between 11.50 Hong Kong dollars, or
$1.48, to 14.50 Hong Kong dollars, or $1.87, per share. It will
also offer 2.34 billion shares in the form of American Depositary
Shares in a price range of $14.76 to $18.61.
</P>
<P>
   If the offering is fully subscribed at the middle of the price
range, the company said, it would raise $4 billion. At the top end
of the range, the proceeds would be almost $5.3 billion, making
Unicom the largest offering in Asia outside Japan. NTT, the
Japanese phone giant, spun off its cellular operation, NTT DoCoMo,
in a record offering that raised $18 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Unicom said it planned to use the cash from the offering to
underwrite a $12 billion expansion of its cellular, long-distance,
and data networks. Although the company is an also-ran in the
mobile-phone market, it operates the largest paging business in
China, with 43.5 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese authorities have helped Unicom by giving it
licenses and injecting the paging business,'' Look said. ``This is
a very sexy story.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Certainly, China Unicom's story has had the elements of a
corporate soap opera. In its early years, the company's status as
an upstart was appealing to foreign investors like Deutsche Telekom
and France Telecom. They agreed to put in money, even though it
meant setting up awkward joint ventures to circumvent China's
restrictions on foreign investment in telecommunications networks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1998, the Chinese government declared these
arm's-length investments illegal, and ordered the company to
dissolve them. China Unicom spent many months in often-rancorous
negotiations with the partners _ in the process, becoming a symbol
of the perils of foreign investment in China.
</P>
<P>
   China Unicom said it would take a one-time charge of about $100
million to buy out the remainder of the joint ventures. As part of
the settlement, it will also issue warrants that allow its former
partners to buy shares of China Unicom six months after the initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company's technology foray has been similarly ill-starred.
In February, it signed an agreement with Qualcomm to upgrade its
network with a digital mobile-phone technology known as CDMA, or
code division multiple access. On Monday, it told investors in Hong
Kong it would abandon the plan because CDMA was in danger of being
superseded by ``third generation'' cellular technology in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   With this record of flip-flops and false starts, some analysts
say China Unicom is destined to be a weak sister to China Telecom.
But Unicom can take solace from PetroChina: after being picketed by
protesters and initially spurned by investors, it now trades
comfortably above its offering price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
