<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO STUMBLES BUT FAILS TO BREAK STRIDE IN DAY OF CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BABYLON, N.Y. _ Rep. Rick Lazio stumbled on the campaign trail
Monday, tripping and falling face down onto the pavement at a
Memorial Day parade here and splitting his lip. But the eager
Senate candidate dusted himself off and finished the route before
going to the hospital, getting eight stitches and then marching in
a second parade, in Queens County, alongside the man he replaced in
the race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The injury means that Lazio will most likely have a swollen lip
on Tuesday afternoon, when he is expected to formally accept the
Republican nomination for the Senate at the Republican convention
in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and his supporters quickly seized upon the accident and
sought to turn it to their advantage, both with humor and by using
it to try to illustrate his perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bob Dole, who fell off a stage at a campaign stop in
California during the 1996 presidential race, Lazio quickly poked
fun at his mishap. ``I was so happy to be home that I had to kiss
the ground,'' Lazio, who fell in his own Long Island district, said
after leaving the hospital. ``I didn't know that it would kiss
back.''
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed a hometown parade for Lazio, one he said he has
marched in since childhood. Along the way, he greeted many
spectators by name, shook many hands and kissed many babies. Then,
his jacket and tie and leather dress shoes notwithstanding, he
would sprint back to the head of the parade. It was during one of
these sprints that he slipped and fell face down onto Deer Park
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Dabbing at his mouth with a bloodied handkerchief and a bag of
ice from a nearby deli, Lazio finished the parade. Some spectators
were confused at the sight of him, as shouts of ``Good luck,
Rick!'' and ``Keep her out of New York!'' were replaced by cries of
``You've got lipstick on you'' and, more accurately, ``Your lip is
bleeding!'' When Lazio finished the route, his aides looked on
nervously as he paused to talk to reporters about the speech he
plans to deliver in Buffalo on Tuesday before driving back to his
home in nearby Brightwaters for help.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that once he got home, Lazio's wife, Patricia, who is
a nurse, took one look at his lip and recommended a trip to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   So he got stitches at the Long Island Jewish Medical Center,
switched into a pair of rubber-soled boat shoes with better
traction, and went back onto the hustings to campaign with Giuliani
at the Little Neck-Douglaston Memorial Day parade along Northern
Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time Giuliani campaigned with Lazio since
deciding not to seek the Republican nomination for the Senate
himself.
</P>
<P>
   This parade was not without chaos either. The mayor and the
injured congressman soon found themselves braving a crush of
reporters so unruly that police reinforcements were called in to
restore order. They also tried talking about campaign issues and
economic opportunities over the din of the roaring mufflers of
Rolling Thunder, a motorcycle club made up of Vietnam veterans that
rallied in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor seized on all this as evidence of Lazio's grit. ``Look
at him, he's a real New Yorker,'' Giuliani said. ``He's got a fat
lip, he can talk over the worst kinds of noises, it doesn't bother
him and he's out here answering all your questions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
