<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW WEB SITES ARE ALTERING PATIENTS' VISITS TO DOCTOR
</P>
<P>
   A Web site for physicians created at Stanford University is the
latest entry in a race to transform visits to the doctor by
providing a wealth of online clinical information. Several other
top medical schools are preparing sites of their own, and there are
several commercially operated sites in operation as well.
</P>
<P>
   These Web sites reinforce a doctor's knowledge, suggest
diagnoses, and provide on-the-spot answers to patients' questions
about their symptoms. They also greatly improve medical care for
patients who live far from leading medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE TOY MAKER'S BABY BONUS
</P>
<P>
   At Bandai, a major Japanese toy maker, the talk these days
revolves around one topic _ an announcement that the company will
pay employees 1 million yen, or $10,000, for every baby they have
after their second child. Bandai is offering the largest baby
bounty in Japan, which is struggling to reverse record-low
birthrates that pose many long-term problems.
</P>
<P>
   HYUNDAI FAILS TO FINALIZE RESCUE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's largest conglomerate, Hyundai Group, and its
creditor banks failed to reach an agreement on Hyundai's revamping
plans, its main creditor, Korea Exchange Bank, said. Hyundai and
its creditor banks met to develop plans, including a self-rescue
plan for a troubled construction unit, which is led by Chung
Mong-hun.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND MAY SEEK TOBACCO DAMAGES
</P>
<P>
   With bipartisan political support and a growing national
awareness of public health issues, the Irish government is taking
aggressive steps that could result in Ireland being the first
European country to seek damages from tobacco companies for the
cost of treating smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   CALLS TO CLOSE SIBERIAN PAPER MILL
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists accuse the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper mill of
polluting Lake Baikal, a mile-deep cleft in the Siberian earth that
contains one-fifth of the planet's fresh water, and they have
demanded that it be shut down. But management says the demands for
a shutdown are blocking efforts to clean up the plant.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS REOPEN
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in the United States are open Tuesday; they
were closed Monday in observance of Memorial Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
