u a BC-NY-SOUTHHAMPTON-TAX-2     05-29 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOUTHHAMPTON-TAX-2TAKES(1015)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR CRY IN THE HAMPTONS: ONE MANSION, ONE VOTE  
 BY BLAINE HARDEN  
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mich., Colo., N.D., Ind.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ Behind the privet hedges that shield the
many monstrous mansions in this village by the sea, something
semi-revolutionary is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   The rich folks who summer in the Village of Southampton are up
in arms, in an understated, law-abiding kind of way, about an
American principle for which Colonial patriots tossed tea into
Boston Harbor: taxation without representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't say we cannot afford to pay the taxes _ we never
admit to that _ but we don't like to pay taxes that are onerous and
we don't like to be ripped off,'' said Lowell Harwood, a seasonal
resident. Though he owns a beach house here that he estimates is
worth about $6 million, Harwood, like others with a permanent
residence elsewhere, cannot vote in village elections.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal residents of Southampton, though, are hardly alone
in their hunger for a vote away from home. From Cape Cod to
Colorado, second-home owners are clamoring _ usually with the help
of their lawyers _ for a limited franchise. They want a voice in
how their tax dollars are spent and in how much year-rounders may
charge them for services they seldom use.
</P>
<P>
   Harwood, 70, who made his fortune in parking and property
development in Manhattan and whose glass-and-wood home in the dunes
has a swimming pool, tennis court and putting green, doesn't expect
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to feel sorry for us,'' he said, referring to
himself and his wealthy neighbors on Southampton's Meadow Lane.
``That is not what we are looking for. We just want justice.''
</P>
<P>
   This village, which predates the Boston Tea Party by 133 years,
has been floating in a deep green sea of property tax money since
the 1890s. That's when plutocrats like W.K. Vanderbilt began to
erect gargantuan houses that they insisted on calling cottages.
Since then, in an inexorable march of the moneyed to the sea, more
and more summer people have bought their way into Southampton, as
more and more year-round village residents have been bought out.
</P>
<P>
   According to village officials, about three-quarters of the
village's property taxes are paid by summer people, who have no
vote in local elections unless they choose to make Southampton
their permanent residence. The justice that summer people seek is
the right to vote on village matters, like who will be mayor and
the setting of special tax assessments for roads and water service,
while still keeping their permanent residence back home, which
usually means Manhattan or the suburbs of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Like most states, New York allows residents to claim only one
legal residence for voting purposes. ``You can't have two addresses
for voting,'' said Lee Daghlian, a spokesman for the state Board of
Elections. ``That is the election law.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even some year-round residents of resort communities are
beginning to agree with summer people that the law should bend to
the reality of an increasingly affluent nation where sales of
vacation homes continue to soar. According to a survey this month
by the National Association of Realtors, 377,000 vacation homes
were sold in 1999, an increase of 9.3 percent from the last survey
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a taxation-without-representation thing up
here,'' said John Quenell, a year-round resident of Lower St. Regis
Lake in New York's Adirondack region and a councilman in the Town
of Brighton. ``The way things work out in the eastern end of Long
Island or up here, it is the people who don't live year-round and
don't use the services who end up footing most of the bills. It is
not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Adirondack village of Speculator, year-round residents
last year approved spending $5.3 million to build a school for 103
students. In response, part-time residents, who account for about
40 percent of the school district's tax base and could not vote on
the proposal, filed a federal lawsuit, which is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   There are about a dozen states, including Connecticut, Colorado,
North Dakota and Indiana, that grant nonresidents a vote on some
local issues. The right was endorsed three years ago by a federal
appeals court in Denver, which ruled that seasonal residents in the
tiny resort of Mountain View could, if they owned property, vote on
all local matters in a town where they pay eight times more
property taxes than year-round residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the nonresident property owners have a
sufficient interest in town affairs to make it rational for the
town to include them in the political process,'' ruled the 10th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   This is exactly what Bill Hattrick, a former mayor of
Southampton, believes is both fair and inevitable for summer
communities on the South Fork of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a grave injustice in this country to take the money of
the summer residents and not give them full membership in the
club,'' said Hattrick, a year-round village resident who is
president of the Southampton Association, a group of about 700
mostly part-time residents who own large estates.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars who study tax policy in the United States dispute just
how grave that injustice may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been too concerned that the very wealthy are
underrepresented by our political system,'' said James Hines, a
professor of business economics at the University of Michigan
Business School and director of the school's Office of Tax Policy
Research. ``Even if they have one vote, or in this case, no votes,
their interests are still represented by their economic power.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a limit to how much the locals can charge the rich,
Hines said, because the rich can simply move away. But he added
that in the Hamptons, where competition is keen among the rich and
celebrated to flaunt their money and celebrity, the soak-the-rich
limit might well be incalculable.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, it is unfair,'' said Hines, referring to what he
said is a well-established pattern of year-round residents'
extracting high taxes from seasonal property owners. ``On the other
hand, it is hard to cry your eyes out about it, given all the other
tragedies in the world.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Year-round residents of the Hamptons, who spend their summers
stuck in traffic and who have seen countless potato farms gobbled
up by mansions on steroids, certainly are not shedding tears for
the disfranchised pain of summer people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really make an intelligent decision as a voter if
you are only out here three months a year,'' said Francesca Haley,
a waitress at Silver's Restaurant on Main Street in Southampton,
who lives in nearby Bridgehampton. ``I don't feel they have a right
to dictate how my life is going to be when they are not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Harwood, the wealthy developer, says he does not want to dictate
anything to the year-round residents. He said he merely wants to
fix a costly problem with his water bill, which he says is a
monument to ``taxation without representation and taxation without
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Harwood and about 100 other similarly rich property owners on
Meadow Lane in Southampton pay hefty water taxes to the nearby
Hampton Bays Water District, although they do not receive a drop of
water from the district.
</P>
<P>
   Harwood pays $1,800 a year for this nondelivery of water. He
also pays about $700 a year for water that he does receive from the
Town of Southampton Water Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Since a hurricane severed a water line in 1938, no one in
Southampton Village has been able to take water from the Hampton
Bays Water District. But this has not stopped the annual billing.
The 5,900 or so people who do receive water (and who live next door
in Hampton Bays, a moderate-income community) like having their
water taxes subsidized by rich Southampton folks who cannot use
what they must pay for.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can afford a house like mine, these people feel that I
can afford to pay their water bill,'' Harwood said. ``I don't mind
giving money away to charity, but I don't like it taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   A referendum has been proposed that would allow voters in the
water district to decide if the 100 Southampton property owners in
the district who get no water can stop paying bills, which average
$1,500 a year. The rub in any such referendum, of course, is that
property owners like Harwood, whose permanent residence is in Short
Hills, N.J., would not be eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to see if we can get the vote,'' Harwood said.
``Then we are probably going to have to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians in the Hamptons say that in general, they are
sympathetic to both the frustrations of summer residents and the
resentments of year-rounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Permanent residents feel they can't drive around any more
because of traffic, and sometimes they can't even walk around
because of the crowds of summer people,'' said Joseph Romanosky
Jr., the mayor of Southampton Village, which has a year-round
population of about 3,900 and a summer population of about 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now you are telling them that the summer people should
have the right to vote?'' asked the mayor. ``They don't know these
people and they don't trust them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Thiele, the state assemblyman whose district includes
Southampton, said the Legislature in Albany would sooner or later
be forced to address the voting matter seriously. In his district
on the South Fork of Long Island, nonresidents own more than half
the residential property.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is not going to go away,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
