<HEADER>
A9100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT     05-29 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON REPEATS CALL FOR GUN REGISTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. _ Hillary Rodham Clinton chose to spend Memorial
Day walking in a parade in her adopted hometown on Monday and
offering an attack, albeit indirectly, on her soon-to-be-nominated
Republican opponent for the U.S. Senate over his opposition to
handgun registration.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Memorial Day parades throughout the state
attracted political candidates of every stripe, Clinton said she
selected the relatively modest parade in the town where she moved
five months ago, because it reminded her of commemorations in the
Chicago suburb where she was raised.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the Democratic nominee for Senate, did not mention her
Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, by name. But she indirectly
criticized the congressman's opposition to handgun registration by
re-emphasizing her own position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to reiterate my call for the licensing and
registration of handguns,'' Clinton said, speaking to reporters
after a Memorial Day ceremony in front of the Chappaqua railroad
station. ``I just think we ought to do everything we possibly can
to keep them away from people who are criminally inclined.''
</P>
<P>
   She said several people at the program had told her of their
horror at the recent killing of five employees at a Wendy's
restaurant in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stress what a lot of my neighbors and a lot of
people in the community are saying to me _ we have to do more, not
only to be tough on criminals, but we have to be tough on the
weapons that criminals use,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lazio's campaign, Bryan Flood, declined to
respond directly to Clinton's comments, but he reiterated that
Lazio favors many forms of gun control but not registration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Lazio has long supported common-sense gun control,
often breaking with his own party,'' Flood said by telephone from
Buffalo. For example, he said, Lazio supported the Brady bill and
the ban on assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he believes that before we take the dramatic step of
registration, we ought to look at ensuring that existing
common-sense gun laws are enforced, and this administration's
record on enforcing those gun laws is poor,'' Flood said.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since Lazio emerged as the Republican candidate,
Clinton's aides have been preparing to emphasize his opposition to
some forms of gun control and to public financing of abortions for
the poor. Both are issues that her campaign aides suggest could
help her standing among female voters.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady was received enthusiastically on her first
Memorial Day as a Chappaqua resident. Many along the quarter-mile
parade route cheered as she walked by, amid a small contingent of
Girl Scouts. (Clinton is the organization's national honorary
chairwoman.)
</P>
<P>
   She did not speak at the ceremony after the parade, but she
lingered long after it had ended, shaking hands and posing for
photographs when people asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
