<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-FISHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI PULLOUT HAS FISHERMEN CELEBRATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TYRE, Lebanon _ As a burning red sun sank into the Mediterranean
on Monday, fishermen in this ancient Phoenician port unloaded
record catches from their skiffs and busily repaired nets before
heading out again at dawn Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, such a scene was a rarity. But as Shiite Muslim
guerrillas revel in the end of Israel's 22-year occupation of
southern Lebanon, local fishermen find they have something to
celebrate as well.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen said they are landing record harvests from fertile
fishing grounds that was completely closed off to them by Israeli
gunships.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen said the Israelis often fired upon their boats
that dared to venture off the coast of southern Lebanon. Boats that
did stray into the roughly 10 miles of Israeli-patroled waters, the
fishermen said, were often confiscated by the Israeli navy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis were strangling us like this,'' said fisherman
Elias Safadi, putting his hands around his throat. ``But now we can
breathe. Now the waters that our fathers fished and that their
fathers fished are ours again. We have never been so busy in our
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Safadi, 40, had struggled most of his life to feed his wife and
two young daughters on catches that brought him about $5 a day. But
he has pocketed nearly $100 a day for the last five days since the
Israelis withdrew from the self-proclaimed ``security zone'' they
occupied in south Lebanon to protect northern Israel against
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Since the withdrawal, Safadi said his two daughters, ages 2 and
3, have new shoes. He has also bought his wife a new washing
machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are celebrating, and I am just focusing on working. Who
knows how long it will last,'' said Safadi, who has lived through
Lebanon's civil war and the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
   There are 475 fishermen registered with Tyre Fisherman's
Association, which runs a port that had existed for 1,000 years
under the Phoenician empire before it fell to Alexander the Great
in the fourth century BC.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the organization, Khalil Taha, said that all of the
fishermen are reporting catches at least 20 times the value of what
they have caught in a generation. Although Lebanon has a long
coastline that stretches up to Beirut, the fishermen say the warmer
and most profitable waters are all south of Tyre.
</P>
<P>
   There is some concern that the extraordinary catches could bring
a glut in the market that could plunge retail prices to levels so
low that they could permanently disrupt the market. But for now the
fisherman seemed too consumed with filling their nets to worry
about economic trends.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 22 years the only fishermen able to freely work the
rugged coastline of south Lebanon were a small collection of
inexperienced fishermen aligned with the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis assigned special numbers to a dozen SLA boats, and
left them undisturbed. But other fishermen were subject to
harassment, arrests, beatings, and sometimes gunfire by the Israeli
navy, the fishermen said.
</P>
<P>
   The strict patrolling of the coastline divided the fishing
community sharply along sectarian lines. The Christian fishermen of
the port said they did not dare fish the waters fearing that they
would be suspected as collaborators with the Christian-led SLA. But
the Muslims often defiantly embarked on midnight runs, trying to
avoid the Israeli navy in search of fish.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Malek, 32, a Muslim, said he tried three times to defy
the Israeli ban on fishing, and each time he was shot and wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not political, I am a fisherman. But this is our water,
and we have every right to fish in it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
