<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9106 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-MILITANTS-BOS &LR;      05-29 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MILITANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENIOR LEBANESE MILITANTS APPEAR AT HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ For the first time since they were seized by Israeli
forces, two senior Lebanese militants whom Israel had hoped to
trade for captured air force navigator Ron Arad appeared in public
at a Tel Aviv district court hearing Monday on whether they should
be released.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid, 43, a Hezbollah spiritual leader
abducted in 1989 by Israeli forces in south Lebanon, and Mustafa
Dirani, 49, security chief for the Amal group that captured Arad
when his fighter plane went down in 1986, followed the hearing
through a translator sitting at their side.
</P>
<P>
   Bearded and pale, Obeid wore the white skullcap of a religious
leader, and he looked almost dazed by the attention. Dirani, who
had dark hair and a dark beard, kept his eyes firmly planted on
their lawyer. At one point Dirani, who was captured in 1994,
demanded to speak, repeating assertions that he lost track of Arad
after 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The men, who are being held together in a secret location in
Israel, have denied knowing anything about Arad's current
whereabouts. Neither Dirani nor Obeid has ever been charged by
Israel with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Their lawyer argued Monday that neither man was a security
threat, saying both had stated that when Israel withdrew from south
Lebanon _ as happened last week _ there would be no reason to go on
fighting, .
</P>
<P>
   But the Tel Aviv court, which was packed Monday with observers
and groups opposed to the men's release, delayed issuing a
decision, saying more time was needed to study the arguments. It
will reconvene July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a senior United Nations envoy asked Israel to release
all Lebanese prisoners to lessen tension in southern Lebanon, from
which Israeli troops withdrew last week after 22 years of
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been no serious clashes since Israel
completed its withdrawal, Hezbollah officials in Lebanon said their
guerrilla war against Israel _ which appears at least to have been
suspended _ will not end until the Lebanese prisoners are freed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the prisoners are Hezbollah fighters tried and jailed in
Israel, but Dirani's and Obeid's detention is directly linked to
missing airman Arad Dirani, who was responsible for Arad after the
airman was captured, took Arad with him when he split from the Amal
group two years later. After Dirani was abducted by Israel, he
reportedly told his interrogators that in 1989 he transferred Arad
to Iranian Revolutionary Guards in Lebanon. Since then, there
apparently has been no concrete information on where Arad is held
or whether he is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue is one that has been kept alive in Israel, where
``Free Ron Arad'' bumper stickers are common and Arad's family is
invited to meet with Israeli politicians and defense officials. If
Arad is still alive, he is 41 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The basic argument in court is over whether Dirani and Obeid
pose a threat to Israel's security _ which would block their
release _ or should be released because they have no information
about Arad and are being held illegally, defense lawyer Zvi Rish
said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of releasing the two men arose last month when the
High Court of Justice ruled that Israel could not hold people
simply as ``bargaining chips,'' to be traded for soldiers missing
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling, which followed years of petitions by
Rish, Israel released 13 Lebanese citizens who had been held for 14
years or longer. Some had never been tried for any crimes, while
others had long before served out their sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was hailed by human rights groups but sparked anger
among some Israeli politicians, who have prepared a bill that would
give the state the legal right to hold people who act against the
state or whose detention may aid in securing the release of
Israelis held by enemy forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NJ-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-29 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NJ-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE PRIMARY IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 30:
</P>
<P>
   The Senate race in New Jersey, lately overshadowed by the recent
political drama in New York, now moves to center stage with two
hotly contested primary elections on June 6. Voters must choose
Democratic and Republican nominees for a general-election contest
that could figure in the battle for control of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic race offers a choice between Jon Corzine, an
earnest, big-spending political novice, and Jim Florio, a
battle-scarred but knowledgeable former governor.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's strong record of achievement has vastly improved the
lives of New Jersey residents, while his strong personality has
also created an army of enemies, even within his own party.
Florio's scrappy nature helped produce such gems as the Pinelands
Preservation Act that now protects 1 million acres in the state.
</P>
<P>
   During his terms in Congress and as governor, he fought to
create the Superfund, as well as to clean up and preserve the
state's beaches. As governor, Florio stood up to the auto insurance
industry, and his success in making New Jersey the first state to
outlaw semiautomatic assault weapons made him a favorite enemy of
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of a court order, Florio increased education
financing by springing a surprise tax increase of $2.8 billion on
New Jersey voters. The political blunder, now the stuff of legend
in New Jersey, led to his defeat by Christie Whitman in 1993. But
it is important to remember that Florio's failure was one of
salesmanship, not in his choice of remedies for schools that needed
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine is also an advocate of educational improvement and such
worthy goals as universal health care. The fact that he is a former
co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. who retired with a $400 million
fortune makes his unabashed, old-fashioned liberalism all the more
striking. But an unselfish nature cannot substitute for deep
knowledge of public policy. When it comes to such details as
explaining the $30 billion price tag of his health insurance
proposal, Corzine is simply not in Florio's league.
</P>
<P>
   He is also tone deaf on the issue of money in politics. Corzine
has spent more than $30 million in a largely self-financed campaign
and has used his deep pockets for contributions to local parties as
a way to win the support of other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when candidates should be moving toward financial
transparency, he has cited partnership agreements with Goldman
Sachs as the reason for refusing to release a detailed account of
his sources of wealth. All that might be tolerable if Corzine had
advanced a detailed plan for campaign finance reform, but his grasp
of that issue seems hazy and perfunctory.
</P>
<P>
   For all these reasons, we urge New Jersey Democrats to vote for
Florio as the more seasoned and knowledgeable candidate. We do so
with full respect for the nobility of Corzine's political impulses
and with the hope that he will become a more articulate student of
public policy.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the four contenders include three
moderates and one former Libertarian. James Treffinger has gotten
excellent reviews as Essex County executive, but the real race is
between Rep. Bob Franks and state Sen. William Gormley.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, a forceful ex-Marine, is widely admired in some circles
for the independence he showed in 1990 as the only Senate
Republican voting for Florio's ban on assault weapons. That is a
considerable badge of honor. Franks was in the New Jersey Assembly
at the time, but skipped the key votes. As a congressman, however,
Franks has supported gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these candidates is free of weaknesses. Although they
have similar moderate Republican views, Franks tends to circle
issues more tentatively, coming around slowly even to the strongest
issue in his portfolio, campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, whose fulminations in Trenton are legendary, has less
difficulty standing firm. But he has a mixed record on the
environment, and his campaign is shadowed by his reliance on
campaign contributions from the casino industry and shoreline
developers in his Atlantic City area.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, for his part, has voted to support campaign finance
reform, although he is not a leader on the issue. Despite a
troubling committee vote in 1995 to weaken regulations under the
Clean Water Act, Franks has since won improving marks from New
Jersey environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of his overall record as a dependable member of the
GOP's moderate wing and his better record on campaign finance, we
urge New Jersey Republicans to choose Franks as their Senate
nominee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
