<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS EDGE PACERS, 91-89 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the injured New York Knicks who could slip into
their orange-trimmed jerseys, they used adrenaline as a wonder drug
on Monday night to overcome the various ailments picking on their
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Only Patrick Ewing was unable to play in Game 4 of the Eastern
Conference finals, while Latrell Sprewell danced around on a bad
foot, Marcus Camby leaped on a sore knee and Larry Johnson hung out
on the wing unencumbered by a chronically sore back.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, Johnson was feeling only the euphoria. It was last
year revisited for him. After the Pacers slashed the Knicks'
17-point halftime lead to 1 point with just under seven minutes
left in the game, Johnson anchored himself in front of the right
sideline and launched three 3-pointers over the next four minutes
to give the Knicks a remarkable 91-89 victory at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks evened the four-of-seven-game series at two games
apiece. Game 5 will be played at Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis
on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Once a blowout, Game 4 turned into a tight finish that wasn't
decided until the final seconds. After the Pacers pulled within 3
points, at 90-87, with 6.4 seconds remaining, Sprewell missed two
free throws with 4.1 seconds left on the clock. But on the second
miss, Jalen Rose was called for a lane violation. On the third
attempt, Sprewell connected and gave the Knicks an impenetrable
4-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprewell had his troubles scoring (12 points) and
keeping up with Rose (18 points), he hit the free throw he had to
make. Johnson, who beat the Pacers in Game 3 of last year's Eastern
Conference finals with a 4-point play, made everything else. He
finished with 25 points and was 5 of 5 from 3-point range. With
Sprewell ailing, and Camby (8 rebounds, 5 points) not himself,
Johnson, Charlie Ward (16 points, 7 assists), Kurt Thomas (16
points) and Allan Houston (17 points) were the foils to Reggie
Miller's 24-point night.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks shot 49 percent from the field and limited the Pacers
to 45.6 percent. More surprisingly, they outrebounded the bigger
Pacers, 41-32. The Knicks watched their 17 point-lead at the half
come under a serious threat as the Pacers began to cut into it,
little by little, with Rose playing loose and free. He pulled the
Pacers right back into the game with a wild bank shot over Johnson
with just under 10 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, that cushy lead was down to 4 points. It was down to
77-76 when Miller hit an open 3-pointer in transition three minutes
later. But just as he had done in the past to the Pacers, Johnson
then devastated their comeback with a 3-pointer with 6 minutes 20
seconds left in the game. Waiting patiently on the right wing,
Johnson then hit another 3-pointer with four minutes remaining to
put the Knicks up by 85-76. His third came with just over two
minutes remaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0270 </DOCNO>
