<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9112 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     05-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERCIVAL ENDS JACOBS JINX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND -- Angels manager Mike Scioscia just shook his head no
when asked if he knew anything about Troy Percival's history at
Jacobs Field. In might have been a white lie, but as far as
Scioscia's concerned, the past is old news.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia is only concerned with what his closer is doing now,
and on a breezy Memorial Day afternoon, Percival earned his first
career save at Jacobs Field in the Angels' 3-2, 10-inning victory
over the Indians before a sellout crowd of 42,888 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Percival went into the game having made seven appearances here,
and the numbers weren't pretty: 0-3, three blown saves and a 19.06
ERA. But after the game, Percival wasn't about to reflect on old
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to dwell on anything negative,'' said
Percival, who struck out pinch hitter Alex Ramirez with two runners
on base to end it. ``Any time I get a save or don't get a save with
these guys it always seems to be negative. Sometimes they get you
and sometimes you get them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, they got him, as Percival was 0-6 with an 8.41 ERA vs.
Cleveland in his career overall before Monday. But this one was
different, and he got a boost from Scioscia along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Percival entered the 10th with a 3-2 lead and retired the first
two batters before Omar Vizquel ripped a double to right-center.
Roberto Alomar was up next, but after a meeting on the mound with
Scioscia and all the infielders, Percival walked Alomar
intentionally. That goes against ``the book,'' because Alomar
represented the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy worked as Percival blew a fastball past Ramirez
to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Roberto Alomar is really a guy you don't want to give
a chance to tie the game,'' Scioscia said. ``I have confidence in
Percy, but I was more comfortable with the matchup with Ramirez, or
anyone coming off their bench. I'm thinking we're not going to play
for a tie on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It made sense,'' Percival said. ``You've got a force at every
base (except home). That guy (Alomar) had four plate-appearances
and he'd seen the ball. The other guy (Ramirez) was a player who'd
been sitting on the bench all day. It's just a smart move.''
</P>
<P>
   Percival and the Angels were in a position to win the game
because Troy Glaus homered leading off the top of the 10th to break
a 2-2 tie. It was his 16th homer of the season, second on the team
to Mo Vaughn's 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch, a curveball down,'' Glaus said of the 0-1
pitch by Steve Karsay (0-3). ``I wasn't up there trying to win the
ballgame, just trying to get a pitch to drive and get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn pitched five hitless innings, but
had to leave the game -- despite a plea to stay in -- because of a
tight left shoulder. That left it up to the bullpen to preserve a
2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine threw two scoreless innings before Mike Holtz entered
the game in the eighth. But the defense made two errors in the
inning, allowing two unearned runs to score and tie the game. They
did manage to escape further damage by getting an unusual double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus booted Kenny Loften's grounder to open the inning, but
Holtz struck out Omar Vizquel. Scioscia brought in Shigetoshi
Hasegawa (4-0) hoping for the double-play grounder, but instead
Alomar grounded the ball into right field for a single, driving
Loften to third.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa then got the grounder he was looking for. Manny Ramirez
hit a routine grounder to Adam Kennedy at second, but Kennedy
fumbled the ball away as he was making the flip to Benji Gil at
second. Loften scored and the Indians had runners on first and
second.
</P>
<P>
   David Justice followed with a slow roller through the hole at
short, driving in Alomar to tie the game. But Dave Roberts, who was
running for Ramirez at first, got thrown out at third by left
fielder Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   Justice also tried to take the extra base, but Glaus threw to
Kennedy at second to complete the 7-5-4 double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the way you draw it up, that's for sure,'' Gil
said. ``But it worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
