</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS TIE THEIR LACES, AND SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New Yorkers being a highly knowledgeable lot, Knicks
fans even dispense advice on the proper way to dress before a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tie 'em tight,'' somebody shouted to Latrell Sprewell on
Sunday afternoon, as he laced up the sneaker on his injured left
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Ever solicitous, the fans wanted to see the most possible
support of the tiny fractured bone, and they had other advice
bordering on the inspirational for the assorted walking wounded.
This was before the Knicks stunned the fans _ but probably not
themselves _ by embarrassing Indiana, 91-89, to tie this series at
two games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   It perhaps should be no surprise, since the Knicks jolted the
Pacers the same way last year, also without Patrick Ewing. In the
process, the Knicks have turned the corner from a headstrong and
occasionally loutish bunch in the Pat Riley era to gallant and even
resourceful players under Jeff Van Gundy who fit into the demanding
standards of New York fans.
</P>
<P>
   The fans were looking for miracles when the day began. The
Knicks' predicament was stated quite baldly on the pregame lineup
notes:
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing: ``Acute peroneal tendinitis right foot, day to
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby: ``Sprained medial capsule, right knee, day to
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell: ``Incomplete fracture of fifth metatarsal,
left foot, day to day.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a serious load of injuries. The players reported for
pregame workouts looking pretty good. Of course, they were well
rested, having snoozed on the training tables while the training
staff performed miracles on damaged tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers, meanwhile, looked positively awful. Mike Saunders
and Said Hamdan looked as if they had not slept in days, which, of
course, they had not. ``We pulled out all the stops today,'' Hamdan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the trainers do not report to the Westchester County
training site before a day game, but there was work to be done, so
Hamdan made the long schlep from Nassau County to the Connecticut
border to administer to the legions. ``I've been in restaurants and
bakeries with shorter lines for a table or a loaf,'' Hamdan said.
</P>
<P>
   The work paid off in bodies, since Spree and Camby were able to
stay in uniform for the game, while Ewing had to change into a
handsome dark striped suit, and do his best work waving an orange
rally towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any question of how hard they would play,'' Van
Gundy said. ``The question is whether they'd be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It is to the credit of the Knicks and the league that they
disclosed the injuries. This would never happen in hockey, where
teams conveniently forget to disclose minor details like broken
bones and wrenched joints, for the very good reason that somebody
on the other side would be sure to test that injury early.
</P>
<P>
   Such opportunism seemed beyond the Pacers, sportsmen to the
core. In the absence of Ewing, the Pacers rarely lobbed the ball to
the 7-foot-4-inch Dutchman, Rik Smits, to try to isolate Smits for
his characteristic soft shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers seemed to want to win fair and square, perhaps
confirming Larry Bird's own worst suspicions about his team, that
it does not know how to finish off a damaged opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday brought back memories of last year, when Ewing was also
wobbly, when the Pacers appeared on a straight path to the finals,
only to have uproarious things happen. For the record: the Knicks
won in six games.
</P>
<P>
   It seems almost laughable that the Knicks could be so smooth, so
fine, so accurate, with so many injuries. Sprewell seemed to have
plenty of forward leap, but his lateral moves were suspect. Camby
was visibly hobbling, and Van Gundy saved him for a late spurt.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the game, the fans applauded the Knicks. These were not
the artificial cheers spurred on by the witless sounds from the
public-address system, but rather the warm and impromptu sounds of
fans who had gotten more out of this cool, sweet Memorial Day
weekend than they ever could have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise that had self-destructed in fights and suspensions
in the past is now showing the resourcefulness that New York fans
used to expect. One glaring statistic from the Indiana playoff
series of last year and this is that the Knicks have now won five
and lost one when Ewing could not play at all. Van Gundy said this
fact has been ``manipulated'' by the news media, but it is a fact
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   The trainers are working on Ewing's tendinitis for Game 5. The
few traveling Knicks fans will no doubt dispense medical, emotional
and strategic advice on Wednesday night in Indiana, too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
