<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER VISITS ANGELS CLUBHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND -- Pitcher Kent Mercker, who suffered a cerebral
hemorrhage May 11, visited the Angels clubhouse in Cleveland Monday
and plans to stay in town for the three-game series against the
Indians. He made the two-hour drive from his home in Dublin, Ohio
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You miss this part of it more than playing,'' Mercker said
while sitting in the clubhouse after the Angels' 3-2 win over the
Indians. ``Being around the guys, telling jokes, this is fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just assume when you're playing you can come to the
clubhouse every day and see the guys. When you're not allowed to
see them, being in the hospital for two weeks, you miss 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker said some of his teammates didn't know quite how to
react to him, especially those who saw Mercker the night he had the
hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked at me funny, like I'm going to fall down or
something,'' Mercker said. ``I try telling them nothing's wrong
with me. Everything's fine now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a couple guys, the last time they saw him he was in the
clubhouse throwing up and his head was killing him,'' manager Mike
Scioscia. ``It was awesome to see him. To see him talking about
pitching, to see his mental outlook so good, there's no doubt in my
mind he's going to pitch again sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer Troy Percival visited Mercker in the hospital almost
every day, picking up lunch from Mercker's favorite restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks great,'' Percival said. ``He's a huge part of this
team and we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn had a no-hitter through five
innings Monday, but didn't make it out of the dugout for the sixth.
Washburn had felt tightness in his shoulder the past few days and
still felt it Monday, so Scioscia didn't want to take any chances
and took him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said 'How do you feel?' And I said 'The same,' and he said
'You're done,' '' Washburn said of Scioscia. ``I thought he was
joking, I laughed. But he's looking out for my best interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn admitted he sat next to Scioscia in the top of the
sixth trying to convince him to let him go out for the bottom of
the sixth, but it didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be an attorney because he lost his
argument,'' Scioscia said. ``As much as you want to win the
ballgame, you have to look at the big picture. We're looking at the
long-term impact we expect him to have on our pitching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Washburn is expected to make his next start, Sunday vs. the
Dodgers at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Benji Gil went 0 for 4 Monday and is now hitless in 21
at-bats, his average dipping to .189. He hadn't driven in a run
since May 13, but he drove in two runs in separate at-bats Monday.
He grounded out to shortstop to score Scott Spiezio from third in
the third inning, and grounded into a fielder's choice to score
Troy Glaus from third in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   They were big runs because at that point, they were the only
runs of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to do something to help the team,'' Gil said.
``Whatever I can do, take a walk, bunt, drive in runs without a
hit. That's what my job calls for.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus grounded into a double play in the second inning Monday,
the first double play he's hit into all season. Before Monday, he
led the league in at-bats without hitting into a double play (179).
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS AT CLEVELAND
</P>
<P>
   Time: 4:05 at Jacobs Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: KCAL-9; KMPC-1540, KIK-FM 94.3, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Scott Schoeneweis (5-2, 5.00 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Cleveland's Dave Burba (4-1, 5.23). The Angels are
5-2 on their current trip, with two to play. The Angels have hit 83
home runs this season, which ranks second in the A.L. and fourth in
the majors. The club record for homers in a season is 192 set in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
