<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FACE OF THE PACERS MIGHT NEED A LIFT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Franchises go through changes. Crazy changes, evolutions,
transformations. Franchises renovate. Some change mascots; others
change logos and uniforms. Others, in an attempt to find higher
ground and deeper pockets, change cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers have gone through fewer changes than most.
But now they need a facelift. Monday, a broken-down Knicks team _
one player with a broken bone in his foot, another with a sore knee
and Patrick Ewing out of the lineup _ outran and outhustled the
Pacers, who lost a crucial Game 4, 91-89. After the game, in a
tense losers' locker room, a couple of players were saying that
something had to change. Not heart. Not effort. None of the
subjective stuff writers like to write about. Tactics had to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to get more easy baskets,'' Jalen Rose
said. ``We have to find a way to play a little quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether the Pacers could improve their running game,
Travis Best said: ``Yeah, we like to run more, but you have to get
stops. They were getting too many easy transition baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have been in Indiana since 1967 and, in their biggest
change, went from the American Basketball Association to the
National Basketball Association in 1976. Last year they tore down
one arena and moved into a new one.
</P>
<P>
   Now they appear to be at the crucial point of fundamental
renovation, and that will be even more evident if the Knicks come
back to win the Eastern Conference finals. Indiana had the Knicks
in a corner with a seemingly slim chance for escape: The Pacers won
the first two games, and the Knicks are hobbled with injuries.
Ewing didn't play Monday. Latrell Sprewell has a broken bone in his
foot. Marcus Camby has a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   The loss again raised questions. Are the Pacers tough enough to
finish off the Knicks? Who can be the source of the team's
fortitude? Is Reggie Miller Indiana's strength or merely a star
attraction?
</P>
<P>
   For 13 seasons the Pacers' face has been Miller, who will go
down as one of the deadliest outside shooters in NBA history. But
Miller, 34, has never carried his team to a championship, or even
the finals, and critics contemplating the Pacers' future are
wondering if he ever will. The Pacers are looking for a new face, a
new attitude. Will it be young Jonathan Bender? Young Al
Harrington? Maybe the Pacers are looking for Jalen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good group, a hard-working group,'' Donnie Walsh,
the Pacers' president, said Sunday. ``Unfortunately, in America
you're judged by winning championships.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers won their first ABA championship in 1970, when Miller
was 4. They won championships in 1972 and 1973, when Miller was 6
and 7. The Pacers' NBA cupboard is bare, but Miller's antics have
diverted attention from it. Miller has evolved from an
outside-shooting specialist to a bandanna-wrapped,
eye-patch-wearing bad guy, the trash talker who torments the Knicks
and their No. 1 fan, Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   On May 7, 1995, in one of the most dramatic finishes ever,
Miller scored 8 points in the final 18.7 seconds to beat the
Knicks, 107-105, in Game 1 of the Eastern Conference semifinals;
Indiana ultimately won the series. In 1998 he led the Pacers past
the Knicks, also in the conference semifinals, in five games.
</P>
<P>
   But the wide arc of his playoff history is a checkerboard of
great individual performances and four eliminations in the Eastern
Conference finals. Now the chances for this core of players, led by
Miller, are fading. All of Miller's antics _ the 3-point shooting,
the flopping around to draw fouls _ haven't been enough to catapult
Indiana into the championship round.
</P>
<P>
   It is Miller's misfortune at the twilight of his career to have
as his coach a former player whose reputation casts a shadow wide
enough to dwarf his own. Larry Bird was not only a deadly outside
shooter but a player who possessed unique basketball instincts _
and an instinct for winning _ that Miller seems to lack. You get
the sense sometimes that Bird can't understand why his team's
superstar can't carry them across the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Bird made a pointed reference to Miller's fading
act in the playoffs, after several occasions when Miller went
missing when the Pacers really needed him. He was missing in action
again on Saturday in Game 3, with Indiana trailing the depleted
Knicks, and Miller finished the game on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Jalen Rose could be the new face in waiting. That is,
if he waits. Rose began to blossom last season and continued the
evolution this season. He has a tough veneer. He helped lead a
fourth-quarter rally Monday that got the Pacers back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rose may be the Pacers' new face. He may have to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
