one-of-a-kind dresses directly on her customers, typically dousing
the garments with oils for an aromatherapy effect. Last week, she
introduced her first full ready-to-wear line at Kirna Zabete on
Greene Street. ``I need to make some money,'' said Jimenez, shown
displaying styles that the buyer doesn't have to crack open at home
to see. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- NY-PRICE-OPERA -- Leontyne
Price reads from her version of ``Aida'' to schoolchildren in
Harlem. It has been 15 years since Price retired from the opera
stage by singing ``Aida'' at the Metropolitan Opera, a historic
performance telebroadcast live on television. Now she has the time
to do things like visit Harlem from her Greenwich Village town
house, and make opera fans out of that neighborhood's younger
members. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- SCI-LIVING-WILLS-FINOCCHIO --
Frank Finocchio and his daughter, Bettina, in the Queens apartment
where they cared for his dying wife, Phyllis. They decided not to
use feeding tubes or a respirator. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- May 29, 2000 -- SCI-LIVING-WILLS-II-2-B&AMP;W --
Sample questions from a workbook, and similar worksheets from the
American Medical Association, can help patients and families decide
how final days are spent. The work sheets are not meant to be used
as legal documents, but as points of departure for discussions.
(''Your Life, Your Choice''/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- SCI-LIVING-WILLS-II-1 -- In
absence of living wills, ``oral advance directives'' can be a
guide, said Dr. Navah Harlowe, the director of the Center for
Ethics in Medicine at of Beth Israel Medical Center. ``If a patient
has told his loved ones what his wishes would be, and has lived
life in a certain way so there is no doubt, can't we find a way to
honor his wishes, to listen to his oral advance directive, as
related by family and friends?'' she wondered. (Michelle V.
Agins/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- LADIES-FASHION-2 -- Ever
since designers and fashion editors started tossing about the term
``ladylike dressing,'' one has had the feeling they don't know what
they are talking about. ``Last year the look was Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch and Ralph Lauren polo shirts and khaki pants,'' said Amanda
Hearst, 16, in a clingy sweater over a white tube top and fitted
jeans. ``Right now, we're into blow drying our hair, wearing
delicate jewelry and clothes that fit, especially skirts.''
(Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- LADIES-FASHION-1 -- Ever
since designers and fashion editors started tossing about the term
``ladylike dressing,'' one has had the feeling they don't know what
they are talking about. Brooke Astor's day attire, left (James
Estrin/The New York Times), always includes hat and gloves, no
matter what. ``I don't think there is any such thing as ladylike
dressing,'' said Nan Kempner, shown at home, right, dressed in Yves
Saint Laurent's spring collection. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
