<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 05/29/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-2 -- The
New York Knicks beat the Indiana Pacers 91-89 at Madison Square
Garden on Monday in Game 4 of the NBA's Eastern Conference finals.
Charlie Ward, left, had 16 points, seven assists and six rebounds
to pace the Knicks, who won their second straight and tied the
series at two games apiece; Larry Johnson, right, led the Knicks
with 25. The fifth game is scheduled for Wednesday night in
Indianapolis. (Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-1 -- The
New York Knicks beat the Indiana Pacers 91-89 at Madison Square
Garden on Monday in Game 4 of the NBA's Eastern Conference finals.
Larry Johnson (shown here trying to score against the Pacers' Jalen
Rose, left, and Rik Smits) scored 25 points to lead the Knicks, who
won their second straight and tied the series at two games apiece.
The fifth game is scheduled for Wednesday night in Indianapolis.
(Barton Silverman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 29, 2000 -- NY-SOUTHHAMPTON-TAX
-- From Cape Cod to Colorado, second-home owners want a voice in
how their tax dollars are spent and in how much year-rounders may
charge them for services they seldom use. Lowell Harwood at his $6
million beach house in Southampton. A seasonal resident, he objects
to not having a local vote. ``We don't like to pay taxes that are
onerous and we don't like to be ripped off,'' he said. (Maxine
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- May 29, 2000 -- NY-MRS-CLINTON -- On a day
when Memorial Day parades throughout the state attracted political
candidates of every stripe, Senate candidates Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Rep. Rick A. Lazio used the free publicity to further
their causes. Mrs. Clinton, the Democratic nominee, marched in her
adopted hometown, Chappaqua, N.Y., above (Librado Romero/The New
York Times); Lazio joined Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani for a parade in
Little Neck, N.Y., below. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) AIN EL HILWE, Lebanon -- May 29, 2000 --
PALESTINIANS-CAMPS -- Ahmad Kuleib, 19, second from the right, with
other Palestinian refugees Monday at Lebanon's border with Israel,
where he said he had journeyed ``to look at Palestine for the first
time in my life.'' From the newly opened border area here, the
300,000 Palestinians who have lived for half a century in squalid,
supposedly makeshift refugee camps in Lebanon can now gaze on the
hills of what they consider their homeland. (Rina Castelnuovo/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- NY-WAITERS-RACIAL-2 -- In
New York City's restaurant industry, there has long been a scarcity
of black waiters and waitresses. George Thomas, 35, remembered when
he was trying to get a toehold. ``I have faxed restaurants with my
qualifications, and they expressed excitement,'' said Thomas, who
has been a waiter captain at the four-star Bouley Bakery for the
last year. ``Then they saw me in person, and the whole conversation
changed.'' (Michelle V. Agins/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- NY-WAITERS-RACIAL-1 -- In
New York City's restaurant firmament, one reality has dominated the
city's enormous inventory of distinguished restaurants: a scarcity
of black waiters and waitresses. Daniel Smalls, 36, a former
waiter, is now the manager of Guastavino's, where 40 percent of the
waitstaff of 120 is black. ``A lot of black people began to apply
here when they saw me,'' he said. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- May 29, 2000 -- MASS-MUSEUM-2 --
Of all the dying mill towns in New England, this was perhaps the
deadest. But now North Adams is in renaissance, a nascent Soho in
the Berkshires, mainly thanks to a massive new arts complex, the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, known as Mass MOCA.
(Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NORTH ADAMS, Mass. -- May 29, 2000 -- MASS-MUSEUM-1 --
Of all the dying mill towns in New England, this was perhaps the
deadest. But now North Adams is in renaissance, a nascent Soho in
the Berkshires, mainly thanks to a massive new arts complex, the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, known as Mass MOCA.
(Keith Meyers/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- May 29, 2000 -- MICROBREWERY-3 -- Richard
Doyle, a founder of the Mass Bay Brewing Co., recently added a
sixth 24-hour production day to his brewery's workweek. Indeed,
business for Mass Bay is as good as it ever was at the height of
the specialty beer boom in the mid-1990s. But some of his
colleagues in the Massachusetts microbrewing industry have not been
so fortunate. (Ed Quinn/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- May 29, 2000 -- MICROBREWERY-2 -- At the Sunset
Grill and Tap in Boston, which offers about 60 American craft brews
from its 112 taps, beer ethusiasts still sample the occasional
seasonal Summer Wheat Ale or Octoberfest brew. But instead of
jumping on the new brand of the month, drinkers generally stick
with established products from brewers like Sam Adams and Sierra
Nevada. (Ed Quinn/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- May 29, 2000 -- MICROBREWERY-1 -- Mass Bay
Brewing Co.'s facility in Boston. The brewery recently added a
sixth 24-hour production day to its workweek. Indeed, business for
Mass Bay is as good as it ever was at the height of the specialty
beer boom in the mid-1990s. But some of its competitors in the
Massachusetts microbrewing industry have not been so fortunate. (Ed
Quinn/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 29, 2000 -- FASHION-NOTES -- The designer
Elisa Jimenez, who is 35 and lives in Hell's Kitchen, sews
one-of-a-kind dresses directly on her customers, typically dousing
the garments with oils for an aromatherapy effect. Last week, she
introduced her first full ready-to-wear line at Kirna Zabete on
Greene Street. ``I need to make some money,'' said Jimenez, shown
displaying styles that the buyer doesn't have to crack open at home
to see. (Marilynn K. Yee/The New York Times)
</P>
