<HEADER>
A9143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-IMUS-PRODUCER-NYT &LR;      05-29 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMUS-PRODUCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMUS PRODUCER MCGUIRK DISMISSES `HUMOR GESTOPO' 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This gab session with Bernard McGuirk, one of New
York talk radio's hairraising personalities working with shock jock
Don Imus, is conducted inside a claustrophobic bunker-like studio
at WFAN and begins with his own vocal binge-and-purge session.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk, for 13 years the producer of the wildly _ make that
wickedly _ popular ``Imus in the Morning,'' says its purpose is to
get the expletives out of the way sooner so he can be more
articulate later.
</P>
<P>
   You go, guy. After all, you've been up swilling caffeine since
3:45 a.m. and spilling insults on the air since 5.
</P>
<P>
   So the tape recorder is switched off and McGuirk, shrieking like
an X-rated Richard Simmons in front of a transfixed class of two _
a reporter and a photographer _ gets the nasties out of his system.
And he has significant fun, apparently, expelling them before
smoothing his dress-down-Friday chinos and settling into a squeaky
executive chair from which, between PG-rated answers, he
alternately yanks at and shoves away his microphone like a toddler
confronting a spoonful of vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, McGuirk, who calls Imus his lord, master and
mentor, and happily submits to being labeled ``a bald-headed
stooge'' by the boss in return for being permitted to pay that
homage, was once an altar boy back in the South Bronx _ and wore a
jacket and tie to Cardinal Hayes High School. Easier to believe,
perhaps, is an anecdote about how the producer's mother used to
routinely scrub out his mouth with soap when she caught him
uttering forbidden epithets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it happened to everybody,'' McGuirk says, noting
that it hasn't happened yet to his own children, 7 and 4, but
adding that he'll be armed and ready if verbal insurrection invades
their Lido Beach, N.Y., household. ``And I won't be using wimpy
soap, either. No Irish Spring,'' sneers McGuirk, whose strict Irish
immigrant parents ``came off the boat with barely two nickels to
rub together.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, other authority figures, CBS new correspondent Mike
Wallace among them, have suggested that the mouthy McGuirk, now 39
and coaching Little League in suburbia in his spare time, has again
qualified for the soap treatment despite his age. Only this time
McGuirk's alleged transgression is bigotry, not blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently unsettled by McGuirk's irreverent parodies of black
sports stars _ notably the New Jersey Nets' Jayson Williams _ and
McGuirk's embellishments to Imus' periodically toxic diatribes,
Wallace charged publicly that McGuirk ``glories in the role of
resident bigot'' on the program, and an online opinion journal
recently seconded the assault.
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk, who describes himself and Imus as equal opportunity
satirists and their subjects as fair game for verbal evisceration,
begs to differ. He mutters that a defanged and declawed Imus show
would pack all the punch of National Public Radio and alienate Imus
listeners: ``They don't want to hear nice guys: Nice guys are a
dime a dozen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he thinks of his humor as mean, he said, just cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't glory in anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the times he refers to the New York Knicks, his least
favorite NBA team, as chest-bumping pimps, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's meant to be descriptive, not pejorative. If the NBA were
peopled by a bunch of Romanians, we'd be making fun of Romanians.
To not satirize someone just because of their race, I think that
would be patronizing and racist in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's thesis fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, I'm not a bigot,'' said McGuirk, who said
he put himself through the College of Mount St. Vincent in
Riverdale by driving a cab, after his father, a city bus driver,
kicked McGuirk out when he was 18. He earned ``a fluff degree'' in
communications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived amongst blacks all my life,'' he says of his childhood
in the James Monroe Houses, where, he said, white Irish boys were a
minority. ``I lived in Long Beach in a co-op where the directory
read like Schindler's List, for crying out loud. Yes, I arrive at
the studio at 5 a.m. each day, but before I do, on my way out I
shine my lawn jockeys, and then I stop at the cemetery and knock
over Jewish tombstones. Oh, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Wallace, he says: ``People can be so humorless: That's what
Mike Wallace is, part of the humor Gestapo. The humor Gestapo _
hey, I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuirk says he and Imus, who hired him at WNBC in 1987, police
themselves on what is and isn't offensive . Here is what McGuirk
said they consider off-limits: ``Overt racism, making fun of
cripples or people with cancer, Christopher Reeve jokes . . .
there's definitely a line.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that McGuirk set out to become a wise guy in what he calls
Imus' Greek Chorus of sycophants and lackeys. He said he just
didn't want to spend his life driving a taxi. After being thrown
out by his dad in a rift that lasted a decade, McGuirk said he
spent four years with ``hoodlums,'' entered college at 22, and had
an internship at NBC where, on his first day, Imus made a lasting
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a big drug and alcohol problem then, and he was running
around the station in his boxer underwear screaming and cursing at
the top of lungs,'' McGuirk recalls. ``And of course I thought,
`that's the man I want to spend the next 20 years with.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
