r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     05-29 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSS: `A FAIRY TALE SEASON'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jerry Buss tonight will be sitting in his B level
luxury box suite at Staples Center, peering nervously down at a
garish spectacle he helped create.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the Lakers will be flanked by his designated date
for the evening, for sure to be a skimpily attired woman barely out
of her teens. Seated behind him will be his top Laker adviser,
Jerry West. Seated around him will be an eclectic cluster of
people---team sponsors, old friends, millionaire tycoons,
professional hangers-on and at least five or six striking ladies
limoed straight from Hef's (that's Hugh Hefner to those not hip)
Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   With several aides always nearby to cater to his every need and
whim, Buss cuts the royal figure of a potentate, with the vast new
downtown arena being his principality.
</P>
<P>
   A strong case can be made that Buss, whose team can qualify for
the NBA finals tonight by beating the Portland Trail Blazers, is
the greatest athletic proprietor in Los Angeles history, although
I'm sure Walter O'Malley advocates would offer a stern dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Since Buss took control of the Lakers in 1979, the team has won
five world championships and become one of the most glamorous
franchises on the American sporting landscape.
</P>
<P>
   During his watch, the Lakers have posted the best regular season
record in the NBA in winning more than 67 percent (1143-547) of
their games in a glowing tribute to Buss' deft administrative
touch.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a Peter O'Malley, Buss never has been shy about spending
huge chunks of money to sign a high-profile superstar the ilk of a
Shaquille O'Neal. Unlike a Donald Sterling or Georgia Frontiere, he
never has turned his team into comedic canon fodder for late-night
TV hosts. Unlike an Al Davis, he has not become smitten with
himself from his team's success and become prone to making
disastrous decisions because of obstinacy spawned by an
uncontrollable ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry West,'' Jerry Buss says simply when you ask him the
reason for the Lakers' dominance across the seasons. ``He has been
responsible for putting together our teams. I don't think there's
ever been a greater judge of basketball personnel than Jerry. It's
incredible how he's been able to come with good players in the
draft even though we've usually always been picking in the late
rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   This is true, but Jerry Buss also hasn't for the most part
interfered with West, an unusual development in an era when so many
of those in control of sports franchises meddle disastrously, as
the Fox bumblers did with the Dodgers in their bizarre
excommunication of Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Buss did a couple years ago prevent West from acquiring the
All Star shooting guard, Mitch Richmond, but he has green lighted
West on most other moves, including the off-season luring of Phil
Jackson out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This so far has been a fairy tale season for us, and I think
you have to give a lot of the credit to Phil Jackson,'' says Buss.
``I honestly thought it would take Phil three or four years before
we reached the level we have this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just look what he's done with this team. Shaq is a different
player, and wins the MVP trophy. Kobe (Bryant) is a different
player, and no one is laughing anymore when people say he could
become another Michael (Jordan). The Lakers have evolved into a
different team under Phil. They have a cohesiveness and motivation
that was lacking before, and I think you can attribute such a
change to Phil's coaching. He's done just a great, great job.''
</P>
<P>
   At halftime at a recent playoff game, I met Buss in his suite,
and we walked down a nearby stairway to the Staples Center's cigar
room, where Buss dragged on a cigarette as I asked him questions.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, he was accompanied by an attractive, young female,
who happens to be a waitress at a Seal Beach tavern that has the
same name as that of the former Dodger ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Buss is now in his mid 60s, but he seems to me to be as
energetic as when I first interviewed 21 years ago a few days after
he had bought the Lakers, Kings, Forum and a 13,000-acre Kern
County ranch from Jack Kent Cooke for $67.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Buss was a wealthy man then, but he's a lot wealthier now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can sell the Lakers tomorrow for more than $500
million,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you miss the Forum?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Forum had a great charisma and tradition about it,'' he
replied ``I have some great memories there. Staples Center is
totally different. I think it has taken the fans awhile to adjust
to the change. It's so much larger. But I've noticed in the last
month or two how the place has started to become much louder and
how the fans seem to now really be enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you enjoying these Lakers as much as you did the Magic
Johnson-Kareem Abdul-Jabbar Showtime Lakers?'' I wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a completely different type of team,'' he said. ``The
Showtime teams liked to fast break, and score quickly. This Laker
team has a set-up type of offense. I never thought I'd enjoy a
half-court game, but I'm certainly enjoying these Lakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss' bank account also is flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated the Lakers could gross up to $150 million this
season, with perhaps a third of that winding up in Buss' private
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   While corporate conglomerates have taken over many athletic
franchises, they apparently soon won't be assuming control of the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to give up control of the Lakers,'' said West.
``They're my passion. And I'm enjoying all this too much. If our
key players stay healthy, we figure to have a lot more seasons of
fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
