<SLUG> BC-KOREANAIR-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN AIR PILOTS SET A STRIKE DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pilots at beleaguered Korean Air have voted to go on strike
Wednesday if the South Korean government and the airline do not
recognize their union.
</P>
<P>
   A strike would further damage the credibility of South Korea's
national airline, which flies to four East Coast destinations. Last
year, safety concerns prompted Delta Air Lines to suspend a
code-sharing arrangement with Korean Air.
</P>
<P>
   Korean Air has expanded rapidly over the last three decades,
from an eight-plane local carrier to the world's 13th-largest
airline. But its reputation has been tarnished by several fatal
accidents in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   One was the 1997 crash of a Boeing 747 that was trying to land
in Guam, an accident that killed 228 people. Another was the 1999
crash of an MD-11 cargo plane as it took off from Shanghai, China;
that accident killed all three crew members, and about 40 people on
the ground were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
   The airline has spent more than $100 million on safety training,
hiring Americans to run its safety program. But aviation
specialists say Korean Air has been hampered by a system in which
many junior crew members don't feel free to challenge or question
the actions of superior officers.
</P>
<P>
   An internal Korean Air survey of pilots in 1998 found cases of a
captain hitting a first officer for making mistakes, and of crew
members failing to discuss the expected weather or the amount of
fuel necessary for a journey because the captain alone was
responsible for such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A strike would devastate the airline financially, with losses of
about $11 million a day, and further weaken consumer confidence,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government doesn't want to mar Korea's image by having its
national carrier grounded,'' said Lim Dong Soo, an airline analyst
at Nomura Securities in Seoul. ``Plus, Korean Air will suffer
considerable losses if their planes don't take off. The pressure
will be on all parties involved to avoid a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Korean Air has three nonstop flights a week from Seoul to
Boston, using Boeing 747-400 aircraft, according to the
Massachusetts Port Authority, which owns and operates Logan.
</P>
<P>
   The flights, which arrive on Tuesday, Thursday, and Saturday,
return to Seoul via Dulles International Airport near Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean Air Pilots Union said 1,128 of 1,247 union pilot
members have voted to go on a strike that's scheduled to begin
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government refuses to recognize our union by 6 p.m. May
30, we have no choice but to strike as of 6 a.m. on Wednesday,''
said Ha Hyo Youl, a spokesman for the union.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, in an attempt to placate the pilots, filed an
application with the government to end the pilots' civil service
status, which has been a major stumbling block to the pilots' union
recognition. Under Korean law, civil servants cannot unionize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done everything that we can legally do to avoid a
strike,'' said Yonni Woo, a Korean Air spokeswoman. ``We have a
channel of dialogue with the union that is open 24 hours a day. But
now, when all is said and done, it's up to the government to
recognize the union.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
