u k BC-EDIT-BANKRUPTCY-NYT &LR;      05-29 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BANKRUPTCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A GIFT FOR THE CREDIT CARD INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, May 30:
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans had a decent impulse in seeking to
tighten bankruptcy laws because filings were soaring and cheats
were seeking bankruptcy to evade creditors. But the kernel of good
purpose has now mushroomed into House and Senate bills stuffed with
gifts to the credit card industry, which has gained leverage in
Congress through millions of dollars in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are now putting together a proposal that would
combine elements from each bill. It would impose a rigid means test
for determining which petitioners could afford to repay creditors,
thereby stripping judges of discretion to weigh individual cases.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to force more petitioners to file under Chapter 13,
which could require them to repay creditors at least $170 a month
for up to five years. Fewer petitioners would be allowed to file
under Chapter 7, which wipes away most debts.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal contains a few constructive ideas. It would
partially override laws in states that allow debtors to hold onto
their homes no matter how much they are worth, though the
Republicans threaten to build in loopholes. It would also put a
million-dollar cap on individual retirement accounts that debtors
could keep out of the reach of creditors.
</P>
<P>
   But the overwhelming impact would be to hurt unsophisticated
debtors and go easy on the well-heeled. The proposal fails to
override state laws that allow debtors to lock away millions in
trust, a huge benefit to the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it would make debtors repay more of their credit card debt
after they emerge from bankruptcy, forcing those on modest incomes
to put repayment to credit card companies in competition with
paying for child care. The provisions on repaying loans would force
many more people to lose vehicles needed for work.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would also make bankruptcy procedures needlessly
expensive and complicated. Yet it would do little to rein in credit
card companies _ not even forcing them to disclose on the monthly
statement how long the cardholders would need to repay loans if
they pay only the minimum due.
</P>
<P>
   Drastic measures might be justified if cheating were rampant. It
is not. A prominent study estimated that less than 4 percent of
petitioners can afford to pay creditors.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sens. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota and Patrick Leahy of
Vermont, both Democrats, have scuttled Republican efforts to attach
the proposal onto unrelated legislation where critics would get
little opportunity to amend its punitive provisions. They have
received only timid support from the White House. If President
Clinton displayed some anger, perhaps he could sidetrack the worst
features before they wind up on his desk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
