<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HOLTZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE CENTER FOUNDER EDELE HOLTZ, 82, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edele Nielsen Holtz, who helped create the Clark Center for the
Performing Arts in Manhattan and played an important role in Alvin
Ailey's early career, died on May 20 at the Asheville Health Care
Facility in Swannanoa, N.C. She was 82 and lived in Swannanoa.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz and her husband, Alwin, who died last year, became friends
with Ailey in the early 1960s when a colleague of the young
choreographer approached Holtz about rehearsal space at a new
branch of the Young Women's Christian Association on Eighth Avenue
and 53rd Street in Manhattan, where she was director of activities.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, a peppery, no-nonsense social worker, agreed and
eventually set up programs to benefit dancers, musicians and actors
working in the theater district. Many of the programs, including a
series of workshop performances for new choreographers, were
suggested by Ailey. The performances were presented at Clark
Center, a theater carved out of space that had been a hotel
ballroom. The series provided crucial exposure for young
choreographers who came of age artistically in the 1960s, '70s and
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz and her husband came to New York after working in refugee
and education programs in the Middle East for 10 years, beginning
in 1948 as field staff members of the United Nations-Quaker Project
for Palestinian Refugees in Gaza. The experience served them well
in helping Ailey as much-needed surrogate parents and de facto
booking agents and accountants in the tumultuous early days of
Ailey's company.
</P>
<P>
   During her long career with the YWCA, Holtz was also the
executive director of branches in Brooklyn and New Orleans and was
a staff member of the group's national board.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz is survived by two sisters, Greta Rikard of Salem, Va.,
and Inga Hoffman of Santa Cruz, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000529.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKW-COMETS-LIBERTY-HN     05-29 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-LIBERTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The Comets on Memorial Day hosted what is becoming an annual
celebration at Compaq Center.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an emotional affair during which the Comets hung a third
straight championship banner from the rafters and got their third
set of championship rings. And the butterflies that danced in their
stomachs kept fluttering well into a sluggishly played first half
as they battled the New York Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the result was similar to nine months before,
when the Comets beat the Liberty in the WNBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper scored the 2,000th point of her WNBA career,
Sheryl Swoopes produced a game-high 27 points, and Tina Thompson
added 15 as the Comets beat the Liberty 84-68 in their season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Weatherspoon, who beat the Comets in Game 2 of last
year's Finals with a miracle shot, passed out a game-high 13
assists. But this day, there would be no party-bashing from the
two-time WNBA Defensive Player of the Year, despite the Liberty's
fighting back from a 15-point second-half deficit to close within
six points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was a little concerned,'' said Swoopes, who sat
out almost five minutes of the second half because of leg cramps.
``But never in my mind did I think we were going to lose. I think
that's because of the players we have on this team. We're so
confident in ourselves and in each other that we're going to do
whatever it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 16,285 watched the Comets miss seven of their
first eight shots, play catch-up for 13 minutes, then come roaring
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we played the way we wanted to play, definitely
not for 40 minutes,'' said Swoopes, who missed her first 3-point
attempt, then rattled in her next four while shooting 8-for-17
overall. ``We know we have a lot of work to do. But the good thing
is it was the first game of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   When these two teams, involved in one of the hotter rivalries in
the WNBA, met in last year's championship, Weatherspoon's 52-foot
last-second bomb in the second game of the series forced a third
and deciding game. The Comets roared out of the blocks in Game 3,
faltered only slightly, then sprinted to a 59-47 victory to earn
their third WNBA title.
</P>
<P>
   They had accomplished their mission _ to pay homage to point
guard Kim Perrot, who had died of cancer two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Perrot influence was still very much in evidence Monday.
Near the top of the 1999 championship banner was the inscription,
``No. 3 for No. 10,'' a reference to Perrot's jersey number. That
same notation is on one side of the championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked out (to receive a ring), I don't know why, but
it just made me break down when I saw the `No. 3 for No. 10,'''
said Comets coach Van Chancellor. ``I'm emotionally drained right
now. I know they (the players) have got to be drained. You come out
here, (and) you relive that situation one more time. I wore my
ring, and just looking at it, yeah, I was kind of misty-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the ceremonies drained us a little bit. And then I
thought we were overanxious, trying to do good, look good in front
of all these people. Once we settled down, we played really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the early shooting woes _ and the brilliant
play of New York's Sue Wicks (14 points, six rebounds) and Tamika
Whitmore (a team-high 15 points) _ the Comets trailed 19-13 with
9:04 left until halftime.
</P>
<P>
   But a pair of free throws by Swoopes tied the score at 21, and
her 3-pointer a minute later gave them the lead for good at 24-23.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first trey of the game for the Comets, who were
0-for-7 from long range to that point. But it was not the most
significant.
</P>
<P>
   That came from Cooper with 13:29 to go in the second half,
putting the three-time league scoring champ at the 2,000-point mark
while extending the Comets' lead to 56-44.
</P>
<P>
   What problems may have existed on offense earlier seemed to have
vanished completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't flowing (earlier),'' said Thompson, who
finished with six assists and four rebounds. ``I can't put my
finger on why. It probably had to do with the ceremonies. But we
got over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets used five straight points by Cooper to go up 66-50
with 10:28 left. But following a pair of free throws by the
37-year-old shooting guard, the Comets went scoreless for 4:54.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty scored 10 straight points and pulled within 66-60 on
a 3-pointer by Becky Hammon.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon was on the bench when the Liberty made its
comeback. She re-entered the fray a short time later but was unable
to ignite a rally. A closing 13-5 run in the final 3:20 sealed the
deal for the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, we definitely pulled it together,'' said Thompson.
``We were stopping them defensively. We were getting shots and
hitting free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
