u a BC-FLA-TEACHER-SLAIN-1ST     05-29 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TEACHER-SLAIN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA TOWN HOLDS MEMORIAL FOR SLAIN TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add 6 grafs at end of story)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ After a long weekend of mourning, more than a
thousand residents of this small town gathered at a rally on Monday
to call for an end to violence and to remember a popular teacher
slain on Friday by a seventh grader.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, family and students of the teacher, Barry Grunow, 35,
held hands and encircled Bryant Park here to remember the teacher.
They prayed and talked about ways to prevent yet another school
shooting. The slogan of the rally, held aloft on banners and
printed on T-shirts was ``stop the violence and nurture the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people wore yellow ribbons around their arms and carried
signs reading slogans like ``Love your children, Lock your guns.''
Residents called on lawmakers to take gun control more seriously.
If violence could happen in their tiny community, they said, it
could happen anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part is it keeps happening,'' said Barbara Lynch, who
has lived in Lake Worth for 15 years. ``It happened to a lovely
man, to a community man.''
</P>
<P>
   As many current and former students cried and embraced each
other at the rally, they spoke about Grunow's gentle nature They
said the teacher used to lovingly tease his students, reward them
with cookies and doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kind of teacher you'll never forget because he
believed in hands-on learning,'' said Crystal Bruder, 16, a former
student. ``When we were studying Greek mythology in class, he'd
have us all dress up, and he made me dress up as a tree for
scenery. His lessons were unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning with him was fun,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But students said they would remember Grunow mostly as a friend,
a teacher who tried to be approachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends would go to him when they had problems,''
said Amber Hart, 12, a student of Grunow's. ``We felt comfortable
talking to him. He was so nice. I don't understand why this
happened to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Amber said she also knew 13-year-old Nathaniel Brazill, who is
being held in the death of Grunow.
</P>
<P>
   The boy had been sent home from school on Friday, the last day
of school before summer, for throwing water balloons. According to
police, he returned two hours later with a handgun and shot Grunow
once in the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate was in my advanced math class,'' she said. ``He's a nice
boy. I don't know why he did that to Mr. Grunow. It's all so
confusing.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said on Monday that two boys had told them that
Nathaniel showed them a gun at his home on May 23, said Lt. Raychel
Houston, a spokeswoman for the Lake Worth Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, while searching Nathaniel's room, the police found
computer games and magazines featuring helicopters and guns, which
suggested that Nathaniel was interested in weapons and the
military, Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Barry Krischer said he would call for a grand
jury this week to consider the boy's case. ``It is my intent to try
him as an adult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Helaine Rayman, a Lake Worth resident who organized Monday's
rally, said the solution to school shootings like the one at Lake
Worth Middle School was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's start listening to our children,'' she said. ``Let's be
there for them and nurture them like we are supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunow, who was married with two young children, will be buried
here on Tuesday morning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
