<HEADLINE>
`WONDERFUL MISSION' FOR SPACE SHUTTLE ATLANTIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Gliding through darkness, the shuttle Atlantis and its
seven astronauts touched down in Florida early Monday, bringing
their successful space station repair mission to a close.
</P>
<P>
   With commander Jim Halsell and pilot Scott ``Doc'' Horowitz at
the controls, Atlantis rolled to a landing at NASA's Kennedy Space
Center at 1:20 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's bad hours for the arrival, but we are certainly
glad to be back home,'' Halsell told space agency dignitaries and
ground control teams that assembled on the runway. ``Thanks for the
ride uphill and downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusts, which had threatened to postpone the landing,
diminished to well within NASA's stringent limits for a nighttime
landing. The five-man, two-woman crew arrived in darkness for only
the 14th time in 98 shuttle missions that date back to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Halsell, Horowitz, flight engineer Jeff Williams, mission
specialists Jim Voss, Susan Helms, Mary Ellen Weber and Russian
cosmonaut Yuri Usachev spent Memorial Day in Florida undergoing
routine medical exams, resting and celebrating the holiday with
close family members.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled to return to Houston Tuesday. NASA's Johnson
Space Center plans a brief public welcoming ceremony at Ellington
Field in Clear Lake about 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day mission proved a much needed shot in the arm for the
U.S.-led, 16-nation international space station program.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly efforts have been stalled primarily by Russian economic
and rocket problems since the first two components were joined in
Earth orbit in December 1998. As a result of the shuttle crew's
efforts, the yet-to-be-inhabited station is poised to receive the
long overdue Russian crew module.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts overhauled a power-generation system faltering
because of the delays, revived the communications system, enhanced
the ventilation and fire-detection systems and boosted the
station's altitude by nearly 30 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a wonderful mission. Everything worked just right,''
said Ron Dittemore, NASA's shuttle program manager.
</P>
<P>
   The big crew module is slated for a July launch by the Russians.
Those plans are contingent, though, on a pair of successful test
flights of the module's Proton launcher.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis returned in good mechanical shape, though its
protective exterior was scared by ice fragments from the May 19
liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis is tentatively scheduled to lift off again in early
September, which will require a rapid turnaround by ground crews.
Atlantis will haul supplies and equipment for the crew module on
its next mission.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
