<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT &LR;      05-29 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEVILS TAKE STOCK, AND LIKE THEIR CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ From coach Larry Robinson down to the
fourth-line players, the New Jersey Devils said Monday that they
match up well with the Dallas Stars and are confident they can
defeat the defending champions in the Stanley Cup finals, which
begin here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team grew together so much in the last series,'' Randy
McKay said of the Devils. ``It has given us so much confidence that
we believe we can accomplish anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils don't seem upset by observers who believe that Dallas
will successfully defend its cup. Perhaps those opinions were based
on the fact that Western Conference teams had captured the cup the
past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have an abundance of experienced players, including
three former Montreal captains in Guy Carbonneau, Kirk Muller and
Mike Keane. And the Stars have snipers like Brett Hull, Mike Modano
and Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these teams are closely matched, and it will probably
come down to the special teams,'' Robinson said. ``Both teams are
built along the same lines believing that the game should be played
a certain way. I think it'll be an exciting series.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did in the previous rounds against the top lines of
Florida, Toronto and Philadelphia, Robinson will most likely use
his top line of Patrik Elias, Jason Arnott and Petr Sykora to
counter the Stars' scoring line of Modano, Hull and Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a few great players on their team that can rip the
puck in,'' Elias said, referring to Modano's line. ``We just got to
play smart when we're up against these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also said he would be using the defensive tandem of
Scott Stevens and Brian Rafalski against the Modano line. That
pairing helped contain Florida's Pavel Bure, Toronto's Mats Sundin
and Philadelphia's top line in the first three rounds of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has been the Devils' most dominant player in the
postseason. He has a number of memorable playoff hits, like the one
on Slava Kozlov against Detroit in 1995, when the Devils captured
the cup. His latest one may have ended the career of Philadelphia's
Eric Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Stevens, the Devils will counter Dallas' snipers and
experience with youth and exuberance. The Devils also have more
balanced scoring. While the Stars do not have a player with more
than two goals after Modano and Hull (with nine each) and
Nieuwendyk (with six), the Devils have six players with three or
more goals from players not on the top line, which has produced 17.
</P>
<P>
   Elias leads the Devils with seven goals in the playoffs, Sykora
has six, and Arnott, Claude Lemieux, Scott Gomez and Scott
Niedermayer have four. Bobby Holik, Alexander Mogilny and Sergei
Nemchinov have three apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more balance and we have commitment,'' said John
Madden, a defensive specialist, who has two goals in the playoffs
despite missing three games in the previous round because of an
injury to his right knee. ``All I can say is that we've challenged
some people in these playoffs, and we'll continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've come together as a team. It's a great feeling to
look around and see that the next guy is as committed as you are.''
</P>
<P>
   One of four rookies on the Devils _ Gomez, Rafalski and Colin
White are the others _ Madden said he was impressed by the way all
the players on the Devils had committed themselves to Robinson's
system and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard to get that at the pro level,'' Madden said,
``because there are so many egos involved. That's why I believe in
this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
