<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COOPER-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS GET DEFENSIVE WITH COOPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you want to play for Michael Cooper, the name
of the game is defense.
</P>
<P>
   The former Laker star of the Showtime era made a name for
himself, guarding some of the NBA's best offensive players, notably
former Boston Celtics legend Larry Bird, now coach of the Indiana
Pacers, Walter Davis, George Gervin, Dr. J., and Andrew Toney.
</P>
<P>
   With his slender frame, quick feet and long arms, Cooper always
stood his defensive ground, backing down to no one. He was known
for coming out of nowhere and blocking shots at the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Defensive Player of the Year in 1987, when he won the
fourth of five NBA titles with the Lakers, and was a five-time
all-defensive first team member.
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth head coach of the Sparks, Cooper is again putting
defense first.
</P>
<P>
   Just like he did, Cooper wants his players collectively to deny
and take away opponents strong points and get them out of their
comfort zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got all the credit for doing it, but defense is a team
effort and I wouldn't have been able to be the player that I was
defensively had it not been for my team,'' said Cooper, who was
surrounded by Magic Johnson, Kareem Abdul Jabbar, James Worthy,
Byron Scott, and A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some good defensive standout people on this team. I
think Tamecka (Dixon) is very good when she gets into it, Mwadi
Mabika is very good, Ukari Figgs is good in her own right, and then
La'Keisha Frett. We're going to ask them to take on some tough
assignments.''
</P>
<P>
   As the assistant coach under Orlando Woolridge last year, about
25 percent of practice was reserved for defensive schemes and the
rest was offense, he said. This year, it's the opposite. With
shooters like Mabika and Dixon and Olympians Lisa Leslie and
DeLisha Milton on the court, Cooper felt safe to focus primarily on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But to play defense you need to be in top physical condition, so
one of the first things Cooper established before the players even
arrived at training camp was to talk to each one about being in
shape once practice began. Everyone seemed to follow his
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Trimmer, showing more muscle tone than ever, players like Dixon,
Allison Feaster, Mabika, and Clarisse Machanguana took Cooper's
words to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so important, because a coach may have all kind of
plans and philosophies and techniques that he wants us to do, but
if we're out of shape, shame,'' Machanguana said. ``He can only
work for so long. He's been running everything in practice hard,
hard, hard.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Cooper, there are three basic elements that are
essential to teaching a player good defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a player that understands how to play defense
and the mechanics of it,'' he said. ``Then after that I think it
would be desire. You have to want to desire to play defense. Your
coach can get on you all he wants and if you're going through the
motions, that doesn't do anything. Last, but not least, athleticism
and we have some athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the players he has, Cooper is looking to play full-court
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kind of the way we played on the road in Charlotte and
Seattle. I think we have a good basis. As long as we come out and
stay focused. And that was the key (Friday) is that we didn't play
focused, defensively,'' Cooper said, referring to the 75-69 to
Seattle in their second meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is we don't take too many steps back. I think we did a
great job on the road. Those were steps that we weren't expecting
to take, but we made them.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time he understands the challenges the veterans are
experiencing, especially Leslie, Dixon, and Mwadi, who are now
playing for their fourth coach in as many years with the Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Cooper's experience with the Lakers was the primary
reason why Sparks president Johnny Buss hired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly a lot of his experience I watched from the stands,
since I know what it was all about, the Pat Riley years, the Earvin
Johnson years,'' said Johnny Buss, the son of Laker owner Jerry
Buss.
</P>
<P>
   ``How he had to follow Earvin's lead and do it respectfully and
it with an enormous amount of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Buss said he believes the Sparks' game of musical coaches
will end with the hiring of Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm comfortable with him,'' Buss said. ``It's actually
kind of scary. It's like I'm back with my family. I'm comfortable
that I could never kick my family out of the house. That's how I
feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
