<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS' BIG FELLA SHOULD KEEP HIS SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marcus Camby, you break the news to him. ``Not me,''
Camby said. ``I wouldn't want to be the one to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then you do it, Chris Dudley. You took his place in the starting
lineup. It is your duty. ``Sorry, you got the wrong guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone, please, tell Patrick Ewing before he comes back and _
heaven forbid _ plays. Monopolizes the ball. Clogs the lane. Kills
the Knicks' hopes of making the finals. Ruins the season.
</P>
<P>
   After 13 postseasons, 131 playoff games _ more than 2,500 points
and 1,300 rebounds each May and June since 1988 _ this is hard to
say:
</P>
<P>
   Take a seat, Big Fella. You heard us. Bum foot or not, you're on
the bench for the rest of the Eastern Conference finals against the
Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   And you can stay there _ until the Knicks need a clutch hoop and
touch foul in the final 30 seconds of an elimination game. At which
point, we will again serenade you, apologize for ever cursing your
name and realize how infantile it was to think the Knicks could do
this without you, that somehow they are better off when you're not
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime fan wanted to know at halftime if Jeff Van Gundy is
secretly making Ewing's injury sound worse than it is, the idea
being that the Knicks' coach understands that his team matches up
better with Indiana without Ewing. That, rather than saving the Big
Fella the embarrassment of playing him 20 paltry minutes, he now
has the luxury of an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rik Smits got on the Take Your Sweet Time, Pat bandwagon.
Asked if the Knicks are more potent against the Pacers without
Ewing, Smits replied: ``Sure seems that way, doesn't it? They
really stepped up their game, all the guys, individually.''
</P>
<P>
   The most bandied-about statistic after Game 4 was not the
Knicks' 41-32 rebounding edge. It was their 5-1 record against
Indiana in complete games in the playoffs without Ewing the past
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what makes me laugh about that number now is how the
media can manipulate it,'' Van Gundy said. ``He played seven
minutes in the last game at Indiana, but we count that as with him.
Plus, he's never played a home game in that stretch. That makes it
look a little better, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy added: ``We play well when we share the ball and we
play inside-out. We have four guys we basically go into the post:
Pat, Larry, Latrell and Allan. We play off them. So when he is out,
we still have three post-up guys that we can go to.''
</P>
<P>
   All debate aside, the Knicks swung the ball around the perimeter
as if they were in concert on Monday, finding the open man for
either a 3-pointer or a layup like they had yet to do with such
precision all season.
</P>
<P>
   If Larry Johnson was not waiting on the right baseline to knock
down a pendulum-swinging shot, Kurt Thomas was tunneling through
the nooks and crannies of the Pacers' front line to score a tough
layup. They worked like a machine, five players acting as one.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Thomas looked Allan Houston off as he came around
a screen, like a quarterback faking a handoff to a running back. He
calmly stepped back and knocked down a 15-footer, with all the
confidence Larry Bird had in his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 was more about adrenaline than great basketball. The
Knicks completed all the requisite tasks and received a huge
performance from Latrell Sprewell to snag a victory Saturday. Game
4 was about a team playing to its strength without Ewing, pushing
the ball upcourt as fast as its could, scoring 12 points on the
break, using its speed instead of its guile.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. The Knicks made 10 of 14 3-pointers and they won
by 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one blessing about Patrick being out, it's that
we're fortunate we've been through it before,'' Dudley said. ``We
had to learn to play without him a year ago. But everybody knows we
need him. That's not even a question.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sprewell: ``If someone said you're stronger against the
Pacers without Patrick, well, I don't think that means anything.
It's not fair to say we can win without him in there. He was so
effective in Game 1 when he was in there. We need him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said he may play on Wednesday night in Game 5 in
Indianapolis. The Knicks will probably not be as unpredictable, the
seat-of-their-pants unit that has confounded the Pacers in New York
over the weekend. But they will still be better. It's not even
worth debating at 3 in the morning.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
