<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-ROBINSON-LADN     05-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROBINSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS' ROBINSON IS NO SOFT TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. - Although he was sitting, Larry Robinson
still towered over the packed room.
</P>
<P>
   There was the same proud head, the same soft voice talking
strategy as his New Jersey Devils prepared for tonight's opening
game of the Stanley Cup Finals against the defending champion
Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how he tried to keep the focus away from himself,
Robinson's story is not one strictly about X's and O's.
</P>
<P>
   A year has passed since he was fired as coach of the Kings, and
though Robinson looks no different, so much has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot in the past year, how about the past week?'' he asked
with a smile, his team in the finals only after becoming the first
to overcome a 3-1 deficit to win a conference title.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible, however, to look ahead at this best-of-seven
series with the Stars without looking back at Robinson's 12-month
odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was fired by the Kings at the end of the 1998-99
season, partly because he got them to the playoffs just once in
four seasons. He was criticized for being too soft on his players.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is considered the lightning rod for a team just four
victories from a championship, the same team that fell apart under
head coach Robbie Ftorek with only a month left in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, I am very proud of where I am this year as opposed
to where I was a year ago,'' Robinson said. ``I felt I didn't truly
finish what I started, didn't get the chance to finish what I
started. It's nice to be able to prove I'm not what everybody said
I was, that I was too soft and not able to be a coach because of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings captain Rob Blake says that was never the problem. But
there was little question the team disintegrated in the middle of
last season after Robinson publicly questioned his desire to coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about all that,'' said Blake, who played beside
Robinson in his rookie year. ``I learned so much from him. But I
know we just didn't play for him. We had injuries, but the truth is
we just didn't play. I've always thought he would be a great coach
if he had a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet those close to Robinson aren't sure whether he'll return
next year, Stanley Cup ring or not. The team recently was sold for
$175 million to a group that includes the New York Yankees and New
Jersey Nets and there is a good chance Robinson will walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll back with the organization, but as head coach I
don't know,'' said Devils spokesman Rick Minch, who held a similar
position with the Kings during Robinson's first year in Los
Angeles. `` ``But I think he is more comfortable in this situation,
at this point. But that's just my opinion. The L.A. experience was
great because he learned a lot about coaching. And now he is in a
different situation here, applying everything he learned there.''
</P>
<P>
   After his firing from the Kings, Robinson became an assistant to
Ftorek, who also once coached the Kings. This was Robinson's second
tour with New Jersey - he helped Jacques Lamaire win the Stanley
Cup in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Devils began to crumble under Ftorek's tight reign
in the final month of the regular season, Robinson was asked to
step in. New Jersey, which was bumped in the first round the two
previous s The Devils also were desperate for the strong presence
that the former 6-foot-5 defenseman with six Stanley Cup titles
could provide.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson restored the team's passion and confidence, which
continued to soar during early round victories over Florida and
Toronto. When all that stalled early in the Eastern Conference
finals against Philadelphia, a different side of Robinson emerged.
</P>
<P>
   He unloaded on his players after Game 4, a tirade that was
widely criticized, but now is credited with turning the series
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he told us was coming from his heart,'' Devils
goaltender Martin Brodeur said. ``It touched a lot of guys'
feelings. He's really nice to be around and it's easy to play
hockey for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't see him react like that and not listen. It was great
for him to be able to spit it out. Sometimes coaches have a hard
time getting their messages through, but he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Robinson stresses that the finals ``should be about the
players and nothing else,'' there are plenty of subplots.
</P>
<P>
   - Robinson and Stars general manager Bob Gainey were the leaders
of Montreal Canadien teams that won four consecutive Stanley Cups
from 1976-1979. The teams in this series, which will be gritty and
hard-hitting, appear to be direct descendants of the Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   - Although the Devils are playing for the sport's highest
achievement, captain Scott Stevens still is reeling emotionally
from a Game 7 hit he put on Philadelphia's Eric Lindros. The hit
led to the Lindros' sixth concussion and might end his career.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is the thread that runs through it all. He has helped
Stevens restore his sagging play in the past month and will be a
focal point in getting Stevens' head back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened to me when I was a player,'' said Robinson, who
ended the career of Edmonton's Craig Simpson with a hip check
behind the net. ``It is a difficult thing, but he has to put it
past him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Robinson already has had a Hall of Fame career, the
next two weeks could establish a reputation he never got with the
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of person who looks at things that way,'' he
said. ``I don't really look at it that I was a scapegoat. They
wanted to make changes. That's this business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
