<HEADLINE>
MUMTAZ CONTINUES SUCCESS AT LONE STAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY RAMPELLINI 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Mumtaz remained undefeated at Lone Star
Park at Grand Prairie yesterday when she rallied from last to
capture the $200,000 WinStar Distaff, one of seven stakes that made
up the second annual Lone Star Million Day.
</P>
<P>
   The unique program is the richest day of racing in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a fantastic race,'' said Tom Amoss, who
trains Mumtaz for a partnership that includes sports agent Randy
Hendricks. ``It looked a lot like last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Mumtaz employed the same sweeping tactics to capture
the $150,000 Walmac Lone Star Oaks. For her come-from-behind
victory in the Oaks, she was voted Champion Turf Horse at Lone Star
Park in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The WinStar Distaff, however, might rate as an even stronger
performance for Mumtaz as she rallied against slow fractions to get
past starting highweight Evening Promise. The victory came
following a nine-month break from racing, during which she
underwent surgery to remove a bone chip from her left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old Mumtaz is back,'' said Amoss, who late last week
decided to fly Mumtaz from Kentucky for the WinStar Distaff. ``Not
missing any work has a little bit to do with making this race. We
also felt the race came up at the right distance, and that it fell
at the right time. And, she'd already had success over the
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendricks was unable to see Mumtaz win the Oaks last year
because he was on vacation with his wife in Canada. He made it a
point to be in town for yesterday's race. ``I flew up this
afternoon,'' he said. ``When I watched her make her move around the
far turn, I figure we've got it unless some other horse just
outguns us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumtaz trailed the field before starting to pass horses midway
on the final turn. She proceeded to run down Evening Promise
nearing the wire, and went on to a three-quarters of a length
victory in the mile race in a time of 1:37.28.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I asked her she really took off,'' said Victor Espinoza,
who was aboard Mumtaz for one of his two stakes victories
yesterday. ``When she comes from behind, she's very tough to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumtaz earned $120,000 for her victory, which improved her
career bankroll to $281,065. She has won five of 10 starts, and as
third choice in the wagering returned $10.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
