<SLUG> BC-HKN-YOUNGSTARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' FIRST-TIMERS SAVOR CUP OPPORTUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J._ Stars winger Brenden Morrow has a chance
to do in fewer than 90 games what Colorado defenseman Ray Bourque
hasn't done in more than 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Win a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a chance to do it my first year,'' Morrow said.
``Guys like Bourque have been waiting 21 years to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Stars, the venerable NHL defenseman won't win his
first Stanley Cup this season.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Stars, three other longtime NHL players with a
combined 40 seasons _ winger Scott Thornton and defensemen Sylvain
Cote and Dave Manson _ are in the position to win their first
Stanley Cup. And all of them are grateful, not only for being saved
from losing situations in midseason trades, but specifically this
chance at a Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we used that, as a group, for motivation in the last
series,'' Stars winger Brett Hull said. ``All anyone wanted to talk
about was Bourque. We sat down as a group and said we got Manson,
Thornton, Cote and some young kids that haven't been there before.
Why is \RBourque\S any more special than those guys? We want to
take our guys for them as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those guys have come close before, but none of them
really knew what it was like until the Stars defeated Colorado on
Saturday night in Game 7 of the Western Conference Finals. None of
them knew they would get this close. Ever. They were simply hoping.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get close you wonder how many more chances you'll get
as your career moves on,'' said Manson, who was traded to the Stars
with Cote on Feb. 8 from the Chicago Blackhawks. ``I am definitely
fortunate. The furthest I've been in the playoffs is the
semifinals, and I've been there three times. It's frustrating. It's
mentally and physically draining and then not to reach your goal,
it's devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   So devastating that simply reaching the Stanley Cup Finals is a
relief? Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people phoned me from back home about that
\Rrelief\S,'' said Thornton, who was acquired Jan. 22 in a trade
with Montreal. ``I had mixed emotions. I was elated and happy we
won for a chance to play for the cup. At the same time, I wasn't
celebrating too much. We have four more wins to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when you are traded to a team defending the
Stanley Cup. Manson, Cote and Thornton are expected to enjoy this,
but none are ready to proclaim this run an unequivocal success.
</P>
<P>
   Only winning four more games does that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the players in the dressing room really control the
team in that there is a lot of peer pressure on each other to
compete higher,'' Thornton said. ``That's a fun way to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when you are a few games from realizing the fruition
of a lifelong goal, any way is a fun way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 15 years to get to this point,'' Cote said.
``Certain people will never have a chance to be here. I am lucky
... four wins to go is the chance of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how young or old.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2257EDT &QL; 
