<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGHORNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEACHED-BLOND LONGHORNS GET AN INCENTIVE FOR OMAHA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If the Texas Longhorns make it to the
College World Series, there will be a new blond pitching for the
Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   When the Longhorns (43-19) arrived in Tempe, Ariz., for the
opening round of the NCAA regionals last week, they were greeted by
former Texas All-American Greg Swindell, now with the Diamondbacks,
who delivered a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know what to say to you guys,'' Swindell
began. ``So my wife said, `Just tell them what you're always
telling me _ that you bleed orange and loved pitching at Texas more
than anything else.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was the gist of the speech, which Swindell capped with a
promise: If the team makes it to Omaha, he will bleach his hair
blond.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, in a show of team unity, the Longhorns all became
bleached blonds _ then lost two of three games in the Big 12
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But they came back Sunday to defeat top-seeded host Arizona
State twice, winning the regional and earning a host spot for the
Super Regional round this weekend. They will face Penn State
(45-17) in a best-of-three series beginning at 7 p.m. Friday at
Disch-Falk Field for the right to go to Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   They were guided by several bleached heroes in Tempe _ including
third starter Phil Seibel, who missed two months with an arm injury
but emerged to beat the Sun Devils in Sunday's first game, with
help from closer Charlie Thames, who picked up his 19th save.
</P>
<P>
   The clinching 9-7 victory in the nightcap was powered by a
three-run home run from catcher Ryan Hubele _ who grew up in nearby
Paradise Valley and had a grand homecoming, hitting .529 and
earning regional MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   When ASU rallied in the ninth, Thames was gassed, having thrown
50 pitches in the afternoon game. So Texas brought in second
starter Beau Hale, who had lost a tough 3-1 decision on Saturday.
He struck out the last two Sun Devils to close it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really happy for this team,'' said Texas coach Augie
Garrido, ``because of how hard they've worked and what they had to
do to reach this point.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
