<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER STILL LISTED AS DAY-TO-DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Depending on interpretation, it remains
a mystery whether Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner's sprained right
knee will allow him to play tonight in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He did not skate during the team's practice yesterday,
suggesting he likely won't play. He was clearly ordered to guard
against leaking information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defer all questions of that nature to coach Hitchcock,''
Langenbrunner said. ``I'm day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock suggested Langenbrunner is improving faster than
expected, which suggests ...
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 50-50 right now,'' Hitchcock said. ``We were gearing more
toward Game 2. We are going to skate him \Rthis\S morning and see
how it feels. He is coming along fast. He is a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner injured his knee in Game 5 against Colorado and
missed Games 6 and 7.  &QL; 
Chambers might retire
</P>
<P>
   When Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers last played on Oct. 8, he
didn't pay much attention to details.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he wishes he had. It might have been his last.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, who missed all but four regular-season games with a
knee injury and had neck surgery a month ago, said there is a good
chance he might have to retire after this season. The knee hasn't
responded well to treatment. He said he would see a couple of
doctors in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go check out doctors to see if they have something else
they can think of,'' Chambers said. ``I'm only 33 and I think I can
play. I'll give it one more shot this summer, and if I try to skate
and it doesn't come around that will be it.''  &QL; 
No wasted penalties
</P>
<P>
   The Devils enter the Stanley Cup Finals as the least- penalized
team in the playoffs, averaging 8.9 minutes a game. After watching
the Stars put together strong power-play attacks against Colorado,
New Jersey plans to remain disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot take any stupid or bad penalties,'' Devils center
Petr Sykora said. ``They were scoring really big goals on power
plays. I think it is going to come down to special teams. Special
teams can win it and lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are 20-for-20 killing penalties at home and 48-for-51
overall in the playoffs.  &QL; 
Sticking to his guns
</P>
<P>
   At the season's inception, ESPN analyst and former Los Angeles
Kings head coach Barry Melrose picked the Stars to repeat as
Stanley Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   He held on that pick through the playoffs, even when Dallas
faced a red-hot Colorado team in the conference finals. He's
staying with it now as well as the Stars prepare to meet the New
Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been with them since Day 1,'' Melrose said. ``Everybody
else was jumping off the bandwagon and jumping on Colorado's, but I
never did. I like Dallas. Right now I think \R Ed\S Belfour is the
best goaltender in hockey. I think it's going to be harder than
people think, but I think Dallas will win in six.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Star-Telegram staff writers Jeff Caplan, Jennifer Floyd and J.
Douglas Foster contributed to this report.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
