<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS OVERCOME ADVERSITY TO BID FOR SECOND TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Stars' season began with a Stanley
Cup banner-raising celebration at Reunion Arena. One night later,
first-line center Mike Modano lay unconscious on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Right then, the Stars should have known their season would be up
and down.
</P>
<P>
   Almost eight months later, however, the Stars are four victories
from being back on top of the NHL world. For all their injuries,
new faces and line changes, the Stars again are in the Stanley Cup
Finals, where they play the New Jersey Devils in Game 1 tonight at
7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through so much, starting the year with Modano's
injury,'' Stars winger Brenden Morrow said. ``We are the defending
Stanley Cup champs, so every team was out to get us and wanting to
have their best game against us. We've dealt with a lot of
adversity. We had to fight through a lot. We had to play without a
full lineup pretty much the whole year, and we played well. Now,
here we are _ four games away from winning it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have expected that in a season when the Stars' Cup
runneth over with pitfalls? Well, the Stars for some.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they were losing players and games, the Stars never
lost faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the dressing room expected it, even though we had
faced a lot of injuries and had some down times during the course
of the year, especially in the beginning,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``You know, it's not what you do in October and
November. It's what you do now. Everybody in the locker room felt
that we were good enough and experienced enough to get back here.
Sure enough, here we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season was about thriving. This season was about surviving.
</P>
<P>
   A second Stanley Cup would complete a Stars' season that was
fractured, bent and broken. At times, the Stars were held together
with braces, tape and guts.
</P>
<P>
   Lacerated calves, fractured ankles, separated shoulders and
sprained knees were among the injuries that cost the Stars 395
man-games. It was in the second game that Modano strained neck
ligaments, broke his nose and suffered a concussion on a hit by
Anaheim's Ruslan Salei that forced Modano out of the lineup for
three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 9-11-3 and in last place in the Pacific Division
before a team meeting in Atlanta prior to their Nov. 26 game
against the Thrashers. From that point on, the Stars went 34-18-7,
winning the Pacific Division with 102 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we deserve a lot of credit,'' Stars center Guy
Carbonneau said. ``I don't think there too many teams in the league
right now that could have done what we did this year after winning
the Cup last year. The hangover, the pressure again and all the
injuries, to still get 100-something points is pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest turning point in the season might have come in
Phoenix on Feb. 3. The Stars' 2-0 victory pulled them into a
Pacific Division tie with the Coyotes, who had gone into the
All-Star break with a franchise-record 29 victories and a solid
hold on first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in there with not a big, strong lineup and we came out
with a 2-0 win, and I really felt like the team came together that
game,'' Stars winger Grant Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did not re-sign veterans Pat Verbeek or Dave Reid
after last season. Instead, they signed free agent Kirk Muller in
December, acquired forward Scott Thornton from the Montreal
Canadiens in January and traded with the Chicago Blackhawks for
defensemen Sylvain Cote and Dave Manson in February. The four
newcomers immediately fit in with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Stars soon could be fitted for a new ring.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the Colorado Avalanche in Game 7 of the Western
Conference Finals on Saturday, the Stars find themselves favorites
once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a tough year after you win the Cup,'' Nieuwendyk
said. ``It's hard to get your level up to where it has to be in
October and November, and we didn't get out of the gate very well.
Then, we faced a lot of injuries to key people. It seemed like one
thing after another was happening to our hockey club. But we
managed to go through and win our division again and be in a
position to win another Stanley Cup. I think that's a tribute to
the character and the experience of our hockey club.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2258EDT &QL; 
