<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ SAYS TRADE HURTS, BUT NO HARD FEELINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The trade still hurts, even more than the injured left
foot that could keep him out of the lineup for the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez made that perfectly clear sitting in the Detroit
Tigers' clubhouse yesterday, a few hours before he was hoping to
play against the Rangers for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was hard,'' Gonzalez said, ``Thirteen years with one
club, it did hurt me. They never talked to me ... then I'm traded.
It's business. I understand that. But I was hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Gonzalez insists he harbors no hard feelings toward
his former team after being traded by the Rangers in a nine-player
deal in November.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few vague derogatory references toward the public
relations department, he said the Rangers in general treated him
and their other Latin American players well during his time in
Texas. He spoke highly of general manager Doug Melvin, manager
Johnny Oates, his ex-teammates and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers organization, I have great memories there,''
Gonzalez said. ``The Rangers treated me good; they treated Latin
players good. I have a lot of good friends there, there are good
fans there, it was a good place to play baseball. I don't talk
negative about the Rangers. I appreciate the opportunity. They
signed me to play professional baseball and gave me a chance to
play in the big leagues with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps time heals all wounds, but those comments conflict with
ones made in spring training about the Rangers' poor treatment of
Latin American players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug treated me good. Johnny treated me good,'' Gonzalez said.
``Most everybody in the organization were great. There were some
problems with \Rthe public relations department\S, but that's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said: ``We knew he was hurt by the trade. When I talked
to him on the phone, I told him, `Juan, I've got bad news. You've
been traded.' He was shocked, but players go through that. He
probably thought he was going to play his whole career with the
Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was looking forward to playing against the Rangers
yesterday, and ESPN even chose the game for national broadcast
because of the anticipated reunion. But that was dashed when
Gonzalez was scratched before the game with a strained left heel.
There is a good chance he will not play during the three-game
series against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest in a series of setbacks for Gonzalez and the
Tigers. He has missed seven games because of various injuries, he
has driven in just 19 runs, and the Tigers, going into last night's
game, were 17-29, the second worst record in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also remains eligible for free agency after the season,
and the Tigers are in danger of having precious little to show long
term for the trade that sent pitchers Justin Thompson, Francisco
Cordero and Alan Webb, catcher Bill Haselman, infielder Frank
Catalanotto and outfielder Gabe Kapler to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers offered Gonzalez a $140 million, eight-year deal in
spring training, and it was thought that deal would be completed.
But Gonzalez said he's not ready to commit long term to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big question for me, a big decision,'' Gonzalez said.
``It's a good organization, and it's treated me so great. They have
good fans, a great tradition. But it's a big decision. I want to
wait ... maybe after the All-Star break, maybe at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the future of the team. That's very important.
I'd like to win. This year has started off slow. Everybody's
struggling. But now we're playing a little better against some
better teams. So we'll see what happens.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
