<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS DEFEAT METS, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It took only a three-pitch span to shatter Al
Leiter's run of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets had won all nine of Leiter's starts before
Monday, and they were tied in the sixth inning against the Los
Angeles Dodgers. No Dodger had batted with a runner in scoring
position until F.P. Santangelo came up with a man on second and one
out in the sixth. That is when Leiter's trouble began.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who thrives by pitching inside, drilled Santangelo in
the backside. The Dodger Stadium crowd stirred. One pitch later,
Leiter plunked Mark Grudzielanek just above the elbow. The crowd
hollered. On Leiter's next pitch, Shawn Green rocketed a grand slam
over the wall in right-center. The crowd erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The slam provided more than enough support for the right-hander
Chan Ho-park, who held the Mets to two hits over seven shutout
innings in a 4-1 Dodger victory.
</P>
<P>
   Five innings before Leiter was hurt by Green's bat, Mets
shortstop Rey Ordonez was hurt by Santangelo's helmet on a tag play
at second base. Ordonez left in the bottom of the first; a
nondisplaced fracture of the ulnar bone in his left arm was
diagnosed. He could miss up to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the big blow of the game came from Green, the outfielder who
became baseball's highest-paid position player when he signed a
six-year, $84 million contract after being traded from Toronto last
winter. The homer was his 10th and the grand slam was his second of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did not get a runner past second base off Park, who
improved to 5-4 with the victory. Park helped a few potential
rallies by issuing six walks, but the Mets were 0 for 4 with
runners in scoring position until the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters pitched a scoreless eighth and Jeff Shaw allowed a
run-scoring double to Joe McEwing with two out in the ninth. But
Edgardo Alfonzo grounded out as the potential tying run, ending the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other pitcher in the National League _ the Dodgers'
Orel Hershiser, who is now pitching in the minors _ has hit more
batsmen this season than Leiter, who has eight. It is a necessary
byproduct of pitching inside, and Leiter has otherwise had good
control this year, averaging fewer than three walks per nine
innings.
</P>
<P>
   One area in which Leiter has excelled has been holding runners
on. Leiter, whose record slipped to 5-1, has six pickoffs, the most
in the National League, and it was on one of them on Monday that
Ordonez got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo led off the Dodger first with a walk _ after an error
by Robin Ventura on a foul pop _ and before Leiter's first pitch to
the next hitter, he threw to first. Santangelo was going, and Todd
Zeile threw to Ordonez covering second for what should have been a
routine tag.
</P>
<P>
   But Zeile's throw sailed, and Ordonez leaped for it with his
glove hand outstretched. The three-time Gold Glove shortstop caught
it, whirled and, in one motion, swiped a backhanded tag on
Santangelo.
</P>
<P>
   But Santangelo's helmet plowed into Ordonez's left arm, and
Ordonez fell to the ground in pain. He was examined by team
trainers and left the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Abbott replaced Ordonez at short and more help could be on
the way as soon as Tuesday. The utility player Melvin Mora is
eligible to come off the disabled list, and he has been on a
rehabilitation assignment at Class AAA Norfolk, where he has hit
.333. The right-handed-throwing Mora played his last two games
without a protective bandage on his right index finger, which
needed four stitches after he injured it bunting on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Steve Phillips said before the game that Mora
would probably rejoin the team when it returned home Friday; it is
now reasonable to think that Mora could be brought back sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The reliever Jim Mann, who made his major league debut on
Monday, is the most likely candidate to be sent down when Mora
returns. Mann relieved Rich Rodriguez _ who threw one and one-third
scoreless innings despite two walks _ with one out in the eighth,
allowing singles to Gary Sheffield and Eric Karros before ending
the inning with a pop-up and fly out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
