<HEADLINE>
GREER FEELS DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Rusty Greer wasn't thrilled about spending six weeks
on the disabled list because of ankle surgery, a strained hamstring
and a sore shoulder. But he is convinced his return that he made
the right decision in having ankle surgery to have bone chips
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is night and day compared to what I was running
with before the surgery,'' Greer said. ``Especially starting off
taking the first two or three steps. But I feel like it will be
this winter and spring training before it feels like nothing was
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer admitted the ankle not only affected his speed on the
bases but also his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was from the standpoint in the outfield you have to
get a good jump, and the first two or three steps it what was
affected the most,'' Greer said. ``Balls fell in that _ I'm not
saying now they'll be caught _ but I'll come a lot closer to
catching.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm especially glad I got it done just because having to
go out there every day knowing something is going to hurt you and
it's not going away. It's not fun. You have little nagging injuries
during the season, but most of them are going to go away. The ankle
has been there for two or three years.''  &QL; 
Comerica observations
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates had three observations about Comerica Park,
the Detroit Tigers new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   It's big, especially with a 395-foot power alley to left-center
field. Said Oates: ``I told the guys, `If you're going to get hurt,
you better do it near the infield. Otherwise I'm not running out
there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The grass is thick. Oates said, ``We hit for 25 minutes in early
batting practice and not one ball hit in the gap rolled to the
warning track.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nicer than Tiger Stadium. Said Oates: ``I like tradition
and all that, but it's nice to go into a clubhouse where I can go
into my office and make a phone call, hang up my clothes or eat a
sandwich that you know a rat didn't run across the night before.
We're all spoiled. We like our amenities.''  &QL; 
Catalanotto not ready
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Frank Catalanotto was hoping to be healthy enough to
play the field during the Rangers' three-game with his old team,
the Tigers. But that won't be the case. Catalanotto is still
feeling the strained groin muscle that has been bothering him since
April 12 and remains limited to designated-hitter duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping by Friday he'll be able to play,'' Oates said.  &QL; 
Payroll reduction
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have a payroll of $70 million. General manager Doug
Melvin said if the Rangers had re-signed every player from last
year, they would have had a payroll of approximately $95 million.
That was one of the foremost reasons why he traded Juan Gonzalez to
the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still going to be a year or two before you can evaluate
that trade,'' Melvin said. ``But I stand by what I said before:
It's a trade that will help both clubs if they sign Juan. He's
still going to put up numbers. Obviously if they don't sign him, it
will be a disaster for them. It will be a disaster for us if Justin
Thompson doesn't pitch for us. But we're still proud of the guys we
got.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
