<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9180 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-SHAQ-TEX     05-29 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAQ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COACH, NEW SKILLS HELP FUEL NEW O'NEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Magic and Bird made it look too easy. A year or two in the NBA
and size 'em up for championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   But winning an NBA championship is never easy, as most future
Hall of Famers understand.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Michael Jordan, who needed seven years, Scottie Pippen and
Phil Jackson to reach the pinnacle with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Or Isiah Thomas, who won his first title in his eighth season
with Chuck Daly and the rest of the Detroit Pistons' Bad Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Or Hakeem Olajuwon, who, thanks to MJ's first retirement, helped
transform Houston from Choke City into Clutch City in his 10th
season.
</P>
<P>
   Or David Robinson, who finally became a champion with Tim Duncan
and the San Antonio Spurs last year, The Admiral's 10th in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal thought it would be easier. He even boasted of
winning everywhere _ except in college and the pros. In 1995, his
third season with the Orlando Magic, he reached the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq hasn't been back.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, his eighth, O'Neal has the coach, the teammates
and the will to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just on a mission,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission never seemed more possible for the 7-foot-1,
340-pound MVP, who towered over the league this season. Now, O'Neal
and the Los Angeles Lakers are one victory from reaching the NBA
Finals and their final quest.
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go through a few failures before you realize that
it's worth several sacrifices in order to get to the top,'' said
Mavericks assistant coach Del Harris, O'Neal's first head coach
with the Lakers. ``It doesn't come that easily. \RShaq's\S gone
through some disappointments, and now he's paying a bigger price.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's now 28 years old, and, interestingly enough, Michael
Jordan was 28 before he ever won a championship.''  &LR; subheds:Taking
sage's advice Phil Jackson imparted the sacrifices made by Jordan
and the Bulls to ``get over the hump'' before the season, when Shaq
spent time with the Lakers' new coach on Jackson's Montana ranch.
Jackson told O'Neal that an MVP season, like Jordan's, would be
necessary for the Lakers to add a 12th Larry O'Brien Trophy to
their collection of NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jordan's gravity-defying skills dazzled the league early
in his career, the Bulls did not win. Chicago made the playoffs his
first three seasons but went 1-9 in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's career has followed a similar journey, linking the
league's most dominant inside force with the biggest playoff duds.
In six trips to the playoffs before this year, O'Neal's teams have
been swept out five times, though after the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson set out to change that, much as he did with Jordan.
Learning to trust his teammates and the triangle offense helped
Jordan's Bulls overcome the Pistons and, ultimately, win six NBA
championships. Those same principles have O'Neal and the Lakers on
the brink of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's trying to get through to them the same philosophy we have
in practice,'' Jackson said. ``You go out and do everything with
the intensity necessary for whatever the challenge is. And that you
rise to meet that challenge ... Whether you're front-runners in the
playoffs, or front-runners in the regular season, it's how you get
through when you carry doubts in your head. You just can't have
that. You've got to go play.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time last summer, Shaq focused more on his play
than playing with his Hollywood toys. He did not make a movie or
cut a rap album. He worked on his game. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   And the hard work paid off, with the Lakers storming to 67
victories and at one point threatening to join Jackson's 1995-96
Bulls as the only NBA teams to win 70 games. O'Neal became the
Lakers' first player to win MVP honors since Magic Johnson in
1989-90. O'Neal received 99.2 percent of the first-place votes,
shattering Jordan's 96.5 percent in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a man you just can't believe watching night after
night,'' Lakers legendary radio play-by-play voice Chick Hearn
said. ``He's transcended into a guy that eventually could be named,
if not the best center to ever play, one of the very best. And I'm
talking about Wilt and Bill Russell, Kareem and those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearn has called all six NBA championships won by the Lakers in
LA (the other five were won in Minneapolis). Hearn has watched the
Jackson-O'Neal dynamic from courtside with a perspective spanning
the league's past 40 years and O'Neal's first four in Los Angeles.
Hearn said O'Neal took Jackson's summertime words to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have to change your game, Shaq, \RJackson\S
told him,'' Hearn said. ``You're going to have to separate your
play and add it to the other players. And Shaq has made that kind
of adjustment.''  &LR; subheds:Change is good Shaq always will dunk, and
if other big men could punish the rim as often as he does, they
would gladly trade in their drop steps and fade-aways, too. And
though it may seem unfair, Shaq, healthy the past two seasons after
three years battling various injuries, has added an adequate spin
move and jump-hook to his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the few centers content to stay in the post and not
try to step out and take outside shots,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   He's also setting screens and rebounding with more ferocity. His
13.6 rebounds per game this season were second in the league and
O'Neal's best since 13.9 as a rookie. Shaq led the NBA in scoring
for the second time in his career, nearly becoming the first since
Jordan to average 30. He scored at least 30 points 45 times, with a
career-high 61 against the LA Clippers on his 28th birthday. Shaq
also grabbed 20 or more rebounds in 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's rule changes, designed to free up the offense and
increase scoring, helped Shaq move across the lane with less
resistance. Though O'Neal still gets more than his share of bumps
along the way, he is able to set up even closer to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went from being most difficult to defend to impossible to
defend,'' Harris said. ``And changing the illegal-defense rule on
the strong side now allows him to play the pick-and-roll where he
doesn't have to rotate to anybody. Prior to this year, he had to
pick up someone. Now he can just lay down in there.''
</P>
<P>
   And wait to swat shots. O'Neal averaged 3.03 blocks per game,
his highest total since his rookie season and nearly twice last
season's average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first seven years he played were good, but good because he
was so doggone bigger than everyone else,'' Hearn said. ``He's
still big, but now he's got a lot more perfection to his game. He's
got the desire to go to the hole when he gets the chance. He's
become a great passer. He never was a good passer.''
</P>
<P>
   With the emphasis on spacing in the triangle offense and the
Lakers' perimeter threats (Glen Rice, Robert Horry), O'Neal can
either kick the ball outside or dump it to a slasher (Kobe Bryant,
Ron Harper). Whether bounce, cross-court, swing or no-look, Shaq
passed for a career-high 3.8 assists per game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a point of trying to get a lot of assists, to get
everyone involved. He's gonna get his, and his job is to try get
everyone else involved,'' Horry said. ``If we take shots and miss,
he's gonna go gobble up the rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks forward Cedric Ceballos couldn't help but notice the
change in his former Lakers running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the first- and the second-best player in the game,''
Ceballos said. ``I don't know what he did this summer, but you
can't do nothing with him. There's nothing you can do. He's gotten
to the point where the fouls don't even matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only way they can stop him. I think that's what he
realized this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul shooting, barely over 50 percent for his career, remains
O'Neal's Achilles' heel. He once joked that if he were a good foul
shooter, there'd be no need to practice.
</P>
<P>
   But not even Hack-a-Shaq can stop O'Neal these days. He made all
nine of his free throws in Sunday's Game 4 of the Western
Conference Finals at Portland. A 103-91 victory gave the Lakers a
3-1 series lead.  &LR; subheds:Final ingredient Magic had Kareem. Bird
had McHale and Parish. Jordan had Pippen. O'Neal has Kobe Bryant,
the 21-year-old who considers himself an equal partner in
Showtime's revival.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal feuded with his original Bryant, former Orlando Magic
teammate Penny Hardaway. Billed as the Magic and Kareem of the
'90s, Little Penny and ``Little Warrior'' (the Islamic translation
of Shaquille Rashaun) made one trip to the NBA Finals, in 1994-95.
They were swept by Houston before flaming out. Shaq left Orlando
after four years, signing a $120 million deal with the Lakers, the
team he followed as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   He and Bryant arrived in LA in 1996, and they immediately
clashed. Both thought the other commanded the ball too much. Under
Phil Jackson, they have learned to play nice.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq averaged a career-high 29.7 points per game this season,
Kobe a career-high 22.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Shaq complement each other so well out there now,''
Hearn said. ``Kobe and Shaq are a tandem. They look for each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process. Winning a championship is a matter of
maturing,'' said Harris, who spent the two seasons and six games of
his coaching career trying to reconcile O'Neal-Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq has Kobe Bryant, now 21, alongside, whereas his first two
years Kobe was 18 and 19. It's a matter of a lot of things coming
together.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever said it would be easy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
