<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9310 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-WOLDS-OF-FUN-2NDTAKE-     05-29 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLDS-OF-FUN-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (KANSAS CITY, Mo.: smaller rides.)
Added attractions
</P>
<P>
   But Cedar Fair hasn't shortchanged Kansas City's thrill seekers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the company added the Detonator and the Ripcord, which
each drop riders straight down from heights of almost 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Young families received Cedar Fair's 1997 annual treat in the
form of Berenstain Bear Country, a kiddie park within a park based
on the popular children's books.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the Mamba made its debut, rising 205 feet and dropping
riders at 75 mph. Attendance spiked to around 1.2 million. Last
year was Oceans of Fun's turn, with Hurricane Falls, a white-water
raft ride. Worlds of Fun added a quarter-mile go-kart track.
</P>
<P>
   This year's new ride is the Boomerang, a corkscrewing,
loop-the-looping, 12-story steel coaster billed as the only one of
its kind in the Midwest. It thrills riders not just once at 50 mph
but twice _ backward for the return trip.
</P>
<P>
   Keller knows exactly what's coming in 2001 and beyond, but he's
not tipping his hand.
</P>
<P>
   He will only say that next year's surprise is likely to be
another coaster with ``a different experience,'' while 2002
promises another family attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Half of Worlds of Fun customers are locals who live within an
hour's drive of the park that dominates the Northland's skyline
along Interstate 435. A huge percentage of them are the industry's
core consumer group, 12- to 24-year-old ``thrill riders'' whose
word-of-mouth advertising Keller values higher than the local
park's 50 billboards and torrents of radio and TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a badge of honor to be the first kid in the neighborhood
to ride the Boomerang,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keller has plenty of room to expand and keep the new thrills
coming. The two parks share 115 undeveloped acres, and even the
larger rides consume no more than three acres or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Land is not a worry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two challenges
</P>
<P>
   Two issues facing nearly every amusement park are safety
concerns and accessibility for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, a bill to tighten safety regulations was passed
this year and sent to Gov. Mel Carnahan. If he signs it, it will
take effect Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of any legal changes, Keller said, ``This industry by
its very nature wants to guarantee as much safety as possible.
We're very proud of our safety record.''
</P>
<P>
   At Worlds of Fun, Keller said, rides are inspected daily by park
employees and annually by consultants, insurance carriers and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fall we basically dismantle all of the rides for
extensive maintenance and rebuild,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, there's a continuing debate on increasing
amusement rides' accessibility to disabled people. Proposed federal
regulations raise serious design and cost issues for parks, and
Keller said they also threaten to slow the lines of patrons through
some attractions, cutting into revenue and inconveniencing all
riders.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the rides at Worlds of Fun are already accessible to
disabled people, Keller said, and the park offers a special
handbook to its disabled guests. That 29-page booklet pulls no
punches on the hazards posed by some rides and the imperative that
all riders be physically able to brace themselves and hold on
tight.
</P>
<P>
   Employees are not permitted to help wheelchair users and other
disabled riders, who must board, ride and exit by themselves or
with the aid of a companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do the best we can to offer rides to all people,''
Keller said. ``But there are limitations, just as there are in,
say, driving a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead
</P>
<P>
   Hunt's sale to Cedar Fair in 1995 was valued at $40 million. At
the time one industry expert estimated it would cost at least $130
million to reconstruct the two parks at then-prevailing prices.
</P>
<P>
   It's even more today, Keller said, with the price tag on a
state-of-the-art megacoaster as high as $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   To contain costs, the amusement park industry, like many others,
is going through an era of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Cedar Fair is one of the consolidators.
</P>
<P>
   Based on annual attendance, the trade publication Amusement
Business ranks the company as the world's fifth-largest theme park
operator, behind the four U.S. giants: Walt Disney Attractions,
Premier Parks/Six Flags, Universal Studios Inc. and Anheuser-Busch
Theme Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've acquired a sizable park every couple of years,'' said
Brian C. Witherow, Cedar Fair's director of investor relations.
``We're out there aggressively looking.''
</P>
<P>
   But there just aren't that many big, independent, top-quality
parks like Worlds of Fun left to buy. ``It's not an endless
number,'' he said. ``Knott's and Worlds of Fun were two of the top
ones out there. There may be only a dozen left.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Fair's balance sheet has been strong throughout the '90s,
albeit oddly balanced.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal nature of the business causes dramatically sharp
income spikes in the second and third quarters, with almost total
flattening in the fourth and first quarters.
</P>
<P>
   That's changed for the better since Cedar Fair's 1997
acquisition of year-round Knott's Berry Farm in California, which
generates cash flow 12 months a year.
</P>
<P>
   Annual earnings per share the past three years have averaged
$1.56. Cedar Fair stock closed Friday at 20 1/16, up 3/16. The
company's 52-week high of 25 7/8 was reached last June. The stock
hit 29 1/16 in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
