<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-29 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9311 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-WORLDS-OF-FUN-2TAKES-     05-29 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLDS-OF-FUN-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEDAR FAIR'S WORLD'S OF FUN BEGINS 28TH SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Through a child's eyes, Worlds of Fun is a
magical place, an endless sea of eye-popping colors, heart-stopping
thrill rides and more candy, ice cream and adventure than a mere
day can handle.
</P>
<P>
   The view isn't much different for the adult who runs the place.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Dan Keller is an amusement park guy _ has been
for the better part of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   He started out hawking cotton candy and operating rides at the
Cedar Point amusement park near Cleveland. He was tapped for this
area's top amusement park job in 1995 when Cedar Fair LP bought
Worlds of Fun and Oceans of Fun from Hunt Midwest Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In its 28th season, Worlds of Fun is stable, profitable and
still popular with succeeding generations of youngsters and the
young at heart. Oceans of Fun, its sister attraction, is in its
19th year.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Fair, the world's fifth-largest theme park operator, has
applied its standard business plan _ add a big ride or attraction
each year, and groom and inspire a staff that's friendly and
fastidious about details _ to keep the parks successful.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges are many, including public safety issues,
accessibility for the disabled and corporate growth through mergers
in an industry where few plum properties are available.
</P>
<P>
   The man at the top
</P>
<P>
   Keller manages his piece of Cedar Fair with a hands-on style.
</P>
<P>
   Every day he walks the hilly, wooded 235 acres of Worlds of Fun
and Oceans of Fun on a personal inspection tour, greeting many of
the park's nearly 2,000 seasonal employees by name, jotting notes
to himself and almost obsessively snatching up stray candy wrappers
and litter.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much to pick up, which tells volumes about the
priorities Keller preaches to his overwhelmingly teen-age work
force, which he calls ``the backbone of our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller takes pride in the fact that almost all of the year-round
staff of 100 are former summer workers, many of whom started as
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour at Worlds of Fun one day last week, Keller paused at
the carnival midway's basketball hoop game, grabbed a ball and shot
_ the old-fashioned way, revealing his 50 years. Keller's
underhand-from-the-knees shot was all net.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles. ``I only take about five shots a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After getting his start in the business at the Cedar Point park,
Keller took a detour into the tire industry before earning a
master's in business administration and returning to the world of
roller coasters and summer fun.
</P>
<P>
   He held a succession of executive posts with the company that
became Cedar Fair LP, which is based in Sandusky, Ohio. The
partnership owns Cedar Point, Worlds and Oceans of Fun, Knott's
Berry Farm near Los Angeles, Dorney Park near Allentown, Pa., and
Valleyfair near Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Hunt Midwest sold its amusement parks to
concentrate on its principal businesses of mining and real estate,
Cedar Fair stepped up as an eager buyer, and Keller was headed for
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Lee A. Derrough, Hunt's current president and chief
executive and longtime Worlds of Fun general manager, predicted
Cedar Fair would ``be able to do some things that may be more
grandiose than anything we would have been able to afford.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right.
</P>
<P>
   Executing the plan
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Fair bought the parks for around $40 million and has since
invested around $30 million more in new rides and other
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The park is a profit maker for the company, Keller said, and
local attendance has climbed modestly but within industry norms,
from around 1 million in 1995 to an expected 1.1 million at Worlds
of Fun and 300,000 at Oceans of Fun this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we look back on it, what we expected has come true,''
Derrough said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt's stock holdings, in excess of 1.3 million shares, allow
Derrough to keep an eye on both parks as a member of Cedar Fair's
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was truly a win-win for everybody involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary requirement in this business is capital
reinvestment. They've done a fabulous job. I'm not sure we ever
would have even considered a ride of the scope of the Mamba.''
</P>
<P>
   The parks did grow and mature under Hunt's ownership, adding
such world-class rides as the Orient Express in 1980 and the
all-wood Timber Wolf roller coaster in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But Cedar Fair's aggressive marketing philosophy adds a big
attraction almost every year to keep local customers coming back
for the newest thrill.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Point, the company's flagship park, this year boasts the
world's tallest and fastest roller coaster. The 310-foot high
Millennium Force drops riders 300 feet down an 80-degree incline at
92 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Cedar Fair will debut what it says is the tallest
and steepest water slide in the world, at Knott's Berry Farm. The
Perilous Plunge will drop riders in boats 115 feet down a 75 degree
incline.
</P>
<P>
   Such rides probably aren't in the future for Worlds of Fun.
Kansas City is a smaller market than Los Angeles or Cedar Point's
Cleveland-Toledo-Detroit region, Derrough said, and the economic
realities of return on investment dictate Worlds of Fun will
probably always have smaller rides.
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
