<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS PAY PRICE FOR LEAVING HARPER OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He is supposed to be worn down. His surgically
repaired knees must ache. Whatever skills left after 14 seasons
figure to be more of a liability than an asset.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers guard Ron Harper is no Rasheed Wallace or
Scottie Pippen or Shaquille O'Neal or Kobe Bryant. Harper is just a
role player, a fourth or fifth option, the 36-year-old Rodney
Dangerfield of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers have given him such little respect
that even Harper offers a hearty laugh, considering what has
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   Harper is a glowing example of why the Lakers hold a commanding
3-1 lead in the best-of-seven series. He's turned disregard into
constant daggers that have helped put the Lakers in position to
advance to the NBA finals with a Game 5 win Tuesday night in
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Neal keeps making the Blazers pay for their Hack-a-Shaq
defense, Harper is leading an uprising by the Lakers' supporting
cast. The Blazers are daring the likes of Harper, Rick Fox, Derek
Fisher and A.C. Green to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're paying for it, right?,'' Harper said Monday,
chuckling. ``They're getting beat, right? I wouldn't say this is my
highlight, but it feels good. I'm out there playing and doing what
they ask of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Blazers look inferior, their supposedly superior
talent and depth has been rendered moot.
</P>
<P>
   Portland definitely did not plan on Harper scoring as much as he
has, but that's what happens whenever Pippen leaves Harper to
double-team O'Neal or Bryant. It was Harper who drilled a baseline
jumper to win Game 3. He then tattooed the Blazers with 18 points
Sunday in a Game 4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Since the series began, Harper has harmonized the same chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I tell the guys is, 'My man is not guarding me,'''
Harper said. ``Scottie ain't guarded me all series long.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two biggest games of the season (both on the road),
Harper outscored Pippen, 30-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been getting open shots, and he has been able to take
advantage of them and get to the offensive boards,'' said Pippen,
who is about to lose out to Harper and Lakers coach Phil Jackson as
the former Chicago Bulls attempt to grab another championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that he is able to freelance and roam and do some
things out there. We have to contain guys like Shaq and Kobe, and I
think Rasheed and I and the whole team has done a good job not to
let Kobe and Shaq dominate the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Blazers seem to have few answers for the Lakers when
Bryant and O'Neal find open teammates when the Blazers trap. Harper
not only has provided scoring relief, he's snared key rebounds,
made crisp passes and played decent defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harper has a lot of leadership and uses a lot of heady play,''
Bryant said. ``He knows his spots, and he's been a big key to our
success.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Ron Harper that Jackson remembers from the 1996
playoffs, in series against Miami and Seattle. This is why one of
Jackson's first moves after becoming Lakers coach was to call
Harper, who was considering retirement.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson wears his rings to inspire from the bench, Harper
is the one whose savvy and championship experience nurtures on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about Ronnie's game,'' said Jackson, who
had to pry Harper away from a couch and the golf course. ``He's a
smart player and such a steadying influence, and we're going to
need that to finish this team off.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said if the Blazers keep leaving him open, he'll keep
making a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still know how to score. I have my tricks.'' said Harper,
who won three rings with the Bulls. ``It's not really any kind of
big secret. You go where there's nobody around.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland coach Mike Dunleavy steadfastly insists that he won't
change defensive schemes. The Blazers must work on closing down the
lane and preventing easy layups.
</P>
<P>
   All the Lakers want to do is fight off complacency and stoke the
killer instinct they developed in the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the series is not over,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   And Harper clearly isn't finished, either.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
