<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LOOK FOR CLINCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO -- Everything the Lakers are, they have shown in
taking command of the Western Conference finals. And everything
they are not -- or at least, didn't appear to be -- well, they've
shown all of that too.
</P>
<P>
   All of their strengths have come to the fore with a 3-1 series
lead over the Portland Trail Blazers. But the greatest strength
among them is suddenly the Lakers' ability to make every last
weakness disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Now they can make the Trail Blazers disappear too, with a
victory tonight at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant have played their superstar
roles, but the series has been defined by everything else:
</P>
<P>
   -A bench that was supposed to be inferior to Portland's has been
an asset (see ``28 points, Game 1'').
</P>
<P>
   -A team that couldn't win on the road for two rounds, going 1-3,
made a stand in Portland (see ``Victories, Games 3 and 4.'').
</P>
<P>
   -A 36-year-old guard no longer viewed as a scoring threat hit a
game-winning shot (see ``Harper, Ron -- Game 3'').
</P>
<P>
   -An MVP whose weak foul shooting could be exploited hit all nine
of his free throws, under pressure, on the road (see ``O'Neal,
Shaquille, cross-referenced under `Big Maravich' -- Game 4'').
</P>
<P>
   -And a team with a rich recent history of buckling at the first
sign of playoff adversity made a spectacular recovery from one
potentially devastating blow (see ``Oops, routed -- Game 2'').
</P>
<P>
   Meet the new Lakers, who can win their first NBA Finals berth
since 1991 with a victory tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been nice to be able to say we've met challenges, as
opposed to falling on our faces like we have in the past,'' said
Rick Fox. ``We've been able to say, `Hey, now we've had success,'
and put that behind us and look for a new ax to put away.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed metaphors aside, the Lakers are exuding the confidence of
a championship team. Never has it been more evident than in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   The five-game set against the Sacramento Kings tested them. The
4-1 victory over the Phoenix Suns included just one slip. But the
Blazers posed all sorts of challenges with their depth and
athleticism and youth.
</P>
<P>
   All of it, overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very conscious of it,'' said Glen Rice, the latest Laker
to rise, with a 21-point effort Sunday. ``We learn from our
mistakes and we try and get better. And I think that's the most
important thing about this team is we always look to improve as we
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Each series has given the Lakers a new demon to slay. This time
it was losing their first home game of the playoffs, a 29-point
loss in Game 2, and the home-court advantage. That, and the fact
they suddenly had to win on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after that home loss we kind of had to refocus,''
O'Neal said. ``I think you guys (reporters) were judging us on the
previous road games we played, like in Sacramento and Phoenix. We
didn't play well at all, we really didn't have to play well, we
were playing dominant at home. And once we got our home-court
advantage taken away, it kind of gave us new focus. We've been able
to snap back focus all this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-game set in Portland ``was definitely a big test for
us,'' Rice said. ``We realize that everyone was pretty much saying
that it was going to be an impossible task for us to go up there
and win two games. We've done that, and now to finish it off, we
have to win on our court (tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   Which will pose another set of challenges, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the fact the Lakers have gone 2-3 in elimination
games...
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something we seem to have stumbled around,'' Fox said.
``But we 've also earlier in this postseason here, learned from
some of our mistakes. We went on the road, and beat Portland in two
games whereas in the first series against Sacramento, we couldn't
get that. ... Now we hopet hat we can go out and finish a series
off at home, the way it's supposed to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Or the fact the Lakers often follow big wins with big-time
letdowns...
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, coming off two wins, and just a great team on the
road, you're just oozing confidence,'' Derek Fisher said. ``And now
being back at home, where the last time we slipped up, I think
gives us a little more motivation to go out and really be sharp and
be a little more on top of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   And so no one's getting excited about an imminent Western
Conference title, and coach Phil Jackson is still preaching
big-picture perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't talk about complacency,'' he said, ``as much as we
talked about the journey of a thousand miles begins wih the first
step type of stuff. There's the job at hand that's important to do
and stay focused on that. And how important it is for this team to
understand that, because we've had our letdowns in the past, and we
understand that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
