<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE CUT BACKS BLEEDING HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY DELLA DE LAFUENTE  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - Some Arizona hospitals are hemorrhaging financially as
deep reductions in federal Medicare reimbursements threaten their
future.
</P>
<P>
   Especially at-risk are institutions that care for the poor as
hospitals compete with nursing homes, health maintenance
organizations and other health-care providers that want Congress to
increase payments to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten bloodied. Last year was the worst year by far,''
said Dan C. Coleman, chief executive officer of the Lincoln Health
Network, which operates hospitals at North Mountain and Deer
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's hospitals lost nearly $15 million in unpaid services
for Medicare patients.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare pays for health-care services for people over 65 and
accounts for nearly 40 percent of the total revenues generated by
hospitals in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, Arizona medical centers lost nearly $51 million as
a result of reduced payments from Medicare under the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997. Those losses are expected to swell to about $66
million this year, according to a survey by the Arizona Hospital
and Healthcare Association.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives are tightening existing operations and
shutting community health programs and other unprofitable patient
services as the costs of labor, drugs, blood and new technology are
rising faster than the amount covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Net profit margins at the majority of the state's 70 community
hospitals sank collectively to a negative profit margin of less
than half of 1 percent, or -0.4 percent, down from an industrywide
profit margin among Phoenix area hospitals of 2.2 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers fall well below the national industry standard of
at least a 5 percent profit margin for hospitals to successfully
meet payroll, operating costs and make prudent investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see margins like this in hospitals, there's a great
danger in the Valley that a hospital could close,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln Network hospitals were two of 10 Phoenix area
hospitals that saw their positive net profit margins decline at the
end of the 1990s , according to data gathered for The Arizona
Republic by HCIA-Sachs, a Baltimore-based health information
company. &QL; 
ROCKY YEAR FOR LINCOLN
</P>
<P>
   Like other hospitals, Lincoln's anemic bottom line came after a
rocky year of grappling with Medicare's reduced payments. Profits
slipped at the network's two hospitals, where Medicare accounts for
nearly 30 percent of total revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln stopped the bleeding of red ink last year by shuttering
money-losing services including its popular program for managing
heart and lung diseases, a free health information service for
patients and a busy skilled nursing care unit, where the hospital
was paid $260 a day for care despite the actual cost of $650.
</P>
<P>
   Other Phoenix area hospitals are cruising in similarly chopping
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   `There will come a time when (now profitable) hospitals exhaust
their savings,'' said Jerry Smithson, chief financial officer at
St. Joseph's Hospital and Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has been spending down its savings, posting a net
income of $17.8 million in 1999, with about $6.7 million coming
from investment income. St. Joe's also has pushed back upgrades in
non-clinical services.
</P>
<P>
   At Medicare-dependent Sun Health Corp., health care operations
posted a loss of $1.9 million in 1999, the company's second loss
since the early 1990s. Sun Health , owner of Boswell Memorial and
Del Web Memorial, expects to lose $46 million to Medicare over five
years, said Bill Sellner, the company's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler Regional eliminated costly advertising and marketing
programs and closed an urgent care center in Sun Lakes because it
was draining a half-million dollars from the hospital, which kept
open a more profitable primary care clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Reductions in Medicare payments and the need to hire costly
temporary nursing staff to fill vacant slots cost hospital giant,
Banner Health of Arizona, about $20 million last year. Of that
amount, $14.2 million was lost to Medicare's reduced payment
system. The hospital system expects unreimbursed Medicare costs to
total about $22 million this year at its five hospitals, including
Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center and Desert Samaritan, system
spokesman Dan Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Memorial Hospital divested its medical group practices
and home health businesses because they were costly to run and
facing new competition, said Reginald Ballantyne III, president and
chief executive officer of Phoenix Memorial Health System.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Maricopa Medical Center did not return telephone
calls seeking comment. &QL; 
`I DON'T WANT TO CRY WOLF'
</P>
<P>
   Some hospital executives admit that, in the past, the industry
has overstated the effects of previous Medicare cuts. They are
adamant that the current crisis is real, and threatens the future
of longtime medical institutions.
</P>
<P>
   `I don't want to cry wolf, but the problems are severe. There's
a limit to the amount of money a hospital could lose,'' said John
Rivers, president and chief executive officer of the Arizona
Hospital and Healthcare Association, which is part of a national
lobbying campaign to persuade Congress to restore money cut from
their Medicare payments in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued earlier this month by the accounting firm of
Ernst &AMP; Young and HCIA-Sachs said the Balanced Budget Act created
the greatest instability that hospitals have experienced since the
creation of Medicare in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that nationwide total hospital profit margins
have significantly fallen since the law went into effect. Total
margins fell to 2.9 percent in 1999 from 5.5 percent before the
1997 law. The margins were the lowest since 1984, the study said.
The Federation of American Health Systems, which represents large
hospital chains, paid $50,000 of the report's $200,000 cost.
</P>
<P>
   `The federal government has recognized that they have cut out
all of the fat and now are cutting into the muscle. The hospitals
that have a significant commitment to caring for the poor are truly
threatened,'' St. Joseph's Smithson said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Della.Delafuente(at)Arizona Republic.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-29-00 2352EDT &QL; 
