<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAMB'S NIFTY PLAY BAILS OUT RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Rangers third baseman Mike Lamb has always been able
to hit, but there are supposedly still some questions about his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   He gave at least one answer to those questions last night. He is
perfectly capable of making a game-saving play when a bases-loaded
disaster is looming for the Rangers in the bottom of the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lamb, with the bases loaded and one out in the ninth, made a
terrific backhand stop of Deivi Cruz's wicked one-hopper and turned
it into a game-ending double play, allowing the Rangers to hold on
for a 3-2 victory against the Detroit Tigers at Comerica Park last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty good play,'' said closer John Wetteland, who
set a Rangers record for saves in a month with his 11th in May.
``And he can hit, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamb was 2-for-4 at the plate, but without his superb defensive
play the Rangers likely would have wasted a gritty eight-inning
performance from Kenny Rogers and fallen to their fourth
consecutive defeat. Rogers held the Tigers to two runs on nine hits
through eight innings with an assortment of pitches thrown at
different speeds and different arm angles.
</P>
<P>
   The generic baseball term is junk, but it was highly effective
against a Detroit lineup without Juan Gonzalez, who did not play
because of a strained tendon in his left heel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on I thought he was too strong and was a little bit up
in the strike zone,'' manager Johnny Oates said of Rogers. ``Later
in the game he went back to his off-speed stuff, got his sinker
going and got a lot of ground-ball outs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers turned four double plays, including the one started
by Lamb in the ninth. Luis Alicea and Rafael Palmeiro provided the
offense with home runs off Tigers starter Jeff Weaver in a ballpark
that's supposedly a tough place to hit one out.
</P>
<P>
   But they hit it to dead right field, which, as Palmeiro pointed
out, is about the only place in Comerica that favors a home-run
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else is Death Valley,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Death Valley, the Grand Canyon, Yellowstone Park,''
Alicea said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Palmeiro, ``Nah, Luis can hit them out of any park.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Alicea said. ``At about five a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was his second. For Palmeiro, it was his 14th.
Together they gave the Rangers a 3-2 lead that held up despite
serious threats in the eighth and ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Halter led off the eighth with a double into the
right-field corner off Rogers, declining what appeared to be a
better-than-average chance of stretching it into a triple. But the
rally ended when Jose Macias bunted back to the mound, allowing
Rogers to nail Halter at third.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland took over in the ninth and got into trouble when Dean
Palmer singled off Palmeiro's glove at first and Bobby Higginson
lined a single to right. Luis Polonia then bunted the runners to
second and third, and Robert Fick was walked intentionally to load
the bases.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Cruz, and Wetteland, known to strike out a
batter or two, was thinking double-play ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Runner on third less than two outs, you can't let him get the
ball in the air,'' Wetteland said. ``I was trying to get a cheap
ground-out double play.''
</P>
<P>
   He got one, but it wasn't cheap. Cruz smashed one that Lamb
short-hopped with the backhand. He stepped on third for the force,
then threw home to get Palmer as catcher Ivan Rodriguez held on
during the inevitable collision at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a reaction,'' said Lamb, who was signaled before
the play by infield coach Bucky Dent to look for the
second-to-first double play. ``But I knew Deivi can run, so I felt
if it was an in-betweener I would go home to get the force. But it
all really happened so quickly, I didn't really think about it. I
just did it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
