<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PUMPKIN' FIRE DEFIES EFFORTS TO CONTAIN IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - A fire burning deep into one of northern Arizona's most
pristine forests continued to defy firefighters Monday, May 29,
racing up Kendrick Mountain and threatening a historic cabin and a
lookout tower. Smoke from the fire was threatening to close Arizona
180, a popular road to the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But a blaze that caused evacuation of a Sedona-area campground
and the closure of U.S. 89A was more than half contained.
</P>
<P>
   Fires across Arizona pushed the number of acres burned this year
to more than 34,000 _ almost eclipsing the total for all of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there were about 50,000 acres burned by wildfires.
And while the pace is not quite that of 1995, when nearly 245,000
acres were burned, the season has started early this year with lots
of old, dry timber to burn.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Pumpkin'' fire in the Kaibab National Forest grew to 7,000
acres Monday morning. Then it ran up Kendrick Mountain when winds
on the Mogollon Rim picked up and relative humidities dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Winds were blowing toward the northeast, and about 750 people
were fighting the fire Monday, May 29, assisted by air tankers,
helicopters and bulldozers. Four firefighters suffered minor
injuries, a fire official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire started making some runs along the northeast side of
mountain,'' spokeswoman Emily Garber said. ``It hasn't gotten to
the top, but a lot of the north face has been burned.''
</P>
<P>
   CABIN WRAPPED UP
</P>
<P>
   At the top is a historic cabin and a lookout still used by
hikers. The 1912 cabin was wrapped in silver flame-retardant
material in hopes it could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retardant bombers really drenched the peak,'' Garber said of
the planes that drop a pink mixture of water, fertilizer and
fire-suppressant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made numerous drops to try and slow down the fire. So now
instead of a silver-wrapped house, we've got a pink-and-silver
house.'' The ``Vultee'' blaze, named for an arch in Oak Creek
Canyon, forced the evacuation of Slide Rock on Sunday, May 28,
afternoon. By Monday afternoon, officials were predicting full
containment for this morning.
</P>
<P>
   As those two fires blazed on, authorities were continued to
perform a balancing act with their available resources.
</P>
<P>
   35 CREWS ON JOB
</P>
<P>
   Of 35 elite Type I ``hotshot'' crews working in the Southwest on
Monday, May 29, 22 were assigned to Arizona: two teams from
California mopping up the ``Outlet'' fire on the Grand Canyon's
North Rim; six teams, including one crew from the Wenatchee
National Forest in Washington, fighting the Pumpkin fire; and 14
teams _ including two Montana and three California crews _ on the
Vultee fire.
</P>
<P>
   But officials are worried. So even when crews are released from
the Vultee and Pumpkin blazes _ ``demobed'' in firefighter-speak _
they'll remain at Fort Tuthill County Park south of Flagstaff,
``just in case they're needed to fight fires in the area in the
next few days,'' Coconino National Forest spokeswoman Raquel
Poturalski said.
</P>
<P>
   Command teams for the fires are also being taxed.
</P>
<P>
   `FULLY ENGAGED'
</P>
<P>
   A Kaibab National Forest spokeswoman _ noting that the forest
had six fires on it one day last week _ commented that the Kaibab's
substantial firefighting resources were ``fully engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   She's now on her way to New Mexico for the ``Viveash'' fire
north of Pecos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   The state has been supporting the fires on forest land with its
own equipment, but that, too, is a dangerous proposition. The state
has been lucky so far, with none if its lands burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of walking a tightrope right now,'' said Ron
Melcher, a fire coordinator with the state. ``We always walk it at
this time of year. How many resources can we put in there and still
have enough to fight another fire?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
